<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY'S AFTERLIFE, ASSUMED AND UNSPOKEN 
</HEADLINE>
 (yn) 
 By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the very heart of the final rites for John F. Kennedy Jr.,
his wife and her sister was a claim so utterly familiar, and yet so
disconcerting, that almost all the coverage of the event passed
over it quickly. This was not another example of media failure but
an illustration of a larger problem: how distinct religious beliefs
are transformed when they are filtered into public discourse.
</P>
<P>
   The familiar yet disconcerting claim, one widely affirmed but
nonetheless at odds with many modern assumptions, is, of course,
that the lives of the three young victims simply did not end with
that plane crash. Or, as it is put by a central prayer in the Roman
Catholic Mass of the Resurrection, celebrated for the Kennedys at
St. Thomas More Church in Manhattan: ``In Him, who rose from the
dead, our hope of resurrection dawned. The sadness of death gives
way to the bright promise of immortality.''
</P>
<P>
   In news coverage of that Mass, which was not televised or open
to members of the news media, this central message did not go
entirely unmentioned. But it was usually handled glancingly, in the
course, say, of explaining why the priests would be wearing white
vestments. And it was swamped by discussion of who attended the
service, how they looked, the political past and future of various
Kennedys and the impact on Manhattan traffic.
</P>
<P>
   On CNN, the Rev. John Gallen, the network's expert for the day
on Catholic liturgy, made a yeoman effort to interject a bit of the
rites' religious significance into the coverage, but he was clearly
struggling against television's very short theological attention
span. For every minute he had on the air, at least 10 were spent on
other topics, and more than half his own remarks were devoted to
recalling the presiding priest's relationship to the deceased, the
life of St. Thomas More and the religious issue in John F.
Kennedy's election to the presidency in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, one would think it should not have been
difficult for the news media to focus matter-of-factly on eternal
life as a major theme of the final rites. About 80 percent of the
American people say they believe in the afterlife, whether in the
Christian understanding or some other.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, this is not exactly a rare, esoteric belief. For
all that, it remains a disconcerting one. As countless religious
thinkers have said, the afterlife is not just an extra, and very
long, chapter tacked on to the life lived here and now, but makes
that current life part of an altogether different plot. This belief
defies one of the most powerful world views of the age: the
scientific naturalism for which it is axiomatic that whatever is
real and true must be subject to experimental test and
verification.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two centuries, the rising intellectual tide of
that materialistic naturalism has taken its toll on believers' own
certainty about life beyond the grave. And, though millions of
Americans consider heaven a place no less real than the front
parlor, even firm believers have sometimes shied away from publicly
stressing a life to come. They have been embarrassed by childishly
literal renderings of heaven and hell, or offended by reductions of
human complexity and God's unfathomable ways to harsh and tidy
stories of punishment and reward.
</P>
<P>
   They understand the complaint that dreams of ``pie in the sky
when you die'' have been used to deflect demands for this-worldly
justice. Perhaps most of all, they reject the denigration of the
natural world and human potential that has often accompanied a
focus on a life to come.
</P>
<P>
   So despite the data on belief in an afterlife, no one can be
confident what people have in mind by it, or with what
qualifications they want to speak publicly about it. When this
belief is filtered into public discourse, it is natural to drift
toward vague or common-denominator language.
</P>
<P>
   Thus the allure of President Kennedy's remark, played up in many
news reports of the service at sea, about going back to the ocean,
``whence we came.'' His language evokes a biblical sense of the
cycle of life and death. ``Naked I came from the womb, naked I
shall return whence I came,'' says Job; ``the Lord gives and the
Lord takes away.'' Yet Kennedy's language rings with the imagery of
evolutionary theory as well.
</P>
<P>
   In Sen. Edward M. Kennedy's eloquent eulogy, the brief note that
young John and his bride would now ``be with'' his parents was
similarly open to different interpretations, with only the phrase
``where there will never be an end to love'' suggesting, without
insisting, a more specific religious belief.
</P>
<P>
   Even Father Gallen, trying to make sense of belief in the
afterlife for a presumably pluralistic audience, cast Catholic
teaching in terms of there being ``more than death'' or ``new
life'' that ``wins out over death.'' These are phrases that
certainly encompass religious belief in a personal immortality but
that are also compatible with vaguer or strictly humanistic notions
that positive, constructive forces in the world outweigh negative,
destructive ones.
</P>
<P>
   All this is understandable, and yet it means that the framework
for public discourse about beliefs like the one in an afterlife
comes close to the materialistic naturalism mentioned earlier. Only
close, because there is still ample talk of God _ which may placate
the religious sensibility _ although not a God whose deeds or
promises pose a serious challenge to naturalism.
</P>
<P>
   Is it a necessary condition of contemporary American pluralism,
in which both science and the mass media play crucial roles, that
something approaching naturalism become the default position for
rendering religious beliefs in public discourse? The answer is
unclear. The question, for believers, is very serious.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
