<HEADLINE>
CABLE PROGRAMMER BUYS HOLLYWOOD POST-PRODUCTION COMPANIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY DAVE McNARY 
c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Cable programming giant Liberty Media Corp. jumped
into Hollywood post-production Friday by announcing $162 million in
deals for control of a pair of leading players, Todd-AO Corp. and
Soundelux Entertainment Group.
</P>
<P>
   Liberty will issue shares worth $92.5 million for control of 57
percent of Todd-AO, which put itself up for sale two months ago. In
a separate transaction, Liberty has agreed to invest $70.3 million
in Soundelux in exchange for a 55 percent holding.
</P>
<P>
   The deals come at a time when Hollywood's service providers have
been hurt by intense competition and by major studios' moves to
keep a closer watch on budgets. Both companies are based in
Hollywood with a combined work force of 1,250 and a combined
history of 64 years of independent operation.
</P>
<P>
   ``As consumer demand increases for entertainment and information
in all forms, the infrastructure to produce, traffic, distribute
and store program and commercial content must grow and mature,''
said Liberty President Robert R. Bennett in a prepared statement.
``We believe that these businesses can provide valuable services to
our existing businesses and will play an important role in
providing a new generation of services focused on the evolving
interactive video market.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd-AO, created in 1952 through a partnership between the late
producer Mike Todd and American Optical, said the deal will give it
the financial muscle to follow through with its strategy to become
a worldwide one-stop ``post house.''
</P>
<P>
   Todd-AO shareholders, who have seen their stock rise 60 percent
since management announced it would explore a sale, will receive a
slight, 6 percent premium for their shares at Friday's closing
prices. Liberty will pay one share of Liberty Class A stock, which
closed unchanged at $37, for every 2.5 shares of Todd-A0 stock,
which closed up $1.0625 at $14.
</P>
<P>
   Todd-AO, which has 860 employees and production offices in
Atlanta, Los Angeles, London and New York, has been expanding its
business with a $13 million deal for Sound One Corp. in New York in
June and a $16 million purchase of London-based Tele-CineCell Group
last year. The cost of acquisitions dragged down profits for its
third quarter ended May 31 to $62,000 from $1.6 million in the 1998
period with sales up 3 percent to $28.1 million.
</P>
<P>
   Todd-AO, which has won 18 Academy Awards since it was founded,
hired investment bankers Lazard Freres &AMP; Co. in early June to
advise it on possible merger and sales strategies. British media
giant Carlton and rival post-production house Laser Pacific had
also been rumored to be suitors.
</P>
<P>
   Soundelux was founded in 1982 by Lon Bender and Wylie Stateman,
who remain controlling shareholders. It has 410 employees, with
about 200 in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   Definitive agreements are expected by the end of August on the
deals, which will make Todd-AO and Soundelux part of
telecommunications giant AT&AMP;T Corp. Liberty, which has holdings in
such cable channels as BET, Discovery, E!, Encore, QVC and USA, was
bought by AT&AMP;T earlier this year as part of the purchase of parent
Tele-Communications Inc. and has continued to operate as an
independent entity since the AT&AMP;T deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
