<HEADLINE>
CHARLES MANSFIELD, 77, BANK EXECUTIVE  
 JOHN DAWSON, 97, ANTIOCH ADMINISTRATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla., Ohio)  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Mansfield, a former president and chief executive
officer of the Marine Midland Bank in Manhattan, died Monday at a
hospital in Rockville Centre, N.Y. He was 77 years old.
</P>
<P>
   According to a statement released by his family, Mansfield died
of cardiac arrest following a brief illness.
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield, who lived in Garden City, N.Y., and Stuart, Fla.,
also served as the chief executive officer and chairman of
Continental Copper and Steel Industries of Charlotte, N.C., now
called CCX Inc., when it was based in Cranford, N.J., and
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield was born Oct. 26, 1921, in Manhattan and graduated
from Fordham University. He served in the U.S. Army Air Corps
during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He was hired in 1951 by Marine Midland and rose through the
ranks, becoming president and chief executive officer in 1974. He
left the company shortly after Marine Midland and nine other banks
merged in 1976. Marine Midland is now part of HSBC of London.
</P>
<P>
   He then spent 10 years at the helm of Continental Copper and
Steel Industries before retiring in 1987.
</P>
<P>
   Mansfield was also a governor of the American Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife, Mary; two sons, Charles Mansfield
Jr. of Westhampton Beach, N.Y., and Michael Mansfield of Blooming
Grove, N.Y.; four daughters, Patricia Phelan of Freeport, N.Y.,
Peggy Mansfield of Ventura, Calif., Elisabeth Mansfield of Goshen,
N.Y., and Kate Mansfield of New Haven, Vt.; a sister, Alice Mary
Lissemore of Scotch Plains, N.J.; four grandchildren, and four
great-grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   John Dawson
</P>
<P>
   John Dudley Dawson, an Antioch College administrator who became
known to generations of students at Antioch for his role in
revitalizing the college's approach to co-operative work-study
education, died on Thursday at Greene Memorial Hospital in Xenia,
Ohio. He was 97 and lived in Yellow Springs, Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Dawson gained an international reputation through his work from
1936 to 1953 as director of co-operative education at Antioch, in
Yellow Springs. The idea of integrating work experience with
traditional academic study had been a hallmark of Antioch since
1920, but Dawson greatly expanded the program.
</P>
<P>
   He found jobs for students in businesses across the country,
promoted the concept of employers as ``field faculty'' and fostered
the integration of co-op work with traditional classroom study.
</P>
<P>
   From 1953 to 1967, he served as vice president and dean of
students.
</P>
<P>
   For the next 16 years, he visited more than 100 colleges and
universities around the world as a consultant on co-op education.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Haskins, Ohio, Dawson graduated from Denison University
in 1923, earned a master's degree from Ohio State University and
then went on to do further graduate work at Ohio State, the
University of Michigan and Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   His wife, Nona Dawson, died in 1995. He is survived by three
sons, Evan of New York City, John of Lee, N.H., and Darrell of
Santa Fe, N.M.; and six grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
