A0789 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-RICHARDSON-NYT &LR;      07-31 0572
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-RICHARDSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
H.S. RICHARDSON, 79, HEIR TO VICKS COLD REMEDIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Conn., N.C., Calif.)  (mk) 
 By DANA CANEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ H. Smith Richardson Jr. grew up in a household in
which Vicks Vaporub, the cold remedy, meant more than relief from a
hacking cough.
</P>
<P>
   He was the grandson of the man who developed that product, and
he eventually led the family business, Richardson-Vicks Inc.
Richardson died on Tuesday at New York Presbyterian Hospital after
surgery for pancreatic cancer, his family said. He was 79.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson's business life centered on the family company, which
was founded in 1905 by his grandfather, Lunsford Richardson. The
younger Richardson joined the company in 1938, working at Vicks
production plants and later in the sales department.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning in 1948, Richardson assumed various management
positions at what was then Vick Chemical Co. He became president in
1957 and chairman in 1961. Under his leadership, the company grew
into one of the nation's 250 largest companies, with revenue of
$1.2 billion by 1985, the year he retired as chairman. Several
months after his retirement, the company was sold to Procter &AMP;
Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   One of Richardson's life goals, he once said, was to build upon
the successes of previous generations of Richardsons. To that end,
he positioned the company to seize opportunities in the rapidly
expanding global marketplace by overseeing the development of an
international marketing and distribution system.
</P>
<P>
   By the early 1980s, Richardson-Vicks products, which include
Vicks Nyquil cold syrup, Clearasil acne medication and Oil of Olay
beauty cream, were sold in more than 144 countries, with foreign
markets accounting for 60 percent of revenue. Richardson moved to
Wilmington, N.C., from Fairfield, Conn., after his retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his life, Richardson was involved in philanthropic
and nonprofit organizations, and from 1972 until his death he was
chairman of the Smith Richardson Foundation, which his father had
created to provide support for charitable work as well as for
research and analysis of public policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Richardson had a lifelong interest in leadership
development, particularly in management and corporate governance.
He was instrumental in creating the Center for Creative Leadership,
an institute that trains executives, military officers and
politicians in business and government. Richardson was chairman of
the center's board from 1972 until 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Greensboro, N.C., Richardson lived in Irving Park, N.C.,
until the family business moved to New York in 1933 and the family
itself to Connecticut. He attended the Buckley School in New York
and St. Paul's School in Concord, N.H. In 1944 Richardson earned a
bachelor's degree in chemistry from Yale University, where he was
elected to Phi Beta Kappa. After college he served for four years
as a naval officer during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife of 54 years, Adele, of Wilmington;
three daughters, Adele Richardson Ray and Page Richardson, both of
Chapel Hill, N.C., and Cary Paynter of Wilmington; three sons,
Stuart of Easton, Conn., Peter of Southport, Conn., and H. Smith
Richardson III of Santa Barbara, Calif.; a brother, Randolph
Richardson, of Amagansett, N.Y.; a sister, Grace Stetson, of
Bridgeport, Conn.; 12 grandchildren, and two great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 0009EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
