<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAS-PRICES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAS PRICES REV UP IN SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Gas prices continue to explode like a California
oil refinery and are expected to jump as much as 4 cents per gallon
within the next 10 days, thanks to tight crude oil supplies and
continuing problems at the state's refineries, energy industry
analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   One watchdog group fears that prices at the pump could climb up
an additional 20 cents per gallon over the next 45 days.
</P>
<P>
   The latest scapegoat is a hydrogen pipe at Mobil Corp.'s
Torrance refinery. It caught fire Wednesday morning, putting out of
commission one of the refinery's two hydrogen plants, which are
used in the production of gasoline.
</P>
<P>
   The state's wholesale market responded by immediately sending
prices up about 15 cents per gallon. Analysts say any increases on
the wholesale market usually take about 10 days to reach retail
pumps.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the statewide average for a gallon of gasoline has
increased 13 cents in three weeks to $1.46, as of Monday, according
to Claudia Chandler, assistant executive director for the
California Energy Commission in Sacramento. She predicted the
average would move up another 3 cents or 4 cents over the next
seven to 10 days.
</P>
<P>
   Locally, drivers are already feeling the pinch. Between Tuesday
and Friday, prices at San Fernando Valley pumps increased about 3.9
percent from an average $1.344 to $1.396, according to the Daily
News' twice-weekly survey of area stations. At some stations, the
price for a gallon of regular unleaded gas increased by as much as
10 cents.
</P>
<P>
   The average price for a gallon of gas in Los Angeles on Friday
was $1.43, about the same as it was on July 23, said Charles
Langley, gasoline project manager for the Utility Consumers Action
Network, a consumer watchdog group based in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   He said it would not be ``unreasonable'' to expect price
increases in the next 30 to 45 days ranging from 15 cents to 20
cents. Six refineries control about 90percent of the state's fuel
supply, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The market in California is so consolidated that any hiccup in
the supply line causes serious price increases at the pump,''
Langley said Friday. ``We think a lot of that is due to
opportunistic price gouging.''
</P>
<P>
   California refineries together now refine about 900,000 barrels
of oil per day, compared with 970,000 to 980,000 barrels under
normal circumstances, Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can see we're down between eight and 10 percent,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   This month's price increases are being blamed on a Tosco
refinery in Avon, where there was a fire Feb. 22, and a Chevron
refinery in Richmond, where there were explosions on March 23 and
July 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those two refineries going out causes a very constrained
market for gasoline,'' Chandler said. ``Chevron has a significant
portion of the California supply and they're still not back on
line.''
</P>
<P>
   The February decision by the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries to limit production has pushed up the price of Alaskan
North Slope crude _ which is the main component of gasoline in
California _ from $9.60 a barrel on Feb. 22 to $19.60 on Friday,
Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As their crude oil (price) goes up, so does the crude oil for
the rest of the world,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, the price of gas on the West Coast spot market _ that
is, the market on which surpluses are sold _ was at its highest
level so far this year, said Mary Welge, associate editor for the
Oil Price Information Service in Lakewood, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   It was about $1.10 in Los Angeles and about $1.15 in the San
Francisco Bay area, which is usually hit harder by higher crude oil
prices and other inflationary pressures.
</P>
<P>
   The spot price does not include taxes and other costs that are
added to it on the way to the gas pump.
</P>
<P>
   A tight oil supply and ``myriad refinery problems'' have pushed
up the spot price, Welge said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The West Coast has just been a hotbed for refinery problems
since February _ just one thing after another,'' she said. ``This
has served to put a squeeze on supplies.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the price pressure could be alleviated starting today,
when Tosco's Avon refinery is expected to go back on line, Chandler
said. In addition, Chevron expects cargos of gasoline to arrive
shortly from out-of-state refineries, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do know there are shipments coming that will help alleviate
some of the pressure on prices,'' Chandler said.
</P>
<P>
   Carolin Keith, public affairs manager for Mobil Corp.'s western
region, would not say how much production was reduced as a result
of Wednesday's mishap, in which no one was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   ``All that we're saying at this time is that one of our two
hydrogen plants is down,'' she said Friday. ``The rest of the
refinery is operating. Some of the units are operating at reduced
rates.''
</P>
<P>
   Normally, the refinery each day processes about 130,000 barrels
of crude oil, which produces about 4.2 million gallons of gasoline,
Keith said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
