<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEASTER-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW ABOUT SOME GATES-CRASHING? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every so often something comes over the Internet transom that's
too good not to share. When these gems arrive, they just naturally
get squirreled away for the day when your faithful scribe either
hits a dry hole or wants to play hooky. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Today it's the latter, and this offering comes under the heading
``The Auto Empire Strikes Back.'' It involves alleged zingers
dreamed up by resident General Motors wags in response to a
brickbat heaved their way by Microsoft czar Bill Gates. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   During an info technology confab in the not-too-distant past,
the world's richest man reportedly was holding forth about the
wonders of the computer age. While doing so Gates compared what his
industry had wrought with the shortcomings of what he apparently
considered a more stodgy industry. That was the auto industry,
which while a traditional linchpin of the U.S. economy during most
of the 20th century, nevertheless came up short in the progress
department, in Gates' view. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The way Gates put it, if General Motors had kept up with
technological advancements like the computer industry had, we would
be driving cars that cost $25 and got 1,000 miles to a gallon of
gas. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   To which GM's defenders responded, according to the recently
received missive from a Valued Contributor, those who live in glass
houses shouldn't ... well, you know the rest. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   They say if GM had developed technology like Microsoft, their
cars would be crashing twice a day for no reason. Other glitches
might include the following: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - When you executed a particular maneuver, say a left turn, it
would cause your car to shut down and refuse to restart, in which
case you'd have to buy a new engine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Only one person at a time could use the car, unless you bought
Car95 or CarNT, in which case you'd have to buy more seats. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - New seats would require all users to have the same size
derriere. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - The oil, temperature and alternator warning lights would be
replaced by one ``general car default'' light. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - The airbag-safety system would ask you to respond to an ``Are
you sure you want to deploy the air bag?'' question before the
airbag would work. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - On some occasions, for no reason whatsoever, your car would
lock you out and prevent your entry until you simultaneously lifted
the door handle, inserted the key and held the radio antenna. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - GM would require the purchase and use of a deluxe set of road
maps from a road-map subsidiary, whether the owner needed the maps
or not. Any attempt to delete this option would reduce car
performance by 50 percent, and prompt an antitrust initiative by
the Justice Department. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Each time highway workers repainted the lines on the roads,
car owners would have to buy a new car. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - Each time GM introduced a new model car, all motorists would
have to learn to drive all over again because none of the controls
would operate in the same manner as the previous car. (Meantime,
Macintosh would produce a sun-powered car that went five times as
fast and was twice as easy to operate.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   - When finished driving, vehicle operators would have to press
the ``start'' button to turn off the engine. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   And who said business types don't have a sense of humor? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
