A0806 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-RANGERSTRADE-TEX     07-31 0476
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERSTRADE-TEX </SLUG>
 
ANY TRADE LIKELY TOO EXPENSIVE FOR RANGERS (For use by NYTimes News
Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
ARLINGTON, Texas _ Rangers general manager Doug Melvin doesn't like
to stay on the sidelines at or near the trading deadline. He'll
explore every opportunity if there's a chance to improve his team.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Rangers needed defense up the middle and starting pitching
last year, so Melvin brought in shortstop Royce Clayton and
pitchers Todd Stottlemyre and Esteban Loaiza before the deadline.
</P>
<P>
   The club needed pitching to win its first division title in
1996, so he made a post-deadline waiver deal for John Burkett.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the team out of contention in 1997, he traded third
baseman Dean Palmer for center fielder Tom Goodwin.
</P>
<P>
   So while he was in Pulaski, Va., yesterday to look at one of the
club's rookie-league teams, he was busy trying to deal to upgrade
the starting pitching.
</P>
<P>
   But before he left for Pulaski, Melvin was not optimistic about
a deal before the deadline at 11 p.m. tonight.
</P>
<P>
   With the Rangers holding a commanding lead in the American
League West, a trade would have to land a pitcher who would allow
the team to compete with the New York Yankees and Cleveland
Indians, both in the race for best regular-season record and
consequent home-field advantage, and in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors have linked the Rangers to Darryl Kile of the Colorado
Rockies and Juan Guzman of the Baltimore Orioles, but Melvin
doesn't seem convinced that any of the pitchers who are available
could have the desired impact.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were three guys out there last year that were pitching
well and clubs had an interest in: Randy Johnson, Todd Stottlemyre
and Carlos Perez,'' Melvin said. ``They were all pitching well and
were available. There isn't a group of pitchers you can feel that
way about this year. We're talking about people who walk more than
they strike out, about high ERAs, about taking on a salary plus
giving up players. It's a double-edged sword.''
</P>
<P>
   Teams with pitchers on the block are asking for quality
minor-leaguers, and Melvin is reluctant to pay that price.
</P>
<P>
   ``What might be the heaviest part of not making a deal is our
recognition that we feel good about our young players,'' Melvin
said. ``We feel good about Mike Lamb at Double-A, about Corey Lee,
about Danny Kolb. Ryan Glynn's got some experience now. \RJeff\S
Zimmerman, \RRuben\S Mateo and \RMike\S Venafro have given us an
indication of what they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin has downplayed the team's chances of making a deal and
then pulled off a blockbuster in past seasons, so it wouldn't be a
surprise if he pulls off a trade today, especially if the price
goes down as the day goes on.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, the cost appears prohibitive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a seller's market for pitching,'' Melvin said. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 0016EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0013 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 00:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0813 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIG-BREAK-LADN     07-31 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIG-BREAK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST-TIME DIRECTOR FACES CHALLENGES ON THE SET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDS, this is second in five-part series.) 
BY STEVE CARNEY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SANTA CLARITA, Calif. _ Actors and crew members went missing,
authorities got cranky about permits, and on Friday even the sun
wouldn't cooperate with first-time film director Joanne Small.
</P>
<P>
   She was on location in the arid hills near Castaic Junction,
about 30 miles north of Los Angeles, making a short film she hopes
will launch her directing career. But she was on day two of the
tight shooting schedule for ``Joey Was Here,'' and the midday sun
was throwing glare and reflections on her actors' faces during a
crucial scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to do it over and over again. We're two hours behind,''
she said. But instead of her stress increasing with the noontime
temperature, Small tried to maintain perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to have a sense of humor about this,'' she said.
``It's not brain surgery _ it's making a movie.''
</P>
<P>
   And in movies big or small, no matter how carefully every shot
is plotted in the script, obstacles rear up. But the key to
avoiding disasters is to plan for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``If something goes wrong, you have to switch gears
automatically,'' she said. ``I've been making movies too long.
There's nothing that has caught me off guard.''
</P>
<P>
   Small toiled for years in Hollywood and New York City, editing,
writing and script supervising while working toward a career
directing. This year she got the break she was looking for when she
was picked for one of eight slots in the Directing Workshop for
Women, an exclusive program offered by the American Film Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The winners _ chosen from 150 applicants _ have a $20,000 budget
and only five days in which to shoot their 20-minute masterpieces.
</P>
<P>
   So Small has neither time nor money to spare.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our hardest day, by far,'' she said Friday. ``I'm not
surprised we're a little over schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   In the movie she planned to include a scene with different views
of two characters conversing. But she'll just go with one
perspective _ the glare problems Friday cost her the time she
needed to shoot the other. But she had already planned in her mind
how to edit around the problem.
</P>
<P>
   ``We start the day with a wish list of all the wonderful shots
we'd like to have,'' she said. ``When you're Stanley Kubrick and
you have 10 months to shoot, you get your wish list.''
</P>
<P>
   Small, however, has to keep wishing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the average production cost for a movie from one of
the seven major Hollywood studios was $52.7 million. With a budget
like that, Small could make sequels up to ``Joey Was Here 2,635.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead she's working with equipment on loan from AFI, and a
volunteer cast and crew of friends and acquaintances from the
industry who have lined up to help.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a guy who didn't show up this morning, and we had him
replaced within an hour,'' said Scott Carlson, one of Small's two
producers.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just bob and weave,'' he said. ``She trusts us to know
we'll get it done.''
</P>
<P>
   Other problems popped up like targets in a shooting gallery.
</P>
<P>
   --Crew members couldn't secure permits from Agoura Hills before
the City Hall there closed Friday, so locations for scenes planned
Monday had to be relocated.
</P>
<P>
   --A crane and a Steadicam needed for weekend shooting suddenly
became unavailable, and the crew scrambled to replace them _ making
calls from Orange County to Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   --Three separate California Highway Patrol officers showed up
Thursday to demand permits and scold the crew in what turned out to
be a scheduling mix-up.
</P>
<P>
   --The wardrobe mistress had a car breakdown the same day, and
someone had to meet her at the repair shop and pick up the actors'
clothes.
</P>
<P>
   --An actress slotted for one of the roles in the movie had to
quit Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She called to say she got a paying gig and had to bow out,''
Carlson said. ``They're working actors. We know going into this, if
they get a paying gig, they've got to go. There's no hard
feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   But Small's lead actor _ the Joey in ``Joey Was Here'' _ called
six days before filming began with his regrets. He too had gotten a
paying job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, my first reaction would've been to scream,'' Small
said. ``But my reaction was, hmm, this is interesting. This happens
all the time in the real world.''
</P>
<P>
   So she contacted a budding actor she'd just met, George Stults,
a square-jawed 23-year-old blond from Detroit. Small took it as a
chance to give him his first shot and see how well she does coaxing
a performance out of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What looks to be a disaster turns out to be a miracle,'' she
said. ``He's a star. There's no question he's going big places.
And, hopefully, with me.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
