<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 00:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0829 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEAT-DEATHS-2NDTAKE-K     07-31 0900
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-DEATHS-2NDTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELENTLESS HEAT ADDS MORE VICTIMS TO ITS LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH E. IGOE and MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steven Cook, 40
</P>
<P>
   Lots of folks knew him as Rocky.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rocky Balboa!'' they would cheer when he walked into the Davis
Health Care center at 2826 Campbell Ave. to get a prepared meal.
</P>
<P>
   Steven Cook would smile. Everybody knew Cook dreamed of being a
boxer. A great boxer. The 40-year-old worked out with weights and
equipment in his apartment next door to the center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to be somebody someday,'' he would crow to case
workers with a laugh. ``And then I'll ask: `Who are you?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Cook was mentally ill but lived independently. When he was found
July 21, Kansas City police reported his apartment was about 95
degrees, with no fan or air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a strong individual,'' said Danny Davis, who runs Davis
Health Care. ``He was very motivated and he was very friendly when
you met him.''
</P>
<P>
   For all his boxing bravado, Cook was also a quiet person,
sometimes even a loner, who was loyal to his friends.
</P>
<P>
   About 30 case workers and friends gathered at a memorial service
Friday at the Network Rehabilitation Services Center at 3121
Gillham Road to remember their friend. There were songs, a prayer,
laughter and memories.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a nice person,'' said Carol Allman, a case worker with
Davis Health Care. ``Everybody liked him.''
Ralph Generaux, 81
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Generaux said cool air hurt his bones.
</P>
<P>
   He would tape over the air conditioning vents when staying at
his nephew's house. While being driven on errands, he would close
off vents in the car.
</P>
<P>
   During the stifling heat of recent days he adamantly refused the
offer a window-unit air conditioner for his two-room apartment on
the second floor of a house near Westport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I begged him,'' said niece Jan Generaux. ``But he was so
bull-headed. He would have taken it out of the window, or never
turned it on.''
</P>
<P>
   Late Wednesday afternoon, a concerned neighbor called Generaux's
landlady, Lucille Isaacs. Immediately, she had a bad feeling.
</P>
<P>
   They found the 81-year-old Army veteran and cancer patient dead,
in his shorts in his straight-back chair, his head tilted back as
if asleep. One box fan was running in a window -- in the other
room. The other windows were closed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a stubborn old man,'' upstairs neighbor Dwight Sexton
recalled fondly. Sexton tried to get Generaux to at least accept
another fan, but he had refused.
</P>
<P>
   Generaux had some friends in the vicinity of his home in the
3800 block of Wyandotte Street. His health had deteriorated in
recent months but he still smoked heavily. He liked to sit in his
chair and watch television, especially football and game shows.
</P>
<P>
   Sexton would pick up some groceries for him. A young girl two
houses down would bring up his mail from the street box. Isaacs and
her son Arnold Isaacs would bring him Thanksgiving and Christmas
dinners.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew him really well,'' Lucille Isaacs recalled. ``You
could set your clock by when he paid the rent.''
</P>
<P>
   Generaux served in Europe and Africa in World War II. In later
years he was a handyman.
</P>
<P>
   Generaux had prearranged his own funeral and had all his papers
in a box in the kitchen. When his niece and nephew, Ed Generaux,
went to retrieve the box Thursday afternoon, after all the windows
had been opened, they still could hardly stand the oppressive heat
in the apartment.
</P>
<P>
   Generaux could be cranky. He sometimes answered the phone with
``Goodbye.'' If you asked him how he was he'd say, ``Terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   But those who knew him well didn't fault him for his
temperament. He was old, and he was ill.
</P>
<P>
   Jan Generaux said she would become exasperated trying to
convince Uncle Ralph that cool air would make him feel better.
</P>
<P>
   ``He would say, `With all that's wrong with me, nothing is going
to make me feel better.' ''
Charles Dyer, 73
</P>
<P>
   His well-worn and hollowed chair in front of the TV was empty.
</P>
<P>
   A pipe teetered on an ashtray, ready for a pinch of tobacco and
a good smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Gertrude Jones didn't want to move anything. His housemate for
the past 10 years, she hadn't even gone into his room since he died
Sunday night in his sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just don't want to change anything right now,'' said Jones,
69, sitting on her living room couch. ``I have to get myself
together before doing anything. It just doesn't seem like he's
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   The two met about 11 years ago, Jones recalled Friday. They were
next-door neighbors in a Linwood Boulevard apartment building. It
was a loud and raucous place and the two swapped dreams about
living out their older years in a quiet home all their own.
</P>
<P>
   They decided they could pay the bills together. In 1989, they
settled into a bungalow along Indiana Avenue. Each had a room. They
passed the days chatting, watching TV together, talking about the
old times or barbecuing on their porch. Dyer would sometimes invite
some friends over for a card game.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday night, he told Jones that he wasn't feeling so well.
He slept on the second floor, but the fans there only pushed the
hot air around. The next morning, she called for him and there was
no response. She summoned a friend, who called 9-1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had gotten to be so tight. It was just me and him,'' Jones
said. ``We laughed and talked a lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
