<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 00:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0832 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEAT-DEATHS-2TAKES-KA     07-31 0921
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-DEATHS-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELENTLESS HEAT ADDS MORE VICTIMS TO ITS LIST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RUTH E. IGOE and MATT CAMPBELL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Willard Medley's relatives checked on the
75-year-old Kansas City man several times a week. On Sunday, they
persuaded Medley to turn on his air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   But he mistakenly turned his heater on instead. With that error,
Medley became another of Kansas City's heat wave statistics.
</P>
<P>
   When relatives found him dead in his home Tuesday, the
thermostat read 95 degrees, hotter than it was outside.
</P>
<P>
   State health officials reported Medley's and two other
heat-related deaths in Kansas City on Friday as the mercury burst
past the 100-degree mark for the seventh straight day downtown.
</P>
<P>
   Those deaths bring the area toll to 13 and fit the pattern of
similar deaths in that they involved older residents. Most of them
didn't have air conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Lindholm, chairman of the Kansas City Heat Advisory Task
Force, said everyone working in neighborhoods -- including police
officers, firefighters, and water meter readers -- was making a
concerted effort to check in on isolated people, especially the
elderly, who might need help escaping the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got just about every public servant in the Kansas City
area coming together,'' he said. ``In a few of the (death) cases,
they were within a stone's throw of a cooling center. That's just a
needless tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service has kept Kansas City's weather
status at the heat advisory level. On Thursday, the task force
upgraded Kansas City's weather status to heat alert, setting in
motion the opening of several additional cooling centers.
</P>
<P>
   At least 11 cooling centers were running Friday, although some
were not well patronized.
</P>
<P>
   Residents walked down East Ninth Street trying to shield
themselves from the heat. Some were walking home. Others were
catching buses. But the cooling center at the Salvation Army
attracted few residents.
</P>
<P>
   Staff members said some residents stopped by in the morning to
drink water or lemonade and sit on the cushioned chairs. But in the
early afternoon, the air-conditioned center was empty.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's high temperature at Kansas City International Airport
was 103 degrees, while downtown clocked in at 104. The heat index
downtown reached 114, compared with 109 at KCI.
</P>
<P>
   National Weather Service meteorologists in Pleasant Hill
reported that a cold front was heading into the Kansas City area. A
low-pressure system coming across the Dakotas was scheduled to hit
the metropolitan area today, bringing showers and thunderstorms,
said Leanne Vonqualen.
</P>
<P>
   Today's high should be about 10 degrees lower than we've seen in
the past several days, Vonqualen said. Sunday is likely to be about
the same, with a dip into the mid-80s by Monday, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``So that'll seem a lot cooler than it has been,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday could have things heating up again, she said, but added
that the worst might be over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're going to see a heat wave like now. We have
a chance of cooler temperatures.''
</P>
<P>
   The death toll from the heat rose to 28 across Missouri by
Friday afternoon. On Friday, two more people with heat-related
illnesses were reported in critical condition at Truman Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   At least three other deaths in the state -- in Boone and Greene
counties -- were possibly heat-related, but not confirmed. The
official count is of those ruled heat-related by a medical examiner
and reported to the state Department of Health.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri's count was the highest in the nation amid a heat wave
that has smothered the East and Midwest. St. Louis reported no new
deaths by Friday afternoon and the toll there remained at 14. There
was one heat-related death in Cape Girardeau County.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, there also was one heat-related death
in Jackson County, two in Cass County.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, family members and friends were mourning area heat
wave victims, including Medley, Steven Cook, Ralph Generaux and
Charles Dyer.
Willard Medley, 75
</P>
<P>
   Medley always lived life on his own terms, relatives said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always told him that if it got too hot, we would come get
him. But he was too proud to ask for help,'' grandson Casey
Clevenger said.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Kansas City, Medley traveled the world in the Navy and
as a truck driver. He lived in Carrollton, Mo., for a time and
returned to Kansas City in the early 1970s. He had lived in the
same house since.
</P>
<P>
   Medley was known as a wizard with his hands, fixing cars,
tinkering with appliances and pounding nails. He built the deck at
his home.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a jack-of-all-trades,'' grandson Larry Medley Jr.
recalled. ``We never had to call someone to fix something while
Grandpa was around.''
</P>
<P>
   But as Medley's eyesight and hearing started to fail, he found
it tougher to keep up his home. When Medley recently complained
about a high water bill, Clevenger discovered a basement pipe that
had burst weeks earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Melvin Anderson, Medley's next-door neighbor, said he feels
guilty about not investigating when he hadn't seen him for several
days. He had assumed everything was all right because he thought he
had heard Medley's air conditioning running.
</P>
<P>
   ``We should all keep an eye out for the older folks,'' he said.
``I know I'm going to make sure my family is taking care of my
grandmother in St. Louis. You never know when something can
happen.''
- MORE -
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
