<HEADER>
A0838 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-GOOD-NIGHT-WITCH     07-31 0356
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-GOOD-NIGHT-WITCH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE GOOD NIGHT WITCH 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Saturday, July 31:
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; This is the measure of phenomenal. Two weeks ago Friday, a little
$60,000 movie, produced by two filmmakers no one ever heard of,
starring three unknown actors and shot mainly in the woods outside
the tiny country town of Burkittsville, Md., opened in 27 theaters
around the country, from New York City to Orlando, from Orange
County, California, to Baltimore. It has no sex, no guns, no
visible violence. It is about the ``legendary'' Blair Witch, whom
no one ever sees, and the three aspiring young documentary
filmmakers who interview people in the town about her by day, and
then chase her through the dark woods with their cameras at night.
They die trying to capture her on film, one by one. By the end of
the first showing of the movie _ which is supposedly their
unfinished documentary, found after their disappearance in the
woods _ the teens and twentysomethings of America had found a scary
new thrill, and the witch had become a movie star.
</P>
<P>
   In 26 of those 27 theaters, including New York's, ``The Blair
Witch Project'' broke every previous attendance record. No one at
this point can explain its success, or knows what will happen as
the movie opens in 1,000 theaters across the nation this weekend.
There is reason to credit the Internet, on which the producers
began to put out the word 18 months ago. There is reason for
parents to be thankful that their children are drawn to a movie as
innocent as a ghost story told over a campfire at night. There is
reason to think that Burkittsville, where the town signs have
already been stolen for souvenirs, is about to be besieged.
</P>
<P>
   It hopes to take advantage. ``Hi, this is the Town Office,
Burkittsville, Maryland,'' callers to the mayor's office are told.
``If this is in regard to `The Blair Witch Project,' it is fiction.
However, we welcome you to our community, and you will see that we
have rich farmlands, mountains and a quaint village. Looking
forward to meeting you.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 0047EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
