<SLUG> BC-AUTO-REVIEW-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMFORT IS KING IN CONVERSION VAN
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB GOLFEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The big Ford van was cruising northward on Interstate 17, but
the boys in the back were busy having an adventure in outer space.
</P>
<P>
   Captain Picard was shouting or ders across the bridge of the
Starship Enterprise as the big, beefy 1999 conversion van roared up
the steep freeway grade north of Black Canyon City.
</P>
<P>
   An hour later (our time, not space time), we were parked in the
lot of a Camp Verde fast-food joint. Van shades drawn, the
dad-pilot joined the boys to eat burgers and watch the explosive
conclusion of Star Trek: Insurrection.
</P>
<P>
   A decidedly weird outing. And it was a jolt to watch the end of
the space movie, pop it out of the VCR, then draw the shades and
find ourselves surrounded by the bright sunlight of rural Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Though really, no weirder than watching The Waterboy on the
movie screen of a Boeing 747 flying at 30,000 feet in the middle of
the night.
</P>
<P>
   For many people, a conversion van is the vehicle of choice for
long-distance traveling. Not quite as commodious as the Starship
Enter prise, there's plenty of room in terms of modern-day
earthbound vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion van was a full-size, rear-drive Ford Econoline
panel van, the kind most often seen toting a plumber's business
supplies or delivering appliances. Once the converter gets done
with it, you'd hardly recognize its proletarian ori gins.
</P>
<P>
   This type of conversion van, sold complete at Ford dealerships,
is a Universal Luxury Conversion Van, made by the Glaval Corp. of
Elkhart, Ind. (It's the official con version-van company of NASCAR,
by the way, which essentially means you get a cool NASCAR sticker
in the rear windows.)
</P>
<P>
   And along with the plush seven-seater accommodations, wood trim
and extensive comfort and appear ance features, it comes with a
built-in television, complete with VCR and game ports for Sega,
Nintendo or Play Station.
</P>
<P>
   A kid's dream.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors recently fueled the debate about TVs in cars, and
whether family values were being heavily undermined, earlier this
year when it unveiled minivans that included optional built-in TV
sets.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever your feelings about either having kids joining Mom and
Dad on the open road or disappear ing into a video cocoon, the
point is that, for many families, this feature could spell the
difference between having a great trip or having a miserable trip.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the TV feature, the conversion van seems like the
most comfortable, painless way to take a long trip, especially if
you take them often. Riding up high in a luxury van is akin to
traveling by motor home or corporate jet.
</P>
<P>
   The seats on this Universal model are big, cushy affairs, more
like easy chairs than car seats. In some ways (especially with the
TV), they resemble living rooms on wheels, allowing various
configurations of the number and positions of the passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Big picture windows with shades, thick rugs, lots of cubbies and
plenty of cupholders are all part of the comfort mix. Every
passenger has loads of wiggle room in every direction.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the TV, our test vans were equipped with fabulous sur
round-sound stereo systems, some of the best I've heard in a
factory-equipped vehicle. For grown-ups, this is a much hotter
setup than the TV.
</P>
<P>
   All the components, including the trick rear seat that folds up
for additional cargo or flops flat into a double bed, seem
well-constructed and durable.
</P>
<P>
   One beef concerns the driver's seat power control, mounted awk
wardly in the front of the bottom cushion and looking tacked on
rather than properly integrated. Also, too much of the wood-tone
material on the dash and center console is of hard plastic, not
quite matching the real wood decorating the rear compartment.
</P>
<P>
   And the double rear doors, so handy for tradesmen, are awkward
for families and create a tangible blind spot in the center where
the doors meet, when seen through the rearview mirror.
</P>
<P>
   There were a few significant glitches on our test vans,
including one that had a rear AC unit that wasn't hooked up to the
vents and a TV that was wired incorrectly to the VCR.
</P>
<P>
   Two different types of Universal conversions were driven, one
with a high top and one with a standard roof line.
</P>
<P>
   The high-top, basically a fiber glass height extension, was
nicely finished in wood with an exotic recessed lighting system,
which gave the interior a spacious feel. A second rear-mounted
air-condition ing system provided cool air through ceiling vents, a
nice system for interior comfort.
</P>
<P>
   The low-top was not quite as jazzy, though comparably equipped,
including the rear AC. A big difference was that, instead the TV
being mounted up high (obviously, in back of the driver and
front-seat passenger), it was mounted on a console on the floor.
Two things are faulty about this TV mounting: It blocks passage
from the front seats, and the outboard passengers in the third
bench seat can't really see the screen.
</P>
<P>
   Either van is a nice driver, handling as well as possible for
such a heavy, basic sort of truck and responding well to throttle,
brake and steering inputs. The big Ford vans are a class act, and
the conversion equipment does nothing to take away from that.
</P>
<P>
   Both vans were equipped with Ford's strong 5.4-liter V-8, a
smooth, quiet-running engine that accelerates nicely and tackles
hills with ease.
</P>
<P>
   The Ford van has a base price of about $19,000, reaching $25,930
fully equipped for converting, in cluding $700 for the bigger
engine and $1,800 for the exterior-trim package, rear AC and remote
lock ing. Fully converted by Glaval, with an entire page of extras,
the price hits a substantial $43,000.
</P>
<P>
   There are a number of different configurations for these vans,
and some are undoubtedly less expen sive.
</P>
<P>
   Though the price of the conver sion van is not cheap, it is
compara ble to its main competition, Detroit's big luxury
sport-utility vehicles, such as the upscale Cadillac Esca lade and
Lincoln Navigator.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion van has much more a sense of being a vacation
machine, though, especially for those families who often venture
out into the far reaches of our home. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Ford/Universal &QL; 
Conversion Van &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Vehicle type: &QL; 
Seven passenger, multidoor van, rear-wheel drive. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Price as tested: &QL; 
$42,855. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Engine: &QL; 
5.4-liter V-8, 235 hp at 4,250 rpm, 335 lb.-ft. of torque at 3,000
rpm. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Transmission: &QL; 
Four-speed automatic. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wheelbase: &QL; 
138 inches. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EPA fuel economy: &QL; 
13 mpg city, 17 highway. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Highs: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Luxury comfort. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Load of features. &QL;
</P>
