<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILD-HEAT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMID HEAT WAVE, WILDLIFE DEALS WITH IT IN ODD WAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL GRAHAM  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Frogs are sneaking indoors and squirrels lie
panting in the shade.
</P>
<P>
   This heat blast doesn't feel any better to them than it does to
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're finding frogs in our buildings,'' said Nancy Honerkamp,
superintendent of Weston Bend State Park. ``We just had two in one
of our restrooms with water. They were green water frogs. I think
their puddle is gone.''
</P>
<P>
   Mother Nature's creatures adapt to the heat, but it troubles
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had squirrels lying on their bellies with their arms and
legs out in the shade, panting,'' said Lynn Youngblood Sloan,
director of the Burr Oak Nature Center in Blue Springs. ``They'll
lie there 15 to 20 minutes and when the ground warms under their
body, they take their front paws and pull themselves to a cool
place. Anything to get cool.''
</P>
<P>
   The squirrels are trying to digest a full meal after visiting
feeders at the Missouri Department of Conservation center. But the
heat keeps them and other critters from making it to their normal
tree perches for a post-meal nap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had doves lying in the grass and spreading their wings
out to cool off,'' Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   The heat may kill creatures already weak with disease or
advanced age, said Wendy Sangster, a Conservation Department
biologist.
</P>
<P>
   But most animals find shade and stay quiet during the daylight
hours, moving about to feed and drink at night or in the early
morning.
</P>
<P>
   Wildlife isn't as easily spotted because the animals seek
shelter from the heat. Deer and turkey that normally feed early and
late during daylight in fields at Burr Oak haven't been seen
lately, Sloan said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Honerkamp has seen deer and turkeys moving in fields in
full sunlight when the heat is most fierce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost like they're disoriented,'' she said. ``They may
be desperate to find water. It's possible they're moving to
watering holes they don't normally use.''
</P>
<P>
   Backyard trees may be strangely void of songbirds because
they're staying quiet to keep cool or seeking water.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of birds coming into my watering spots have their mouths
open and look like they're panting, they're thirsty,'' said Laura
Gray, director of the Martha Lafite Thompson Nature Sanctuary in
Liberty. ``It's the first time I've ever seen birds wait in line
for the bird bath.''
</P>
<P>
   People can help their backyard wildlife cope by making sure bird
baths are full or by placing additional containers of water outside
for animals.
</P>
<P>
   The heat does increase the chance for fish kills in ponds and
streams, said Dan Lekie, a biologist for the Kansas Department of
Wildlife and Parks, although few have been reported to date.
</P>
<P>
   ``Animals are better prepared to handle this than we are,''
Lekie said. ``They don't get used to air conditioning and then go
back into the heat. They're just there. They don't become dormant.
But they become more lackadaisical and do less and less.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 0110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
