<HEADER>
A0863 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOON-SHOEMAKER-AZR &LR;      07-31 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOON-SHOEMAKER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPACE GEOLOGIST GETS WISH FOR LUNAR BURIAL
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN STANLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eugene M. Shoemaker always wanted to go to the moon.
</P>
<P>
   This morning, he got his wish.
</P>
<P>
   The Lunar Prospector spacecraft was scheduled to crash into the
moon early Saturday, scattering the Arizona geologist's ashes
across the landscape he dearly loved.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gene is the first human to be laid to rest on another
celestial body,'' said Carolyn Porco, pro fessor of planetary
sciences at the University of Arizona. ``This puts a human face on
the heavens, and they will never again be the same.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunar Prospector was launched last year to orbit the moon and
map its surface. Knowing the craft would fall to the surface when
its fuel ran out, scientists placed Shoemaker's ashes aboard it as
a tribute to him. The plan angered some Navajos and other Native
Americans who hold strong taboos about death and consider the moon
sacred.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's crash landing, however, is no accident.
</P>
<P>
   An engineer in Texas came up with the idea of deliberately crash
ing the Lunar Prospector and ob serving the debris cloud to
determine whether there is water on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   Some scientists believe Prospec tor detected signs of water
frozen in the lunar soil. If so, that water may be used someday to
support manned lunar colonies.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker, a longtime Flagstaff resident, invented the field of
astro geology (space geology) in the 1960s. He trained astronauts
and led the team that examined the moon rocks brought to Earth by
the Apollo missions.
</P>
<P>
   He first made his reputation on Meteor Crater near Winslow in
1960, Porco said. Shoemaker's work proved the crater was the result
of a cosmic impact, rather than volcanic as everyone else had
assumed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gene made the connection be tween the heavens and the Earth in
a way no one had done before,'' said Porco, who worked with
Shoemaker on NASA's Voyager missions in the 1980s. ``He was a
pioneering fig ure, way ahead of everyone else. He almost
single-handedly convinced NASA to provide geological train ing for
astronauts. All the science we got from Apollo wouldn't have been
there without him.''
</P>
<P>
   And, she added, Shoemaker des perately longed to test his ideas
on the moon. Personally.
</P>
<P>
   It was not to be. In 1963, Shoemaker was diagnosed with a
medical condition that ended his dream of being an astronaut and
going to the moon.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the biggest disappoint ment of his life,'' Porco said.
</P>
<P>
   His dream lost, Shoemaker plunged into his work.
</P>
<P>
   David Levy, comet hunter and Parade magazine science editor,
discovered 13 comets with Gene and his wife, Carolyn. The most
famous was their find in 1993 that a comet had been ripped into
pieces by Jupiter's gravitational forces. Astronomers described the
chucks of comet as ``a string of pearls.''
</P>
<P>
   Comet Shoemaker-Levy 9 made headlines when astronomers realized
it would slam into Jupiter's atmos phere with the force of millions
of nuclear explosions. The cosmic col lision in July 1994 was
visible even in small telescopes.
</P>
<P>
   About an ounce of Shoemaker's remains were encapsulated in a
polycarbonate vial about the size of a lipstick container and
placed aboard the Prospector when it was launched in January 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The vials, made by Celestis Inc. of Houston, have carried the re
mains of 55 people into space, including Star Trek creator Gene
Roddenberry and 1960s LSD advo cate Timothy Leary. Leary was later
involved with the L-5 Society, an organization that advocated elabo
rate space cities orbiting the Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Shoemaker is the first to have his remains stay in space. The
others burned up as they re-entered Earth's atmosphere, like
meteors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gene was so dearly loved and admired. If anyone deserves this
honor, it's him,'' Porco said.
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone agrees.
</P>
<P>
   When Prospector was launched, Albert Hale, then Navajo tribal
chairman, said the plan to put Shoemaker's remains on the moon
showed ``gross insensitivity to Na tive American religious
values.''
</P>
<P>
   To the Navajo and some other Indian tribes, having anything to
do with the remains of a dead person is a major violation of tribal
traditions. It usually can be countered only by having expensive
ceremonies done by tribal medicine men.
</P>
<P>
   Hale, an attorney in private prac tice in Window Rock, didn't
know whether the tribe's medicine men planned a ceremony to restore
harmony, but recalled that they did so when it was discovered ashes
had been spread in the San Francisco Peaks, sacred to the Navajo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust the leadership to uphold our tradition,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Porco and Levy don't understand Hale's concerns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never dreamed anyone would be offended by this,'' Porco
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the moon belongs to everybody,'' Levy said.
</P>
<P>
   Porco came up with the idea of a ``space burial'' for Shoemaker
while reading an account of his death in an auto accident in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``It just hit me,'' she said. ``So, I got on the phone
immediately. I selected the epigraph and had it laser engraved on
brass foil.''
</P>
<P>
   The epigraph is from Romeo and Juliet:
</P>
<P>
   And, when he shall die,
</P>
<P>
   Take him and cut him out in little stars,
</P>
<P>
   And he will make the face of heaven so fine
</P>
<P>
   That all the world will be in love with night,
</P>
<P>
   And pay no worship to the garish sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those words just seemed a perfect fit, as inspirational as
Gene was,'' Porco said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a scientific purpose for this crash,'' Levy said.
``We're hoping to find evidence of water on the moon. But whether
we do or not is secondary to the attempt. . . . If he were alive, I
know he'd be pleased.'' &QL; 
John Stanley can be reached at (602) 444-4414 or at
john.stanley &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
