<HEADLINE>
HEAT WAVE BRINGS MEMORIES OF KC'S TERRIBLE YEAR OF 1980 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BRIAN BURNES  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- In 1980 the heat was almost biblical.
</P>
<P>
   Crops browned over. Fish floated dead on the surface of Swope
Park Lagoon. And Kansas City area residents fell as if stricken by
plague.
</P>
<P>
   As of Friday, officials had attributed the deaths of 13 Kansas
City area residents to the heat.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, 176 died of it.
</P>
<P>
   Through Thursday, the Kansas City area had endured six straight
days of triple-digit readings downtown. But starting on July 4,
1980, temperatures topped 100 for 17 straight days downtown.
</P>
<P>
   It represented the worst heat wave in 44 years.
</P>
<P>
   Residents -- mostly those without air conditioning -- fled to
malls, libraries or pools. But in some tragic instances, they
remained behind locked doors and windows as their dwellings became
ovens.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the 1980 heat wave's principal legacy today is a
heightened awareness of the dangers of prolonged heat, especially
on the indigent and elderly living alone.
</P>
<P>
   But that year's heat, unlike a flood or a high wind, was a
cumulative disaster that seemed to sneak up on the city.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Biery, then director of the Kansas City Health
Department, said the heat's timing was terrible.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes about two weeks for the human body to acclimatize to
go through that transition,'' Biery said. ``But this hit us in
early July. People were still thinking `spring' and suddenly they
were in the middle of 105-degree days.''
The worst weekend
</P>
<P>
   Between 7 a.m. and noon July 11, 1980, officials found 12
victims. The worst weekend may have been July 12-13, when as many
as 15 bodies jammed the 22-by-22-foot freezer in the county morgue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember that it was just one body after another, most of
them elderly people, and by the time they got to us they were
decomposing,'' said Bonita Peterson, then Jackson County medical
examiner and now an independent pathologist.
</P>
<P>
   The scene of death was almost exclusively indoors.
</P>
<P>
   During a 1936 heat wave, Kansas Citians had escaped to the
outdoors. Before the arrival of air conditioning, residents formed
overnight communities during vast sleep-ins in open spaces like
Swope Park.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, many of the city's older and indigent residents stayed
inside.
</P>
<P>
   One factor was economic. The death rate in 1980, a study later
suggested, was some 10 times higher among people in lower-income
brackets. They often were apartment dwellers, often without air
conditioning.
</P>
<P>
   Still, some of the dead had fans or air conditioners they didn't
use.
</P>
<P>
   ``People apparently just thought they could tough it through, or
not spend their pension money on utilities,'' Biery said.
</P>
<P>
   In July 1980, Kansas City Power &AMP; Light customers used more than
twice the current they had the previous July.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor in the deaths was fear of crime.
</P>
<P>
   One newspaper reporter, accompanying the crew of a mortuary
transport firm, noticed how windows in the apartments of the
deceased often were locked or sealed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of them had their windows nailed shut,'' said Gerald
Hoff, a Kansas City Health Department epidemiologist.
</P>
<P>
   Isolation also caused people to die.
</P>
<P>
   ``Older people tend not to ask for help, they tend to be
isolated and don't always have family around to check on them,''
said Roger Coleman, executive director of the Westport Allen
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result, it's very easy for them not to know what is
happening to them, or why they are not feeling well.''
</P>
<P>
   Daytime high temperatures downtown proved the manifestation of
monotony: 103 degrees on July 4, 103 again on July 5.
</P>
<P>
   The daytime peaks may not have been the more deadly, officials
later speculated. It was the high nighttime temperatures, and the
lack of any respite, that apparently discouraged many.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was not just an ordinary hot summer in Kansas City,'' Biery
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was unusual was that the nights stopped cooling down. We
noticed that we didn't really have a rising death rate until the
official evening temperatures did not go below 85 for the third day
in a row.''
</P>
<P>
   From July 8 through July 11, inclusive, low temperatures stayed
between 85 to 89 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I became convinced it was a psychological factor,'' Biery
said. ``We had anecdotal information that people just sort of gave
up at night after the third day.''
A deadly trend
</P>
<P>
   Across the country 1,265 persons died from the heat wave and
drought.
</P>
<P>
   Missouri had the greatest number of deaths with 311, while
Kansas had 72. Missouri Gov. Joseph Teasdale declared a state of
emergency on July 14, alerting National Guard units and asking for
federal funds to purchase fans and air conditioners.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, social service agencies did what they could,
providing meals, fans and other assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember delivering ice and fans, particularly to those who
were in walk-up apartments,'' said Jim Nunnelly, then chief
administrator of the Samuel U. Rodgers Community Health Center on
the city's East Side. ``I also remember clearing a room and
allowing elderly people who wanted to come inside the building and
beat the day's sun.''
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Police Department established a heat wave
command center. Before disbanding on July 25, it handled more than
10,000 calls for information and assistance.
</P>
<P>
   In the Kansas City area, two-thirds of those dead had been
white, one-third black. A slight preponderance were women.
</P>
<P>
   But the demographic group that seemed to suffer the most was the
under-informed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today there is a much higher awareness,'' said Coleman. ``It
seems that 15 minutes of the news every night is devoted to the
weather. TV is constantly bombarding people on how to take care of
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Peterson: ``That wasn't true at the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
