<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 01:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0887 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CELTIC-MUSIC-KAN &LR;      07-31 1209
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELTIC-MUSIC-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY SINGER TRACES OLD `AMERICAN' SONGS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE POPPER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was late afternoon on July 4th when, without fanfare or
announcement, Connie Dover, one of America's finest interpreters of
Celtic music, stood before some 50 of her friends and neighbors in
the front yard of a Platte County, Mo., farmhouse.
</P>
<P>
   And there she sang an old song.
</P>
<P>
   The water is wide,
</P>
<P>
   I cannot cross o'er ...
</P>
<P>
   Her style that day was piercingly simple, unembellished by the
lilting grace notes that often mark the Celtic ballads for which
she is best known.
</P>
<P>
   Beside her on a folding chair sat Phil Cunningham, a Scottish
musician and recording producer.
</P>
<P>
   He accompanied Dover on the accordion, his chording as spare and
evocative as the distant droning of a lone bagpipe melded with the
wind.
</P>
<P>
   When Dover was done, she was greeted not by cheers but rather by
a collective sigh, as if she had touched something deeper and more
connective than simple appreciation.
</P>
<P>
   And then she and Cunningham bade farewell. For early the next
day they were heading south to a recording studio near Nashville,
Tenn., to do the final ``mix'' on Dover's fourth solo album, a
recording that marks a significant departure for her.
</P>
<P>
   Her previous albums were all recorded in Scotland and reflected
her fascination with the music she found there and in Ireland.
</P>
<P>
   But Dover chose to record her latest album in this country. For
it is a unique song collection that traces the evolution of Celtic
music on the American frontier.
</P>
<P>
   `` `The Water is Wide' is a good example,'' she said recently.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a ballad that almost everyone knows, though they're not
sure how or when they learned it. It's part of a musical tradition
we all seem to share. It's considered an American song, and indeed
it is now, but it was actually born across the seas.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the ballad made its first published appearance in
Edinburgh, and initially told of a Scottish noblewoman falsely
accused of adultery and left heartbroken and alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``That story has disappeared in the American version,'' Dover
said. ``But what's left are the deeper expressions of longing, love
and sorrow that derived from it. We lost the narrative along the
way, but we kept the core.''
Old, new country
</P>
<P>
   Dover first conceived of this special album, titled ``The Border
of Heaven,'' more than 10 years ago. And she was uniquely prepared
to undertake the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raised in Arkansas and Missouri; I studied at Oxford;
I've recorded in Scotland, and I've worked on a Wyoming cattle
ranch,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Dover, who grew up in Kansas City, experienced her first real
immersion in Celtic culture when she spent her junior college year
studying history at Oxford University.
</P>
<P>
   While in Great Britain, she took special tutorials in the
British ballad tradition and traveled repeatedly to Scotland to
research old songs.
</P>
<P>
   Not long after her return home, she achieved local fame as the
lead singer for the Kansas City-based band called Scartaglen.
</P>
<P>
   But her wide-ranging interests and intense wanderlust led her
constantly into new musical territory. In 1992, for example, she
met the renowned cowboy balladeer Skip Gorman on a Wyoming cattle
drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a trail cook, and Skip was out there singing and
collecting songs,'' she said. ``We started singing together for
fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd sing an old song I'd found in Oxford, and Skip would say,
`You know, that reminds me of a cowboy tune.' And he'd sing it, and
we'd both marvel at the similarity. The more we sang together, the
more we understood how connected the musical forms truly are.''
</P>
<P>
   On Dover's new recording, scheduled for release this winter, she
and Gorman sing ``The Streets of Laredo'' together.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America, you hear that melody and think of a dusty Texas
cow town,'' Dover said.
</P>
<P>
   But in its first incarnation, the song told not of a doomed
cowboy but of a young sailor dying of syphilis in a London
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tracing its evolution, you find that an old Irish ballad was
transmuted to meet the needs of people who found themselves in a
different world,'' Dover said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In America there are versions that tell of miners, loggers and
gamblers, all dying young, regretful and alone. Only the melody and
the common thread of loss and melancholy remain.''
</P>
<P>
   As the project matured in Dover's mind, she went to Scotland
again to research ballads at the University of Edinburgh's School
of Scottish Studies.
</P>
<P>
   She began haunting antiquarian book shops throughout the British
Isles and the United States, seeking old ballad collections. She
roamed across America, tracing various versions of the songs she'd
found abroad.
</P>
<P>
   She spent days at the public library in Miles City, Mont., and
then scoured the McCracken Research Collection at the Buffalo Bill
Historical Center in Cody, Wyo.
</P>
<P>
   And as she repeatedly discovered American counterparts for
numerous old Celtic songs, she felt a deepening sense of
rootedness.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important not to feel random in this world,'' she said.
``But instead to feel the significant ties we share to the past and
to each other. This work has been a way for me to feel my own place
in a long series of human connections.''
Evicted, betrayed
</P>
<P>
   In her research, Dover came across the story of an 18th-century
bagpiper who joined thousands of other Scots fleeing eviction,
famine and English oppression as the Highlands were ``cleared'' to
make way for sheep.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1773, the piper, along with some 200 others,
boarded a rotting hulk bound for Nova Scotia.
</P>
<P>
   But the piper was penniless, and the ship owners ordered him
ashore. His countrymen, however, took up a collection to pay his
fare and then shared their own meager rations with him throughout
the long voyage.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how important their music was to them,'' Dover said.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving in Nova Scotia, the Highlanders proudly disembarked,
wearing their tartans and marching behind their picked piper. But
they faced a cruel surprise. They had been promised land that did
not exist, and 122 starved to death that winter.
</P>
<P>
   Moved by the story, Dover sought a song to reflect the
experience of dislocation and loss associated with emigration -- a
song to begin her album.
</P>
<P>
   She found it in Nova Scotia with the aid of Rosemary McCormack,
a Gaelic scholar and folklorist.
</P>
<P>
   In English it is titled ``The Blessing,'' and its narrator sings
of friends who have forever left their Scottish homeland.
</P>
<P>
   Farewell to you and Goodnight to you,
</P>
<P>
   Goodnight to you and blessings go with you ...
</P>
<P>
   Dover's rendition on the album is as direct and unadorned as was
her singing on July 4th. It is a heartfelt simplicity that
represents her recognition of a profound historical process.
</P>
<P>
   ``When people are forced to strip their existence down to its
bare bones and divest themselves of everything they can't carry,
they still have their songs and memories,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And as a song is passed down from person to person, from
generation to generation, it is only the essence that survives. And
that essence is often as stark and haunting as the half-forgotten
past.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
