<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-KOSOVO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PERILOUS PEACE IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If it is true that Washington and its NATO allies stumbled into
an unwanted war for Kosovo, it is equally true that the victors
have stumbled into a treacherous stewardship of postwar Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Peace, of course, is better than war, but Kosovo is still cursed
with killing, looting, destruction of artistic treasures,
unaccountable people in power, and a well-meaning but ungainly
civil administration run by the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The basic concept of Kosovo as a temporary protectorate in the
care of NATO peacekeeping soldiers and UN administrators is
beginning to look like an unworkable contradiction. Because the
international custodians have left ambiguous the crucial question
of who will govern a territory that still belongs to Serbia only in
the most technical sense, the province is being taken over,
undemocratically, by the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   This de facto takeover by the men with guns has been made easier
because the UN has been characteristically slow to dispatch the
international policemen promised.
</P>
<P>
   Even when the police arrive, the most they can be expected to do
is limit the revenge killings of Serbs and the looting of their
property. They will not be able to prevent the KLA from exercising
power within the society of Albanian Kosovars.
</P>
<P>
   When the 5,000 UN civil administrators arrive, they are to
collect taxes and customs duties and administer Kosovo's utilities,
public health, education, communications, and reconstruction. These
UN administrators are to hire both Serb and Albanian employees.
Already, Albanian Kosovars are complaining that the first UN
officials are perpetuating the kinds of unfairness the Albanians
suffered under the defeated Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   The primary goal of the international community should be to
foster true democratic governance by Kosovars, preventing Kosovo
from becoming a replica of Albania's bandit state. Then the
question of whether Kosovo will be an autonomous province or an
independent state should be addressed squarely. And the sooner UN
administrators terminate their protectorate, the better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 0152EDT &QL; 
