<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0037 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 01:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0902 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-DOCTORS-BOS     07-31 0368
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-DOCTORS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A DOCTORS' BILL OF RIGHTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, August 1, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The matter of how doctors should conduct themselves in relation
to their patients was supposed to have been settled some 24
centuries ago by one of the fathers of medicine, Hippocrates. Part
of the Hippocratic oath that doctors swear to uphold even to this
day says: ``I will prescribe regimen for the good of my patients
according to my ability and my judgment and never do harm.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet who has not heard doctors lamenting that harm is being done
day in and day out by health plan bookkeepers who are denying care
to patients and overruling what doctors recommend?
</P>
<P>
   Heretofore the evidence has been largely anecdotal, but a recent
survey conducted by the Harvard School of Public Health and the
Kaiser Family Foundation found that nearly 90 percent of the
physicians interviewed reported care denials from health
maintenance organizations and that two-thirds of these denials
caused serious harm. Half said such denials had caused a decline in
the overall health of their patients.
</P>
<P>
   Managed care came as a way of controlling skyrocketing health
costs, and HMOs are here to stay. Happily for New Englanders, the
National Committee on Quality Assurance's annual report on the
industry says the Bay State's HMOs are the best in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it is the doctor who knows best what is best for the
patient. Although excessive or unnecessary medical procedures
should be and will be discouraged, doctors should not be asked to
acquiesce in doing harm to their patients.
</P>
<P>
   Congress is now debating a patients' bill of rights, and the
Kaiser Family Foundation's Drew Altman got it right when he said:
``This study shows that whether you're for the Republican or
Democratic approaches, there's a need to reduce the disputes
between health professionals and health plans and a need for a
mechanism to resolve these disputes.''
</P>
<P>
   What is called for is a doctors' bill of rights that will
protect the caregivers of this country from being forced to break
their oath, which was in force long before managed care.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 0153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 01:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0904 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDITORIAL-ASSASSINS-B     07-31 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-ASSASSINS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SCHOOL OF THE ASSASSINS' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since the CIA masterminded a coup against the government of
Guatemala in 1954, the human rights record of the United States in
Latin America has too often been a shameful one. One of the most
notorious symbols of this is the Army's School of the Americas,
which trains Latin American soldiers. It ought to have been closed
long ago, and a proposal sponsored by Representative J. Joseph
Moakley and approved in the House this week will, it is to be
hoped, bring that day closer.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was in El Salvador a couple of years ago, I was often
asked `How can you keep that school open?' '' Moakley said. ``They
called it the `School of the Assassins.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Moakley led a congressional investigation into the murders of
six Jesuits in El Salvador in 1989. Nineteen of 26 soldiers
implicated in the deaths were graduates of the school. So were
those who plotted the murders of Archbishop Oscar Romero and four
American nuns; Peruvian officers convicted of murdering nine
students; and scores of others implicated in human rights abuses.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, instructors used manuals that included information
about paying bounties for enemy dead, false imprisonment, and the
use of truth serum. Because of a US fixation on anticommunism, the
school had little regard for human rights.
</P>
<P>
   The school has since changed its focus to instructing soldiers
in drug interdiction. There are enough human rights dangers here to
question whether that training should be done, let alone at a place
with a vile reputation. Moakley is not opposed to the notion of
some sort of training, but definitely not at the School of the
Americas.
</P>
<P>
   Moakley took up leadership on this cause from former US
representative Joseph Kennedy. Senator Edward Kennedy will shepherd
the proposal through the Senate. The measure would not close the
school but would prevent the Army from paying students to attend
and would send a strong signal that the school should be shut for
good.
</P>
<P>
   Latin America is enjoying a resurgence of democracy, and the
United States should nurture these fragile governments to maturity.
Closing the school would show that the United States is ready to
live up to its ideals throughout the hemisphere.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 0154EDT &QL; 
