<HEADER>
A0908 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-DIAMONDBA     07-31 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-DIAMONDBACKS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS MAKE ALL THE WRONG MOVES IN LOSS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kevin Brown threw 115 pitches. It was enough for
23 outs, and apparently no more.
</P>
<P>
   With the Los Angeles Dodgers holding a four-run lead and an
Arizona runner on second, Dodgers manager Davey Johnson opted for
his makeshift bullpen rather than his $105 million stud.
</P>
<P>
   Five batters later, pinch-hitter Greg Colbrunn doubled in two
runs off Jeff Shaw and Arizona had the lead. The Diamondbacks went
on to win 6-5 Friday in yet another example of how everything the
Dodgers touch eventually turns to mush.
</P>
<P>
   Brown pitched 72/3 innings. He allowed five hits and two runs,
but watched as the Diamondbacks scored five times in the eighth to
deprive the right-hander of his 12th win.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Pedro Borbon walked his only batter and Shaw (2-4) blew
his second straight save opportunity after only blowing one through
his first 21 chances.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing the Dodgers try these days works. They held a bonfire in
the bullpen once to exorcise the demons and came away with nothing.
They've rearranged the lineup, and nothing. They've tried playing
with the stockings pulled up to their knees, and nothing.
</P>
<P>
   So as the non-waiver trading period ticks down to its 9 p.m.
deadline today, the Dodgers expect nothing to happen.
</P>
<P>
   General manager Kevin Malone will be tempted to deal one of his
prized young starters _ Ismael Valdes, Chan Ho Park or Darren
Dreifort. But the Dodgers' decision makers say it's unlikely
anything will happen.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing, it seems, can turn around the season. Nothing can make
it end soon enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've reiterated to Kevin that he really needs to look
long-term,'' Dodgers CEO and president Bob Graziano said. ``He's
going to look at what's going to improve the club long-term _ not
just dumping payroll or just making us better for the rest of this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   It's that philosophy that's kept this past week quiet at Chavez
Ravine. (Bad baseball has kept it quiet for the season.)
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers actively shopped first baseman Eric Karros, pitcher
Carlos Perez and second baseman Eric Young, who is now on the
disabled list and can't be traded. But the interest was in the
three pitchers, with whom the Dodgers don't want to part with
unless they are blown away by an offer.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, offers for Dreifort, Valdes and Park haven't been up
to the Dodgers' liking so far.
</P>
<P>
   ``There doesn't seem to be any moves available to get better,''
said Malone, who's also hampered by expensive, multiyear contracts.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Dodgers (45-58) will probably elect to keep their
current course. Not the one that has them hopelessly floundering
near the bottom of the division, but the one of building the farm
system and scouting department so they aren't reliant on free
agents and trades. Done correctly, the farm system supports the
major-league club when injuries occur and provides prospects that
can set up in-season trades for playoff pushes in years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our philosophy is going to remain consistent,'' Malone said.
``Our focus is on building, and in scouting and in development.''
</P>
<P>
   While Malone said he still believes something could happen to
turn around the season and thrust the Dodgers back into playoff
contention, the reality is they are 12{ games out of a postseason
spot with 59 games remaining. The math isn't flattering.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see (a deal) happening,'' Johnson said. ``Recently, I
had discussions with Kevin, I always talk with him, about
personnel. In certain areas, especially in the pitching end of it,
unless you get some of it back, (it's tough to part with it).''
</P>
<P>
   So Graziano and Malone and Johnson agree it doesn't make much
sense to make a deal now just for the sake of trying to save an
irretrievable season when the cost may be next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know this season hasn't gone according to plan,'' Malone
said. ``If we can get better now, to help us get better for the
future, we'll probably look to improve.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
