<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 02:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0926 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-MERCEDES-LADN     07-31 0686
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS ON BRINK OF REGAINING NO. 1
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Pete Sampras sits on the cusp of tennis history
and talks about a change of priorities.
</P>
<P>
   By beating eighth-seeded Wayne Ferreira of South Africa 4-6,
6-3, 6-3 Friday in the quarterfinals of the Mercedes-Benz Cup at
UCLA, Sampras needs only to beat qualifier James Sekulov in today's
1 p.m. semifinal to take over the world's No. 1 ranking again.
</P>
<P>
   By doing so, he would set the mark for being No.1 for 271 weeks,
breaking Ivan Lendl's record.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here was the second-seeded Sampras on Friday, happy that he
ended a four-match losing streak to Ferreira but talking about how
being No. 1 is no longer as important as it has been the past six
years, when he finished the year No. 1 each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Don't get me wrong, I still love being No. 1,'' he said. ``But
to stay No. 1, unfortunately, you have to eat, live and breathe
tennis, especially if you want to stay there. You're dealing with a
lot of factors off the court.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the year, I got pretty comfortable with what it takes to
be No. 1 .... Earlier this year, I tried to figure out what my
priorities were.''
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, top-seeded and defending champion Andre Agassi
earned a semifinal berth when his opponent, seventh-seeded Lleyton
Hewitt of Australia, retired with a sprained left ankle with Agassi
leading 5-4 in the first set. Agassi next meets another Australian,
Andrew Ilie, tonight at 7:30.
</P>
<P>
   Small injuries last year started Sampras on his personal
inventory. He missed L.A. last year to have a wart removed from his
foot. He injured his left quadricep in the U.S. Open semifinal loss
to Patrick Rafter. He withdrew from a tournament in Lyon with a
back injury.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year he skipped the Australian Open because playing
the final seven weeks of the 1998 season in Europe to finish No. 1
was too much.
</P>
<P>
   In the recent Davis Cup Sampras played only doubles, yet still
enjoyed the experience of competing for his country. In other
words, enjoy watching Sampras play now because he might not enter
as many tournaments next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to play more Davis Cup in the future,'' he said. ``Of
course, the Slams will always be a pinnacle of my year. (But) the
big thing is to play more Davis Cup. In other years, it was hard to
give that commitment to being No. 1 and playing Davis Cup.''
</P>
<P>
   With his future plans firmly set, Sampras went out Friday and
played what he said was his best match against Ferriera, whom he
hadn't beaten since 1995 on clay at Hamburg, Germany.
</P>
<P>
   Although he lost the first set, Sampras felt he was playing
well, charging the net more and getting 59 percent of his first
serves in.
</P>
<P>
   ``In all the times we played, that was the best he's played,''
Ferreira said. ``He was more aggressive, chipping and coming in a
lot more, which he never did.''
</P>
<P>
   Hewitt didn't give himself a chance to catch Agassi. He reached
for a shot but came up short, spraining his ankle in the process.
He stayed down for more than 10 minutes before walking over to the
sideline to get his ankle taped. He tried to hit a few balls in
practice but decided he couldn't continue.
</P>
<P>
   He was to have his ankle X-rayed Friday night at UCLA Medical
Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm disappointed,'' he said in a statement. ``The injury came
at a really bad time. Hopefully, it will heal in the next couple of
days and be ready for the Canadian Open.''
</P>
<P>
   Agassi said he didn't see Hewitt's injury because, satisfied
Hewitt wasn't going to get the shot, he had turned away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I certainly didn't think it was a good idea to continue the
match,'' Agassi said. ``You risk yourself to a possible different
injury, let alone injuring something else.''
</P>
<P>
   Sampras continues today against Sekulov, who wants to beat
Sampras so Sekulov's countryman, Rafter, can retain the world's top
ranking for a second week.
</P>
<P>
   As if Sampras needed any more motivation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks for telling me,'' he said. ``I'll go to sleep thinking
about it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
