<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DAY-TRADING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAY TRADERS LIVE ON THE EDGE IN CYBERSPACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURBANK, Calif. _ Tom Pothoff's workday starts at the bleary
hour of 5:30 a.m. His mind and his instincts had better be sharp.
His livelihood depends on it.
</P>
<P>
   Pothoff has about an hour to digest the day's financial news and
decide which way the Wall Street wind is blowing before he hunkers
down for his daily ride on a financial roller coaster.
</P>
<P>
   Pothoff earns his living as a day trader, a profession where a
long-term hold on a stock can last all of 45 minutes. Guess wrong,
blink or take a coffee break, and large chunks of cash can vanish
into cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times when I buy a stock and my heart will just
start pounding,'' Pothoff said Friday after the market had closed.
``There is stress obviously, but it's not like people are ready to
do something drastic. If they had a losing trade, it's all part of
the game. Hopefully you win more than you lose.''
</P>
<P>
   It's also a little uncomfortable now for some in this profession
awash in the harsh spotlight of tragedy. Its most notorious
practitioner has become Mark O. Barton, a former day trader who
killed 12 people in Atlanta, including his wife and their two
children, and then killed himself Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Nine victims were shot at two day-trading brokerages. The
killings have focused national attention on the high-stakes,
frantic practice of trading stocks online, most of the time from
home but many times from offices across the country just like the
ones Barton ambushed.
</P>
<P>
   It's a relatively new profession, fueled by the speed and access
of the Internet. In it, practitioners try to amass profits by
trading stocks based on minute-by-minute changes in prices. Trades
take seconds, which is how long it can take for small fortunes to
be made and lost even though the price may shift only by pennies.
</P>
<P>
   Brokerage industry estimates say individual traders can
sometimes account for up to 25 percent of a day's stock market
activity.
</P>
<P>
   The peaks can be very high.
</P>
<P>
   And the valleys very low.
</P>
<P>
   A letter left behind by Barton suggested he was depressed about
trading losses, police said Friday. Barton, a former chemist, had
lost roughly $105,000 in stock trading in less than two months.
</P>
<P>
   The industry appeared to be aware of the stresses associated
with day trading before Barton went on his killing spree.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the National Association of Securities Dealers
board approved a rule that would require online brokerage services
to screen customers to determine whether they are suited to the
lightning-fast daily trading style.
</P>
<P>
   ``With day trading, there's no quicker way to stare into the
abyss of your soul,'' said Joey Anuff, a San Francisco day trader
and editor of Suck.com, a Web site owned by Lycos that focuses
attention on bad Web sites. ``A day trader's life is always about
the deal they missed or a stock they got stuck with.''
</P>
<P>
   Anuff is writing a book, ``Dumb Money: Confessions of a Day
Trader,'' that he says will be published in September by Random
House. He says that day trading can be a stressful occupation.
</P>
<P>
   It seems to attract people who like being drawn to the edge,
where the abyss can be filled with profits or financial ruin.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an extreme activity,'' Anuff said. ``You have to operate
from a mind set of total confidence without any hesitation. If you
hesitate, you're dead. And you have to face the fact that the
problem is you. You'll never be able to blame your losses on anyone
else.''
</P>
<P>
   But you can't just log on and start trading.
</P>
<P>
   Day traders typically lease software that facilitates this type
of electronic commerce for about $300 a month. An investment in
high-speed Internet access and powerful personal computers are also
musts.
</P>
<P>
   So is an investment of at least $5,000 in an account with
companies that support electronic day trading.
</P>
<P>
   Pothoff, for example, monitors two computer screens full of
financial information, business news shows and a chat room for day
traders.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, his initial assessment told him the trading day
would not be good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were down 18 points below fair value, which meant it was
going to be a pretty bloody day,'' he said, referring to a
calculation day traders use to assess whether the market will be
gaining or losing ground. ``It started off pretty bad and continued
throughout the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Pothoff did not like the signals the market was sending on
Friday, so he did not make any trades. Nevertheless, it was still a
workday filled with a constant rush.
</P>
<P>
   That's a little bit too much excitement for Phillip Soufer. He
tried day trading and didn't like it. Now he's a position trader,
holding onto stocks for a longer period of time than day traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like a few days or a few weeks to be more prepared. It's a
lot more dangerous to day trade because you have to be more precise
with your timing. It's a lot more stressful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The stress doesn't bother Abbie Zands. He trades by the minute
and then runs a party rental equipment company after the market
closes.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, there is a risk. But then that's part of the attraction,
too, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely grates on you,'' he said of day trading. ``You
just treat people around you different depending on how you did
that day. It's hard not to take what you are doing during the day
and displace it on your loved one. But you've got to take
responsibility for your actions and no one else.''
</P>
<P>
   Zands made two trades on Friday. They went the right way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should be a decent weekend,'' he said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
