<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-TWINS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAINING ANGELS KEEP ON LOSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The locker to Gary DiSarcina's left was once
occupied by Dave Hollins. To his right was the empty locker of
Randy Velarde. And it made the Anaheim Angels shortstop pause for a
moment Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I've got cooties,'' DiSarcina said.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina, though, is well aware of the harsh reality for teams
that have fallen out of the pennant race before the trading
deadline. Teams will trade proven and productive veterans for young
and talented prospects. And in doing that, the front office is
calling this season a wash.
</P>
<P>
   While Hollins was sent away months ago, Velarde and pitcher Omar
Olivares were traded to the Oakland A's Thursday for three
minor-leaguers. Pitcher Chuck Finley could be sent to the Yankees
or Indians any minute now, with the trading deadline coming tonight
at 9 (PDT). Reliever Shigetoshi Hasegawa also has drawn interest
from teams.
</P>
<P>
   With all the trade talk, there was plenty of action in the
clubhouse before Friday's night's game between the Angels and
Minnesota Twins. And that was more than the Angels could say about
the game, a 3-1 loss before a fireworks-show-anticipating crowd of
38,319 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Twins pitcher Brad Radke threw a complete-game, seven-hitter.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels have now lost 13 of their past 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   The only good news for the Angels was that starter Ken Hill went
61/3 innings and allowed only one run and six hits. But all that
means is he is another candidate to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   As for Velarde and Olivares, DiSarcina was sad to see them go,
especially Velarde, his double-play partner. But he added: ``I'm
happy to see them go to a winning team.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Angels are not a winning team really seems to tick off
first baseman Mo Vaughn. Vaughn, who signed a six-year, $80 million
contract and was counted on to put the team over the top, was
animated during a clubhouse conversation that turned the heads of
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have an opinion on (the Velarde/Olivares
trade),'' Vaughn said. ``The main thing this team has to focus on
is to get ready for the first day of spring training.... My concern
is seeing what's left after the season and making sure the
attitude's straight.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, what's here in February is important. My concern is
not September, it's February. That's when we'll be able to make a
better evaluation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
