<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YANKEES-RED </SLUG>
 SOX-BOS  
 YANKEES TROUNCE RED SOX
 &HT;    (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Face-saving in the Fens took a flier early for the Red
Sox Friday night, from the moment the Olde Towne Team took the
field against the Yankees and heard boos from a Yawkey Way mob
(33,777) that brought their Bronx cheers with them.
</P>
<P>
   It only got worse from there, as Sox starter Mark Portugal put
his name in the history books by giving up home runs to the first
two Yankee batters, Chuck Knoblauch and Derek Jeter, then added
redundancy to the list of Sox insults by literally falling flat on
his face before the first inning was over.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, too, was the night, as the Sox made two errors in the
second inning, when the Yankees scored four more times, then
surrendered three more runs in the third en route to a 13-3
spanking that dropped Boston back into third place, a half-game
behind Toronto and 7 1/2 games behind the Bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've given up leadoff home runs before, but not back-to-back,
right out of the chute,'' said Portugal, who lasted just four outs
in his shortest stint in nearly three years and tied an American
League record when he was taken deep by Knoblauch and Jeter.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch hit Portugal's second pitch of the game into the
left-center-field screen for a 1-0 Yankee lead. Jeter, who has
reached base in 98 of the 100 games in which he has played, hit
Portugal's fifth pitch into the center-field bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   The home runs by the game's first two batters tied an AL record,
which has been done 25 times in all, three times this season. The
Yankees hadn't done it in 44 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a horse (fertilizer) day at the ballpark,'' said
Portugal, who also did a full gainer off the rubber when his right
foot gave way while he was delivering a pitch to Chili Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``One game, forget about it, and go out and kick Roger's butt
tomorrow _ hopefully.''
</P>
<P>
   Portugal's allusion to Clemens was a reminder that the heavy
artillery is still to come Saturday afternoon on national TV, when
the former Sox ace makes his premier appearance in pinstripes on
Yawkey Way.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees may not bear the greatest-team-ever tag they wore
last season, when they won 114 regular-season games, but they're
still on pace to win 99 this season. As if that isn't bad enough
for the We-Hate-New York faction, consider this: The Mets moved
into first place in the National League East Friday night, making
this the latest point in a season the Yanks and Mets have led their
respective divisions.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch had five hits, matching a career high, Jorge Posada
doubled twice and homered, and Scott Brosius had three hits for the
Yankees, who pounded out 16 hits six days after a 21-run, 21-hit
salute against the Cleveland Indians in Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees had lost two straight in the blast furnace that
doubled as Chicago's Comiskey Park the last two nights, but
recovered behind Hideki Irabu, who surrendered John Valentin's home
run off the Coke bottles and a fly ball by Troy O'Leary misplayed
into a double by left fielder Shane Spencer in the first, then held
the Sox to four hits the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if they felt a little cooler tonight than in the
last couple of days,'' Yankees manager Joe Torre said, ``but they
seemed a little lighter, a little livelier.''
</P>
<P>
   The Bombers were still showing life during their last at-bat,
when fill-in outfielder Chad Curtis had to be restrained from Sox
reliever Mark Guthrie, who already had taken a bullet for the team
by absorbing a four-run seventh inning, which jacked his ERA to
6.44.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said to me, `Why are you taking them, swing at the ball,'
'' Curtis said of his exchange with Guthrie. ``Then he called me a
few choice words.
</P>
<P>
   ``At that moment, I was more inclined to have him scream in my
face than at the back of my head.''
</P>
<P>
   The night was one long slap upside the head for the Red Sox, who
struck out 12 times against Irabu, the Japanese import who matched
his career high in whiffs. Irabu, who was the beneficiary of last
weekend's onslaught against the Indians, is now 7-0 with four
no-decisions in his last 11 starts.
</P>
<P>
   He was especially tough on Butch Huskey, the new Sox DH, who
made a compelling case against flying back and forth from Seattle
in the span of a day by whiffing three times and popping out in his
final at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to say that had any effect on my game,'' said
Huskey, as he fastened his seat belt and put his seat in an upright
position after the game.
</P>
<P>
   Portugal could only wish he could pin his night on an excuse
like jet lag. The Sox starter, who has never beaten the Yankees,
lost for the third time this season against the Bombers and sixth
time in his career, the first three losses coming another lifetime
ago, when he was with the Twins over a decade ago.
</P>
<P>
   His ego took a further beating in the second, when errors by
Nomar Garciaparra and Trot Nixon led to three unearned runs out of
the four the Yankees scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``My team got me back in it, and I went out there and gave it
back up again,'' Portugal said. ``They did everything they could to
keep us in the game, and I gave it up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
