<HEADLINE>
BIG SECOND HALF BOOSTS SPARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAMELA LEWIS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The undermanned Utah Starzz, which suited up
just eight players, gave the Los Angeles Sparks a little more
trouble than anticipated Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sparks (15-6) scored 11 unanswered points midway through
the second half to finally shoot down the Starzz 87-77 en route to
their fifth consecutive victory before 5,576 at the Forum.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't the prettiest game at first, but once we got started
we were on our way,'' Sparks coach Orlando Woolridge said.
``Gordana (Grubin) had some great 3-pointers at clutch times, and
we had some great individual efforts.''
</P>
<P>
   Grubin, who scored 16 points and dished out five assists, made
back-to-back 3-pointers to give the Sparks some breathing room,
66-58 with 6:36 to play.
</P>
<P>
   Utah failed to answer, going scoreless for four minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The last-place Starzz (7-14) were clearly at a disadvantage with
leading scorer Natalie Williams out with a foot injury and newly
acquired players Cindy Brown and Korie Hlede in Salt Lake City
getting their physical exams. They were acquired Thursday from
Detroit, in a trade for Utah's Wendy Palmer and Olympia
Scott-Richardson.
</P>
<P>
   But the Starzz didn't look like a depleted team in the first
half. The Sparks were troubled by Utah's defense and trailed 39-37
at the break.
</P>
<P>
   If not for Lisa Leslie's steady work against 7-foot-3 Margo
Dydek, who had 19 points, 11 rebounds and five blocks, the Sparks
would have been in deep trouble. Leslie responded with 24 points,
19 of which came in the first half, along with 10 rebounds and six
steals.
</P>
<P>
   The Sparks' Mwadi Mabika added 11 points and 10 rebounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
