<HEADER>
A0945 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBC-CSUN-PONCIANO-LAD     07-31 0358
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-CSUN-PONCIANO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PONCIANO MULLS COACHING OFFERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CHRIS BRANAM  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A few weeks from now Ron Ponciano could be
standing on a football practice field in Van Nuys or designing a
defensive scheme for a small school in Kansas. Either way, he isn't
finished with Cal State Northridge, the school that fired him as
head coach July 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going away,'' Ponciano said. ``The truth will come
out.''
</P>
<P>
   Ponciano is considering an offer to be the defensive coordinator
at McPherson College, a Division II program in Euclid, Kan. He also
has a standing invitation to be the assistant head coach at Valley
College.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues haven't shied away from Ponciano, who was let go by
CSUN for what the school considered ``serious and substantial''
violations of NCAA rules. He said he isn't sure which job he will
take.
</P>
<P>
   But he is sure he will be vindicated by what he thinks is in the
report, which is expected to be released Wednesday or Thursday.
Ponciano said the school's top two allegations against him are: (a)
As the head coach in 1998, he bought a plane ticket for a recruit;
and (b) he misappropriated state funds when he was the Matadors'
defensive coordinator in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Sources within the school said the report, written by internal
auditor Peter Dinauer, is finished. Its findings were planned to be
announced Friday, but representatives of the NCAA have come to
Northridge, sources said, to read the report and conduct their own
investigation, causing the delay.
</P>
<P>
   The CSUN investigation began May 19 when the athletic department
received an anonymous letter detailing several allegations against
Ponciano and offensive coordinator Rob Phenicie. Phenicie resigned
under pressure on July 7.
</P>
<P>
   Dinauer, who joined the university May 12, is heading what the
school terms an ``internal inquiry.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Kearin, a former Matadors assistant, was hired last week as
the interim head coach for this season. Football practice begins
Aug. 10 and the season opener is Sept. 4 at home against Western
Oregon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
