<HEADER>
A0950 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ANGELS-REWRITE-LA     07-31 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REMAINING ANGELS KEEP ON LOSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The locker to Gary DiSarcina's left was once
occupied by Dave Hollins. To his right was the empty locker of
Randy Velarde. And it made the Anaheim Angels shortstop pause for a
moment Friday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I've got cooties,'' DiSarcina said.
</P>
<P>
   DiSarcina, though, is well aware of the harsh reality for teams
that have fallen out of the pennant race before the trading
deadline. Teams will trade proven and productive veterans for young
and talented prospects. And in doing that, the front office is
calling this season a wash.
</P>
<P>
   While Hollins was sent away months ago, Velarde and pitcher Omar
Olivares were traded to the Oakland A's Thursday for three minor
leaguers. Pitcher Chuck Finley could be sent to the Yankees or
Indians any minute now, with the trading deadline coming tonight at
9 (PDT). Reliever Shigetoshi Hasegawa also has drawn interest from
teams.
</P>
<P>
   With all the trade talk, there was plenty of action in the
clubhouse before Friday's night's game between the Angels and
Minnesota Twins. And that was more than the Angels could say about
the game, a 3-1 loss before a fireworks-show-anticipating crowd of
38,319 at Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Twins pitcher Brad Radke threw a complete-game, seven-hitter.
The Angels have now lost 13 of their last 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   The only good news for the Angels was that starter Ken Hill went
61/3 innings and allowed only one run and six hits. But all that
means is he is another candidate to be traded.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Finley is rumored to be going to the Yankees for
pitchers Ramiro Mendoza and Ryan Bradley (Ayala High). And he's
rumored to be going to the Indians for second baseman Enrique
Wilson and pitcher Willie Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   Or he might not go anywhere at all.
</P>
<P>
   Finley met with Angels general manager Bill Bavasi after
Friday's game and Bavasi filled Finley in on the latest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Billy said `It's your decision, but I've got to make sure I
get your market value,' '' Finley said. ``He's going to come to me
and say they've met our demands, now it's up to you, or they didn't
meet my demands, you're staying here.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley told Bavasi his deadline for a deal is 3 p.m. today, not
the league-imposed 9 p.m. (PDT) deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not entertaining anything after that,'' Finley said.
``I've got to get ready to pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley is scheduled to start tonight's game against the Twins,
and if he does, he's staying put. Sources close to Finley have
indicated the left-hander is leaning toward staying.
</P>
<P>
   The main sticking point of a potential trade involves a contract
extension. Finley is a free agent at the end of the season and both
the Yankees and Indians are reluctant to part with anything
significant if Finley plans to re-sign with the Angels next season.
</P>
<P>
   Finley, though, won't say whether or not he's open to signing an
extension with Cleveland or New York, joking: ``You're assuming
I'll live that long.''
</P>
<P>
   Finley and the Angels reportedly have been talking about a
two-year extension worth $14 million.
</P>
<P>
   As for Velarde and Olivares, DiSarcina was sad to see them go,
especially Velarde, his double-play partner. But he added: ``I'm
happy to see them go to a winning team.''
</P>
<P>
   That the Angels are not a winning team really seems to tick off
first baseman Mo Vaughn. Vaughn, who signed a six-year, $80 million
contract and was counted on to put the team over the top, was
animated during a clubhouse conversation that turned the heads of
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't have an opinion on (the Velarde/Olivares
trade),'' Vaughn said. ``The main thing this team has to focus on
is to get ready for the first day of spring training. ... My
concern is seeing what's left after the season and making sure the
attitude's straight. For me, what's here in February is important.
My concern is not September, it's February. That's when we'll be
able to make a better evaluation.''
</P>
<P>
   With or without Finley, Vaughn seems intent on taking control of
the Angels clubhouse after a season that has blown up in his face.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of comments made, and the first thing
everybody on the club has to do is worry about themselves and how
they play the game,'' Vaughn said. ``In this clubhouse people need
to stop pointing fingers. Admit your mistakes then go out and play
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of getting involved in things we shouldn't be
getting involved in. We have to concern ourselves with looking in
the mirror and not worrying about what everybody else is doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
