<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MECHE, A-ROD RIGHT AT HOME AGAINST ORIOLES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN RALEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Guys like Randy Johnson and Ken Griffey Jr. might have
built the place. But so far, Safeco Field was made for Gil Meche
and Alex Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   Working in tandem for the second time in 10 days, the
20-year-old Meche turned in another precocious outing on the mound
Friday while Rodriguez backed him with the ultimate offensive move,
a grand slam. Their efforts added up to a 7-4 Mariners victory over
the Baltimore Orioles before a sellout crowd of 44,931, the club's
eighth full house in nine Safeco games.
</P>
<P>
   A rookie completing his first month in the majors, Meche (2-1)
became the first Mariners pitcher to win twice at the new ballpark.
He went 61/3 innings, scattering five hits, leaving only to break
in a new reliever, not because he was in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   With the bases full and one out in the fifth, Rodriguez erased a
2-1 Orioles lead by lining one high into the left-field seats, for
his 12th homer of the month and fifth career grand slam.
</P>
<P>
   If this all sounds a bit familiar, Meche went seven innings and
notched his first victory while Rodriguez cleared the bases with
another slam to break up a tie game on July 19 at Safeco, their
teamwork leading to a 7-5 victory over the Arizona Diamondbacks.
Indeed, the replay board works at the new yard.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might bring it up to him tomorrow, just to give him a
hint,'' Meche said of this two-man trend. ``It's huge. It's a
pretty good feeling when you're down and someone gives you a whole
bunch of runs like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Breaking new ground Friday night was Steve Sinclair. Replacing
Meche, the newly acquired left-handed reliever struck out the first
batter he faced _ as well as the second _ in one inning of work.
Tradition for lefties in the Mariners bullpen this season, as the
since departed Damaso Marte and Allen Watson can attest, has been
to serve up a first-batter homer in their debuts. Or in Marte's
case, a first-pitch homer.
</P>
<P>
   Meche was pulled with one out and one runner on in the seventh.
He could have kept going, having thrown just 100 pitches. But
manager Lou Piniella saw a chance to insert the new guy from the
Toronto organization, an opportunity to settle his insecure
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to get Sinclair into the game in a situation to get
the nervousness out, and their lefties were coming up,'' Piniella
explained.
</P>
<P>
   Said Sinclair, ``Being the only left-hander out there, I know I
have to do the job, especially in big games.''
</P>
<P>
   A five-game big-league veteran now, Meche was sharp, throwing a
shutout for the first four innings. He retired his first three
batters in a most unusual way, having each foul out.
</P>
<P>
   The rookie got knocked around a little in the fifth when, with
one out and two runners on, he grooved a 3-2 pitch to Charles
Johnson. The ball sailed over Griffey's head in center field for a
double, hitting the wall on one bounce and giving Baltimore a 2-0
lead.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson was overmatched his first time up against Meche, going
down swinging in the third. He was impressed with the young
right-hander's stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he pitched very well,'' the Orioles catcher said.
``He located his pitches very well. He threw hard. He had a good
slider. He had us down long enough for the bullpen to come in and
close the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Meche survived his fifth-inning peril. The same could not be
said for veteran Orioles reliever Arthur Rhodes in the bottom half
of the frame.
</P>
<P>
   Replacing starter Jason Johnson and entrusted with a 2-1 lead
and the bases loaded, Rhodes struck out Griffey on four pitches.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez worked the Baltimore lefty to a 2-2 count, then
crunched a ball over the hand-operated scoreboard in left. It was
his 24th homer and his club's seventh grand slam this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was actually a pretty good pitch, a fast ball in,''
Rodriguez said, not totally satisfied. ``I was fortunate to put
good wood on it and put it over the fence. I was just hoping it
wouldn't go foul. ... I still have to play better. I've been
playing like a dog lately.''
</P>
<P>
   Not according to the numbers. Despite missing 32 games with a
knee injury, the Mariners shortstop is now hitting home runs more
frequently than Griffey, the American League leader with 33.
Rodriguez's long-ball rate is one every 11.33 at-bats; Griffey is
one every 11.75.
</P>
<P>
   For those who believe in things cosmic, the next tag-team match
at Safeco for Meche and Rodriguez comes against the Tampa Bay Devil
Rays on Wednesday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
