<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0967 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      07-31 1680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(th) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Aug. 1:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   JAPAN-DECLINE (Tokyo) _ After a dazzling century in which Japan
emerged on the globe first as a feared military power and then as a
formidable economic one, Japan's influence may be on the wane. The
real problem is not the economic crisis that dominates the
headlines, but a pair of intertwined long-run concerns: The work
force is shrinking fast, and Japan undermines its economy's
productivity by squandering money on life support for moribund
industries and backward regions. By Nicholas D. Kristof. (With
photo, map.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGO-PEACE (Goma, Congo) _ ``Lusaka dead?'' asked Bizima
Karaha, a spiffy rebel alternating between two cellular phones,
then a third served up like soup by a hovering assistant. ``What I
can say is that the Lusaka accord is suffering.'' The accord,
drafted earlier this month, is the closest that the huge African
nation of Congo has come to peace since its most recent rebellion
began a year ago, on Aug. 2, 1998. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   U.S.-SATELLITE-LIMITS _ Only months after tighter restrictions
on satellite exports took effect, concern is growing within the
aerospace industry and in Congress that the new rules are
entangling manufacturers in red tape, delaying launches and hurting
American satellite makers in foreign markets. By Andrew Pollack.
</P>
<P>
   EAST-EUROPE-MEN (United Nations) _ Across many of the
post-Communist countries of the former Soviet Union and in parts of
Eastern Europe, the ratio of men to women is falling, the United
Nations says in a new report, because men in those countries are
leading shorter and less healthy lives. By Paul Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-U.S.-NUKES (Washington) _ At first, the questions from his
Chinese hosts seemed harmless enough to George A. Keyworth, a
nuclear scientist. It was 1980, and Keyworth, the chief physicist
at Los Alamos National Laboratory, had traveled to China to lecture
on his research into fusion energy _ not about nuclear weapons. He
was determined to stick to his topic, and not wander into loose
talk about secret information. But in hindsight, as it investigated
leaks of nuclear secrets to China, a congressional committee has
charged that the episode, while inadvertent, bordered on a
negligent breach of security by a senior scientist. By James Risen.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-PRIVATE-FARMS (Birobidzhan, Russia) _ Here in the Russian
Far East, private farming is a calling only for the brave. Viktor
V. Shubin has made a go of it, but in the neighboring Amur region,
Sergei Kitayev gave up farming after two years and is driving a
taxi, his dreams defeated by an economy that has given little
support to enterprising farmers. By Celestine Bohlen. (With photo,
map.)
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-REBUILD (Gornje Obrinje, Kosovo) _ The green countryside
here is strangely quiet; the sounds of children only intermittently
pierce the silence. The Yugoslav tanks and Serbian police cars that
intimidated the Kosovo Albanians who live here are gone and NATO's
troops are scarcely felt or even needed. But now that the fighting
is over, Kosovo's Albanians face an uncertain future. By Jane
Perlez. (With photo, map.)
</P>
<P>
   MIDEAST-PALESTINIANS (Jerusalem) _ Palestinian officials said
Saturday that an Israeli request for changes in the two sides'
latest peace agreement was not acceptable and that the two-week
delay agreed on last week for considering those changes was a waste
of time. By Ethan Bronner.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   NANTUCKET-DEVELOP (Nantucket, Mass.) _ Nantucket is an island
under siege. Once treasured by a relative few for its cobblestone
streets, picket fences bathed in icy-pink roses and isolation,
Nantucket is awakening to the din and clash of construction,
threatening both its look and its historic integrity. By Tracie
Rozhon. (With photo and map.)
</P>
<P>
   BRADLEY-CAMPAIGN (Des Moines, Iowa) _ Former Sen. Bill Bradley's
presidential campaign headquarters in Iowa is a dark, spartan
affair. The rent: $250 a month. By contrast, Vice President Al
Gore's headquarters is a sprawling, sleek space in a choice
neighborhood. The rent: $4,000 a month. At first glance, the Gore
operation is far more impressive. Yet impressions can be deceptive.
By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   MIAMI-TRAFFIC (Miami) _ In 1999, people tell traffic horror
stories the way they used to tell crime horror stories of the Miami
of 10 years ago. Gridlock has replaced home invasions and drug
murders on the front pages of South Florida newspapers, as Miami
chokes on its own traffic. By Rick Bragg. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   GA-SHOOT-TRADERS _ The pause in the relentless stream of stock
tips scrolling up the screen in the Internet chat room called
Daytraders was brief, and it was mechanically enforced. But after
the shooting spree last week at two Atlanta firms that specialize
in the rapid-fire buying and selling of stocks known as day
trading, several hundred online investors observed a virtual moment
of silence. By Amy Harmon.
</P>
<P>
   GUN-ID-SYSTEM _ As cities and states challenge the gun industry
to change its marketing practices, one proposal that keeps coming
up is the creation of a nationwide data base of bullets and
ammunition shell casings. Like a human fingerprint, every gun that
is fired leaves a unique series of marks on a bullet and shell
casing. There is just one problem: Over the last decade, the FBI
and the Federal Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms have
championed two competing bullet and shell tracing systems and
poured more than $40 million into them. By Barry Meier.
</P>
<P>
   TEST-BAN-TREATY _ In the wake of the Chinese spy scandal,
support is growing in the United States for ratification of the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, a global accord meant to end the
development of new kinds of nuclear arms. The process of treaty
deliberation and approval had been moribund for nearly two years,
but is now showing signs of life. By William J. Broad.
</P>
<P>
   HUMAN-GENOME _ The human genome may be as much as four billion
chemical units in length, one-third larger than previously thought,
according to new calculations by Celera, a company that has
undertaken a project to decode the genome by 2001. By Nicholas
Wade.
</P>
<P>
   NYC-SUMMER (New York) _ Across the city, there are parks and
playgrounds, schoolyards and street corners that have always served
as improvised summer retreats, unglamorous, but rich and fully
used. They are the places of summers lived out by children for whom
a fancy day camp is a pipe dream, and by fathers and grandmothers
for whom vacation is an absolutely local experience. By Joe Sexton.
(With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VA-HOSPITALS (Washington) _ Even after eliminating half of its
hospital beds in the last five years, the federal health care
system for military veterans still spends more than $1 million a
day to operate unneeded hospital buildings, where a dwindling
number of veterans receive care in underpopulated wards, federal
investigators say. By Robert Pear. (With photos.)
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-GUNS (Washington) _ As Americans puzzled over the
latest deadly shooting spree, House leaders appointed
representatives Saturday to a conference between House and Senate
lawmakers on gun control, a long-delayed, pivotal step toward the
enactment of any new restrictions on firearms by this Congress. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   BIZ-TAX-BREAKS (Washington) _ As House and Senate leaders try to
reach a deal on tax cuts, it is not just the average taxpayer who
has something at stake. A wide array of businesses and industries
is fighting to protect tens of billions of dollars in special
benefits that have made the competing tax cut bills the most
lucrative for business in years. By Alison Mitchell.
</P>
<P>
   RESTAURANT-TAX-LOBBY (Washington) _ Americans are eating out
more often than ever before. And yet, association lobbyists managed
to convince House Republicans this summer that restaurants were
suffering enduring harm from the government's decision in 1993 to
reduce the tax deductibility of business meals, to 50 percent from
80 percent. By Joel Brinkley.
</P>
<P>
   WELFARE-REPORT (Washington) _ Thirty-five percent of all adult
welfare recipients were working last year, or actively preparing
themselves for work, and all states met the basic work requirements
of the 1996 welfare law, the Clinton administration said today. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN _ On Friday afternoon I went to see ``Runaway
Bride.'' It wasn't hooky. It was work. I needed to check out
Richard Gere's portrayal of a hard-boiled New York newspaper
columnist. Pundits, after all, have enough of an image problem
without Hollywood mucking it up further. By Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 11:30 a.m. ET.
</P>
