<HEADLINE>
TV WEATHER SEGUES: IT AIN'T THE HEAT; IT'S THE BALONEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089) 
(bl) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Whew, the heat's been torture this summer, hasn't it?
And speaking of torture, what about all those contrived segues to
the weather on happy-talking local television newscasts?
</P>
<P>
   Here is a recent sampling from that very hot media town, New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   _ By CAREN LISSNER
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The news at 5:30 a.m. on Channel 7 (ABC), July 18.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: David Cone pitches a perfect game at Yankee
Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Loo, newscaster: The weather's still not so perfect. Bill
Evans' here to tell you about it.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 11 o'clock evening news on Channel 7, July 25.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: A man was rescued from a river by the New York
fire department.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Goldberg, weatherman: Not the way to cool off.
</P>
<P>
   Sandra Bookman, newscaster: Although I think I felt what he was
feeling. It was hot today.
</P>
<P>
   Goldberg: It  &UR; was &LR;  sticky today!
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 10 o'clock evening news on Channel 5 (Fox), July
26.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: The problem of poisonous jellyfish at beaches.
</P>
<P>
   Rosanna Scotto, newscaster: Should we blame it on Nick?
</P>
<P>
   John Roland, newscaster: We blame everything else on him.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Gregory, weatherman: . . . Well, listen, at least we broke
the high 90-degree weather we had over the weekend. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The news at noon on Channel 7, June 15.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: Passing motorist saves children from car stuck
in swamp.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Evans: That's a good story!
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Loo: And we've got good weather!
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 10 o'clock evening news on Channel 5, June 15.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: Researchers have reversed themselves and now
say that living near high-tension wires might possibly cause
cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Rosanna Scotto: Maybe they go to the Nick Gregory school of
forecasting: Maybe, possibly, 50-50. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 11 o'clock evening news on Channel 2 (CBS), June
16.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding segment: A preview of the next day's stories,
including an event at Coney Island.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Clark, newscaster: Unfortunately, it may rain on their
parade. . .
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 6 o'clock evening news on Channel 7, June 17.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: The Knicks prepare for their next playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Champion, weatherman: With the showers moving in the area,
the big game now is, how much rain can we pull out of this, and can
we get it out of the way by the weekend?
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 11 o'clock evening news on Channel 7, June 18.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: Movies made with new, brighter digital film are
being tested in theaters.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Ritter, newscaster: No virtual preview of our weather. It's
the real thing coming up next with Sam Champion. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 10 o'clock evening news on Channel 9 (WOR), June
20.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: A new satellite, the SeaWinds Quikskat, will
make it easier to predict hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   Logan Crawford, newscaster: Well, our own SeaWinds Quikskat,
Larry Cosgrove, is here. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: May 6, on the 10 o'clock evening news, Channel 9.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: Mayor Rudolph Giuliani encourages people to
take their dogs to the vet.
</P>
<P>
   Ernie Anastos, newscaster: I'm sure Bob Barker would second
that, right? And here he is, by the way. No, this is not Bob
Barker. It's the real Storm Field.
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Blackmon, newscaster: With good news about the weekend,
we hope.
</P>
<P>
   Storm Field: Yes _ Well, uh, no.
</P>
<P>
   Anastos: Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 10 o'clock evening news on Channel 11 (WPIX), May
7.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: A reporter for the station wins an award for
Long Island reporting.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Watkins, newscaster: Congratulations, Frank. Now we'll have
a little expose on that dreary weather. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 11 o'clock evening news on Channel 2, May 7.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding segment: Preview of a story about a man struck by
lightning who survived.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Clark: All we're getting struck by is foggy weather this
weekend. Mark's got the forecast. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 5 o'clock evening news on Channel 2, May 10.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: A landslide at a state park in Hawaii kills
six.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Clark: All they expect to fall in Hawaii is sunshine.
Linda Church in tonight for Mark Danon. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 11 o'clock evening news on Channel 2, June 20.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: A helicopter in California had to make an
emergency landing right on a highway. No cars were hit and nobody
was hurt.
</P>
<P>
   David Diaz, newscaster: That's amazing. Tremendous luck. What
about tomorrow morning, for all the cars that won't be dodging
planes . . . What about the weather, Linda?
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 10 o'clock news on Channel 5, May 11.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: Cindy Crawford posing naked and pregnant on the
cover of a women's magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Rosanna Scotto: Cindy has nothing on Nick's wife. Athena's
pregnant, right?
</P>
<P>
   Nick Gregory: . . . Are you kidding? Geez, I don't even want to
look at her naked anymore, period.
</P>
<P>
   John Roland: More than we need to know. Just do the weather.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 6 o'clock evening news on Channel 7, May 2.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: There's a new treatment for back pain.
</P>
<P>
   Ritter: Lee Goldberg has been breaking his back _ sorry _
</P>
<P>
   (Laughter and groans from the studio.)
</P>
<P>
   Lee Goldberg: _ extending this weekend's weather.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: May 6, the 5 o'clock evening news, Channel 7.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: Ducklings in Ohio were rescued after falling
into a sewer.
</P>
<P>
   Roz Abrams (to forecaster Champion): And, my little duck . . .
(laughing) I can't even do the segue. OK Sam, what's up in the
weather world?
</P>
<P>
   Rest of Eyewitness News team: Awwwww.
</P>
<P>
   Champion: Oh, leave us alone.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: May 11, the 6 o'clock evening news, Channel 7.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: Babies listening to classical music.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Beutel, newscaster: Well, we can't give you any music, but
maybe we can soothe you with the weather forecast with Sam
Champion.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 10 o'clock evening news on Channel 11, May 16.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding segment: Previews of stories to come.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Thompson, newscaster: We'll tell you how a bunch of
monkeys are turning up pregnant. Right now, Joe is turning up with
a look at our workweek forecast.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 11 o'clock evening news on Channel 2, May 18.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: Paula Jones will earn money as a phone psychic.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen Clark: Next, our meteorologist looks into his crystal
ball to see how long our foggy weather will last.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 11 o'clock evening news on Channel 4 (NBC), May
20.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding segment: Preview of a story about a diet from the
Bible that makes people healthier and helps fight illness: the
``Hallelujah Diet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sue Simmons, newscaster: Well, hallelujah, it's time for Janice
Huff!
</P>
<P>
   Janice Huff, forecaster: Hallelujah, the weather's great!
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast: The 11 o'clock evening news on Channel 7, May 20.
</P>
<P>
   Preceding story: A look at ``Neurobics,'' ways to exercise your
mind as you age.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Beutel, newscaster: I'm  &UR; thinking &LR;  about the weather. . . .
</P>
</TEXT>
