<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 11:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0981 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NANTUCKET-DEVELOP-ART     07-31 1330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NANTUCKET-DEVELOP-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NANTUCKET WORRIES THAT ITS PAST IS BEING RENOVATED AWAY
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map and photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By TRACIE ROZHON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NANTUCKET, Mass. _ On Orange Street, a winding thoroughfare in
the historic Old Town, carpenters are gutting a 19th-century
federal house. They have stripped off the original plaster walls
and jacked up the well-worn wide floorboards, replacing them with
freshly sawed lumber. The rat-a-tat-a-tat of a nail gun rips
through the salt-swept air.
</P>
<P>
   Near the town's old windmill, a 1950s bungalow has been
demolished and a house three times its size is rising, almost as
wide as its site. Behind it, a new guest house has knocked out an
old apple tree.
</P>
<P>
   A few blocks away, the Baptist Church, which has been without a
steeple since the early 1960s, is about to get a new one from
Sprint Communications _ designed to hide the company's cell-phone
antenna inside. Some older citizens argued that the steeple should
be wood, but the town approved fiberglass, which Sprint said would
transmit a better signal.
</P>
<P>
   Nantucket, an idyllic, mist-covered island 30 miles out at sea,
is under siege. Once treasured by a relative few for its
cobblestone streets, its picket fences bathed in icy-pink roses and
its isolation, Nantucket is awakening to the din and clash of
construction, threatening both its look and its historic integrity.
Wealthy visitors who crave a piece of its weathered charm are
buying up houses and ripping them apart, on a scale never seen here
before _ often with the aid of loopholes in the town's laws.
</P>
<P>
   That may come as a surprise to people who have not visited
lately or to those who believe that Nantucket is protected by the
strictest preservation guidelines _ 184 pages _ in the country. And
it is true that the town prescribes only eight historic paint
colors for doors. But it is also true that landowners can shoehorn
a second house onto their quarter-acre lot _ and that is exactly
what dozens of people are doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, the pace is frightening,'' said Eugenie Voorhees,
chairwoman of Nantucket's Historic District Commission, the agency
charged with protecting the island's landmark houses but which
seems powerless to stop many of the changes here. ``We had the
lesson of the Hamptons. We had the lesson of Cape Cod. And we still
got it wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Big money is arriving on the island in private planes and
100-foot yachts, paying prices that even real estate agents never
dreamed of: In the last decade, the price of the average antique
house near Main Street has soared from $350,000 to close to $2
million, an increase three times greater than for similarly
well-located houses in the Hamptons.
</P>
<P>
   Every morning, the nine-seater Cessnas take off from Hyannis,
bearing carpenters with tool belts; one architect estimates that
300 workers arrive every summer workday on ferries and planes.
</P>
<P>
   Although Nantucket has always been a blue-chip kind of place, it
was a kind of seedy blue-chip place, where the money was so old it
was brittle, and very, very quiet. Homeowners often did not bother
to paint until they saw the bare wood on the clapboards; autumn
clematis clambered rundown fences; old buoys piled up in front of
ramshackle wharf dwellings. Most visitors rode bicycles; if they
stayed all summer, they brought over a rusty Jeepster.
</P>
<P>
   Now Nantucket's cobblestone streets are clogged with Mercedeses
and Range Rovers. The Hub, the town's newspaper shop, displays
racks of Town and Country magazines showing recent arrivals like
Arie L. Kopelman, president of Chanel, on his tidy brick path,
wearing Nantucket Red sailing pants with Belgian shoes _ footwear
rarely seen near a sailboat. His wife, Coco, is seen clutching a
tiny Nantucket basket.
</P>
<P>
   Up on Cliff Road, where vintage cottages are knocked down almost
as soon as they go on the market, the fashion designer Tommy
Hilfiger two years ago paid $4.6 million for a house with views of
Nantucket Sound. As a sign of how much things have changed, the
Hilfigers are being applauded for not demolishing it.
</P>
<P>
   On- and off-islanders debate whether the development is worse in
the Old Town or outside it, amid the rugosa rose and heather, and
some prominent urban planners say the added density in town is a
natural evolution and even adds to the charm. Robert D. Rivers,
administrator of Nantucket's Historic District Commission, said
that roughly 15 to 20 antique houses were demolished or gutted each
year, out of 2,200 historic structures on the island, ``and that
puts a sizable dent in the resources.'' Many are gutted to
accommodate air conditioning or to create today's enormous
kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gut rehabs are beginning to take out the structure of so many
houses,'' said William R. Klein, Nantucket's first director of
planning and now the research director of the American Planning
Association. ``You're losing a part of the historical integrity of
the building. It's a real important connection with the generation
that lived before us. It's very sad.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nantucket Building Department says the number of building
permits has stayed the same over the last three years. ``But what's
changed _ and it doesn't show up in any statistics _ is the scale
of the construction, and the dollar amounts,'' said Steve Butler, a
building inspector. ``We've been crazed trying to monitor things.''
</P>
<P>
   Nantucket's design guidelines were written in 1967, and cover
only new construction: roof slopes, materials and the shape of new
skylights and dormers. In the late '60s, and even during the
guideline's revision four years ago, the town fathers did not
envision the destruction of the old structures built before the
middle of the 19th century.
</P>
<P>
   The goal for the Old Town of Nantucket, the guidelines read, is
``to preserve as unchanged as possible the old structures built
before the middle of the 19th century in their original settings
and conditions.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a kinder, gentler time,'' Ms. Voorhees said. ``People
didn't think about pushing the envelope. Now it's a runaway
situation.''
</P>
<P>
   The commission has the power to prevent demolition _ but not
interior renovation _ of listed historic buildings. But new
homebuyers have found loopholes: After they have gutted the inside,
they just keep going, often claiming that the beams and floor
joists were rotten.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the commission filed suit in Nantucket District
Court, charging the owners of one house with effectively
demolishing their 100-year-old farmhouse. ``They claim it's a
renovation,'' Ms. Voorhees said, ``but there's only four boards
left.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem could be the way the commission is set up.
Most historic boards are appointed with slots for preservation
experts, while Nantucket's commission may be the only elected
historic board in the country, and its members are not always
up-to-date on preservation strategies, Rivers said. Altogether, he
said, the commission's ``tools are just not adequate to deal with
this new phenomenon.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone rues the changes in town.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like an Italian hill town: full of life and very
walkable,'' said Robert Davis, founder of Seaside, the Florida
Panhandle resort town whose Main Street is partly modeled on
Nantucket's.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Andres Duany, the noted town planner who is a
leading proponent of ``new urbanism,'' a model of suburban design
based on principles of traditional towns, say they worry more about
the outskirts of town, where development is so intense that a new
shingle-style villa was built, speculatively, in front of a giant
water tower.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're probably going to ask $3 million,'' said Curtis
Barnes, of Nantucket Real Estate. ``You've got to go with progress
but then there's a time when you say `Hell, no.' But I've never
heard `Hell, No.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Last year, two of the town's most prominent summer residents
Boston architect Graham Gund and Max Berry, a high-powered
Washington lawyer, founded the Preservation Trust of Nantucket.
Berry, who who has been coming to the island for 30 years, said he
had become frustrated with the town's bureaucracy and its elected
historic commission.
</P>
<P>
   Some islanders, however, say that the commission did right by
Berry in approving his new 6,000-square-foot Victorian replica at
the end of Brant Point, which replaced a smaller
turn-of-the-century beach house. Berry founded the Preservation
Trust right afterward, and to some it appeared as if he decided to
preserve the island after he got to build what he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   One of the focuses of the trust is on promoting deed
restrictions that protect historic interiors. Under the trust's
program, the homeowner agrees to restrict changes to the property
in perpetuity, and also donates money to pay for the inspections
necessary to oversee such restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   But the value of a house is diminished by the restriction, and
in the last two years, only two people have signed up.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to blame the property owners for the rush to
construct. But the problem is not the millionaires, argued
architect Hugh Newell Jacobsen, who has designed a half dozen
houses here. ``The town fathers have got to change the zoning if
they don't like these houses.''
</P>
<P>
   They tried to do just that two years ago, when townsfolk voted
down a moratorium on houses more than 3,500 square feet. And now,
even development critics here point out that Nantucket already has
50 percent of its undeveloped acreage in conservation easements and
land banks.
</P>
<P>
   Not everybody here is eager to sell out.
</P>
<P>
   ``See that couple,'' said Curtis Barnes, the real estate agent,
pointing out a gray-haired man and woman parking their bicycles in
front of their immaculately groomed and perfectly located North
Main Street clapboard cottage.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always walking up to them and offering them
millions,'' he said. ``But they just keep saying no.'' He paused,
and smiled proudly. ``See, we're not  &UR; all &LR;  heathens.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
