<HEADER>
A0985 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-DECLINE-ART-4TA     07-31 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-DECLINE-ART-4TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JAPAN SEES SIGNS OF A LESS INFLUENTIAL FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Locator map and
graphic are being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can
make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By NICHOLAS D. KRISTOF    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ After a dazzling century in which Japan emerged on the
globe first as a feared military power and then as a formidable
economic one, its influence may be on the wane.
</P>
<P>
   The real problem is not the economic crisis that dominates the
headlines, but a pair of intertwined long-run concerns: The work
force is shrinking fast, and Japan undermines its economy's
productivity by squandering money on life support for moribund
industries and backward regions.
</P>
<P>
   In the next few decades, unless Japan somehow manages to arrest
current trends, it may find that its share of global economic
output has shrunk considerably.
</P>
<P>
   Japan's working-age population peaked in 1995 and is falling
quickly. The overall Japanese population will still rise a tiny bit
until 2007, because of the long life expectancy of today's
retirees. But after that, the Japanese government's official
projections show the country's population tumbling rapidly, from
126 million today to 100 million in 2050 and 67 million in 2100.
</P>
<P>
   ``If influence is measured by GDP, then Japan's influence will
decline,'' said Chikashi Moriguchi, a prominent Japanese economist
who has studied the aging of Japan, referring to the gross domestic
product.
</P>
<P>
   While other industrialized countries also face low fertility
rates and aging societies, Japan is in a particular bind because
for cultural and sentimental reasons, it cannot easily avail itself
of the two obvious solutions: easier immigration to shore up the
population and ruthless restructuring to boost productivity.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has some tremendous underlying economic strengths, ranging
from well-trained and committed workers to huge private savings.
Companies like Sony and Toyota may continue to expand and become
even more titanic global businesses while their home market becomes
relatively smaller.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the link between population size and global economic
influence is far from absolute, as India demonstrates at one
extreme and Hong Kong at the other. Even if Japan's share of the
world's economy continues to decline, ordinary Japanese may live
more enjoyable lives in a less crowded country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan will be more of a middling power, less important than it
is now in the scheme of things, and it may be more comfortable with
that,'' said Hugh Patrick, director of the center on Japanese
Economy and Business at Columbia University.
</P>
<P>
   But Japan's shrinking population, many economists argue, makes
it difficult to see how Japan can continue to play the role of
Asia's leading power. Historically, the world has usually adjusted
more easily to the ripples from a declining power like Japan than
to those of a rising power like China, but the economic and
political ramifications will still be far-reaching.
</P>
<P>
   What will Japan look like in a few decades?
</P>
<P>
   No one knows, of course, but the late-night horror television
scenario might be something based on life today in the little
island of Akashima, in the Goto chain in southern Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshie Kokou, a friendly 70-year-old fisherman, stood on a bluff
on Akashima the other day, smiling shyly and speaking lovingly of
the throngs of friends and family members who surrounded him. The
only catch is that Kokou was standing in the cemetery. Akashima's
hospital, school, stores and most of its homes are abandoned, and
aside from Kokou only four people still live on the 128-acre
island.
</P>
<P>
   Akashima, its seaside cliffs jutting out of a blue-black ocean
that is hospitable mostly to the passing whales, has lost people
(it had 300 inhabitants at its peak a few decades ago) not so much
because women had fewer babies as because people moved to the
cities. But Akashima offers a glimpse of Japan's difficulties in
generating the kind of boom in productivity that might help make up
for a shrinking work force.
</P>
<P>
   From the 1950s through the 1980s, productivity grew much more
quickly in Japan than in the West. But Japan's total factor
productivity, the broadest measure, is now growing by only about
one-half of one percent per year, much less than half the level of
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Fundamentally, the reason is that Japan steadily lost its
capacity for what the economist Joseph Schumpeter called ``creative
destruction.'' Japan never built up a huge public welfare system,
but it has instituted safety nets and subsidies to create a welfare
state for companies and towns and declining industries.
</P>
<P>
   The result is welfare dependency among inefficient corporations
and moribund economic sectors and fading islands and villages.
Instead of ``picking winners,'' Japan is now picking losers and
subsidizing them on a huge scale.
</P>
<P>
   Even tiny Akashima, a minnow in the Sea of Japan, is taking up a
whale's share of the national resources. Just the other day,
several barges chugged into Akashima's port to begin a $2.5 million
project to expand it and build a new pier.
</P>
<P>
   It may seem odd to be spending so much money on a project that
serves only five full-time residents, but that is only the
beginning. The government also provides a $490,000 annual subsidy
to the twice-daily ferry to Akashima and a neighboring island,
Oshima, which has 70 residents.
</P>
<P>
   At a huge cost, the government also has laid down undersea
cables to Akashima to carry electricity to the five residents.
Indeed, to demonstrate its absolute disregard for expense and
efficiency, the government has laid down not just one cable but
two.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is to insure a stable supply of electricity,'' said Choji
Tanikawa, an official in the regional offices on the main island of
Fukue.
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the other subsidies: the underwater telephone
cable, the postal delivery, the weekly clinic by a public doctor.
The island of Oshima next door has what must be one of the best
student-teacher ratios in the world: there are three students and
nine teachers.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   All the subsidies help reproduce mainland life even on the
remotest islands.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nobody left here, but I like it,'' said Tama Shiowaki,
a 74-year-old woman who was bustling down the path on Akashima.
``Feel this fresh air! I get up at 5 a.m. to feed my chickens and
ducks, and I'm so healthy here.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I just hope young people come back,'' she said. ``When I was a
kid, there was a store over there,'' she said, pointing to a
collapsed building peeking from the thick brush. ``And over there.
And there. And down by the cemetery as well. And now they're all
gone.''
</P>
<P>
   In another world, the bustle of downtown Tokyo, Kaoru Yosano is
minister of international trade and industry and is thus charged
with maintaining Japan's future international competitiveness.
Sitting at a conference table in his vast office, the size of a
typical Japanese apartment for a family of five, Yosano sips his
tea and admits that he is struggling for solutions to the
population problem _ in vain.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no easy answer,'' Yosano said bleakly. ``My mother
was one of eight children. My father was one of 11. My wife and I
were each one of five children, and we ourselves have two children.
When we look further ahead at the next generation, well, I don't
hear much from my sons about having babies.''
</P>
<P>
   (Yosano's two sons, both married, one with one child and the
other without any, both declined to be interviewed.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Former Primer Minister Takeshita once told me that in the year
2500, Japan's population will be down to one person,'' Yosano said
with a glum smile. ``When that happens, I suppose Japan's global
influence inevitably will have declined.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan is not, of course, the only country facing low birth
rates. Japanese women give birth to an average of 1.4 children,
while World Bank figures show Spain, Bulgaria and Latvia tied for
the lowest ``total fertility rate'' in the world, at 1.1. Even the
United States will grow primarily because of immigration because
its total fertility rate, of 2.0, is slightly below the level
needed for a self-sustaining population (which is 2.1 to account
for such factors as babies who die before adulthood).
</P>
<P>
   So what sets Japan apart is not so much that its women are
having fewer babies, but rather the combination it represents: The
world's second-largest economy is now one of the world's least
fertile and fastest-aging societies. Latvia's fertility crisis will
affect Lithuania; Japan's will shape the entire global economy.
</P>
<P>
   The essence of the challenge is a shrinking work force. The
government predicts that the working-age population of Japan will
drop by about 650,000 a year over the next 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   If those projections hold up, then even assuming that more women
and old people hold jobs and that productivity continues to grow
steadily at the same rate as in the 1990s, then Japan's gross
national product in 2050 will be 5 percent smaller than it is
today. Assuming that the rest of the world continues to grow
economically at about the same pace as it has in recent decades,
that would leave Japan with less than one-third the share of global
output that it now enjoys.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, each Japanese worker will have to support more
non-workers, as the aged rise from one-sixth of the population now
to one-third by the middle of the next century. This means that
simply for Japan to retain its present per capita income, each
worker will have to increase output to make up for the growing
numbers who are idle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think Japanese living standards are going to
improve,'' said Robert Alan Feldman, chief economist at Morgan
Stanley in Tokyo and one of the first Japan specialists to focus on
demographic constraints. ``Japan's GNP is going to shrink, and on a
per capita level it may also be a little bit lower.''
</P>
<P>
   None of this is fixed, of course. If Japan could boost
productivity dramatically, then fewer workers could still produce
as much as today's work force or even more.
</P>
<P>
   But the pattern of subsidies to Akashima _ repeated in small
islands and hamlets around Japan _ helps explain why Japanese taxes
and utility charges are so high, and why Japan has steadily seen
its productivity growth slow down. Because it lays down undersea
cables for people like Mrs. Shiowaki, NTT charges unified telephone
rates across the country that are so high that they have stifled
Japan's growth of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Japan has some dazzling technologies, and these could perhaps be
the basis for boosting productivity and allowing Japan to hold its
own economically for a time. But Japan's strongest sectors, such as
technology, are hobbled by regulation and by the burden of having
to support the weakest industries.
</P>
<P>
   High per-minute telephone connection charges mean that most
Japanese do not spend much time surfing the World Wide Web, for
instance. National law forbids discounting books, to protect small
shops and consumers in remote areas, so there is no incentive to
buy books on the Internet. The upshot is that Mrs. Shiowaki has her
inexpensive telephone, and Japan has no Amazon.com.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, high electrical charges, postal rates and taxes have
made it increasingly difficult even for efficient Japanese
businesses to compete internationally. It is, for example, more
expensive to mail a letter within Tokyo than to mail it from
America to Tokyo. Japanese companies began to do their mass
mailings from America, to save on postage, so the Japanese
government banned the mailing of domestic advertising from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Why does Japan so obstinately subsidize its past at the expense
of its future?
</P>
<P>
   One reason is a political system in which small towns and rural
areas wield disproportionate influence, such that an upper house
member of Parliament from rural Tottori prefecture has only
one-fifth as many constituents as a member from Tokyo. The late
economist Mancur Olson, in examining why great economies lose their
dynamism, emphasized the rise of special interests that win
protections and clog up the gears of a market economy; although
Olson was writing primarily about the experience of the West, the
same analysis applies to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what is just as important as special-interest politics is a
profound Japanese commitment to equality across the country, and a
revulsion for ``jaku niku, kyo shoku'' society _ one where the
strong eat the weak. Most Japanese accept that businesses may be
predatory abroad, but there is some yearning for them to be
vegetarians at home. There is a genuine and broad-ranging sympathy
for the weakest elements of the economy, and there are virtually no
calls for cutting off the spigots of cash for rural areas or
declining industries.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Japan has fostered a gentle, merciful brand of
capitalism, one that keeps dying businesses on artificial life
support. The effort to run a country as if it were a Disney movie
strikes Americans as deeply admirable and hopelessly naive, and
Japan has indeed found it increasingly difficult to nurture an
economy drawn entirely in cheerful pastels.
</P>
<P>
   In a system too squeamish to let industries or islands die,
taxes increasingly go to rescue the feeblest competitors, those
that in a more ruthless system would have gone the way of
blacksmiths and buggy-whip factories. Take Japan's ubiquitous
sento, or public baths, for although they are a tiny industry they
are symptomatic of Japan's difficulties letting go of its past.
</P>
<P>
   These sento are glorious nooks of steam and history, privately
owned, where people can go and scrub and then relax together in an
oversize, overheated tub. After adjusting to the sensation of being
boiled alive, it is difficult to think of anything more pleasant
than a Japanese bath, or anything less essential.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, of course, the sento were necessary
institutions, because many families had no bath or shower at home.
Now nearly all homes have baths, and young people almost never use
the sento, but Japan cannot muster the courage to let them go
bankrupt. So, even though their time is past and they have no hope
of competing in the market place, many sento are kept alive with
government loans and subsidies that each year total almost $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   The result is not only higher taxes but capital and labor that,
in the public bath industry, are at Indonesian levels of
productivity and dropping. Everybody knows one way to raise
productivity here _ let the sento go bankrupt _but Japan is not
prepared to pay that price.
</P>
<P>
   The same kinds of sentimental subsidies keep islands like
Akashima alive. There has not even been any discussion of cutting
back the ferry service to once daily, and islanders seem stunned
when they are asked whether the government should continue to
provide expensive services to a tiny, aging population.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've never talked about cutting off services,'' said
Mankichi Kokou, 73, an Akashima resident. ``Even if this becomes a
ghost town, the services will continue. They have to.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a good deal of talk about how Japan may be beginning a
``third revolution'' of social and economic transformation as great
as the Meiji period beginning in 1868 and the post-World War II
era. Increasing mergers and the breakdown of the lifetime
employment system give some evidence of this, and officials are
talking a good game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is essential that we radically transform this nation's
system and character in order to promote further prosperity,''
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, as Obuchi suggested, the key changes are yet to
come. Japan's steps have been tentative, and South Korea has more
obviously embraced markets in just the last 18 months than Japan
has in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Another way that Japan could stave off the demographic
projections is by encouraging large-scale immigration.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, in particular, has shown that a country need
not worry too much about low birth rates so long as immigrants fill
the ranks of workers. And America has brought in not only low-wage
laborers, working as nannies or farm workers, but also computer
technicians and software engineers who have contributed enormously
to the dynamism of Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great strength of America is that it draws in continually
the best of everywhere,'' said Jagdish Bhagwati, a Columbia
University professor of international economics who is from India.
``Japan cannot really match that openness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan has the bottleneck,'' he said, ``of not being really
open to foreign cultures.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It has been 145 years since Japan abandoned its ``sakoku''
policy, which meant barring almost all foreigners. Yet even now
Japan is more hostile to immigration than any other industrialized
country: It is, for example, exceptionally difficult for foreigners
to acquire Japanese nationality without marrying a Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Chinese are sneaking into Japan to take
dirty or dangerous jobs, and they are beginning to leave an imprint
on the country. But because some of the Chinese immigrants are
gangsters who are handy with cleavers, many Japanese are more
frightened than ever of large-scale immigration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the government would try to find any other means of
solving the labor shortage rather than mass immigration,'' said
Charles Horioka, an American economist at Osaka University. ``Japan
is so concerned about maintaining cultural and racial
homogeneity.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tokyo made an all-out effort, it could recruit many of the
best young scholars and engineers from India, Taiwan, Vietnam and
China to study and work in Japan. That could revitalize the economy
and create a boom of entrepreneurship, but few in Japan seem
enthusiastic about that idea, and many seem fatalistic about the
waves of Asian migration that bypass Japan and continue on to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``English has become a common language, so it's natural for the
best and brightest to go to America to study,'' said Yosano, the
international trade minister. ``If they come to Japan, then they
face the language barrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I envy America for attracting them, but that's just the way it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative is for Japan to try to boost its own
fertility rates, by persuading women like Miki Fujii to have
babies. Mrs. Fujii, 32, has a good office job in Tokyo and the last
thing she wants is a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a matter of whether having a child is worth all
the stress and pressure,'' Mrs. Fujii said. ``Besides, I'd get no
help from my husband. He has this traditional idea that women
should raise children and that they enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard men say they're staying at work late because going
home early means having to take care of children, and they'd rather
work than do that,'' Mrs. Fujii continued. ``I totally understand
that. I think it's quite natural to feel that way. I know I would
feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan is a difficult place for a woman to raise a child, partly
because in practice this is a nation of single mothers. Husbands
stagger home late from the office or a bar, and a government poll
found that fathers spend an average of just six minutes a day
looking after their children.
</P>
<P>
   Profound social changes _ such as the emergence of husbands who
changed diapers _ might help fertility rates. But the Japanese
government's bleak population projections already assume some
recovery in fertility. If the total fertility rate stays where it
is, then the population will plummet even faster: to 92 million in
2050 and 50 million in 2100.
</P>
<P>
   Some Scandinavian countries have raised fertility a bit by
offering improved child care and various other incentives, and some
Japanese localities are even offering cash rewards for extra
children. Still, in countries like Sweden that have tried this
approach, the cost has been considerable and the long-term increase
in fertility very slight.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, an increase in birth rates would take a long time to
work through the system, for nearly all of Japan's labor force in
the year 2025 has already been born.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot evade the phenomenal change in population structure
and phenomenal change in population size,'' said Makoto Atoh, one
of Japan's leading demographers. ``It's an inevitability derived
from the current level of fertility and longevity.''
</P>
<P>
   Atoh said that Japan could partly compensate for the decline in
the labor force by having the elderly hold their jobs longer and by
encouraging more women to work. Fewer Japanese women hold jobs than
in most Western countries, so there may be room to expand the rate,
he noted, but he said that Japan's population will shrink so
quickly that adjusting to it will be very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem of the aging of Japan's population will be how
to pay for it. The social security system is underfinanced by a
huge sum about equivalent to Japan's entire annual gross domestic
product, and corporate pension funds are underfinanced by hundreds
of billions of dollars, leaving them with a burden equivalent in
scale to the banking crisis that has dogged Japan's economy for the
last half-dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   As for Akashima, the island remains a gorgeous but depressing
reminder of what can happen to a place when its population ages.
Most of the remaining people on Akashima say they believe that
there will still be at least one person living on the island for
the next decade, but there is the sobering example of another
nearby island, Himejima, which has been entirely abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of my young days, I remember how my friend lived
over there, and another friend's house was over there,'' said
Yoshie Kokou, the fisherman, pointing sadly at clumps of bushes.
``And I long for the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear young people aren't having kids now,'' he said. ``I
guess it's just the changing times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
