<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 12:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0989 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INTERNET-ME.COM-REVIE     07-31 0786
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-ME.COM-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTENTION, WANNABE GAZILLIONAIRES: HOW TO TURN YOURSELF INTO AN
IPO 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
(Eds: In online addresses, replace (AT) with the symbol, which
cannot be transmitted to some newspapers.) 
 (bl)  
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   To: Potential Investors
</P>
<P>
   From: me(AT)me.com
</P>
<P>
   Subject: Internet Start-up and Initial Public Offering
</P>
<P>
   It's not just young upstarts from Silicon Valley or Silicon
Alley anymore. Even the old freight-delivery dowager UPS is
declaring itself an Internet player (it ships a lot of stuff bought
on Web sites) and announcing that it is going public. The IPO craze
has reached the point that the stock exchanges themselves are
hatching plans to sell shares. So I believe the time is right to
take the Internet-IPO phenomenon a pioneering step further, which I
plan to do, with my new company, me.com.
</P>
<P>
   The company promises to be an extraordinary opportunity for a
select group of investors, and I'm giving you a chance to be one of
them. Since I am in the pre-IPO stage, the exact details of my
company are still a closely guarded secret. Good buzz, as we all
know, can be worth billions in today's frenzied market.
</P>
<P>
   A careful blend of mystery and hype are key ingredients in the
marketing plan of any good Internet start-up. As part of the
comprehensive marketing strategy, I will also be shaving my head,
piercing two or three body parts (as yet undisclosed), and lying
shamelessly about my age.
</P>
<P>
   The company is positioned across three markets with explosive
growth potential _ the Internet (see company name above),
intellectual property (I have lots and lots of ideas) and the human
genome project (hey, I have as many genes as anyone else).
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the company's losses are already mounting. But as we all
know, in the Internet era there are no losses, only investments. In
the hyperspeed land grab for mind share and market share in the New
Economy, actually making money is a character weakness _ a sure
sign of a worrisome lack of imagination in not being able to come
up with more and more ways to spend money. The financially meek,
after all, will not inherit the high-tech economy's Next Big Thing.
</P>
<P>
   Me.com has already attracted the financial backing of Dick
Digit, the Internet visionary and co-founder of harebrained.com, a
company I regard as nearly as path-breaking as my own. Dick, of
course, is now a gazillionaire because harebrained.com was acquired
only four months after it was founded for a stupefying sum by a
major computer company desperate to jump on the Internet bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings me to the company's long-term (a maximum of six
months) strategy, which is founded upon two plans that are
calculated to trigger results. Plan No. 1: Create some buzz and
persuade Microsoft that America Online is anxious to buy me.com,
which will prompt Microsoft to buy the company so that its
archrival will not get it. Plan No. 2: Plan No. 1 in reverse.
Convince America Online to snap up me.com to keep it out of
Microsoft's clutches. Either way, me.com is a decided winner.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, I think I should say a bit about an aspect critical to
business but regrettably neglected in most Internet start-ups _
management. The management structure and philosophy behind me.com
is, I'm proud to say, one of its unique features. It is the
ultimate ``lean'' company, quick and responsive, distinctively able
to react faster than flame mail over a T3 line. Me.com has a
totally flat organizational structure, no layers of bureaucratic
flab bogging down the decision-making process. I am the chairman,
chief executive officer, chief technology officer and sole employee
of me.com. It's all me, just me.
</P>
<P>
   Addendum: F.Y.I.
</P>
<P>
   The Net being the Net, if you actually go looking for www.me.com
on the Web, as many of you wannabe gazillionaires will doubtless
do, it will indeed take you somewhere, though, unfortunately not to
me(AT)me.com. Last week, Net surfers would find a page that was
part of the corporate Web site for Job 1 Systems Inc. of Sunnyvale,
Calif., a company that provides ``financing and strategic services
for start-ups.'' But Brian Job, a graduate of Stanford and the
Harvard business school, said he had just sold off the Web address,
or domain name, to an eager bidder. And like everything else on the
Net, me.com is changing fast.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1208EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
