<HEADER>
A0992 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-U.S.-SATELLITE-LIMITS     07-31 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.S.-SATELLITE-LIMITS-870(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EXPORT RULES ARE SAID TO BE A THREAT TO SATELLITE INDUSTRY 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ANDREW POLLACK    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Only months after tighter restrictions on satellite exports took
effect, concern is growing within the aerospace industry and in
Congress that the new rules are entangling manufacturers in red
tape, delaying launches and hurting American satellite makers in
foreign markets.
</P>
<P>
   Since March, commercial satellites and their components have
been treated like weapons for export purposes, requiring licenses
from the State Department rather than the more lenient Commerce
Department, which had jurisdiction.
</P>
<P>
   The shift was ordered by Congress in a measure passed last
October in response to revelations that two U.S. satellite
manufacturers, Hughes Electronics Corp. and Loral Space and
Communications Ltd., might have helped China improve its rocket and
missile technology while investigating Chinese launch failures in
which the companies lost satellites. Both companies, which are
under criminal investigation, maintain they did not harm national
security.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospace industry executives say the rules have hindered them
from supplying even U.S. allies. And beyond exports of finished
products, it can take months to obtain licenses that are needed to
bid on foreign projects, they say.
</P>
<P>
   The result, industry executives say, is that U.S. companies are
losing foreign customers who are worried that delays could
jeopardize billion-dollar projects. They say such problems could
threaten the competitiveness of the $30.7 billion U.S. industry,
which leads the world and had an $11.5 billion trade surplus last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the State Department does not change the way it does export
licensing, the U.S., which has dominated commercial space, will
lose position and it will have an effect for a decade,'' said Dr.
Richard A. Aubrecht, vice chairman of Moog Inc., of East Aurora,
N.Y. His company has lost some small contracts to supply parts for
satellites that are being manufactured in Europe, he said. ``The
reason given is they are unwilling to sign up with a U.S.
company.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockheed Martin Corp. could not bid in time to supply a
television broadcasting satellite to a European company, a contract
potentially worth more than $100 million. In a July 16 letter, the
company, Societe Europeenne des Satellites, said its urgent need
for capacity made it impossible to wait for Lockheed to obtain a
needed permit.
</P>
<P>
   Claims of lost business are difficult to verify, and some
customers are willing to wait. Last year, Loral warned the Clinton
administration that it would lose a contract or have to pay
penalties if it did not get a permit to export a satellite to China
on time. The permit came late but there were no penalties.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration opposed the return of satellite
export licensing to the State Department, which had jurisdiction
before 1996. But State Department officials say industry complaints
are based more on fear than actual losses, and point out that the
U.S. satellite industry managed to maintain leadership even when
satellite exports were last controlled by the State Department.
</P>
<P>
   ``I suspect that to some extent this is concern over what people
think might happen,'' said Eric D. Newsom, assistant secretary of
state for political and military affairs. ``I have no specific
evidence of any business having been lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Executives say the business now moves at a faster pace, making
delays less tolerable. With the development of multisatellite
systems providing direct-to-home television broadcasts, telephone
and Internet service, commercial launches have tripled since the
early 1990s. Satellites are built and launched within 18 months,
down from two-and-a-half years.
</P>
<P>
   Still, foreign satellite manufacturers and operators say the
rules could discourage them from buying American.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just creating a lot of difficulties for us as operators
and certainly creates a market disadvantage for American
manufacturers,'' said Conny Kullman, chief executive of Intelsat,
the 143-nation organization that operates international
communications satellites.
</P>
<P>
   Kullman said there was a delay in a license for Loral to ship
components for Intelsat's next generation of satellites to Alcatel
S.A., a French manufacturer that was to make part of the
satellites. The license came just before Intelsat was to implement
an alternative plan that would have delayed the first satellite's
completion by two months, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Executives say some restrictions have no bearing on national
security. Lockheed needed a license to send defective parts back to
their German manufacturer for repair.
</P>
<P>
   Launch schedules could be imperiled, some executives say,
because permits are needed for American manufacturers to present
technical information to foreign companies that underwrite space
insurance.
</P>
<P>
   ``That has truly paralyzed the space insurance business, and
that will paralyze the space business,'' said Douglas A. Heydon,
president of the U.S. unit of Arianespace Inc. ``Business is
essentially grinding to a halt.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Hughes, a unit of General Motors Corp., still lacks insurance
for the next satellite for its DirecTV television service,
threatening to force a delay in the scheduled August launch. The
company said it had received permission to talk to insurance
companies and hoped to settle the matter soon.
</P>
<P>
   Delays in launching U.S. satellites on foreign rockets come at
an awkward time, because several U.S. rockets have recently failed.
</P>
<P>
   Even some congressmen who have criticized the industry's
dealings with China have expressed sympathy, but say jurisdiction
will not be returned to Commerce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think they're to some extent valid,'' Rep. Curt Weldon,
R-Pa., said of industry complaints. But, he added, ``the process
didn't work'' before.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Thad Cochran, R-Miss., said the State Department had not
used $2 million appropriated by Congress to hire more examiners.
``It's not the law,'' he said. ``It's the failure to carry out the
responsibility as directed by the law.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dana Rohrabacher, R-Calif., is pushing for looser
restrictions for exports to allies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The industry has to recognize that they're getting hit because
some people in the industry reacted in an irresponsible way that
was damaging to our national security,'' he said. Nevertheless, he
added, ``We can't let the misdeeds of some people in this very
important industry cause an overreaction that will damage the whole
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In an interview and in Senate testimony last month, Newsom of
the State Department conceded that its Office of Defense Trade
Controls was understaffed, with 14 State Department and four
military officers reviewing 45,000 munitions license requests a
year. The transfer of satellite exports will add 2,500 to 3,000 to
that total.
</P>
<P>
   He said the $2 million was not spent because the State
Department had to review priorities in the face of an overall
funding shortage. But he said the department was prepared to hire
as many as 23 people, mainly to review license requests. Newsom
also said the State Department intended to set up an expedited
system for exports to major allies.
</P>
<P>
   The transfer of commercial satellite exports to Commerce
Department jurisdiction, which started in 1992, was completed by
President Clinton in 1996 after an industry lobbying effort led by
C. Michael Armstrong, then the president of Hughes and now head of
AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, the Clinton administration was charged in
Congress with being lax on security after the revelations about the
China disclosures.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The biggest losses for U.S. companies under the new tighter
rules have been in sales to China. Hughes forfeited a $450 million
contract to provide communications satellites to a Singapore
company with ties to China's military.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the State Department suspended a license for Loral
to export a satellite to China, delaying the launch. If the
contract is canceled, Loral will have to refund $124 million and
absorb about $50 million in other costs, the company has said.
</P>
<P>
   An executive at one of the three major U.S. satellite makers _
Hughes, Lockheed Martin and Loral _ said none of them met the June
15 bidding deadline to supply one or two satellites to APT
Satellite in China, a contract that could be worth $100 million to
$300 million. Two French companies did place bids. But APT still
seems willing to give the Americans more time.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some problems stem from confusion over the new rules and
cautious interpretations of them in the wake of the China
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Aerospace Industries Association officials say Raytheon could
not bid to supply $50 million of chips to Alcatel because the State
Department did not rule last fall on whether the chips were subject
to the restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The system went dormant,'' said Joel Johnson, vice president
for international affairs at the trade group. ``No one would make a
decision.'' Raytheon declined to comment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
