<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 12:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0995 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-TAX-BREAKS-NYT &LR;      07-31 1202
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-TAX-BREAKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TAX CUT BILLS WOULD GIVE BUSINESSES BILLIONS IN LONG-SOUGHT
BENEFITS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By ALISON MITCHELL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As House and Senate leaders try to reach a deal on
tax cuts, it is not just the average taxpayer who has something at
stake. A wide array of businesses and industries is fighting to
protect tens of billions of dollars in special benefits that have
made the competing tax cut bills the most lucrative for business in
years.
</P>
<P>
   With the new era of surpluses leading Republicans to push for
the largest tax cut since Ronald Reagan's in 1981, the latest bills
have proved a bonanza for the lobbyists who clog the corridors
outside the House and Senate tax-writing committees.
</P>
<P>
   In several instances, the vast $792 billion tax cut measures
passed by the House last week and the Senate on Friday give
corporations victories that they have been seeking since Reagan
crowned his second term with an overhaul of the tax code. That
overhaul made way for a reduction in individual tax rates by
closing scores of corporate loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   Many lobbyists say they had been stymied for years because
federal deficits had made tax breaks with a large cost to the
Treasury unthinkable. But with a pro-business Republican Congress
now dealing with a federal surplus, Clint Stretch, the director of
tax policy at the accounting firm Deloitte &AMP; Touche, was only half
joking when he said that some of the tax breaks in these bills were
ones companies had been seeking ``probably since the dawn of
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with broad-based personal tax cuts, the House bill
includes $80 billion or more in business tax reductions over the
next 10 years, while the Senate bill has about $50 billion. Despite
their differences, each of the two bills provides $792 billion in
total tax cuts over the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The measures include tax relief for multinational corporations
and for small businesses, assistance to the oil and gas industry,
aid to the nuclear energy industry, a tax reduction for railroads
and one for seaplanes, and a reduction in the corporate capital
gains tax that analysts say will be particularly helpful to the
insurance and timber industries.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever plan emerges from conference faces a veto from
President Clinton because of its size. And it will be months before
the shape and contents of a final package will be clear. But
industries and their lobbyists were still scrambling to get their
provisions into the bills, in hopes that they would be favored for
inclusion in the final bill. And some seemed almost giddy at their
success.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got the sun, moon and the stars,'' said Kathleen O'Leary, a
lobbyist for the National Restaurant Association, which in the
House bill won a phased-in provision to make 80 percent of the cost
of business meals tax deductible, instead of the current 50
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The business meal deduction had been reduced in Clinton's
deficit reduction package of 1993. Ms. O'Leary said the association
had hoped to win it back inch by inch. In fact, the association had
been supporting legislation that would raise the deduction to 80
percent only for companies that earned $5 million or less. But the
House applied it to all business, at a cost to the Treasury of $8.4
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Republican leaders defend the tax provisions as ones that will
help declining industries and keep American business competitive
overseas. ``These tax relief measures will make sure that we are
competitive in the next century and that we can keep our economic
growth moving in the right direction,'' said John Feehery, a
spokesman for House Speaker Dennis Hastert.
</P>
<P>
   But Congress is promoting such tax breaks at the same time it is
struggling to find ways to cut scores of domestic programs by 10
percent or more to stay within the boundaries of the 1997 balanced
budget agreement.
</P>
<P>
   And that has led Democrats to charge that Republicans are
putting special interests ahead of the common good. ``Without a
single dime of the surplus dedicated to strengthening Medicare, the
Republicans managed to shovel in almost $100 billion worth of tax
breaks for special interests,'' said House Minority Leader Dick
Gephardt of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   One Republican, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, voted for the
Senate tax bill but also excoriated some special interest
provisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can we justify giving a $33 million tax break next year to
companies producing electricity from chicken waste, when senior
citizens have to forgo some of their Social Security benefits if
they must work to make ends meet?'' he asked.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Democrats have their favored causes, too. On the
final day of debate on the Senate tax cut, Sen. Patrick J. Leahy,
D-Vt., won a tax break for maple syrup producers who tap trees on
timberlands. Under the provision, they would have the same income
threshold for paying unemployment tax as maple syrup producers
whose trees are on farms.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, industries argue that they are just receiving tax
treatment equivalent to that granted other businesses or clearing
up quirks in the tax laws. But such changes can raise broader
policy questions.
</P>
<P>
   Take the tax provision won by military contractors. Since the
early 1970s, Congress has used the tax code to subsidize U.S.
exports by allowing American companies to exempt about 15 percent
of their export income from tax. But in 1976, Congress decided that
weapons exporters should get only half the tax benefits allotted
other exporters.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Sam Johnson, R-Texas, who took up the cause of the military
contractors, said in a letter to House members, ``Let's stop using
the tax code to punish our defense industry.''
</P>
<P>
   He argued for and won a provision in the House bill to give the
contractors the same tax treatment as other exporters _ at a cost
to the Treasury of $1.1 billion over a decade. The Senate bill
phases in the change differently, costing $798 million over the
same period.
</P>
<P>
   But not all members of Congress see such a subsidy as a public
good. ``Why in the world, when the U.S. has such a substantial
portion of the market, do taxpayers need to subsidize us to promote
conventional arms races all around the world?'' asked Rep. Lloyd
Doggett, D-Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the military contractors' victory may prove
short-lived. Lawmakers say a panel at the World Trade Organization
recently made a preliminary ruling that this entire provision of
the American tax code was an illegal export subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   One of the largest business provisions in the House tax bill is
a change in the way multinational corporations are allowed to
allocate their worldwide interest deductions. The change has the
effect of allowing them to take more credits for paying taxes
overseas, and thus reduce their domestic taxes.
</P>
<P>
   In the House bill, which phases the change in faster than the
Senate's, the cost to the Treasury is $24.8 billion over a decade.
The Senate version would cost $12.6 billion.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an expensive provision to fix,'' said William H.
Laitinen, assistant general tax counsel to General Motors, one of
the many companies that wanted the change. ``But now there's some
more leeway from the projected surplus.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0996 &Cx1f; var-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WRITING-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      07-31 1120
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WRITING-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE END OF WRITING: CONTENT PROVIDED BELOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By JENNY LYN BADER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   My friend the fiction writer is sensitive, so I asked the
dreaded question directly. ``How's the novel coming along?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Very well, thanks,'' she answered. ``I'm workshopping it right
now.''
</P>
<P>
   At this moment, individuals are workshopping short stories,
novellas and plays. Others have screenplays or theater pieces in
development. Still others engage in content creation. They create
content, or provide it, for the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Actively productive souls everywhere are developing scripts.
Workshopping books. Providing content.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't anyone  &UR; write &LR;  anymore?
</P>
<P>
   Not necessarily. Some pesky writing tasks have been eliminated,
with the popularity of projects like the script-free MTV show ``The
Real World,'' which chronicles the daily taped lives of not
entirely compatible roommates. Or the summer horror flick ``The
Blair Witch Project,'' where rather than writing dialogue in
advance, the filmmakers sent the actors into the woods,
intentionally frightened them for days on end, and then filmed
them. What once had to be written can just be lived.
</P>
<P>
   But even when writing occurs, why is it no longer called
writing? I started to wonder this back in the heady days of the Web
entertainment boom, when I was hired to write a Web drama. At that
point, the Microsoft Network was using the ``television model'' to
try to conquer the Web. The ``show'' would ``air'' twice a week on
an MSN ``channel.'' I was the sole writer.
</P>
<P>
   Well, I was definitely sole. But the writer part became
increasingly unclear. A few weeks into the assignment, MSN
executives were starting to notice that the Web is like TV about as
much as it's like a sliding door _ they both have a screen. They
wanted to stop calling the episodes ``episodes.'' The producer
asked me what we should call them. ``Stories?'' I asked.
``Chapters?'' ``Chapters!'' said the producer. ``Jenny Lyn, that's
very `print.''' She told me to stop being ``so print.'' She said
the suggestion was ``very old media'' of me.
</P>
<P>
   This was an insult. Old media, once a role model for new media,
had become an evil twin as the new form struggled for its identity.
And the words of old media had gone too. When the producer
introduced me to the programming staff, I expected her to say I was
the writer of the site.
</P>
<P>
   Instead she said: ``This is Jenny Lyn. She's the creative on
this project.''
</P>
<P>
   Naturally I was flattered. I didn't have to worry about being
creative. I was the creative. Creative, an adjective in my youth,
was now a glamorous noun.
</P>
<P>
   But this new job title also betrayed an underlying suspicion by
the producers that writers don't really  &UR; do &LR;  anything; they somehow
simply  &UR; are. &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``Creative'' had become a noun in the same alarming way
``workshop'' turned into a verb. Once, writers attended fiction
workshops. Now, writers workshop fiction. The act of sharing the
work with others has become part of its creation, and the sense of
the individual starts to get lost. Once, writers escaped into the
wilderness to cultivate their voices. Now, they gather together
with each other or with development executives to hone their craft,
make contacts, compare their voices, or make their voices sound
more like one another. Meanwhile, the only people going into the
wilderness are the terrified actors in ``The Blair Witch Project''
who aren't cultivating their voices but do scream a lot.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the way that sensational events occur in book
publishing is by avoiding cultivating those voices. Instant books
bear the name of one writer but are actually divided up among
different writers, all refraining from writing in their own style.
</P>
<P>
   That's how book-packaging houses _ the writing factories of the
literary industrial revolution _ get them done so quickly. If a
book is, say, about a timely vegetable scandal, one writer will be
assigned the tomatoes, the next the carrots, and so forth.
</P>
<P>
   Such compartmentalization has occurred in the film and
television industry for years, but has gotten more extreme with the
growth of the sheer numbers of people on writing staffs, performing
uncredited rewrites, or doing ``polishes.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, the publishing and film worlds will soon have a joint
writing factory in the form of Tina Brown's media convergence
empire, which will put nonfiction articles into ``development''
before they are even written.
</P>
<P>
   Screenwriter and author William Goldman has decided to expose
the anguish of the development process in a new way. In July, he
offered studio chiefs a spec screenplay _ yes, a screenplay written
for no pay by one of Hollywood's highest paid writers _ to studios.
But there's a catch. The screenplay, ``The Big A,'' is not
finished. Any studio head who wants to read it must return a
written response with comments. And Goldman plans to publish these
comments, plus critiques from six screenwriters, along with the
incomplete screenplay, in a forthcoming book.
</P>
<P>
   In Hollywood, the ultimate expression that film development has
mechanized the writer's creative process is the screenwriting
software that solves story structure problems and suggests plot
twists. If it actually worked, perhaps writers could simply
``program'' or ``input'' instead of having to ``write'' in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   The unspoken threat of the digital era is that it will chip away
at the individual author's voice and intent, that content will
become more and more automated and mass produced.
</P>
<P>
   The heroes of the digital era will be those who restore
individual voices. It seems remarkably fitting that it was Peter
Norton who purchased the love letters of J.D. Salinger, the last
guy to escape into the wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   Norton made his fortune inventing Norton Utilities, featuring
the Norton Disk Doctor, a program that salvages the memories of
crashed computers. With heart-warming functions like ``UnErase,''
it is one of the few software innovations with a sense of justice.
Norton demonstrated that sense of justice and respect for memory
and author's intent when he purchased the letters for $156,500 and
then offered to return them to Salinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``He may want them returned,'' Norton said. ``He may want me to
destroy them. He may not care at all.'' He said he would leave it
up to the writer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1216EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0097 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 12:16 </DATE_TIME>
