<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 12:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1000 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POWER-FUNERALS-REVIEW     07-31 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POWER-FUNERALS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE YEAR OF THE POWER FUNERAL: WE MUST TALK. LET'S DO MOURNING. 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By DOUGLAS JEHL  
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RABAT, Morocco _ Weren't funerals supposed to be solemn, somber
affairs, where mourners whispered the right words and shop talk was
taboo?
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't have known it last week in Rabat, the setting for
the latest mourning ritual in what has become the year of the power
funeral in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
   There was the new prime minister of Israel, Ehud Barak, in his
first three-way meeting with President Clinton and Palestinian
leader Yasser Arafat. There was Clinton again, bonding anew with
King Abdullah of Jordan, his youthful new ally. And there was Barak
again, in a clinch with Algerian President Abdelaziz Bouteflika,
whose country is still formally at war with Israel. Syrian
President Hafez Assad was nowhere to be seen, but not out of any
lack of respect for the departed, King Hassan II of Morocco. The
Syrian leader knew what the other guests were plotting, and he had
no intention of allowing himself to be cajoled or even bumped into
a first-ever encounter with an Israeli leader.
</P>
<P>
   Once known as the domain of vice presidents and other varieties
of deputies, state funerals are turning out to be a good place for
the bosses themselves to do business. Back in February, even Assad
joined the galaxy of presidents, princes and prime ministers who
turned out to mourn the loss of Jordan's King Hussein. (There, the
organizers had promised to keep the Israelis out of his sight.)
Russian President Boris Yeltsin made that pilgrimage, too, despite
being woozy from ill health, apparently not wanting to be left out
of such an all-star gathering.
</P>
<P>
   In March, Bahrain buried its emir, Sheik Isa bin Salman
al-Khalifa, too quickly for many leaders to attend the funeral
itself. Morocco chose a more accommodating course, setting aside
the Muslim tradition that says a body should be buried within 24
hours of death. That made Rabat, for a day, the diplomatic capital
of the world, with a slew of side talks that included a state
dinner for French President Jacques Chirac given by King Mohammed
VI just hours after he had laid his father to rest.
</P>
<P>
   Even for regular folks, of course, funerals tend to bring
together people who might otherwise prefer not to be in the same
room. As everyone knows, a shared loss sometimes leads to
reconciliation, with hugs and tears at graveside or a wake. It is
only natural, then, for diplomats to try to translate that funeral
factor into diplomacy _ particularly in the Middle East, where
leaders tend to find reasons not to get together. Any meeting
between an Israeli prime minister and an Arab leader is still
considered news. Even the Arabs have trouble finding common ground;
it has been three years since they last gathered for a summit.
</P>
<P>
   And there is recent precedent for state funerals producing
diplomatic gestures. The death of Israel's Yitzhak Rabin in 1996
brought King Hussein and Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak to
Jerusalem for their first public visit. A meeting between Assad and
King Abdullah after King Hussein's funeral has left relations
between Syria and Jordan warmer than at any time in decades. And in
Rabat, the guests at King Hassan's funeral included Bouteflika, the
first Algerian leader to visit Morocco in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   As everywhere, bigger breakthroughs require more than mourning
gestures. But with pivotal leaders like Assad and Arafat
approaching their 70th years, this year of the power funeral may
also serve as a reminder that their time too, inevitably, is
running out.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
