<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 12:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1013 &Cx1f; var-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-POLITICS-REVIE     07-31 1131
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER KOSOVO CONFLICT, A MODERATE LEADER IS ECLIPSED BY MILITANTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (The Week in Review)  
 (NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For international clients' use by
special arrangement only. Asian and European points: contact Karl
Horwitz in Paris for details and prices (Phone: 47 42 17 11; FAX:
47-42-80-44). Latin American points: contact Olivia Vasquez in Los
Angeles (Phone: 310-996-0075; FAX: 310-996-0089)  
 (bl)  
 By STEVEN ERLANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia _ Ibrahim Rugova, where have you been?
</P>
<P>
   In the two months since NATO won the war in Kosovo and the young
fighters of the Kosovo Liberation Army proceeded to grab power, the
diffident and puzzling pacifist who was once considered Kosovo's
president made only one flying visit to the province. Instead,
Ibrahim Rugova remained in Italy, leaving his party and his
reputation to wither. Only on Friday, after direct prodding from
Western leaders, did he return to the province to live, or so he
says.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova has had reasons to stay away, some of his own making. But
they reflect the extraordinary difficulty that NATO and the United
Nations face, despite their theoretically unlimited powers, in
trying to build any fair, democratic political order in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A 55-year-old literary critic educated at the Sorbonne, Rugova
was the moderate around whom the world's hopes for reconciliation
in Kosovo revolved for nearly 10 years. Back when Yugoslavia first
began to fall apart, Kosovar Albanians elected him as their leader
in secret (and thus not entirely credible) elections, and his
policy of Gandhi-like passive resistance to the Yugoslav government
was widely supported until about two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, after Kosovo's extraordinary burst of violence,
Rugova's time looks to be over. He and his party are being pushed
aside by the hard young men of the Kosovo Liberation Army and their
political leader, Hashim Thaci, only 29, who at least tried to
fight the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   But Washington and the West also played an important role in the
decline of Rugova and the rise of Thaci, and thus in the
radicalization of Kosovo. Because Thaci has a history of
intolerance for dissent, many Albanians quietly wonder whether real
politics, moderate or otherwise, will be possible in Kosovo by the
time, a year or more away, when the United Nations and the
Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe organize
elections.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova remains popular among the middle-aged and the educated.
But he is a reluctant politician who dislikes pressing the flesh or
even uttering firm statements, and he has always been an annoying
figure for American diplomats. In February, when talks to reconcile
the Serbs and Kosovar Albanians were foundering at Rambouillet, the
Americans were happy to promote Thaci, rather than Rugova, as the
Albanians' chief negotiator. It was Thaci whom they backed as the
prime minister of a provisional government.
</P>
<P>
   Rugova has made many mistakes. He was passive in dealing with
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic and trusted in Milosevic's
promises. His policy of urging Kosovar Albanians to boycott Serbian
and Yugoslav elections was instrumental in keeping Milosevic in
power from at least 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Once NATO began bombing Serbia in March, Rugova criticized the
humanitarian catastrophe that befell Kosovo's Albanians, even as he
met with Milosevic during the war. His willingness to do so,
although he insists it was under duress, is widely believed to have
put his life in danger from supporters of Thaci and the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   And Rugova suffered a great loss with the killing in May of his
thoughtful adviser, Fehmi Agani, a man capable of talking to all
sides. Agani is nearly universally believed to have been killed by
the Serbian police, but the police still insist he was killed by
the KLA.
</P>
<P>
   On July 15, Rugova returned to Pristina to a welcoming crowd.
But he only stayed a few hours, refused to meet Western
peacekeepers and U.N. administrators and then quickly returned to
Italy, apparently objecting to the number of seats Thaci had
allocated to the KLA's political allies in a new Council for
Reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini, criticized
Rugova for remaining in Italy and not returning to Pristina ``to
play the role his own elections have entitled him to play.'' Even
before Secretary of State Madeleine Albright stopped in Rome to
deliver a similar request _ having visited Kosovo herself _ Rugova
admitted that Dini was right and promised to return.
</P>
<P>
   But his presence cannot erase his main failure, which was his
inability to win independence or even more autonomy from Milosevic,
creating a vacuum of frustration that made the rise of the Kosovo
Liberation Army inevitable. His position was undercut by the
failure of Washington to deal with the problem of Kosovo at the
1995 talks in Dayton that ended the Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   Dayton shattered the Kosovars' expectations that their policy of
nonviolence would be rewarded, as well as their trust in the West.
The beneficiaries at Dayton were the fighters in Bosnia, not the
pacifists in Kosovo, weakening Rugova's authority considerably. The
Americans argued that there was no time to deal with Kosovo at
Dayton, but then the Clinton administration did little to deal with
it afterward, either. It was the summer of 1998 before the West
really took notice _ after the rise of the KLA had produced a
Serbian counter-terrorist offensive that was so brutal that even
the West could not turn away.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in its intensifying campaign against Milosevic _ and in
its mistaken belief that a few days of bombing would cause him to
yield over Kosovo _ the Clinton administration finally sealed
Rugova's political fate by embracing the KLA and Thaci at
Rambouillet.
</P>
<P>
   Albright devoted much of her attention there to Thaci, and her
close aide and spokesman, James Rubin, has taken on Thaci as a
project, conducting negotiations with him over the KLA's promises
to demilitarize.
</P>
<P>
   That may be one reason that Rugova was not in Pristina on
Thursday when Albright made a triumphal visit there, giving Thaci a
warm hug.
</P>
<P>
   While all that may help explain why Rugova kept away from Kosovo
for so long, it offers little hope that his return will rally the
forces of reconciliation and compromise. After so many deaths,
there is too much Albanian rage, and Rugova is too weak.
</P>
<P>
   Even members of his own party, the Democratic League of Kosovo,
are fed up with him now. His absence ``has caused us great harm,''
said Fadil Hysaj, one of the party's leaders. ``There can be no
more politics based purely on loyalty to one person.'' The future
of a moderate Kosovar politics, Hysaj suggested, was now at stake.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1244EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0109 </DOCNO>
