u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CHINA-U.S.-NUKES-NYT &LR;      07-31 0975
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-U.S.-NUKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCIENTIST FINDS BLURRY LINE BETWEEN FRIENDLY TALK AND SECURITY
BREACH 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JAMES RISEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ At first, the questions from his Chinese hosts
seemed harmless enough to George Keyworth, a nuclear scientist.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1980, and Keyworth, the chief physicist at Los Alamos
National Laboratory, was in China to lecture at a research center,
happy to engage in some simple academic give and take. He knew the
audience was filled with Chinese nuclear weapons experts eager for
insights into American weapons designs, but he figured he could
handle whatever questions they threw at him.
</P>
<P>
   Keyworth had traveled to China to lecture on his research into
fusion energy _ not about nuclear weapons. He was determined to
stick to his topic, and not wander into loose talk about secret
information. But a congressional committee, as it investigated
leaks of nuclear secrets to China, has charged that the episode,
while inadvertent, bordered on a negligent breach of security by a
senior scientist.
</P>
<P>
   In China, Keyworth found himself being peppered with
increasingly detailed inquiries that related directly to nuclear
weapons. Benign inquiries about fusion and astrophysics soon gave
way to pointed requests for information about such highly
classified matters as the ignition conditions of the hydrogen
isotopes deuterium and tritium _ and about the then-new neutron
bomb.
</P>
<P>
   Keyworth now says he fended off the demands for specifics, but
he did respond in one instance by offering an analogy. Deuterium
and tritium ignite at such low temperature levels, he told the
audience, that you could just about get ignition by dropping them
on the floor.
</P>
<P>
   Keyworth came home believing he had avoided the traps laid out
for him by the Chinese, and had not betrayed any American secrets.
Yet he was concerned enough to report the incident to Los Alamos
and to intelligence officials. ``When I came back, I used this
example many times to show how completely benign conversations
could turn into uncomfortable situations in China,'' Keyworth said
in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Within a year, Keyworth moved on to the high-profile post as
science adviser to President Reagan.
</P>
<P>
   But 19 years later, the episode was resurrected by a House
select committee that investigated China's nuclear thefts and
illicit technology transfers. In its May report, the committee
mentioned it _ without identifying Keyworth _ as a cautionary
example of the security risks that American scientists confront in
dealing with China.
</P>
<P>
   In many ways, the Keyworth case underscores how international
exchanges often lead government scientists into gray areas, where
the line between vigorous scientific debate and the compromise of
national security information can be blurred. Scientists from
government weapons labs involved in exchanges in China and other
countries need useful and creative discussions with fellow
scientists, but must constantly remember the difference between
stretching the rigid bounds of classification and breaking them.
</P>
<P>
   And it also shows how scientists view their own foreign
scientific exchanges differently than do counterintelligence
watchdogs.
</P>
<P>
   In the congressional report, from the select committee chaired
by Rep. Chris Cox, R-Calif., a scientist is depicted as having
crossed an obscure line. The report states that ``the incident
involved the inadvertent, bordering on negligent, disclosure of
classified technical information by a U.S. scientist lecturing'' in
China. The report adds that the scientist ``was pressured'' by
counterparts there ``to provide a solution to a nuclear
weapons-related problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather than decline,'' the report says, ``the scientist, who
was aware of the clear distinction between the classified and
unclassified technical information that was under discussion,
provided an analogy.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials at several government agencies confirmed that
the reference in the Cox report is to the Keyworth episode.
</P>
<P>
   Keyworth says he is outraged that the episode has been
resurrected in the Cox report in a way that he says is distorted.
He says that no one from the Cox committee tried to reach him to
discuss the matter. And he strongly denies that he provided any
classified information to the Chinese during the exchange. The
analogy he provided was nothing more than simple physics and was
``absolutely unclassified,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I most certainly did hold scientific discussions in China, and
many of those discussions did run right up against the rules of
propriety, no question,'' Keyworth said. ``But I don't believe
those bounds were crossed.''
</P>
<P>
   American officials say that the Cox committee was never told the
identity of the scientist, and only included the episode in the
report based on classified briefings it received, either from the
FBI or the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
   Keyworth says he can think of no other incident that fits the
description in the Cox report.
</P>
<P>
   Several American officials say that the FBI did look into the
episode in the 1980s. The FBI ultimately decided that since
Keyworth had voluntarily described the episode when he returned
there was no reason to pursue the matter.
</P>
<P>
   Keyworth recalled that not long after he left the White House in
January 1986 he was interviewed by FBI agents, who told him they
were interested in learning more about the growing contacts between
Los Alamos and China.
</P>
<P>
   ``The FBI said they had observed that a considerable amount of
exchange had been developing between Los Alamos and China, and they
said they were curious about its nature and content,'' Keyworth
said. ``I discussed that with them, I believed to their
satisfaction. But the question of an improper exchange of
information was never raised. I dealt with them on a helpful
basis.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
