<SLUG> BC-WELFARE-REPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHITE HOUSE RELEASES GLOWING DATA ON WELFARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ore., Mont., Wis., Iowa, Wyo., Md., N.C., N.M., Pa., Ark.)  (mk) 
 By ROBERT PEAR    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Thirty-five percent of all adult welfare recipients
were working last year, or actively preparing themselves for work,
and all states met the basic work requirements of the 1996 welfare
law, the Clinton administration said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The administration issued new data on state welfare programs
ranking the states' performance in moving people from welfare to
work.
</P>
<P>
   Oregon, Montana, Wisconsin, Iowa and Wyoming reported the
highest employment rates for welfare recipients, with more than 55
percent working at least 20 hours a week in each state.
</P>
<P>
   Maryland, North Carolina, New Mexico, Pennsylvania and Arkansas
reported the lowest rates, with fewer than 20 percent of recipients
working. But these states, like most of the nation, have
substantially reduced the number of people on welfare.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton plans to cite these data on Tuesday when he
goes to Chicago for a conference of the Welfare to Work
Partnership, a group of business executives committed to hiring
welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Reed, the president's chief domestic policy adviser, said
Clinton would urge the executives to redouble their efforts and
``finish the job of welfare reform.'' He said the president would
also admonish Republicans in Congress to keep their hands off the
money promised to states in the 1996 law.
</P>
<P>
   Each state is entitled to a fixed amount of federal welfare
money, regardless of how many people qualify for assistance.
Welfare rolls have shrunk far more than most officials expected,
and $4 billion of federal welfare money remains unclaimed at the
Treasury. Some Republicans in Congress, seeking money for other
federal programs, have said they may take some of it, an idea
opposed by governors of both parties.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some in Congress want to break faith with the states,'' Reed
said. ``We will lock arms with the governors against that notion.
The job of welfare reform won't be done until we move every
able-bodied person from welfare to work.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton says the proportion of welfare recipients who are
working is four times as high today as in 1993, when he took
office.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's report provides the first full year of work data
available under the 1996 law. Every state and the District of
Columbia met the basic work requirements for 1998. The law
stipulates that 30 percent of adults on welfare should work at
least 20 hours a week, but the requirement is relaxed in states
that have substantially cut their caseloads, as most have.
</P>
<P>
   In December, the administration reported that most states had
met the work requirements for 1997, when 25 percent of welfare
recipients were supposed to be working. Those data were based on
just three months of experience, and not all states had to file
reports.
</P>
<P>
   New York state, with 37.5 percent of its adult welfare
recipients working last year, was close to the national average.
Connecticut, at 41.4 percent, was above the average, while New
Jersey, at 26.5 percent, was below. Florida, California and
Illinois were close to the average, with rates from 35 percent to
38 percent.
</P>
<P>
   States are subject to financial penalties if they do not meet
the work requirements. But a little-known feature of the law can
radically reduce the requirements for states that have sharply
reduced their welfare rolls. If, for example, a state has reduced
its caseload by 25 percent since 1995, the proportion of welfare
recipients required to work in 1998 is reduced by 25 percentage
points. So just 5 percent of recipients must be working.
</P>
<P>
   This feature of the law completely offset the federal work
requirement in states where the caseload dropped more than 30
percent from 1995 to 1998. That happened in five states, Indiana,
Oklahoma, Oregon, Wisconsin and Wyoming. As a matter of state
policy, those states continued their aggressive efforts to help
welfare recipients find work.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two-thirds of the states would have met the work
requirements for 1998 without any special credit or dispensation,
because more than 30 percent of their welfare recipients were
working.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, White House officials said, Clinton will plead with
Congress once again to provide more money for child care. The
administration says the demand for child care is growing as more
parents enter the work force.
</P>
<P>
   When the Welfare to Work Partnership was created in May 1997,
many people saw it as a symbolic gesture by public-spirited
companies. But on Friday, Eli Segal, its president, said: ``This is
not about charity or corporate responsibility. It's about the
bottom line.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1257EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 12:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1024 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUSSIA-PRIVATE-FARMS-     07-31 1216
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-PRIVATE-FARMS-ART-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH CHINESE HELP, A FEW PRIVATE FARMERS PREVAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. A map is being
sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make individual
purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BIROBIDZHAN, Russia _ Zhuang Yimin reaches into the pigpen, and
pulls out a piglet, which squeals frantically as he clips its tiny
teeth with gardening shears. He drops it onto its mother's ample
belly, and picks up its sibling for another deft display of the pig
management skills he brought here from Harbin, China.
</P>
<P>
   His boss this summer is Viktor V. Shubin, 45, a former land
surveyor who decided to try his hand at private farming in 1991,
the year the Communist lid finally came off the Russian economy.
</P>
<P>
   Here in the Russian Far East, private farming is a calling only
for the brave. Shubin has made a go of it, but in the neighboring
Amur region, Sergei Kitayev gave up farming after two years and is
driving a taxi, his dreams defeated by an economy that has given
little support to enterprising farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Vitaly Komlov, director of the Birobidzhan agriculture
department, said that of the original pioneers who staked out land
in the early 1990s here, only a fraction _ about 350 _ had stuck it
out. Many have steadily expanded their domains _ private farms now
account for 35,000 acres compared with 6,200 in the mid-90s. But
their farms make up less than 10 percent of the region's arable
land. The rest is held by the rickety remnants of the old Soviet
collective farm system.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have very difficult climatic conditions here,'' Komlov
said, ``and a lot of farmers weren't able to handle the risk.''
</P>
<P>
   Shubin's success is due in large part to the tips learned from
Chinese seasonal workers, who showed him first how to raise
vegetables, then watermelons and now pigs. In addition to Zhuang
and his wife, who work with his 80 sows and their offspring, he has
hired another 36 Chinese workers. They spend their nights in a
dormitory on his farm and long days in the fields, carefully
coaxing watermelon plants through holes in the plastic sheeting
that keeps the soil moist.
</P>
<P>
   All together, about 600 Chinese farm workers are in Birobidzhan.
The region was settled by Russian Jews sent here by Stalin in the
1920s. It is still officially known as the Jewish autonomous
district, although after steady emigration to Israel and the West,
only 10,000 of its 210,000 residents are Jews.
</P>
<P>
   The arrangement with the Chinese appears to have worked well for
everyone, at least on Shubin's farm, an untidy spread of sheds,
equipment and rutted roads 20 miles outside the town of
Birobidzhan.
</P>
<P>
   Zhuang and his wife, Lizhe, 35, make about $120 a month _ or
twice their regular wage in Harbin. They work long hours, but as
Zhuang said through an interpreter, ``I didn't come here to travel,
but to work.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Other Chinese workers said that with the money they make during
six months of work in Russia, they can take six months off at home,
tending to their houses and garden plots. In exchange for their
labor, Shubin initially gave the Chinese employees a share of the
crop, selling the rest on contract to the Russian military and
other government organizations. Now as China's appetite for Russian
timber increases, he is offering his Chinese partners cut lumber,
felled from his forests and cut by Russian workers on his farm.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Here in Birobidzhan as in the rest of Russia, farmers do not
actually own land. They either rent it with 50-year leases or are
allowed to hold it for themselves and their heirs. After eight
years of economic reform, there is still no law regulating the sale
of land.
</P>
<P>
   Shubin, for instance, insists that his 2,200 acres _ which
include farmland, forests and bogs _ are his, outright. But he is
not allowed to sell them.
</P>
<P>
   In some parts of Russia, land _ even under these uncertain terms
_ is a valuable commodity. Here in the Far East, in a region that
gets hit alternately by blizzards and monsoons, where most of the
land is forested or soggy, or both, the local government seems
almost willing to give it away _ or to rent it for as little as 60
cents a year per hectare, about two-and-a-half acres.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Starting with 250 acres, Shubin at first went into beekeeping.
But when that venture failed, he moved on to vegetables _ then a
rare commodity in the Far East, where agriculture traditionally has
been large scale and mechanized, and unsuited for labor-intensive
cash crops.
</P>
<P>
   In the Soviet era, vegetables were shipped in from western
Russia, and fruit from the Caucasus, at subsidized prices. Then,
when the border with China opened, Chinese traders rushed in to
fill the vacuum, at cheaper prices.
</P>
<P>
   Now, more and more Russian farmers here are growing vegetables
and watermelons themselves, borrowing Chinese techniques. ``They
have centuries of experience at raising vegetables,'' Komlov said,
``and Russians are ready to learn from them.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Shubin, 45, and his wife, Tatyana, a physician, have no
complaints. They drive a Japanese car, live in a newly acquired
house in Birobidzhan and have taken vacations in Thailand. One of
the farm's newly built sheds is stacked high with wooden barrels to
store pickled cucumbers and cabbage.
</P>
<P>
   Next year, Shubin plans to plant rice. ``The Chinese grow rice
on the other side of the Amur River,'' he said. ``There is no
reason why we can't too.''
</P>
<P>
   But for every success story like Shubin's, there is a sorrier
tale, told by a farmer who did not clear the hurdles of a rigid
agricultural system that has still not adapted to a free market and
the wild gyrations of that market here.
</P>
<P>
   Such is the tale told by Kitayev, who lives several hundred
miles away in the Amur region. Like Shubin, he decided in 1991 to
strike out on his own, moving from the Pacific island of Sakhalin
to the empty spaces along the Amur. Like Shubin, he began with 250
acres, on the outskirts of the city of Blagoveshchensk.
</P>
<P>
   He planted buckwheat and soybeans, he raised cattle _ 40 head _
and pigs, 56 in all. He borrowed from local banks to buy equipment,
and he lined up contracts for the sale of his crops.
</P>
<P>
   But for everything he did right, something went wrong. The
interest rates on credit shot up, at one point by 100 percent a
year. The price of animal feed also skyrocketed. Some of his seed
stock disappeared when he put it in the shed of a local collective
farm for safekeeping. And when he went to sell his harvest, his
buyers balked at the contracted price.
</P>
<P>
   He stuck it out for two seasons, but when the soybean contracts
collapsed he turned his crop into oil and sold it himself, in
five-quart bottles, to North Korean and Chinese workers who live in
these parts.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Kitayev is back driving a taxi, which was his first job
as a young man.
</P>
<P>
   Would he ever go back to commercial farming? Not now, said
Kitayev. The disappointments were too great, too bitter. ``Ten
years ago, there was an incentive to try,'' he said. `` I was an
optimist. But even optimists get tired.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
