<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 13:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1025 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-REBUILD-ART-70     07-31 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-REBUILD-ART-700(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FAMILY GONE, A LIFE TO REBUILD IN KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JANE PERLEZ    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   GORNJE OBRINJE, Yugoslavia _ The green countryside here is
strangely quiet; the sounds of children only intermittently pierce
the silence. The Yugoslav tanks and Serbian police cars that
intimidated the Kosovo Albanians who live here are gone and NATO's
troops are scarcely felt or even needed.
</P>
<P>
   The homes of the Delijaj family, brick dwellings scattered along
a dirt track, are also quiet as the men and women, seemingly
drained of emotion and uncertain of the future, rebuild lives
wrecked by a year of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Ten months ago, 21 members of the extended Delijaj family were
killed in a gully here, their bodies left strewn across the forest
floor. After a summer of guerrilla warfare against the Serbian
police, it was a dramatic display of Serbian violence, the mass
killing that first propelled NATO into threatening to bomb
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The bombing eventually came, in March. When it did, the
survivors of the killings here, unlike many other Kosovo Albanians
who fled to neighboring Macedonia and Albania, stayed put in this
Drenica Valley region, a heartland of the Albanians' Kosovo
Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The men, led by Imer Delijaj, 39, the young patriarch of the
family, fought, apparently prevailing in three battles against the
Serbian police and the Yugoslav army but then losing control of the
village in the final month.
</P>
<P>
   The women, the elderly and the children were dispatched to the
nearby town of Glogovac, where they holed up in a relative's house,
surviving on rations ferried from the village at night by Delijaj's
brother Enver. The village's teen-age boys, a favorite target of
the Serbian forces, were sent to hide in the Berisha Mountains
where, Delijaj said, they scavenged from nature.
</P>
<P>
   Now that the war is over, Delijaj, who said he was the local
commander covering seven villages for the Kosovo Liberation Army,
is proud of one thing.
</P>
<P>
   Almost every house in the village was badly damaged during the
fighting and six of his soldiers died, he said. But here, there was
no repeat of the killings last September. Those who were unarmed
survived, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to defend the young men during the war,'' he
said, as he sat on a cushion on the floor of his house. ``In some
villages many young men were killed in massacres. We sent ours into
hiding.''
</P>
<P>
   In the village, sustenance came from three cows and a cache of
flour. In the Berisha hills, the young men learned to survive on
grass and milk. ``It's very difficult for a human to die from
starvation,'' Delijaj said.
</P>
<P>
   In September he lost 10 members of his immediate family,
including his wife and three of his four children, in the killings
carried out by the Serbs, apparently in retaliation for many deaths
in house-to-house fighting with the guerrillas.
</P>
<P>
   Delijaj said his loss made him more determined in the fighting
this spring. Now he weighs his grief against the outcome: a Kosovo
regained for the Albanians by NATO bombs, nominally administered by
the United Nations and NATO-led peacekeepers _ a Kosovo formally
still part of Yugoslavia yet rapidly losing its Serbian minority.
</P>
<P>
   ``I lost a lot, and have a lot of pain that can't be
recovered,'' he said. ``But the weapon on my shoulder was worth it
because someone had to die. It is much better that 10 people of my
family die and we are freed from Serbian policemen always coming to
ask whether we have weapons. It's a national war _ if you don't
sacrifice, then you can't take the gain.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Delijaj _ who has remarried and served lunch of fresh
vegetables and bread prepared by his new wife, Nexhmije, to several
visitors _ expressed doubts about how permanent or how fulfilling
the victory might be.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is like a game of waiting,'' he said. ``It's not clear
from the agreements that Kosovo will be free in 10 years. There's
not a single clear definition for the future of Kosovo. It's not
freedom if you are free for one day. This country will be run by
NATO and the United Nations and the borders guarded by Serbia. And
then we go to the woods again.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As an example of what he sees as the hold Serbia keeps over
Kosovo, Delijaj said that thousands of Kosovo Albanians were still
being held in jails in Serbia after being sent there at the start
of the war.
</P>
<P>
   Western human rights organizations have reported that at least
2,000 Kosovo Albanians are in Serbian jails. Delijaj has no
evidence but is convinced the number is higher.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not freedom when our prisoners are held in Serbia,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Until he is certain that Kosovo will be independent and safe
from Serbian control, he will keep the best of his weapons, he
said. So far, he said, he and his fellow fighters in the village
have complied with NATO requests to hand in weapons, but _ in a
pattern believed common throughout much of the province, where it
is traditional to bear arms _ have turned in only their worst.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Delijaj said he no longer considered himself a soldier in
the rebel force. ``I said I would remain if they paid me,'' he
said. He does not want to be a policeman, as may other rebel
fighters who meet standards being established by the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he is considering returning to work at the
ferrous-nickel plant in Glogovac. He was employed there as an
electrician until 1992, when he was laid off, along with many other
Albanians, by the Serbian management. Now that many Serbs have
left, he will be able to reclaim his rightful job, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Delijaj seemed unimpressed by any of the political leaders in
Kosovo. ``I have one thought about Rugova, Krasniqi, Thaci and
Qosja,'' he said, reciting the last names of four prominent Kosovo
Albanian leaders representing competing streams of political
thought. ``They should take directions from the people and if they
were together it would be better for the people.''
</P>
<P>
   He is also unimpressed by the quality of the ministries of the
so-called provisional government of the Kosovo Liberation Army. He
went, he said, to one of the ministries where he had friends from
the guerrilla force to find out whether forensic experts would come
to examine the bodies of his slain family members. ``I went three
times and I still can't get an answer,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   If he can find the money, Delijaj said, he would like to conduct
a reburial. But first, he would like the Finnish pathologist Helena
Ranta, who came to the grave site last December but was barred by
the Serbs from doing much work, to return.
</P>
<P>
   Then, he said, he would like the exhumed bodies taken to a safer
place than the soggy ground near his house where they were hastily
buried last September and where today a tangle of wildflowers and
tall grass covers the makeshift graves.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
