<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1037 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYC-ARMSTRONG-ART-NYT     07-31 1258
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-ARMSTRONG-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ARMSTRONG, ROAD TO TOUR VICTORY BEGAN IN THE HILLS OF NORTH
CAROLINA 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo of Lance Armstrong is being sent to NYT photo
clients. Nonsubscribers can make individual purchase by calling
1-888-603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(th) 
 By FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong's victory last Sunday in the three-week Tour de
France was especially dramatic because of his return from
testicular cancer that had spread to his abdomen, lungs and brain.
</P>
<P>
   But Armstrong would never have ridden this year in bicycle
racing's most storied race, let alone win it, except for one
exhausting week in April 1998 on the roads and mountains of western
North Carolina with two exceptional friends.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's doctors say the cancer is gone now. His racing
career would have been gone, too, but for the rescue effort of
Chris Carmichael and Bob Roll, who subtly showed him how he could
help himself by racing again.
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael has coached Armstrong since Armstrong was a teen-ager
on the U.S. national team. Roll is a longtime friend of both
Carmichael and Armstrong. He has ridden in four Tours de France and
now, at age 38, races mountain bikes.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong's cancer was diagnosed in October 1996 and arrested by
two operations and four intense one-week chemotherapy sessions. He
sat out all of 1997, returned to racing in 1998, quit an
early-season race in France and flew home to Austin, Texas, ready
to retire from the sport.
</P>
<P>
   In telephone interviews last week _ Carmichael from France and
Roll from Denver _ reflected on what happened to change Armstrong's
mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never seemed comfortable in Europe,'' Carmichael said. ``He
wanted to ride, but I think because everybody wanted him to. He was
saying, `Cycling is not that important to me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When he came back, I saw he had never given himself a chance
to decompress. You go through what he did as a racer; you never let
doubt enter your mind. You just pound through it. Then, all of a
sudden, you're not racing, and things like brain surgery and
chemotherapy become more important.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're an office worker and get sick like that, you just
don't go back to work and pick up a pencil. Things are not the
same. Lance needed to understand that life would be different. He
needed time to sort things out. When he did, he realized he
couldn't quit that way, that if he was going to end his career he
had to find a race to end it.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong picked the U.S. pro championship in Philadelphia that
June for his final race. Carmichael had other ideas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought if he committed to one race, the desire might come
back to race again,'' Carmichael said. ``And if it didn't, who said
he had to race again? But we said if you're going to race even once
more, you have to be in shape. Let's put together a training camp
and get ready.''
</P>
<P>
   At Carmichael's suggestion, they decided to train out of Boone,
N.C. In 1995 and 1996, Armstrong won the Tour DuPont, then
America's leading stage race, partly because he rode so well in the
North Carolina hills, especially Beech Mountain near Boone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that getting him on those roads,'' Carmichael said,
``he would start reflecting that he was back where he started to
become the king of American cycling. He could get good memories
flowing again.''
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong needed a training partner. When Carmichael suggested
Roll, Armstrong said, ``That's perfect.'' And when Armstrong called
Roll, Roll's wife, Chiara, urged her husband to accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bob has incredible talent and personality,'' she said.
``He could boost anybody's morale. Bob made Lance remember all the
good things about cycling.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael was sure that would happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lance wasn't going to get down with Bob around,'' Carmichael
said. ``We knew he would be inspiring for Lance. Bob is loose, with
no anxiety. Riding with Bob on those hills could get Lance's
thoughts rolling.''
</P>
<P>
   Roll recalled a conversation with Armstrong the previous summer
at a bike show in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was at a real low point,'' Roll said. ``He couldn't get a
job and was pretty dismayed at the way the bike industry and teams
had come to treat him. The Tour de France was the last thing on his
mind. One thing that had sustained him when he was sick was the
thought of racing again. His goal was to be a healthy, functioning
person, but once he got to Europe in 1998 I think he had serious
doubts about the viability of the whole racing thing.''
</P>
<P>
   In April 1998, Armstrong and Roll began a training camp far from
a phone, far from any modern comforts. As Roll put it:
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris wanted somebody to remind Lance where the sport came
from, what the sport meant to people and to Lance and his
generation of riders. We had no specific agenda. We'd ride those
mountains for seven or eight hours a day, and we talked as we rode.
We talked about the future and what Lance could do.
</P>
<P>
   ``We trained hard in miserable weather conditions, but I don't
care if it's raining or hot, if I'm in France or Morocco, I just
love to be on a bike. Any day on a bike is a good day. Lance picked
up on that, and we rode with a little more intensity every time.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we went along, I tried to remind Lance how gifted he is as
a bike racer, how important it was for his peace of mind that he
try his hardest and take whatever comes, whether it's the Tour or a
local criterium in Texas. If you make your best effort, you should
be satisfied. If you turn away from the sport without having made
your best effort, it would always bug you.''
</P>
<P>
   Carmichael recalled that week in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just the three of us,'' he said. ``They rode their
bikes hard and I followed in a car. We rented a cabin, and at night
I did the cooking and they washed the dishes. In seven days, they
rode over 800 miles, mostly climbs. There was no flat land there.
</P>
<P>
   ``One day, after seven hours of riding, we did Beech Mountain.
Lance hit it and left Bob just as they got into the meat of the
climb. Lance's name was still painted on the road from two years
before, and that reminded him of the good times.
</P>
<P>
   ``April was beginning and it was 40 degrees and raining. Lance
was riding and I was yelling at him, just like in a race. I said,
`Want to get in the car? There are 20 miles to go.' He said, `No
way.'''
</P>
<P>
   At that point, Carmichael said, Armstrong changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he realized he wanted to race and he would do it for
his reasons,'' Carmichael said. ``I had a feeling he would be
stronger than before. I wasn't thinking he would win the Tour de
France, but I thought he would come back with a new attitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of those things you don't plan. You just have to go
in there for the right reasons. It's all a fairy tale right now,
but you don't go in there thinking you're writing a fairy tale. It
was a great time for him. It was closing a wound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't know if he was going to die. Here was a kid I started
coaching when he was 17 and I didn't know if I was going to his
funeral. But he came back and I coached him and cooked for him.
That's real satisfying. That week in the mountains brought him
back.''
</P>
<P>
   When the accounts from Carmichael and Roll were relayed to
Armstrong, he smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``That week was the turning point, absolutely,'' Armstrong said.
``Everything about it was special _ the people, the conversations,
the setting, the lousy weather, the cabin. I learned there that I
still loved racing and training. I learned I really loved it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
