<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-GUNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE AND SENATE BEGIN TASK OF RECONCILING GUN MEASURES
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By FRANK BRUNI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ As Americans puzzled over the latest deadly
shooting spree, House leaders appointed representatives Saturday to
a conference between House and Senate lawmakers on gun control, a
long-delayed, pivotal step toward the enactment of any new
restrictions on firearms by this Congress.
</P>
<P>
   But the fate of those restrictions remained in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders said that the compromise legislation
likely to emerge from the committee, which is charged with
reconciling the differences between the juvenile crime bills that
passed the House and the Senate, would not include the strict
regulation of gun shows that gun-control advocates in both parties
have, to this point, made their line in the sand.
</P>
<P>
   Those advocates could therefore decide to reject any package of
more modest measures that would come out of the committee as too
paltry.
</P>
<P>
   For their part, opponents of gun control could line up against
any new restrictions at all, creating enough negative votes from
the two camps to doom the legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, the outcome of one of the most bitter debates
in Congress this year may not be determined until September, weeks
after schools around the country have reopened. It was the shooting
deaths of 12 students and one teacher at Columbine High School in
Littleton, Colo., in April that started the current gun control
debate.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans and Democrats said Saturday that while the
shootings in Atlanta on Thursday, which occurred at an office
complex and left nine dead, might hasten a resolution, the incident
would probably not substantially change the positions of any of the
conference participants.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should permit the shooting in Atlanta
yesterday to detract from a thorough, sobering, deliberate dialogue
in the conference,'' Rep. Howard Coble, R-N.C., who is among the
conference members appointed by the House, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Nita Lowey, D-N.Y., said, ``If the Republican leadership
did not act after the tragedies in schools, I worry they won't act
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Democrats said they found hope in the fact that the House,
by a 305-84 vote, including a majority of Republicans, approved
instructions for the House conferees that called for some type of
regulation of gun shows that would ``effectively preclude criminals
and other prohibited purchasers'' from obtaining firearms.
</P>
<P>
   The instructions further said that conferees should reject ``any
measure that would weaken the effectiveness of background checks
currently conducted'' at gun shows, which is precisely what
Democrats had argued was what the Republican-favored measure did.
</P>
<P>
   But the language in the nonbinding instructions probably was too
vague, and the attention that most lawmakers paid to it was too
cursory, to conclude that House members who voted for the
instructions had become receptive to the more stringent gun-show
measure.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrat-sponsored gun-show measure that was approved in the
Senate _ but that failed in the House _ required all vendors at gun
shows to conduct mandatory background checks on customers and gave
those vendors up to three business days to get the results from law
enforcement officials. Currently, only licensed dealers at gun
shows must conduct those checks, while hobbyists and collectors are
exempt, and the dealers have three business days to do so.
</P>
<P>
   The much less-stringent measure that most House Republicans
favored, and that had passed in the House as an amendment to a
gun-control bill that ultimately failed, obligated all vendors to
conduct background checks but limited those checks to 24 hours.
Under this proposal, federally licensed dealers would, in fact,
have less time to conduct the checks.
</P>
<P>
   House Republican leaders had said that they would not object to
the inclusion of individual measures that had been approved by the
House before its gun-control package died.
</P>
<P>
   Those include child-safety locks and a ban on the possession of
assault weapons by most people under age 18.
</P>
<P>
   But they said the legislation would not include the more
stringent gun-show measure that a majority of House members
rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tom Daschle, the Democratic minority leader, said that
gun-control advocates would be hesitant to endorse any legislation
that lacks what they consider a strong gun-show provision.
</P>
<P>
   The reconciliation conference will probably begin next week.
Senate leaders had appointed that chamber's conferees on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Henry Hyde of Illinois, the senior House Republican among
the conferees, discouraged any hopes of a conclusion before
Congress begins a monthlong recess on Aug. 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect this to be a difficult _ but certainly not impossible
_ conference,'' Hyde said.
</P>
<P>
   The three Republican Senators appointed to the conference are
Orrin Hatch of Utah, Strom Thurmond of South Carolina and Jeff
Sessions of Alabama. The two Democratic Senators are Patrick J.
Leahy of Vermont and Edward M. Kennedy of Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   The House appointed different conferees for different aspects of
the juvenile crime legislation. For gun control, all the conferees,
seven Republicans and five Democrats, are from the House Judiciary
Committee.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
