<HEADER>
A1050 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GA-SHOOT-TRADERS-ART-     07-31 1070
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GA-SHOOT-TRADERS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR DAY TRADERS, A MOMENT OF SILENCE AND SOME SOUL-SEARCHING 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Calif., Texas, Conn.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By AMY HARMON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The pause in the relentless stream of stock tips scrolling up
the screen in the Internet chat room called Daytraders was brief,
and it was mechanically enforced. But after the shooting spree last
week at two Atlanta firms that specialize in the rapid-fire buying
and selling of stocks known as day trading, several hundred online
investors observed a virtual moment of silence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violent acting-out is often associated with high levels of
stress, and we cannot ignore the setting in which he chose to vent
his rage,'' the chat room's manager, David Mason, told his
assemblage on Friday, referring to Mark Barton, who killed nine
people at the two trading sites before shooting himself.
</P>
<P>
   In cyberspace and in trading rooms, many of the nation's
swelling ranks of day traders repudiated the notion that Barton's
own day-trading activities contributed to the violent outburst.
</P>
<P>
   ``This had nothing to do with day trading,'' said a middle-aged
woman getting into a Mercedes convertible in the parking lot of the
All-Tech Investment Group in Montvale, N.J., on Friday afternoon.
``The guy was a nut,'' said the woman, who described herself as a
day trader.
</P>
<P>
   But the incident _ along with the mediocre performance of the
stock market in recent days _ has also prompted a smidgen of
soul-searching among the amateur investors who use the instant
availability of stock information via the Internet to buy and sell
the same stocks within a single trading day for quick personal
profit, or loss.
</P>
<P>
   ``Day trading's stresses are not more or less than most jobs,
but there are different kinds of stresses,'' wrote an investor who
uses the name Eileen in the Daytraders chat room. ``E.G., there is
no security at all, and no regular paycheck.''
</P>
<P>
   Those particular stresses, like coping with wild gains and
losses from day to day, are unfamiliar to most Americans, who have
begun to indulge in day trading by the thousands only in recent
years. That is in part why All-Tech, where Barton once traded in
the Atlanta office and where he opened fire last week, employs a
psychologist as part of its training program for those wanting to
become day traders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to train people in what goes through your mind when
you're trading,'' said Mark Shefts, president of All-Tech. ``We
want to help make people aware of what goes through your mind when
you're making money and when you're losing money.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems that being aware of what you are doing, however, does
not always help you stop.
</P>
<P>
   A 31-year-old San Francisco lawyer said that in addition to
borrowing as much as he was allowed against his stock portfolio, he
had borrowed $20,000 from his credit card company and put the money
directly into the market. As a result, at times he borrowed up to
$40,000 to buy securities, mostly in Internet stocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``During conference calls and drafting sessions, I would sneak
out to check my portfolio,'' said the lawyer, who asked that his
name not be used because he did not want his firm to know about his
trading or his family to know about his debts. But, he said, he
could not resist the potential payoff. ``I was a gambler sitting at
a table'' in Vegas, he said. ``My palms got sweaty thinking about
how much money I could make.''
</P>
<P>
   When the market soured, the lawyer said, he simply had to admit
to himself, ``Well, that was dumb.'' He then waited out the market
until it rebounded, and paid off the interest on the money he
borrowed to buy the securities in the first place. He remains
heavily in debt.
</P>
<P>
   Still, while psychologists warn about the stress of living in a
state of perpetual high risk and investment experts warn that
long-term investing has proved far more profitable, most day
traders blame the mechanics of the system for their heightened
sense of anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   A telephone interview on Friday with a 37-year-old day trader in
Texas was continually interrupted as he checked the status of the
unfulfilled order he had placed minutes before with the online
brokerage Charles Schwab.
</P>
<P>
   ``They hold an order for up to eight minutes,'' fumed the
investor, who said his account had dropped to $94,000 from $120,000
a month ago. ``That's fine for some old guy who buys Pepsi one
morning and sells it the next.''
</P>
<P>
   But the delay foiled his ability to take advantage of an uptick
of three-eighths in the stock price. ``My order was at one-eighth
and I would have sold at the half,'' he said. ``I'd already be out
with three or four hundred dollars in my pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   The trader, who is known in online trading chat rooms as Captain
Jack but did not want to see his real name in print, pays someone
else to run his oil business so he can trade full time.
</P>
<P>
   Jokes about ``going trader,'' replacing ``going postal'' as the
term for seemingly random violent eruptions, circulated through
day-trading discussion forums on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Gardner, co-founder of the Motley Fool, one of the oldest
investment information sites on the Internet, said he thought there
was a connection between Barton's trading and his rampage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not fair to say that day trading caused this, but I do
think there's a casino mentality to it that would tend to draw
somebody who was very intense,'' Gardner said. ``It makes sense
that the outcome of that intense personality and intense failure
would compound the likelihood of this kind of behavior.''
</P>
<P>
   Gardner, an advocate of long-term investing, admonishes day
traders to face the fact that their strategy is just ``bad math.''
</P>
<P>
   That may be true, but most day traders seem to agree with Jim
Cox, a 20-year-old senior at the University of Connecticut who
thinks it is possible to beat the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in this chat room for a couple of years, and I've
noticed all the nicknames change,'' said Cox, who frequents the
Daytraders chat room. In less than a year, Cox said, he has made
$190,000, sometimes borrowing as much as $100,000 against his
account. ``I'm assuming 80 percent of them fail. But you have to be
smart. If I keep going the way I am, I can make $10,000 a week
easy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1339EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
