<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 13:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEST-BAN-TREATY-NYT     07-31 0600
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-BAN-TREATY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER CHINESE SPY SCANDAL, NEW SUPPORT FOR TEST BAN TREATY
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By WILLIAM J. BROAD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the wake of the Chinese spy scandal, support is growing in
the United States for ratification of the Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty, a global accord meant to end the development of new kinds
of nuclear arms. The process of treaty deliberation and approval
had been moribund for nearly two years, but is now showing signs of
life.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday nine of the nation's top nuclear scientists and
experts, including architects of the first atom and hydrogen bombs,
wrote the Senate to urge the ratification of the treaty, which is
sponsored by the United Nations. Its enactment, they said, would
help block damage from Chinese atomic espionage.
</P>
<P>
   In May, a House committee, led by Rep. Christopher Cox,
R-Calif., said China had stolen secret data on seven of America's
most advanced warheads.
</P>
<P>
   Backers of the test ban see it as a way of blocking any nation
from making new kinds of nuclear weapons and the world from
engaging in new arms races. Such a ban is possible because makers
of nuclear arms in most cases must detonate new designs in fiery
blasts to spot flaws and insure potency. So the absence of
explosive testing acts as a brake on nuclear arms development.
</P>
<P>
   The nine experts, in a letter sponsored by the Union of
Concerned Scientists, a private group based in Cambridge, Mass.,
that strongly backs arms control, said the Senate's ratification of
the treaty ``would greatly help to protect the United States
against the weaponization of stolen nuclear secrets.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We may never know whether Chinese nuclear weapons development
benefited significantly from espionage,'' the signers added. But
the treaty, they said, would help keep any lost secrets from
speeding the development of deadly arms.
</P>
<P>
   The letter quoted Harold Agnew, a former director of the federal
center for the design of nuclear arms at Los Alamos, N.M. ``If
China doesn't resume testing,'' he said, ``no harm will possibly
have been done other than to our egos.''
</P>
<P>
   The letter was sent on Friday to all senators by the Washington
office of the Union of Concerned Scientists.
</P>
<P>
   The nine experts who signed the letter are Dr. Hans A. Bethe, a
Nobel laureate who helped design the first atom bomb; Dr. Freeman
Dyson, an emeritus physicist at the Institute for Advanced Study in
Princeton; Dr. Richard L. Garwin, a weapons expert who has long
advised the federal government; Dr. Kurt Gottfried, a Cornell
University physicist who is chairman of the Union of Concerned
Scientists; Dr. Marshall N. Rosenbluth, a pioneer of hydrogen
bombs; Dr. Jeremiah D. Sullivan, a physicist at the University of
Illinois; Adm. Stansfield Turner, a past director of Central
Intelligence; Dr. Herbert F. York, a past director of the Lawrence
Livermore National Laboratory; and Adm. Elmo R. Zumwalt Jr., a
former Chief of Naval Operations.
</P>
<P>
   Federal experts suspect China may already have used some stolen
American secrets in prototype devices detonated before Beijing
ended its nuclear blasts in 1996 and signed the test ban. If so,
test-ban advocates say, the treaty's ratification and global
strengthening would help limit further damage by making it
difficult for China to resume testing.
</P>
<P>
   The Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty has won the backing of 152
countries, including the United States, which pushed for its
adoption and was the first country to sign. President Clinton
called it ``the longest-sought, hardest-fought prize in the history
of arms control.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
