<SLUG> BC-MIDEAST-PALESTINIANS-460&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PALESTINIANS REBUFF BARAK ON REVISING PULLOUT PLAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ETHAN BRONNER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Palestinian officials said Saturday that an Israeli
request for changes in the two sides' latest peace agreement was
not acceptable and that the two-week delay agreed on last week for
considering those changes was a waste of time.
</P>
<P>
   A statement issued Saturday following a Friday night meeting of
the cabinet of Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader, said it is
``impossible to renegotiate such an agreement after it has gained
official status.''
</P>
<P>
   The chief negotiator for the Palestinians, Saeb Erekat, added in
a telephone interview that the Palestinian position has been clear
and consistent _ that the agreement, the Wye River memorandum,
which trades land for security, must be carried out without delay.
</P>
<P>
   The accord, negotiated and signed under Benjamin Netanyahu, the
former Israeli prime minister, calls for three Israeli land
transfers in the West Bank to Palestinian control. Israel carried
out the first phase but then Netanyahu said the Palestinians were
not living up to their commitments under the framework and canceled
any further transfers. Shortly thereafter, new Israeli elections
were called and the agreement was frozen.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Ehud Barak, the new Israeli prime minister, who has
vowed to sign a comprehensive agreement, met with Arafat on the
border between Israel and the Gaza Strip. At that time, Arafat
accepted a two-week deadline to determine whether the Palestinians
would accept a proposal to rewrite the time frame and terms of the
Wye accord, which was concluded last fall in Wye River, Md.
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Barak would like to fold the third redeployment
called for under Wye into a final peace agreement between the two
sides rather than carry it out and then negotiate again. This is
partly because, after the third withdrawal, a number of Israeli
settlements in the West Bank would be isolated and he fears that a
heightened risk of terrorism and other tensions could derail the
process again.
</P>
<P>
   But Barak has also said that if, after the two weeks, the
Palestinians insisted on sticking to the Wye formula, he would live
up to his side of the agreement.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Barak, Meirav Parsi-Zadok, reiterated that on
Saturday but again made clear that the prime minister fears that
the Wye redeployments could lead to trouble before a full accord is
negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians, who felt Netanyahu had not acted in good
faith, are suspicious and say they see carrying out the plan as a
test of the new Israeli leader's credibility.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine if the Palestinian side had asked to reopen the
negotiations,'' Erekat said. ``They would have said of us, `These
people are not honest and not reliable.'''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Erekat said that last Tuesday at Erez, Arafat showed no interest
in redefining the Wye agreement.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Arafat told Barak 17 times that he cannot accept his
proposal and Barak insisted 17 times that he think about it,''
Erekat said. ``We do not want to be seen in a position of rejecting
or refusing anything. The Israelis are the ones who want the
changes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Palestinians also demanded that Barak dismantle hilltop
outposts set up by Jewish settlers in the West Bank since the
signing of the Wye accord last fall. The settlers hope to make it
harder for Barak to give back land.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Parsi-Zadok, the Barak spokeswoman, said the government's
position is that any new outpost set up since Barak took power
would be dismantled _ something which occurred last week _ but
those set up before the new government took office would be subject
to review by an inter-ministerial committee to be set up this week.
</P>
<P>
   Arafat was in Egypt Saturday meeting with President Hosni
Mubarak. Barak was to leave Sunday for Moscow to discuss Russia's
role in the peace efforts. The Syrian president, Hafez al-Assad,
who has sent clear signals of his willingness to restart
negotiations with the Israelis, visited Moscow in June.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
