<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: HE WENT THE DISTANCE BEFORE THIS RACE BEGAN 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Lance Armstrong burst out of Cancerland last week, bicycle
wheels buzzing, to win the Tour de France and an immediate place in
several different icon queues; not only is he an inspiration to
patients and another example of American resurgence in the world
sports arena, he is also a role model for celebrities _ he had
actually completed the mythological hero's journey that was once
the qualifying tournament for superstars.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine covers, however, had already been assigned to John
F. Kennedy Jr., whose poignant tragedy is somewhat less threatening
than Armstrong's victory. Like the early deaths of Kennedy's father
and uncle, Martin Luther King Jr. and Malcolm X, John John's
passing will be used to feed our imagination with fantasies of what
might have been, even though he never even pretended to play in
their league. The latest organ of celebrifiction, Tina Brown's Talk
magazine, will probably add to all this when the first issue
appears this week.
</P>
<P>
   There's not much to imagine about Armstrong. At 27, he became
only the second American to win one of the most physically
demanding athletic events. Apparently he did it without the
performance-enhancing drugs that most Europeans favor. But then, he
was cranked in ways almost unimaginable; he had just come through
the Tour de Chemo, where you only have to finish to get the
winner's yellow jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Winning the Tour de France three years after a diagnosis of
testicular cancer that had spread to his lungs and brain, Armstrong
became a version of what some activist groups for the disabled
call, in both admiration and denigration, a ``super-crip.''
</P>
<P>
   He is an example of what a determined person can accomplish as
well as an unfair comparison to those who can't quite measure up.
Testicular cancer has far higher cure rates than most cancers, even
in its later stages, although its drug treatment is nasty and
temporarily debilitating. In the cancer patient's struggle to
return to everyday life, Armstrong had the advantage of an
uncomplicated goal _ climbing back on his bike and pedaling like
crazy.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, his accomplishment was astounding. Sportsman of
the Year is not a big enough award for him. His triumph ushered in
a week in which the major league umpires reversed their decision to
resign, the Detroit Lions star Barry Sanders retired (or made a bid
for a trade) because his teammates weren't good enough for him,
General Manager Bill Walsh of the San Francisco 49ers hired the
thug-back Lawrence Phillips without the standard hypocritical
decency of either alibi or apology, Mark McGwire briefly held the
home run lead without benefit of a blood or urine test (is he ahead
or behind last year's Andro pace?) and nine UCLA football players
pleaded guilty to illegally using handicapped parking placards on
campus (they should have pleaded moral handicap).
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, Armstrong must be anointed sports' Grown-Up of the
Year.
</P>
<P>
   In the world stage queue, Armstrong's victory followed triumphs
by the U.S. women's World Cup soccer team and Pete Sampras, and the
emerging promise of Marion Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Revisionism has already begun to niggle at the soccer champions.
Did they have an unfair advantage, coming from America, ahead of
most of the rest of the world in women's team sports, thanks to the
feminist movement and Title IX? And what about the defining
photo-op, Brandi Chastain's stripping down to her Nike Wonderwoman
bra? Did that make it the World B-Cup? Had she rehearsed the move?
(Did Wade Boggs practice riding before circling Yankee Stadium on a
police horse after the 1996 World Series?) One hopes she did. We
could feel we are with responsible people.
</P>
<P>
   Even the great Sampras, who seems only slightly less extroverted
than the Great Gretzky, has come in for his share of sniping,
despite his amazing statistics. Last month, he won his sixth
Wimbledon singles title, which was also his 12th Grand Slam title.
He is clearly too good, this robojock, his serve too hard, his
strokes too schooled.
</P>
<P>
   I like that about Sampras. His intensity is focused in a
professional way, unlike, say, John McEnroe or Jimmy Connors, who
needed to stay in their zones with the equivalent of tantrums and
trash talk, which is as much about keeping one's demons at bay as
it is about distracting the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Up ahead is a potential champion whose sport goes on hiatus for
years at a time. Marion Jones could win as many as four gold medals
this month at the track and field world championships in Seville,
Spain, perhaps five at the Sydney Olympics. But she better have a
great backstory or some serious attitude if we are to pay attention
much past the Games.
</P>
<P>
   And how long will Lance stay on our radar? In this overheated
time when a golfer's winning putt and a pitcher's third strike are
both described as courageous, here comes this guy riding too fast
on skinny wheels over scary roads. Of course, he had such a
headstart. Desperately riding away from death, he couldn't be
properly intimidated by a bicycle race. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
