<HEADER>
A1063 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RESTAURANT-TAX-LOBBY-     07-31 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RESTAURANT-TAX-LOBBY-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESTAURANT ASSOCIATION SEES ITS PERSISTENCE PAY OFF 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BIZ-TAX-BREAKS.) 
(js) 
 By JOEL BRINKLEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Standing on a ballroom stage in Las Vegas, Nev.,
earlier this year, Herman Cain, president of the National
Restaurant Association, sang to his members, crooning in a rich
baritone: ``If I can see it, I can do it; if I just believe,
there's nothing to it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe I can fly; I believe I can touch the sky!''
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, the unusual performance from the industry's
top lobbyist raised a few eyebrows among the restaurateurs in the
audience, who were there for an association convention. But in
truth, Cain had reason to crow because the restaurant industry is
flush.
</P>
<P>
   Americans are eating out more often than ever before. Average
check prices are higher than they have ever been. More than 10.2
million people are employed in restaurants, more than at any time
in the past. And total industry sales are expected to reach a
record high this year, $354 billion.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, association lobbyists managed to convince House
Republicans this summer that restaurants were suffering enduring
harm from the government's decision in 1993 to reduce the tax
deductibility of business meals, to 50 percent from 80 percent. The
tax cut bill passed by the House includes a heavily lobbied
provision that raises it back to 80 percent. The tax bill that
passed the Senate on Friday does not contain the provision, meaning
more lobbying lies ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1993, when the industry was trying to block the cut in
the tax deduction, the restaurant association ran television
commercials warning of disaster for the industry's most vulnerable
employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a waitress, and a good one,'' Jan Bergwall, from a small
town in Maryland, said in one advertisement. ``I'd better be,
because my three sons depend on me. But I might not have a job much
longer. President Clinton's economic plan cuts business-meal
deductibility. That would throw 165,000 people out of work. I need
this job.''
</P>
<P>
   The lobbying effort failed. And as it turned out, the
association's own statistics show that restaurant employment set
records in 1994 and again in 1995, when restaurants added more than
300,000 employees.
</P>
<P>
   The association is using the same approach now to fight a
proposed increase in the minimum wage. Recently it released the
results of a survey taken of its members, and the restaurant owners
reported cutting ``more than 146,000 jobs from restaurant
payrolls'' after previous minimum-wage increases, in 1996 and 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, Bureau of Labor Statistics figures
show that restaurant employment nationwide increased by 162,400
jobs in 1996 and 119,200 in 1997. Lee Culpepper, a vice president
with the association, acknowledged the overall gain in jobs, but
argued that the rate of increase would have been higher, if not for
the minimum-wage increases.
</P>
<P>
   For other lobbying aims, the association likes to make the point
that its membership is not dominated by minimum-wage workers. ``A
popular misconception about the restaurant industry is that it is a
collection of low-wage jobs, with nominal impact on a region's
economy,'' one association policy paper says. Restaurant employees
at all levels make more money than most people believe, the
association says, and play an important role in regional economies.
</P>
<P>
   Because of its broad range of interests, the trade group expends
copious energy lobbying on issues that do not seem immediately
relevant to the industry. For example, the restaurant association
has lobbied to block the government from taxing airline
frequent-flier miles. Tourists eat out, Culpepper explained. And
frequent-flier miles drive tourism.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Even when it works on issues of direct concern to restaurants,
the association sometimes uses arguments that do not bear on its
direct self-interest.
</P>
<P>
   For example, it raises constitutional concerns against a
proposal to lower the legal blood-alcohol level for drivers to 0.08
percent. In most states now it is 0.10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The lobbying arguments are framed around earnest constitutional
concerns: ``States would be forced to adopt a 0.08 blood-alcohol
level or lose precious federal highway dollars,'' one association
fact sheet warns. That, it adds, is not the way democracy should
work, as ``states should have the flexibility to enact measures
that they feel would work best in their particular state.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact sheet never mentions a more fundamental concern:
restaurants might sell fewer drinks.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant association, founded in 1919, is one of the
oldest trade groups in the city. But for most of its history it was
a sleepy, back-water organization. In recent years, though, it has
climbed into the top level of Washington lobbying groups. ``Last
year, Congress didn't pass anything that hurt us,'' Elaine Z.
Graham, a senior vice president for the association, said with a
smile and a lift of the chin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1401EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1064 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-GWYNN-BOGGS-ART-N     07-31 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-GWYNN-BOGGS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOGETHER BUT SEPARATELY, GWYNN AND BOGGS APPROACH 3,000 CLUB
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Graphic on Boggs, Gwynn and Ripken is being sent to NYT
graphics clients. Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by
calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The way they talk, Tony Gwynn and Wade Boggs would be delighted
if they could somehow link bats, take simultaneous swings and
stroll into the 3,000-hit club together.
</P>
<P>
   They would probably settle for attaining membership the same
night.
</P>
<P>
   That night should come this week. Entering Saturday's games,
Boggs needed eight hits and Gwynn nine to become Nos. 22 and 23, or
in their thinking perhaps, Nos. 22 and 22a, to reach 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' Boggs said, meaning the proximity in
which they will achieve a plateau they innocently embarked on 17
years ago, both as rookies in 1982. ``Our careers have paralleled
each other for so long, I think it's fitting that we do it in the
same year.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn said, ``I do, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The two hitting marvels were on a conference call together last
week and the admiration and respect they have for each other came
through clearly.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me, Wade was the guy who set the standard,'' Gwynn said.
``When I broke in to the big leagues, Wade was there already.''
</P>
<P>
   Boggs, two years older than Gwynn, began the 1982 season with
Boston. Gwynn started the season in the minor leagues and was
promoted by San Diego in mid-July.
</P>
<P>
   Boggs batted .349 his rookie year, then won the first of his
five batting titles in 1983, hitting .361. Gwynn batted .289 that
first season, then .309 in 1983 after beginning the season late
because of a fractured wrist. He won the first of his eight batting
titles in 1984 with a .351 average.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wade came out of the blocks and had seven straight 200-hit
seasons,'' Gwynn said, referring to the seasons 1983 through '89.
``He was just rolling on. He was the type of hitter I wanted to be
like. I was having success in the National League, but not at the
level he was having. He became the hunted. He's the guy you had to
chase. He became the guy I wanted to be like. I wanted to emulate
what he did.''
</P>
<P>
   Boggs said a key to the relationship they have maintained at a
distance is that they have always played in different leagues, with
Boggs in the American and Gwynn in the National.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never had to compete against each other,'' Boggs said. ``I
never had to worry about Tony, like is he passing me? I could root
for him to win the batting title. I had to fight Carew and Brett
and all those guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sat back and relaxed when I would read about what Tony was
doing. I didn't have to treat him as an adversary. It's like we
were allies. I was pulling for him. It's hard to pull for someone
you're competing against. It helps my stock if Tony does well.''
</P>
<P>
   That's because they have always hit alike. ``My style and Wade's
style were very similar,'' Gwynn said. ``There's nothing wrong with
it. You do it over the course of 162 games. It's not flamboyant.
You grind it out. If you come and watch us play one game, you're
not going to be impressed. If you watch us play 20 games, you say,
`He can play the game.'''
</P>
<P>
   When Gwynn and Boggs get their 3,000th hits, it will mark the
sixth time that two players reached the magic number in the same
season. The last pair to do it were Robin Yount and George Brett,
who became Nos. 17 and 18 three weeks apart in September 1992.
Keeping with the togetherness theme, they were inducted into the
Hall of Fame last Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But no season has produced three 3,000 hitters. This one should.
</P>
<P>
   Barring injury, Cal Ripken, who needed 34 before Saturday, will
join Gwynn and Boggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many try to climb that mountain and very few get up there,''
Boggs said. ``Now Tony and Cal and I are on the verge of sticking
our flag in that mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   The cyclical nature of the achievement has been interesting.
Between 1942 and 1970, Stan Musial (in 1958) was the only player
who made it. Then seven players rushed to 3,000 in the 1970s, the
most in any decade. But between 1979 and 1992, Rod Carew (in 1985)
was the only one. When this year's three players make it, the '90s
will have produced eight players with 3,000.
</P>
<P>
   The kindred spirits Gwynn and Boggs will be the first to reach
3,000 since Paul Molitor got there with two weeks left in 1996.
Seven of the last 11 did it in September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked Molitor last year what to expect,'' Boggs said. ``He
said just treat it as a roller-coaster ride. That's what it is. Ups
and downs. One day you don't get hits; the next you get two or
three. He said enjoy the ride. That's the perspective I've tried to
keep in my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn said he spoke with Molitor just before spring training
this year. ``When you get to this point, you have to have fun,''
Gwynn said Molitor told him. ``You can't get caught up in all the
hype. Do the things you've always done. That's the advice I'm
trying to take.''
</P>
<P>
   On the conference call, Gwynn and Boggs had exhausted their
time, though they could have offered much more.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wade, go get 'em, man,'' Gwynn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, man, good luck,'' Boggs replied.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good luck,'' Gwynn said, and they hung up.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
