<HEADER>
A1065 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MIAMI-TRAFFIC-ART-NYT     07-31 1175
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MIAMI-TRAFFIC-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IT'S THE TRAFFIC, NOT THE HEAT, THAT MAKES MIAMI TORPID
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo and map are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(nk) 
 By RICK BRAGG    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ While driving in Miami may be a red-faced,
stress-filled,
curse-under-your-breath-as-you-glare-hatefully-at-other-drivers
nightmare, parking has never been easier here in the nation's
third-most-congested city.
</P>
<P>
   Commuters will park for long minutes in passing lanes on the
hated Route 836 connector between Miami International Airport and
downtown, long enough to have a sandwich, make a few telephone
calls or, some commuters say, grind their teeth until they hurt.
</P>
<P>
   They can park for as long as an hour, with the help of an
accident or some minor road construction, in the commuter lane of
Interstate 95, although they do have to put their car back in
``Drive'' every few minutes or so, to creep forward a few feet.
</P>
<P>
   And on U.S. 1, a main north-to-south road that commuters have
nicknamed ``Useless 1,'' the whole six-lane highway can become a
parking lot at any time of day, though at rush hour it would be
faster to run along the roofs of cars than to actually try to drive
in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's enough time to get to know the person sitting in the
car next to you,'' said Dolly Hernandez, who lives in West Dade and
works for a law firm in downtown Miami. She takes Route 836 to
Interstate 95. ``I dread getting up in the morning,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, people tell traffic horror stories the way they used to
tell crime horror stories of the Miami of 10 years ago. Gridlock
has replaced home invasions and drug murders on the front pages of
South Florida newspapers, as Miami chokes on its own traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It cuts years from your life,'' said Irene Rodriguez, who
lives in southwest Kendall, south of Miami, and commutes to
downtown Miami and her job as an assistant vice president for CBG
Bank. ``It seems like I spend half my morning in the car.''
</P>
<P>
   Daily commuters, city planners and politicians view it as a
major issue _ if not the major issue _ in deciding this city's
future. Sandwiched by the Atlantic Ocean and the Everglades, with
almost no room left for urban sprawl, Miami-Dade's population of
just over two million can only become more dense and its roads more
jammed, transit experts and city planners agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``I used to enjoy driving,'' said Danny Alvarez, director of the
Miami-Dade Transit Authority. ``Now, I dread the thought. Our
population has grown _ in 10 years by more than 20 percent _ and
our transportation system has not kept up.''
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, voters in Miami-Dade County went to the polls
on Thursday to decide on a 1-cent sales tax increase intended to
abolish many toll booths and raise an estimated $240 million in
annual tax money for expanding the city's train service _ called
Metrorail _ and its bus service.
</P>
<P>
   But voters turned it down, saying that an improved mass transit
system would not be used enough to justify the tax in a city where
almost everyone seems to have a car. Others said they simply could
not trust officials and local government to effectively use the
money from that sales tax because of a legacy of corruption by
public officials in South Florida. Either way, the sales tax seemed
to offer no guaranteed solutions for the gridlock people here are
forced to live in.
</P>
<P>
   Even Mayor Alex Penelas of Miami-Dade said, just before the
vote, that it would not bring an end to congestion.
</P>
<P>
   The tax vote was designed to give people a choice, of whether to
drive or ride an expanded mass transit system, Alvarez said, ``and
keep it from getting worse.''
</P>
<P>
   Norman Braman, a wealthy car dealership owner, arts patron and
the leader of the anti-tax movement, said that people would not
ride mass transit if they could drive, and that the proposed
expanded Metrorail system _ the current system has been called a
failure by many people here _ would waste $100 million a mile. That
is how much it was expected to cost to build it.
</P>
<P>
   He warned, in the last-minute campaign against the tax, that
much of that money, knowing Miami-Dade County's history with such
projects, would ``disappear. It's special interest money,'' Braman
said.
</P>
<P>
   Miami area residents are so used to corruption and wasted money
that it is almost an accepted form of doing business. They would
trade a little corruption, if it meant an open passing lane.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is your worst nightmare,'' Ms. Hernandez said of her
commute. ``I wake up at 5 in the morning so I can make it to work
by 9. When I get to work it feels like I have already been awake
all day and like I had just driven down from the Panhandle to get
here.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   It is no better in more residential areas, like Coral Way, a
banyan-shaded, pretty street that desperate, cursing commuters
swarmed to in failed expectations after giving up on the
glacier-movement of U.S. 1. But at least on Coral Way, one gets to
park in the shade.
</P>
<P>
   Traffic is so bad that some commuters guard their ``secret
routes'' like maps to buried treasure.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Paulino, a process server who works in downtown Miami,
used to commute from Cutler Ridge, in southern Miami-Dade County,
in traffic that backed up ``for miles and miles'' on U.S. 1. ``It
was atrocious,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He began to view his commute almost as a military operation.
``It was a mission to get downtown,'' he said. ``I got to the point
that I learned shortcuts, and I would keep them all a secret
because I didn't want everyone else to catch on.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Paulino gave up. He moved in close to downtown. ``I'm a
happy man,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   But as much as Miamians hate their traffic, they love their
cars. With the possible exception of the cellular phone, the car is
their favorite piece of machinery.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wouldn't use public transportation even if it was free,''
Ms. Hernandez said. ``It's too much of a hassle. People like that
independent feeling of driving to work themselves, in the comfort
of their own car with their own radio.''
</P>
<P>
   Planning experts agree that it is hard to change such attitudes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most people,'' said Elizabeth Platter Zyberk, dean of the
school of architecture at the University of Miami, ``are afraid of
change, as soon as someone proposes something new such as a transit
line through their neighborhoods.''
</P>
<P>
   It will only get worse. ``In 20 years, we expect a 35 percent
population increase,'' said Jose Luis Mesa, director of the
county's Metropolitan Planning Organization.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, traffic keeps on, well, not moving.
</P>
<P>
   Vivian de las Cuevas, a summer associate at a downtown law firm,
lives in Coral Gables, which is just seven miles away. ``If I leave
work between 5 and 6,'' she said, ``I won't make it home for two
hours.''
</P>
<P>
   It lends new meaning to the song lyric:
</P>
<P>
   ``They paved paradise
</P>
<P>
   and put up a parking lot.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1415EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
