</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, Aug. 1, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   A tempering of the extreme heat across the Northeast and Middle
West will occur Sunday as a cool front passes slowly southeast
across the regions. Scattered showers and thunderstorms will form
near the leading edge of the cooler air over the Ohio Valley and
interior Northeast Sunday morning. Meanwhile, hazy and hot
conditions along the Northeast seaboard will yield to clouds and
spotty thunderstorms as the front approaches from the west later
Sunday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Breezes from the north and northwest will import noticeably
cooler and less humid air into the Great Lakes region Sunday.
Beneath ample sunshine, afternoon readings will return to
seasonable levels from Chicago to Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms will erupt from the
west-central Plains to the northern Middle Atlantic states as a
slow-moving cold front undercuts and lifts very humid air. The rain
may be heavy in western parts of Nebraska and Kansas where winds
from the east ascend the sloping terrain. Farther south, abundant
sunshine will stretch from Texas to Georgia where afternoon
temperatures will approach 100 degrees in many areas.
</P>
<P>
   Scattered clouds and isolated thunderstorms will migrate to the
southeastern Rockies on Sunday. The storms will be most numerous
during the afternoon when the uneven heating of the varied terrain
promotes vigorous rising currents of moistened air. Plenty of sun
and warm conditions will cover the western Rockies and West Coast,
though morning clouds will be found along the immediate coast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: THE END IS NEAR
</P>
<P>
   While July 1999 was one of the warmest of record in the
Northeast, the upcoming month brings the hope for cooler air. In
August, the lessening daylight will contribute to a slight decline
of temperature. Typically, the nation experiences a degree drop in
average monthly temperature between July and August. An exception
is near the Gulf and southern Atlantic coasts where still rising
water temperatures delay the temperature fall. The warmer waters
provide fertile breeding ground for tropical storms which often
show an increase in frequency during August.
</P>
</TEXT>
