<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, Aug. 1, moved Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   _ On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   CELEBRATION-SCHOOL-REVIEW (Celebration, Fla.) _ Trouble in
educational paradise: When the Celebration School first opened
three years ago in this town created by Walt Disney Co., it was
ballyhooed as an educational gem designed by top experts from
across the country. It was to be a world-class institution that
would take children from kindergarten through 12th-grade using the
most advanced educational methods. But now, parents are withdrawing
their children from the school. By Douglas Frantz. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-DICTATORSHIP-REVIEW (Undated) _ Recent developments in
China indicate that totalitarian regimes, already flummoxed by the
fax machine and the cellular phone, may be facing the biggest
high-tech challenge of all in the Internet. By Barbara Crossette.
(`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   RAGE-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Atlanta office massacre seemed to
some like another gruesome indicator of a trend toward workplace
violence and rage. But it is far from clear that what has been
dubbed `workplace rage' is really on the rise, say researchers. And
similar doubts have been raised about other so-called `rages,'
namely road rage and air rage. Anecdotes are being christened as
trends, says one expert. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   WRITING-REVIEW (Undated) _ Creative individuals are
`workshopping' short stories, novellas and plays. Others have
screenplays or theater pieces `in development.' Still others engage
in `content' creation. They create content, or `provide' it, for
the Internet. Actively productive souls everywhere are developing
scripts. Workshopping books. Providing content. Doesn't anyone
WRITE anymore? Why don't they call it WRITING? By Jenny Lyn Bader.
</P>
<P>
   WOMEN-ASYLUM-REVIEW (Undated) _ No one denies that their stories
are horrific: rape, beatings, genital mutilation or the threat of
it. But foreign women seeking asylum from violence at the hands of
family members in their home countries have received a mixed
welcome in the U.S. By Susan Sachs.
</P>
<P>
   HEAT-TV-NEWS-TEXT-REVIEW (New York) _ A look at contrived segues
to the weather on happy-talking local New York television
newscasts.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-ME.COM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Me.com, an Internet start-up
and IPO opportunity. By Steve Lohr.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week, leading
with the Woodstock riot.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moved in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   LATIN-LEFT-REVIEW (Montevideo, Uruguay) _ The left in Latin
America is doing well with voters in part because it has shucked
old ideological trappings and moved toward the center. Its
acceptance of democratic pluralism and compromise, mixed with hefty
dollops of self-criticism and the rejection of old doctrines and
platitudes, are helping the left re-emerge as a winning force in
much of Latin America. By Clifford Krauss.
</P>
<P>
   POWER-FUNERALS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Weren't funerals supposed to
be solemn affairs, where mourners whispered the right words and
shop talk was taboo? You wouldn't have known it last week in Rabat,
the setting for the latest in what this year in the Middle East has
become the year of the power funeral. By Douglas Jehl.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-POLITICS-REVIEW (Belgrade) _ What ever happened to the
moderate Albanian leaders in Kosovo? As the young fighters of the
Kosovo Liberation Army take control, Ibrahim Rugova, the diffident
and puzzling pacifist who was considered Kosovo's president, has
remained abroad, leaving his party and his reputation to wither. By
Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
