<HEADER>
A1078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      07-31 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GREAT EXPECTATIONS   
 NOT PERFECT, BUT GOOD 
CLASSIC PINIELLA 
WHO MAKES THE CALL? 
A NOD TO A UNION PIONEER
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Knowing how it feels to be in the spotlight, Tony Gwynn said he
felt sorry for Mark McGwire. ``He has to do what he did last year
or he's considered a failure,'' Gwynn said of the 70-home run man.
``But his performance this year has been amazing.''
</P>
<P>
   Going into Saturday's game, McGwire was five home runs from his
own celebrated plateau: 500 home runs. That stratosphere is
populated by 15 players.
</P>
<P>
   McGwire was also tied with Sammy Sosa for the season lead with
38. But while Sosa was five games ahead of his 1998 production,
McGwire was well off his. This year he hit his 38th in St. Louis'
103rd game; last season he hit it in the team's 89th game.
</P>
<P>
   In a different home run race, despite a recent flurry, Albert
Belle continues to trail Jay Bell, 27 to 25. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Not Perfect, but Good
</P>
<P>
   Javier Vazquez has pitched better since David Cone's perfect
game than Cone has. Vazquez was the Montreal pitcher whose
teammates gave him no help in making 27 consecutive outs against
Cone on July 18. But in his two starts since that 6-0 loss, Vazquez
pitched a complete-game four-hitter in a 5-1 victory over
Pittsburgh and a complete-game three-hitter in an 8-2 decision over
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In Cone's two starts since he was perfect, he has definitely
been imperfect, allowing 14 hits, seven walks and 10 runs (six
earned) in 11 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Classic Piniella
</P>
<P>
   When the Seattle Mariners began a series in Minnesota last
weekend, Lou Piniella, their manager, bragged to the umpires during
the pre-game lineup exchange that he had not been kicked out of a
game all season. The weekend's not over, the umpires reminded him.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Piniella did not survive the Sunday game. As part
of his ejection, he exhibited a classic Piniella performance,
storming out of the dugout, flailing his arms, screaming
demonstrably and trying to yank third base out of the ground. When
he was unable to extricate the base from its slot, Piniella
resorted to an old standby _ kicking dirt.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the dirt found its way onto Durwood Merrill's pants. ``I
think,'' Merrill drawled after the game, looking at his pants,
``I'm going to have to get me some new umpire pants. These are kind
of dusty.''
</P>
<P>
   Who Makes the Call?
</P>
<P>
   George Steinbrenner is notorious for his complaints about
umpires, filling the American League's film library for years with
footage of what he feels are bungled calls. But Richie Garcia, one
of the umpires who is losing his job, tells of two incidents in
recent years when the Yankees' owner tried to dictate who umpired
at home plate.
</P>
<P>
   Garcia recalled that in the 1995 playoffs, Steinbrenner did not
want Dale Scott behind the plate for the second game and in a
subsequent season did not want a young umpire there because of a
call he had made at first base the night before.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was chaos in that office,'' said Garcia, who was the crew
chief in both instances. ``They called me in my room at 9 o'clock
in the morning and said get up here.''
</P>
<P>
   Garcia said he offered to call Steinbrenner and tell him that
he, Garcia, would make that call, but the league declined the
gesture. Nevertheless, as in the Scott incident, the young umpire
worked the plate.
</P>
<P>
   A Nod to a Union Pioneer
</P>
<P>
   Nolan Ryan holds 48 major league records, most noteworthy of
which are his seven no-hitters and 5,714 strikeouts. But last
Sunday, in his speech at his Hall of Fame induction, he achieved
another first. He became the first player, upon entering the hall,
to utter Marvin Miller's name. Of course, he went well beyond just
mentioning Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Saying that the former head of the players union had an impact
on him, his family and ``many ballplayers sitting in this audience
today,'' Ryan related how after his first year in the major
leagues, in which he earned a $7,000 salary, he had to pump gas so
that he and his wife, Ruth, ``could live through the winter until
baseball season started.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller, Ryan said, ``brought that level up to where the players
weren't put in that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Miller did not attend the induction ceremony but heard about
Ryan's remarks. ``That was very gracious of him,'' the retired
union leader said.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, meanwhile, continues to be the man who has made the
greatest impact on baseball who has not been elected by the
Veterans Committee to the Hall of Fame. Hall officials explain that
the executive category from which the committee can select one
person each year always has been interpreted as including officials
from Major League Baseball or the National Association, the minor
leagues organization.
</P>
<P>
   The Hall of Fame's board of directors is reviewing the rules.
Given Miller's role, like it or not, he had a greater impact on
baseball than any executive this side of Branch Rickey.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1431EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0142 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 14:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1080 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-JETS-NYT &LR;      07-31 0837
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-JETS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATWATER ARRIVES AS SECRETARY OF THE SECONDARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By GERALD ESKENAZI    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ After being involved in 1,301 tackles for the
Denver Broncos, 32-year-old Steve Atwater now has the job of
showing the Jets how to make a big play.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Jets were pushovers in that regard last season _
after all, the defense orchestrated by Bill Belichick came within a
point of tying the Dolphins for yielding the fewest points in the
National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   But how much easier life on the Jets would have been if there
had been a free safety to play consistently. In the opening game,
the 49ers' Garrison Hearst huffed and puffed for 96 yards in
overtime at San Francisco, along the way eluding the rookie free
safety Kevin Williams, who had a clean shot at a tackle.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was one of three players the Jets tried at the position
last year, along with Jerome Henderson and Corwin Brown. Brown was
on the field at Indianapolis in Week 11, missing Marshall Faulk in
the open field when he turned in an 18-yard catch and run to set up
the Colts' winning score. Free safety wound up being the only
position in the Jets' secondary in which a starter was benched.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Atwater, a free agent, who was anchoring the defensive
secondary as the Jets went into their first weekend of summer camp
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atwater's main job is to prevent any big plays from
happening,'' Belichick explained. ``If big plays are happening when
the free safety's out on the field, then that's not good. He should
be able to hold any running play from a major gain, and to prevent
big passing plays over which he has control.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwater has done this so well and so often that he has been
elected to the American Football Conference's All-Pro team eight
times, including last season.
</P>
<P>
   If there is anything left in Atwater _ the Broncos felt there
wasn't enough, at least not for $2.6 million this season _ the Jets
will be better off at free safety. But Denver's defensive
coordinator, Greg Robinson, a former Jets assistant, took Atwater
out of third-down passing situations late last season.
</P>
<P>
   Atwater said he was never specifically told he was too slow. But
he understood that was the message. Why else take out the free
safety _ the so-called center fielder _ on obvious passing plays?
</P>
<P>
   He is 6 foot 3, weighs 215 pounds and is one of those ``good
people'' who enhance a team and a city. One of his first acts on
becoming a Jet was to become involved with a Long Island
organization that promotes the use of child safety seats. In Denver
he worked for the Colorado Coalition for the Homeless. He plays in
charity golf tournaments.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the Broncos' reluctance to keep him in their plans,
Atwater went out in grand style. Against the Jets in the conference
championship game, he knocked the ball loose from Alex Van Dyke,
halting the Jets' final fourth-quarter rally. And in the Super Bowl
victory over Atlanta he was the Broncos' second-leading tackler.
</P>
<P>
   So now, is he trying to show the Jets what it takes?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't take anything for granted,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He was one of the veterans Coach Bill Parcells was talking to
Thursday night, on the eve of the training camp, when he warned
them: ``There are no incumbents. You've got to win your jobs.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwater is one of several off-season free-agent names the Jets
acquired: Roman Phifer of the Rams at linebacker, Tom Tupa (punter)
and Scott Zolak (quarterback) from the Patriots, and Eric Green
(tight end) from the Ravens.
</P>
<P>
   Not so long ago, the Jets used to bring in players who had seen
better days _ such as Art Monk and Leonard Marshall _ as much to
show off their Super Bowl rings as to display their talent. While
the rings didn't fade, the talent had. But in this case, Atwater is
not joining a Jets team without success, at least in the last two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just want to show the Jets I can play,'' Atwater said. ``All
they know about me is what I did at Denver.''
</P>
<P>
   An admiring Belichick said: ``He brings in his work ethic and
his ability to hit. He is very intelligent and picks up things very
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Atwater will not brag about the past, and so he sidestepped a
question about what he brings to the table. ``I haven't brought
anything to the table yet,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Atwater is not ready to concede that the Broncos have faded with
the retirement of John Elway. The Jets meet the Broncos again at
Denver in Game 4.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still a great team with Bubby Brister at quarterback
and Terrell Davis running,'' Atwater said. ``There still are some
very good players there. When we talk now about how they beat the
Jets, I point out that the Jets had six turnovers and it's
difficult to win with so many.''
</P>
<P>
   So, he isn't showing off his Super Bowl rings, as Ronnie Lott
and Marshall and Monk did when they got here?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have the rings with me,'' Atwater said. ``There's
something wrong with the diamonds. I'm getting them fixed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
