<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1081 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      07-31 1079
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BUSHES PLAY IT SAFE IN FLORIDA  
 THE CHRISTIAN COALITION'S IOWA PROBLEM  
 DOG IS GONE; OWNER WANTS TO STAY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Wash.)  (mk) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES JR.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was a time when Jeb Bush thought a straw poll of
Republican presidential contenders was a great idea. At least that
was the case in 1995, when he was running the poll that is
sponsored every four years by the Republican Party of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed to him then that the poll, combined with a series of
speeches by candidates, was a good way to give a big boost to the
party, the candidates and the state _ and, not incidentally, also a
good way to give a big boost to his ambition to someday be governor
of Florida.
</P>
<P>
   But now, with straw poll time once again drawing nigh _ the
Republican Party's annual state convention is set for Oct. 8 and 9
_ Bush, who has achieved his goal of becoming governor, seems to
hold a different view of the quadrennial beauty contest.
</P>
<P>
   When Al Cardenas, the man he picked to lead the state's
Republican Party, canceled the 1999 poll the other day, Jeb Bush
did not object, even though his brother, Gov. George W. Bush of
Texas, sees megastate Florida as one of the keys to success in his
presidential quest.
</P>
<P>
   Cardenas said the poll would be more divisive than instructive.
But he left standing the invitation to all candidates to address
the party convention.
</P>
<P>
   Jeb Bush's office said the governor had had nothing to do with
Cardenas' decision and ``didn't really feel strongly either way''
about the cancellation of the poll.
</P>
<P>
   Then brother George sent word from Texas that he had all but
decided to forgo the opportunity to make a speech at the
convention.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a presence there, someone representing us,'' said
his campaign spokeswoman, Mindy Tucker. ``But as far as I know,
Gov. Bush is not coming.''
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here?
</P>
<P>
   The Bush boys are not saying anything beyond what they already
have said. But political pros in the Sunshine State say it appears
that the brothers have decided that Florida already is in the Bush
bag, given Jeb's powerful influence in the state and George W.'s
runaway standing in the polls, and thus there is no reason to risk
the possible embarrassment of a bad showing in an unscientific
straw poll.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, the brothers also seem to believe there is no reason
to risk a stage appearance with competitors who need the attention
much more than George W. does.
</P>
<P>
   Ruffling Feathers in the Lord's Name
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of straw polls...
</P>
<P>
   A recent dustup in Iowa between Steve Forbes, the publisher who
is seeking the Republican presidential nomination, and Bobbie
Gobel, the vocal new head of the state's Christian Coalition, has
national leaders of the coalition deeply worried.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gobel, who runs a Des Moines hiring agency when she is not
``doing the work of the Lord,'' as she puts it, said last week that
Forbes had tried to draw a contract with her to round up temporary
workers to vote for him in an Aug. 14 straw poll in Ames that is
shaping up as the first major test of Election 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes flatly denied the accusation and in turn accused Ms.
Gobel of political tampering.
</P>
<P>
   National coalition leaders are feverishly trying to smooth
things over. And they are wondering what, if anything, they can do
about the outspoken Bobbie Gobel.
</P>
<P>
   The Christian right vote is a major factor in Iowa politics, and
Ms. Gobel says she intends to make it an even bigger one. Recently
she began calling on laggards in the Republican field, especially
those over on the hard right, to get out of the race and clear the
way for ``godly'' candidates with a better shot.
</P>
<P>
   She has not named any names thus far, much to the relief of
national coalition leaders, who tend to avoid taking sides publicly
early in presidential contests and urge state leaders to do
likewise. But she came close with her Forbes accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Coalition leaders at the national headquarters in Chesapeake,
Va., some of whom have close ties to Forbes, questioned Ms. Gobel
about her accusation and pressed her to reconsider. Then they
issued a statement saying that ``recent characterizations of events
surrounding the upcoming Iowa straw poll are unfortunate and in our
view inaccurate.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gobel immediately objected to the statement, saying: ``I was
told to go along with it. I don't go along with it. I'd rather burn
a bridge than burn my country.''
</P>
<P>
   Coalition officials in Chesapeake say the Iowa matter is under
``internal review.'' But in the meantime, unannounced, a team of
political troubleshooters has been dispatched to Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   No More Dog Not to Kick Around
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1994, a campaign ad that featured a telegenic golden
retriever named Chestnut helped George Nethercutt, a Republican,
win Washington state's 5th Congressional District from the
powerful, long-entrenched Democratic incumbent, Speaker Tom Foley.
In the ad, Nethercutt said that Foley, desperate to win, had
accused him of ``everything short of kicking my dog.''
</P>
<P>
   He vowed he would be a more high-minded legislator who, unlike
Foley, would go along with term-limits advocates and serve no more
than six years in the House. Then, casting a loving glance at his
fetching retriever, he also promised, `And I'd never hurt you,
Chestnut.''
</P>
<P>
   Foley, sensing the effectiveness of the ad, turned to Nethercutt
in the final debate of the campaign and said: ``George, I'm not
after the dog. Believe me.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, in his first bid for re-election, Nethercutt returned
to the airwaves with Chestnut, telling voters he had made good on
all of the campaign promises he made back in 1994, then adding,
``And I still don't kick my dog.''
</P>
<P>
   He won a second term. And then a third in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Now, halfway through that third term, Nethercutt has had second
thoughts about leaving Washington after just six years. He says he
is scrapping his promise and will run for a fourth term next year.
</P>
<P>
   And Chestnut?
</P>
<P>
   Alas, the congressman will not have him not to kick around
anymore. He died last week after a battle with cancer.
</P>
<P>
   What do term-limit advocates have to say?
</P>
<P>
   ``Dogs are special to us, too, and we certainly grieve for the
loss of Chestnut,'' said Paul Jacob, executive director of U.S.
Term Limits. ``But the equally sad fact is that Rep. Nethercutt is
a promise-breaker. We intend to go after him next fall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
