<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 14:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1082 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-UMPIRES-ART-780(2     07-31 0852
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-ART-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VETERAN MINOR LEAGUE UMPIRE FEELS BLUE DESPITE CALL TO MAJORS
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz., N.M.)  (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers may make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(rk) 
 By JACK CURRY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mike Everitt has a soothing way of discussing his 12 uncertain
years of umpiring games in the minor leagues. He remembers driving
843 miles overnight to get to the next game, trying to subsist on
$20 a day and a marriage that could not survive his time-devouring
job. He wondered about the sacrifices. Is this worth it?
</P>
<P>
   So when Everitt received a call from the American League 10 days
ago and was offered a full-time job at $95,000 a year, his hands
trembled. He had worked in the major leagues as a fill-in umpire,
and had been waiting a dozen years to hear he had made it on a
permanent basis.
</P>
<P>
   This was why he devoured the official rule book and why he once
went three months without seeing his second wife while he worked in
Triple-A. Finally, the elusive call came.
</P>
<P>
   But the emotions that should have been blissful were tinged with
sadness. Everitt was one of 25 Triple-A umpires who were offered
jobs after more than 50 major league umpires had tendered their
resignations in a contract negotiating strategy that failed
miserably. Some umps were permitted to rescind their resignations,
but 22 umpires lost their jobs. During the disarray, Everitt was
hired.
</P>
<P>
   ``This call was tough in the way that the job came about,''
Everitt said. ``I would have much rather made it to the big leagues
another way. But I guess this is how it was supposed to be. I would
much rather not have this turmoil because so many guys have treated
me so well. I think for all of us who have fortunately gotten jobs,
I don't think we're celebrating.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an awkward time for some umpires and an awful one for
others because Richie Phillips, the chief negotiator for the Major
League Umpires Association, advised his members to challenge
baseball and it backfired. That is where the 34-year old Everitt,
who umpired his first major league game in 1996 and has filled in
for vacationing or injured umpires 158 times since then, found
himself amid these unprecedented changes.
</P>
<P>
   That may be one reason Everitt is cautious. He does not want to
seem boastful, or unsympathetic toward the umpires who have lost
their jobs. He proudly spoke of being part of the umpiring
fraternity and how he has umpired 159 major league games. No. 160
is Monday night at Yankee Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``With everything that has went on, it's hard to believe I'm a
major league umpire,'' said Everitt, whose appointment becomes
official on Sept. 1. ``It really hasn't sunk in yet.''
</P>
<P>
   As Everitt spoke by telephone from his home in Chandler, Ariz.,
he looked for a baseball from his first major league game: June 20,
1996 at Oakland. Three years and a month after Everitt made his
debut as a part-time major league umpire, the AL, amid the regular
umpires' pending resignations, asked him if he wanted a steady
check for about four times what he earned in the minors.
</P>
<P>
   For Everitt and the 24 other new umpires, it was a delicate
question that was going to be asked only once. Union experts have
said in interviews that since the major league umpires had sent in
letters of resignations, the minor league umps have not defied the
union by accepting positions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the position I was in, you know, there was hesitation, yet
I knew what the right thing to do was,'' said Everitt, who did not
belong to a union in the minor leagues. ``I'm very loyal to
umpires, but what I have wrestled with for the past 20 days is this
wasn't a strike issue. As far as crossing a picket line and being a
strike replacement or taking someone's job in that fashion, it's
not anything like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``But at the same time, I have so much respect for so many
umpires. I realize what they go through. It's not just throw on the
clothes and go to the ballpark and work. There's a lot more to it
than it looks on TV.''
</P>
<P>
   John Hirschbeck, one of the 14 umpires who refused to resign and
a leader of a block of umps who have grown disillusioned with
Phillips' leadership, was in Cleveland with Everitt when an AL
official called. Hirschbeck emphasized that Everitt and the other
newly hired umps ``absolutely did not'' violate the union and
should not be maligned.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's much more difficult to become a major league umpire than
it is to become a major league player,'' Hirschbeck said. ``There's
no turnover. What is happening now is something that hasn't
happened in the history of baseball. The jobs are so few and far
between.''
</P>
<P>
   Everitt politely declined to comment on whether he expected
friction from other umps for his decision. But Hirschbeck, who is
torn between being thrilled for Everitt and sad for those who lost
jobs, firmly said, ``If there is anything against them, it will be
minimal and it will not be tolerated.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Before this failed move, umpires had some of the most secure
jobs in baseball because they were rarely fired. There are 68
positions that pay from $95,000 to $262,500, and attrition usually
occurred only through retirements. Even though Everitt worked 23
games in 1996, 37 in 1997, 60 in 1998 and 39 so far this year, he
had no assurances that he would ever be hired full time.
</P>
<P>
   Until the July 14 resignations, few umpires would even have
considered leaving a job that calls for them to work only seven
months a year for an average salary of $150,000 to $175,000 and
does not require a college degree. Umpires generally arrive at the
park 90 minutes before a game and work about 3 1/2 hours. What
umpires need is keen eyesight, a thick skin, an acceptance of
traveling to different cities two or three times a week and mental
toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you blow a couple of calls,'' Everitt said, ``you're on
`Sports Center.'''
</P>
<P>
   Even before Everitt left New Mexico State University 45 credits
short of a degree to attend Harry Wendelstedt's Umpiring School in
1987, he had heard the statistics of how fewer than 1 in 100 minor
league umpires are promoted to the majors. Still, Everitt, who
wanted to be a major leaguer when he pitched at Aztec (N.M.) High
School, persevered through one year in rookie ball, three in
Single-A, two and a half in Double-A and four in Triple-A. Waiting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ordinarily, there's very little movement and you're just
getting up here on retirement,'' Everitt said. ``This year is a
little different.''
</P>
<P>
   Umpires are an isolated crew, strolling onto the field, getting
booed if they receive any reaction at all, and knowing that they
are four against the world. Many describe their lives as exciting
and tense during games, but lonely and stale before and afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Because umpires receive a $240 per diem for their hotel, food,
cab or car expenses and tips for clubhouse attendants, they rarely
stay at the hotels ballplayers frequent, and negotiate the best
possible rates on their own. Many umpires share cabs or cars
because a $50-a-day rental rate is much more desirable when divided
by four.
</P>
<P>
   The umpires receive prepaid airline vouchers from the major
leagues for first-class tickets and must make their own
reservations. Since they fly commercially, they are unable to leave
for the next city immediately after games, which teams do. An
umpire works about 130 regular-season games and has four one-week
vacations, so he is away from relatives and friends for long
periods. Despite the incessant travel, however, Hirschbeck called
the job nirvana.
</P>
<P>
   ``I work six months a year,'' Hirschbeck said. ``I don't even
count spring training. Plus you get four weeks off. It's easy to
look at the negatives, but I look at the positives. I thank God
every day for my job. Everything I have in my life is from
baseball. How can I not be grateful?''
</P>
<P>
   This lifestyle is a dramatic improvement from the one Everitt
knew in Triple-A, where he was paid $3,400 a month, the best salary
for a minor league umpire, and received a $20 per diem. Since the
Triple-A season runs only until early September and minor league
umpires are not paid in the off-season, Everitt had to find
temporary jobs in the winter. He has driven cars for a rental
company, supervised youths at a juvenile detention center and done
maintenance work at a golf course.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major league umps get paid year round,'' Everitt said. ``That
is something I can't really fathom until the day I go to the
mailbox and get the check.''
</P>
<P>
   But like any other umpire, majors or minors, Everitt's travel
schedule will remain hectic. He will be away from his pregnant
wife, Michelle, a juvenile probation officer, for weeks. Everitt
says it takes one month after the season for he and his wife to
regain some normalcy in their relationship, and he has stopped
trying to explain his absences to neighbors.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 12 years, Everitt often asked himself why he
continued to be an umpire. Even in the last 10 days, he has asked
the question. The answer is simply that he loves his job and would
be miserable if he was home and not umpiring. Even if leaving home
will become more difficult after Michelle gives birth to their
first child sometime around Jan. 1, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I might have to fly her to New York and have the baby there at
midnight,'' Everitt said. ``We were told we weren't going to be
able to have kids because of fertility problems and we were close
to adopting. All of a sudden, she just got pregnant. This year has
just been a miracle in a lot of ways.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1457EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 15:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1085 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UNSCOM-BUTLER-NYT     07-31 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UNSCOM-BUTLER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARMS AIDE WHO QUIT ASSAILS U.N. ON IRAQ
</HEADLINE>
  (nk) 
 By JUDITH MILLER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a defense of his troubled tenure as chief of the United
Nations Special Commission responsible for disarming Iraq of
weapons of mass destruction, Richard Butler has accused
Secretary-General Kofi Annan of trying to destroy the commission
because it was ``too independent.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler, who resigned as chairman of the commission on July 1,
also savagely criticizes virtually everyone else associated with
the protracted effort to disarm Iraq of unconventional weapons. The
exception is the Clinton administration, which he says, contrary to
allegations by Scott Ritter, a former weapons inspector, was
largely steadfast and alone in its efforts to ``hold Saddam's feet
to the fire.''
</P>
<P>
   He also repeats allegations that Yevgeny Primakov, the former
Russian prime minister who was foreign minister at the time,
received personal payments from Iraq. He provides no evidence for
this charge, which Russian officials have denied, other than citing
what he calls ``intelligence reports from an outstanding source.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler, a former Australian ambassador to the United Nations and
disarmament expert, issues his bitter indictment of many of his
former colleagues, along with Iraqi and Russian officials, in an
article to be published Monday in the first issue of Talk, the
heavily promoted monthly magazine edited by Tina Brown, the former
editor of The New Yorker and Vanity Fair.
</P>
<P>
   Billed as the ``inside story'' of his efforts to disarm Iraq,
the article is Butler's first detailed account of the decline and
fall of the Special Commission, known as UNSCOM.
</P>
<P>
   It contains little that is new about Iraq's cheating, the events
that ultimately led to the Special Commission's problems and its
expulsion from Iraq, or the extent to which Butler's personality
and uncompromising style may have compounded the commission's
difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   But it does reveal the depth of Butler's fury and frustration
over his failure to win allies among the senior U.N. officials on
whom his mission depended.
</P>
<P>
   The account highlights in particular his contempt for Annan and
other U.N. officials and diplomats who, in Butler's view, have
permitted Iraqi President Saddam Hussein to retain the capability
for mass murder.
</P>
<P>
   Calling Annan's behavior ``deeply alarming,'' Butler describes a
succession of incidents, several of which have not been previously
reported, in which he says the secretary general dealt with Iraq's
political challenges and cheating by ``papering them over with
diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Annan and his immediate staff sought to hand Saddam the
greatest possible prize: the destruction of UNSCOM,'' Butler
asserts, because ``UNSCOM was too independent to work within the
mainstream of the U.N.''
</P>
<P>
   Shashi Tharoor, Annan's spokesman, called Butler's assertion
that the secretary general had tried to destroy the Special
Commission ``bizarre'' and ``errant nonsense.'' He noted that Annan
had involved himself in UNSCOM affairs only ``at critical moments
to resolve specific crises.'' Saying that Annan had not read the
article, Tharoor deferred further comment.
</P>
<P>
   According to Butler's account, the U.N. ``cave-in'' to Hussein
began in 1996 when Rolf Ekeus, the highly regarded Swedish diplomat
who was Butler's predecessor, agreed to Iraqi restrictions on the
access of weapons inspectors to sites that Baghdad deemed
``sensitive'' for national security reasons. Butler calls the move
a ``direct violation'' of Security Council resolutions.
</P>
<P>
   After Butler took over in 1997, Russia, China and France refused
to block Iraqi efforts to bar the inspectors from ``presidential
sites,'' which, as Butler states, were eight areas covering 30
square miles that included 1,100 buildings, many of which were
ideal for weapons storage.
</P>
<P>
   Butler charges that Annan was not only soft on Hussein and
enamored of diplomacy for its own sake, but tried to undermine
UNSCOM's work.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, Butler asserts that Annan pressed him to accept
Iraq's exclusion of American citizens from inspection teams. ``I
was incredulous,'' Butler writes. He said he prevailed only after
explaining to Annan that giving Iraq veto power over the
composition of teams would undermine their quality and set an
``unacceptable precedent.'' He called the incident his ``first
glimpse'' of Annan's ``tendency to sacrifice substance to his
notion of diplomacy.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he asserts that Annan failed to grasp essential
distinctions involving the commission's disagreements with Iraq on
the eve of the secretary general's much-publicized trip to Baghdad
in February 1998. The trip produced an agreement that led
temporarily to resumed inspections _ and to Annan's description of
Hussein as ``a man I can do business with.'' Annan has subsequently
expressed regret about having been so optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   When Butler wanted to test the agreement quickly by sending out
inspectors, Annan is quoted as asking him to wait. As Butler
anticipated, his inspectors were eventually taken to sites that he
and other inspectors agree were ``sanitized'' before their arrival.
</P>
<P>
   Butler is also strongly critical of Russia, recounting that
Primakov told him in Moscow that sanctions against Baghdad should
be lifted and Iraq free to sell oil for profit so that Russia could
collect the $7 billion it was owed by Iraq for weapons.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Butler praises President Clinton, who he says urged
him at an impromptu meeting at a New York party in March 1998 to
``do your job down the line'' and ``go get their armaments.''
</P>
<P>
   While noting that he knew that American and British support
would not suffice for rigorous weapons inspection ``in the face of
weakening resolve'' in the Security Council, Butler only obliquely
refers to America's role in the spying scandal that more than
anything else undermined international confidence in the Special
Commission and his stewardship of it.
</P>
<P>
   Butler accuses Ritter of making ``misleading and misguided''
statements about America's alleged use of the Special Commission to
spy on Iraq. Butler does say that he rejected proposals, not solely
from the United States, that ``might have served or been construed
to have served'' purposes other than disarming Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   But, specifically mentioning allegations that Washington sought,
as he puts it, ``to piggy-back on UNSCOM for its own national
intelligence purposes,'' Butler writes only: ``I would lament
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Several inspectors who were read portions of the article said
that Butler's version seemed accurate. But some added that the
account did not reflect the extent to which Butler's abrasive style
and perceived closeness to Washington adversely affected his
credibility within the Security Council, to which the Special
Commission reports. ``Richard Butler was part of our problem,'' one
official said. ``And so was the Clinton administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Butler is now diplomat in residence at the Council on Foreign
Relations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1504EDT &QL; 
