<HEADER>
A1088 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-LIONS-NYT &LR;      07-31 1015
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-LIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIFE WITHOUT SANDERS BECOMES A GAME PLAN
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By THOMAS GEORGE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAGINAW, Mich. _ Footballs were indeed being run, passed and
kicked in the Detroit Lions' training camp when the team grunted
through its first days of practice.
</P>
<P>
   Mystery and intrigue, however, swirled among them as their No.
20 remained retired, in Europe, after his unexpected and thunderous
decision last Wednesday to leave the Lions after 10 seasons. Former
teammates and coaches of Barry Sanders here were attempting to
recover from the jolt and make sense of what to some of them seemed
senseless.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bailey, a nine-year pro cornerback in his third season
with the Lions, said: ``When I heard about it, I thought, `This is
crazy.' We heard about it like everyone else did on TV. After it
was over, we all discussed the timing of it. Just before training
camp? Some guys thought that was bad. For the entire team, this was
a stunning deal. It was like your 15-year-old daughter coming home
and telling you she's pregnant. What can you do? You sit there,
numb. Barry obviously had a lot on his mind, more than we thought
he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only a month or two ago, he was up with us near Detroit
playing basketball. Shoot, guard, dribble _ Barry's an athlete and
he can do it all. He's Barry. There was no hint he would quit.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey continues: ``But here's the thing _ we won with Barry and
we lost with Barry. He's not here and we are going to go on and win
or lose without him. We've got to go out and play and realize that
we have a whole new world now with a lot of new opportunities for
the entire team now. We've just got to go out and see it. And
embrace it.''
</P>
<P>
   That is the challenge for the Lions now _ embracing change, not
wilting under it.
</P>
<P>
   Gone are Sanders and his long, thrilling spins and runs. Absent
is the wheel from which the Lions offense had flowed. Removed is
his ability to force defenses to focus foremost on him. Gone, too,
is a quiet, reserved player not really known by many of his
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Now, other Lions have an opportunity to lead on the field in
ways that they never have. Coaches must design schemes for the team
to play in a way that it never has, without Sanders. This could
mean a more methodical and more physical ball-control offense, with
a passing game that can become more of a focal point, and with a
defense that can now firmly lead.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Moeller, the Lions' linebackers coach, said: ``Who wants to
lose great players? You lose them all the time with injury and
through free agency, but not quite like this.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone else is going to have to surface now as a star of this
team. This should bring us closer together. Now we can't hit the
home run as readily in the running game, but we can do steady
damage. This is where you need good leadership among your veteran
players. That's going to help decide how this all shakes down. Who
is going to lead now?''
</P>
<P>
   Not only on the field, but also on the sideline. Bobby Ross, the
Lions' head coach, is where it must start, and Ross knows it. He
appears under siege. The darts are flying. The man who ran Barry
Sanders out of town, the regimented coach who is too tough on his
players in his words and in his practices. Too inflexible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where does all of this stuff come from?'' Ross asked. ``I'm a
little befuddled. I am a demanding coach who wants my players to
hustle and work hard, and how is that different from any head coach
in the National Football League? I spend a lot of time with our
football players working on relationships. I want full and complete
effort, and that does not mean measuring everyone's contribution as
the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one will ever know how much I tried to work with Barry. The
last seven months have provided a lot of distractions. Everyone
wants to see Barry come back, and I do, too. We'll just have to
wait and see. We don't have a clear indication what running backs
are going to become available just before the season, so we'll have
to wait and see on that. But it is my job to challenge the players
and I'm going to do that and they can't be so fragile that there
becomes finger-pointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross and the Lions believe they can be a contending team this
season. The defense is greatly improved, and the offense can still
produce under the second-year quarterback Charlie Batch and a
bushel of impact receivers led by Herman Moore. Ron Rivers,
Sanders' longtime backup, is listed as starter now at running back
and just behind him is the rookie Sedrick Irvin from Michigan
State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see it as an opportunity,'' Rivers said. ``If it's my time,
so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Lions players say they believe Ross, in his third season as the
Detroit head coach, is adapting to them as the players are adapting
to Ross. Last year, during Detroit's troublesome 5-11 season, Ross
criticized his team and separated the level of effort from the
coaching (good) and the playing (poor).
</P>
<P>
   Players noted that their playbooks include fines for criticizing
teammates and coaches publicly, then asked why Ross could do it.
They said Ross has apologized.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody does not always agree with the leader,'' Bailey
said. ``There is going to be opposition, but the key is to get most
along for the ride. Coach is doing that.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert Porcher, Detroit's robust defensive end in his eighth
season, does not see gloom with the loss of Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Barry is retired and I'm respecting that,'' Porcher said.
``We've got to approach training camp differently. I am. I used to
come to camp and just try to get through it to get to the regular
season. Now my approach is to work hard every day in camp to get
better. People say we won five games last year with Barry and this
year without Barry we can't possibly win even another five. If I
wasn't playing, maybe I'd feel the same way. You've got to play the
games.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we avoid injury, let's see what happens. We've lost
something great, but all we need is a chance to do something great
and shock people even more. It's here. We have it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
