<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-IN-GERMANY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN GERMANY, BASEBALL TAKES FIRST MAJOR STEP
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Ill.)   (Eds: Georg with one `e' cq) 
(nk) 
 By ALAN MAIMON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN _ No inner voices guided Georg Bull, nor were any lush
cornfields in sight. Nevertheless, Bull set out to build a baseball
stadium in a strange place. The year was 1994 in the eastern German
town of Strausberg, or more specifically, a tract of land once used
to train soldiers in the East German army.
</P>
<P>
   Enduring the stares of perplexed locals for the whole summer,
Bull built it. And, sure enough, they came from as far as the
Dominican Republic and the United States and as near as
Strausberg's block housing complexes. Baseball in eastern Germany
took its first major step.
</P>
<P>
   Bull, a native of the western German city of Mannheim and a
former catcher on the German National Team, then created the
Strausberg Sun Warriors. Five years after taking the risk of
building a stadium before having players to fill it, he now coaches
the only team in eastern Germany to play in the country's top
semipro league. The Sun Warriors have clawed their way to the
premier German league with merit-based promotions each of its five
seasons and have picked up sponsors like BMW along the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Georg is a baseball pioneer in eastern Germany,'' said Frank
Fulton, a native of Virginia and coach of the German National Team
since last year. ``Baseball is a real sleeping giant that he has
helped to awaken.''
</P>
<P>
   Weekend doubleheaders this season in Strausberg have drawn
capacity crowds of 700 to the house that Bull built. In the absence
of a popular local soccer team, the Sun Warriors have become
Strausberg's No. 1 sports attraction.
</P>
<P>
   ``West Germans learned baseball from American soldiers and play
in million-dollar stadiums,'' Bull said. ``Our fans love the fact
that we're the only team representing eastern Germany.''
</P>
<P>
   In spite of the American presence, German baseball lags far
behind the top teams in Europe, especially Italy and the
Netherlands. While western Germany had teams, Americans dominated
the rosters and natives rarely got playing time. Still, to compete
in Germany's first division, Bull has been forced to supplement
local talent with players from abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Jason Olms, 22, played at Principia College, a Division III
school in Illinois, before coming to Germany to continue his
baseball career. Olms supports himself by playing in the league,
earning between $8,000 and $10,000, and lives in a former army
barracks behind the stadium, which is a dormitory for foreign
players.
</P>
<P>
   Wilgen (Willie) Reyes, a 30-year-old native of the Dominican
Republic, is the Sun Warriors' oldest player. A naturalized German
citizen, he is also a member of the national team that is in Italy
for the European Baseball Championships this week.
</P>
<P>
   It is the native Strausbergers on the team, however, who provide
a glimpse into eastern Germany's baseball future.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Franke, 17, had never picked up a baseball bat before
attending a free demonstration held by Bull in 1994. Franke tried
his luck against a pitching machine and connected on eight of 10
balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I played tennis up until that time,'' Franke said. ``When my
dad saw me hit the baseballs, he smiled and said that tennis might
not be the right game for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Franke plays second base on the German Junior National Team,
which was fourth in the European Championships in 1997. And his
father is president of the team in Strausberg.
</P>
<P>
   Bull's organizational talent has made Strausberg a role model
for other eastern German cities struggling to build a baseball
tradition.
</P>
<P>
   Magdeburg, a city in eastern Germany plagued by staggering
unemployment and right-wing extremism, fields a team in Germany's
eastern regional league. The team is self-deprecatingly nicknamed
Arme Schweine, literally the Poor Pigs but closer in meaning to the
Poor Saps. It plays in an athletic complex whose name reveals East
German roots, Stadion der Bauarbeiter (Stadium of the Construction
Worker).
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, a soccer game in the stadium forced the Poor Pigs
to improvise a new diamond on a gravel lot behind the city's
university.
</P>
<P>
   Odd situations are nothing new to the team in Magdeburg. When
the Poor Pigs arrived in the city's train station after a road game
in Leipzig last month, Thomas Rochel, the team's coach, had to
explain to suspicious police officers that the equipment bag full
of bats were for hitting baseballs and not people.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know where we stand around here,'' Rochel said. ``Most
people don't understand baseball here. Our goal is to get people
interested.''
</P>
<P>
   Typical of the teams in Germany's 5-year-old eastern league,
Magdeburg fields a team composed of young locals alongside
experienced Latin Americans who have lived in the city since
socialist times.
</P>
<P>
   After last weekend's sparsely attended doubleheader, in which
the Poor Pigs lost both games, the mood was still good. The team
ate German bratwurst and listened to Cuban music as a handful of
Nicaraguan players celebrated the 20th anniversary of the country's
Sandinista revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Bull views teams like Magdeburg's as essential for the further
development of baseball in eastern Germany. ``We started at the
bottom in Strausberg,'' he said. ``If we can make it to the top, so
can they.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
