A1092 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-LEYRITZ-630     07-31 0934
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-LEYRITZ-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEYRITZ RETURNING TO YANKS; PETTITTE MAY STILL BE GOING 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The New York Yankees reacquired Jim Leyritz Saturday to
augment their bench, and even though the trade dominoes remained in
place for a possible swap of Andy Pettitte before the midnight
deadline, manager Joe Torre talked Saturday afternoon as if
Pettitte would remain a Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's just not the type of deal we want,'' said Torre,
referring to the talks with the Phillies. ``I don't think it's
totally dead. There's mouth-to-mouth on this thing.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one trip wire in place would lead to a Pettitte trade:
if the Yankees can acquire Roberto Hernandez from the Tampa Bay
Devil Rays in the hours leading up to the deadline, then they would
most likely deal Pettitte to the Phillies for three prospects.
</P>
<P>
   However, the Devil Rays' front office does not always move with
alacrity, and for the Yankees and the Devil Rays to agree to a deal
Saturday, Tampa Bay would have to quickly settle on players.
Another general manager who considers himself to be in the running
for Hernandez's services said that earlier this week, he contacted
the Devil Rays about a possible deal for Hernandez and was told he
would have to surrender four players. The general manager asked the
Devil Rays to forward a proposal _ and as of this morning, he was
waiting for the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees continued to speak to the Orioles Saturday about a
possible deal for Arthur Rhodes, and if completed, the acquisition
of Rhodes could lead to a Pettitte trade. Rhodes, a hard-throwing
left-hander, would be inserted into their bullpen, joining Mike
Stanton, Jeff Nelson (currently coming back from an injury), Jason
Grimsley, Allen Watson and Dan Naulty in middle relief.
</P>
<P>
   With Rhodes in the fold, Yankee officials would then meet and
discuss whether the staff is strong enough to trade Pettitte. (If
Pettitte is traded, then Triple-A pitcher Ed Yarnall would be
shifted into the fifth spot in the Yankees' rotation).
</P>
<P>
   In return for Rhodes, the Orioles have asked for the Triple-A
infielder D'Angelo Jiminez and Luis De Los Santos, a right-handed
pitcher. The Yankees balked at this, offering De Los Santos and
another undetermined player; the two sides continued to trade
proposals early Saturday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees agreed to the trade for Leyritz on Friday evening,
in exchange for Single-A pitcher Geraldo Padua. As Yankees players
learned of the deal Saturday, the reaction was universal: they
shook their heads and smiled and laughed about the character that
is the king, as Leyritz called himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``He keeps the clubhouse loose,'' Pettitte said. ``He's
definitely unique.''
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz, 35, was batting .239 for the San Diego Padres this
season; he has not played much, accumulating only 134 at-bats,
because of a broken hand. But Leyritz has a great track record as a
power hitter in the post-season, with seven home runs in 59
at-bats, including the game-tying home run in the pivotal fourth
game of the 1996 World Series, which Torre called the biggest homer
of his managerial career.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz used to be Pettitte's personal catcher, but Torre made
it clear that would not be the case this time around. Leyritz will
be used as a role player, sometimes filling in as a first baseman,
sometimes a pinch-hitter, and perhaps developing into a
right-handed designated hitter. This year, designated hitter Chili
Davis is batting .297 with 12 homers against right-handed pitchers,
but his power numbers against left-handers aren't as good _ two
home runs in 91 at-bats, with a .286 average.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz will take the place of veteran infielder Jeff Manto, who
has one hit in eight at-bats since joining Torre's team.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a good hitter and he loves that spotlight,'' Torre said
of Leyritz. ``That's half the battle. He's an improvement on what
we have.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Pettitte heard Saturday morning that it's possible _ perhaps
likely _ that he would remain with the team, but he still seemed a
bit melancholy. He heard about the published comments attributed to
George Steinbrenner: the Yankees' principal owner said he was
deferring to Torre's wishes, and that the manager could get a
chance to straighten out the pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want your owner to want you around,'' Pettitte said
quietly, believing that Steinbrenner's comments were not exactly an
endorsement.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte looked tired, as if he was weary of the prospect of
being traded. ``What's tiring is just not pitching well,'' said
Pettitte, who threw in the bullpen Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   If the Yankees do keep Pettitte, the pressure will remain for
him to do well; before the off-season, he must make Yankee
officials believe he is worthy of the $7 million-to-$7.5 million
salary he will earn next year, and right now, Pettitte is in
perhaps the deepest funk of his career, with a 7-8 record and a
5.65 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   Scouts who have seen Pettitte recently are sure his problems are
related to his confidence. ``He's just got to learn to trust his
fastball again,'' one scout said, ``and think about keeping it down
in the strike zone.''
</P>
<P>
   Assuming Pettitte remains with the Yankees, Torre thinks that
the left-hander will rebound once the trade deadline passes, once
that stress is relieved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the fact Andy will get a chance to stay,'' said
Torre, again adding that there is the chance Pettitte will be
traded before midnight. ``We'll see how he pitches after this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
