<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0151 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 15:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1094 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-31 0926
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: UMPIRES' ACTS LEAVE BLACK MARK ON UNIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Richard Phillips says he will ``fight to the death,'' but unless
the courts bail him out, his umpires' union is already gone, shot
dead with Phillips' own gun, mostly to the cheers of the audience
watching this theater of the absurd.
</P>
<P>
   It's a sad story, almost pathetic. But be it the work of
arrogance or gross tactical miscalculation or both, Phillips has
apparently wrecked his own union and killed off, at last count, 22
careers, not counting his own.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, though, the greater damage may be to the
American labor movement, at a time when it is trying to reverse a
decades-long decline and can least afford the public relations
fallout from Phillips' horrendous call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately, a story like this one reinforces a very old and
inaccurate stereotype of big labor, from the 1930s and 1940s, of
Jimmy Hoffa and the Teamsters,'' said Tom Juravich, the director of
the Labor Center at the University of Massachusetts at Amherst.
``It creates the notion that it all hinges on the personality of
the larger-than-life leader, when the reality is that trade unions
should come down to organization, to the day-to-day rank and
file.''
</P>
<P>
   It's not just Phillips, not just the few dozen umpires who
bought into the cockamamie tactic of negotiation by resignation.
When the pro basketball players were locked out last fall, they
organized a charity game for themselves and wanted to charge $1,000
for a courtside seat. Brother, they seemed to be asking, can you
spare a grand?
</P>
<P>
   As anthems go, that one most likely didn't inspire all those
young high-tech sector workers, the ones organized labor is
desperate to recruit, to bolt from their work stations and make a
run for the nearest union hall.
</P>
<P>
   People always want to talk about how effective sports can be in
at least elevating the debate, educating the masses, on hot-button
issues. Magic Johnson's infection with the virus that causes AIDS
turned up the volume on safe-sex talk. Cancer scares for athletes
like Darryl Strawberry supposedly motivate others to get examined.
Lance Armstrong gives cancer victims hope. Mark McGwire speaks out
against child abuse, and suddenly the cause has been furthered by
his 500-foot clout.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no doubt that sports has a tremendous impact on the
society, and in many cases, the first taste the youth of this
country will get on an issue is through when they read or hear
through sports,'' said Charles Kernaghan, director of the National
Labor Committee, a New York-based human rights watchdog group.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, the notion of this umpires' debacle shaping
anyone's union sensibility has to be as scary a proposition for
organized labor as Ronald Reagan, a marketing disaster along the
lines of the air traffic controllers. And what about all this
coverage for 68 umpires who make from $75,000 to $400,000 _ is it
proportionately in line with the amount of attention 10,000
striking hospital workers would get? Of course it isn't, but sports
unions, which once fought valiantly for benefits that the
blue-collar worker could at least relate to, have for the most part
evolved to represent the celebritization of organized labor.
</P>
<P>
   Their message, however distorted, has tremendous market reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact that popular athletes think unions are good may be a
counterbalance, but clearly, sports unions reinforce the notion
that unions take a self-serving approach and tend to be primarily
about money,'' said Richard Hurd, a professor in labor studies at
Cornell University. ``In that sense, it's not great for the labor
movement.''
</P>
<P>
   The umpires' story is not about money, but then, Phillips did
not allow the dispute to reach the point where his membership could
at least be viewed sympathetically. Phillips has won many battles
through the years, many I applauded, but, sorry, baseball's
mandated enforcement of the strike zone does not qualify as
workplace abuse. The umpires have in the last few years come off as
power-drunk, out of touch with their relative importance to the
game. The decision by Phillips to have his membership stick its
collective head under the guillotine will be remembered as a
landmark act of self-destruction that even Michael Moore can't
defend.
</P>
<P>
   Even with the knowledge that sports owners rip off taxpayers and
hide profits under the pillow, it has become increasingly difficult
to support sports unions as the 1990s have wound down. As Richard
Hurd suggested, they have failed to articulate a relevant social
message, anything beyond greed. When people like Charles Kernaghan
have asked popular athletes to speak out against the companies
engaged in sweatshop abuses abroad, they are met with deafening
silence, individually and collectively. The opportunity to balance
the inevitable resentment of their millions, to get the news media
back in their camp, is lost.
</P>
<P>
   The union-bashing, unfair in how it ultimately affects real
union workers, goes on.
</P>
<P>
   ``People tend to make choices about union membership based on
their own workplace conditions,'' Hurd said. ``But the sports
unions, mainly because of the amount of attention they get, do have
an impact on public perception.''
</P>
<P>
   Here, then, is the public's perception of Richard Phillips: His
blind arrogance has led one-third of his membership to the cusp of
unemployment. What Phillips is calling a ``fight to the death,''
most people see as group suicide. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1530EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
