<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-N.Y.-HEAT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THE CITY OVERHEATS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Sunday, Aug. 1:
</P>
<P>
   July in New York this year was like living in the hot breath of
a big dog _ a subjective measure, true, but just as precise in its
own way as any of the indices that try to put a number on how hot
it really feels. It hasn't yet been as scorching as it was on July
9, 1936, when the temperature reached 106 degrees in Central Park.
There haven't been three consecutive days over 100, as there were
in July 1993 and August 1948, nor have there even been as many July
days over 90 as there were in 1993, when there were 20. What makes
this the hottest July on record isn't the extremes of temperature.
It's the average, which has been more than 4 degrees higher than
normal, nearly 82 degrees, the highest since the previous record in
1955.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the heat of previous summers seems a little academic if you
are caught in a heat wave at the moment. When wind whips through
Times Square, it is a hot wind. If rain falls, it is a hot rain.
Every day brings a kind of annealing. Blasts of superheated air
rising from subway grates meet superchilled air spilling outward
through open doorways. The body heat of strangers crowding a
crosswalk is stirred by the hot exhaust of a bus caught in traffic,
by the engine heat rising from trucks and automobiles gridlocked on
softening asphalt. Sunlight caroms off skyscrapers, doubling and
redoubling the sun overhead. The nominal outdoor temperature _ the
actual high as predicted by the forecasters _ is something most of
us come across only fleetingly, a reasonably tolerable mean between
the extremes of incubation on the city streets and refrigeration
indoors.
</P>
<P>
   In more temperate seasons, the city quiets down enough at night
to create the illusion of silence, like the illusion of starlight
among so many urban street lamps. But those who try to sleep
without air-conditioning, their windows flung wide, know that
silence, like slumber, has been banished by the heat. A million
air-conditioners rumble and hiss all night long, compressors
cycling on and off, fans whirring, washing the city clean of lesser
noises. It would be tempting to lie in bed and imagine what that
collective, monotonous roar sounds like _ a distant waterfall, a
nearby freeway, a plague of low-frequency locusts _ except that if
you sleep without air-conditioning you try not to think at all.
Thinking, on hot nights, is the same as sweating.
</P>
<P>
   For now, all the cool air is in Canada, where the jet stream is
being held hostage. A cold front lies above the international
border like a swag of fresh air, waiting until who knows when to
push southward and eastward and blow July's used-up air out to sea.
The push will come sooner or later, as it does every year, perhaps
as early as this week. Cool air will sweep over the city and only
the subways will remember what July was like. Small consolation,
isn't it? &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
