<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 15:39 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1099 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      07-31 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRO FOOTBALL NOTEBOOK: THE TOP 100; PLAYING GAMES IN ATLANTA; THE
COWBOYS' GAMBLE; AROUND THE LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Detroit running back Barry Sanders announced his
retirement Wednesday, the sports talk programs and studio shows
were filled with arguments about where Sanders ranked among running
backs in the history of the National Football League. It was one of
those maddening, fascinating and sometimes exhilarating debates.
</P>
<P>
   So it is fitting that a new book, which ranks the top 100
professional players of all time, comes along, and it is, of
course, maddening, fascinating and exhilarating.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sporting News Selects Football's 100 Greatest Players''
gets a lot right, and a lot wrong, but arguing over who ranks where
is always the best part of these kinds of lists. The book spans the
entire history of professional football, from Jim Thorpe to
Sanders, who, by the way, ranks No. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve editors from the weekly newspaper took six weeks to
whittle a list of 300 candidates __ all Hall of Fame players or
near Hall of Fame level _ down to the top 100. Some rankings boggle
the mind. Others are exactly on target. Overall it is a top-notch
list.
</P>
<P>
   One source of continuous debate will be the book's comparisons
of modern players with those from earlier generations. The former
Washington quarterback Sammy Baugh, for example, is ranked the 11th
best player while the Dallas quarterback Troy Aikman is 95th. To
one who never saw Baugh play, it makes no sense that Aikman is
ranked so far behind Baugh. To one who watched Baugh win five
division titles, two NFL championships and set 16 passing records
in 16 seasons, Baugh was indeed the better player.
</P>
<P>
   The book is like a time machine, taking you across the history
of the league, and it inevitably raises the question of how players
from the 1920s, say, would do today. Would Red Grange, ranked 80th
best, have enough speed for today's game? Would the Giants' Mel
Hein, who played center in the 1930s at 225 pounds, stand up
against Warren Sapp?
</P>
<P>
   Although the editors made few misses, the list is sure to
generate more arguments when the book is published next month.
Charlie Joiner is No. 100, despite an amazing 750 career catches.
Joe Namath is 96th, one spot after Aikman, and probably deserves to
be higher. Mike Ditka is 90th and could easily have been 15 spots
higher. Brett Favre, who has two 4,000-yard passing seasons, is
82nd. Kellen Winslow, who played in five Pro Bowl games, is 73rd.
Steve Young, who is a sure Hall of Famer, is 63rd, four spots
behind Fran Tarkenton and 22 behind Bart Starr. The Buffalo
defensive lineman Bruce Smith is 58th, running back Tony Dorsett
53rd, and Baltimore tight end John Mackey 48th, although he should
probably be in the top 40.
</P>
<P>
   One of the stranger rankings is that of running back Eric
Dickerson, 38th on the list. He never played on a championship team
and was at times a selfish player, but his not being among the top
30 is a mystery. So is the positioning of O.J. Simpson, No. 26, so
far behind Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   The top 10 are mostly excellent choices. They are:
</P>
<P>
   10. The Dallas defensive lineman Bob Lilly, called a
once-in-a-lifetime player by coach Tom Landry. 9. The Chicago
linebacker Dick Butkus, one of the meanest players in league
history. 8. Walter Payton, who missed one game his entire career.
7. Quarterback Otto Graham, who led the Cleveland Browns to a
47-4-3 record from 1946 to 1949. 6. Wide receiver Don Hutson, who
could have played in any era. 5. Johnny Unitas, the most accurate
quarterback ever. 4. Lawrence Taylor, who to many should be ranked
first. 3. Joe Montana: No one was better in a big game than he. 2.
Jerry Rice, who has both Hall of Fame hands and work ethic. 1. Jim
Brown, who retired at 29. He could have played at least five more
years and owned every rushing record.
</P>
<P>
   Riding the Reeves Vesuvius
</P>
<P>
   The Washington Redskins last week called the Atlanta Falcons to
see if they were interested in trading the Pro Bowl running back
Jamal Anderson. It was more than just an exploratory call since the
Redskins offered a No. 1 pick. The Falcons declined the offer.
</P>
<P>
   But the discussions may be far from over. Washington is expected
to make another offer soon that could include several draft picks,
possibly two No. 1s.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has been putting on a show of bravura, saying in
interviews last week that he might begin speaking out against the
Falcons and coach Dan Reeves. It is Anderson, however, who needs to
be careful.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves has little tolerance for holdouts and has told some in
the Falcons organization that he believes the team can win without
Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   Reeves also does not mind playing games with a holdout. When he
coached the Giants, there were several occasions when his
assistants would talk to their friends about a holdout, telling
them that if the player did not soon report he might not be asked
back at all. This of course would get back to the player and
terrify him. It happened once to the former Giants linebacker Corey
Miller.
</P>
<P>
   If Anderson is not careful, this could get ugly. Not for the
Falcons, necessarily, but for him.
</P>
<P>
   A Cowboy Long Shot
</P>
<P>
   The award for most unreal signing of the year thus far goes to
the Cowboys, who added the troubled defensive lineman Alonzo
Spellman last week. He signed a one-year contract for $400,000 _
there was no signing bonus _ though he can make an additional
$400,000 in incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Spellman suffers from bipolar disorder, a condition that can be
treated by medication. If he does not take his medicine, he is
prone to strange, manic behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years Spellman has been involved in a series of
disturbing acts, the most bizarre of which occurred last year when
Spellman barricaded himself inside the home of his publicist for
eight hours.
</P>
<P>
   The Dallas owner Jerry Jones pledged last year that he would
stay away from troubled players like Spellman. In the April draft,
Dallas could have drafted wide receiver Randy Moss but refused to
do so because of his troubled past. But Dallas was desperate for
Spellman. The Cowboys expect defensive lineman Leon Lett to be
suspended for at least the first four games of the season. If
Spellman is in shape, he could easily start in Lett's place.
</P>
<P>
   Around the League
</P>
<P>
   _ The accident that left the son of the former Giants
quarterback Jeff Hostetler paralyzed has recently taken two happy
twists. First, Hostetler's son, Tyler, who was injured while riding
a sport recreation vehicle, continues to make dramatic improvement.
</P>
<P>
   Second, the actor Christopher Reeves, himself paralyzed,
contacted Jeff Hostetler, and the two plan on working together to
help with charitable causes involving paralysis victims.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Giants' contract negotiations with defensive end Michael
Strahan plod along. Look for a deal to be done by the end of camp.
</P>
<P>
   _ As of Friday, Barry Sanders had still not turned in the
required paperwork to the league office to officially retire from
the NFL. The Lions remain hopeful he will change his mind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
