<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUCATION-RIVALS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    What do the other candidates say?
 &HT;    (With BUSH-EDUCATION.)
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a sampling of other candidates' education policies,
gathered from their official Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats
</P>
<P>
   Bill Bradley: Believes education should be addressed from a
kindergarten through college perspective (''K-16'') rather than
kindergarten through 12th grade. He also advocates national
educational standards, stronger accountability and ``good
technology in our classrooms.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore: Wants preschool available for every child. Wants to end
social promotions and end the use of ``unqualified teachers, some
of whom are teaching in areas they did not study.'' Gore also wants
schools to teach ``character education.''
</P>
<P>
   Republicans
</P>
<P>
   Lamar Alexander: Pushing for vouchers via ``$1,500 Hope
Scholarships for low- and middle-income children to be used at any
school they want and the schools decide how to spend the money.''
Wants to pay good teachers more, replace bilingual education with
``English immersion'' programs and cut federal regulations to give
all schools the same flexibility and freedoms as charter schools.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Bauer: Wants to decentralize major education policy
decisions, giving power to states and communities. Supports
Education Savings Accounts (ESA) and ``other measures to restore
parental choice and parental rights in education.''
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Buchanan: Wants to abolish the Department of Education
and shift its responsibilities to the states. Advocates more
charter and magnet schools and would push for a constitutional
amendment allowing voluntary school prayer to ``take back our
public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth Dole: Pushing to restore discipline to the classroom
and encourage greater participation of parents in their children's
educations. Wants to ``elevate the position of teachers in society
by rewarding excellence and by giving teachers flexibility to be
intellectually creative.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve Forbes: Supports ``public school choice, charter schools,
educational savings accounts, vouchers, private opportunity
scholarships, tuition tax credits, home schooling, English
immersion programs and block granting federal education funds
states so parents, teachers and local officials can use to improve
their public schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Orrin Hatch: Advocates helping school districts finance building
and construction, but does not support doing it through ``another
big federal direct spending program.'' He says there is a federal
role, but ``we are walking a fine line between tax incentive and
federal subsidy, between leveraging resources and establishing a
new form of financial dependence.''
</P>
<P>
   Alan Keyes: Favors school choice, allowing parents to use tax
dollars to send their children to ``schools that reflect the
parents' faith and values.'' Says prayer should be allowed in
schools.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain: Wants to provide ``educational opportunities'' for
disadvantaged children through a three-year nationwide voucher
program. It would authorize $1.8 billion each year be allocated to
states for that purpose. It would be financed by eliminating
ethanol, sugar, gas and oil subsidies.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Quayle: Pushing for vouchers, allowing ``parents to choose
the best schools for their children, particularly children in
low-income families.'' Wants to expand the charter schools program,
strengthen local control of schools and decrease the ``bureaucratic
control from Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
