</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0157 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 15:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1103 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-EDUCATION-COX     07-31 2028
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-EDUCATION-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush must share glory of Texas education success
 &HT;    (Eds: Part of a continuing series on how Gov. George W. Bush's
stands on the issues have played out in Texas.)
 &HT;    (With BUSH-EDUCATION-RIVALS.)
 &HT;    
 &HT;    By A. Phillips Brooks
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Several years ago, 1,200 Austin schoolchildren
would not have spent their summer breaks reading and writing. But
that's exactly what they did this summer in hopes of improving
their reading skills before they enter third grade this month.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, the students, considered ``at-risk'' mostly
because their families are poor, easily could have slipped through
the cracks. They might have been absent the day all students take
the state skills exam. They might have been exempted from the test
as special education or bilingual students. If they took the Texas
Assessment of Academic Skills exam, a majority would have flunked.
</P>
<P>
   But lately, students like these _ minority and low-income _ are
making the greatest gains on the TAAS and showing up their peers
nationally. And reading programs, such as the Summer Opportunity to
Accelerate Reading (SOAR) program, are helping to turn around a
stubborn trend of poor test scores for low-income Hispanic and
African American students.
</P>
<P>
   Rising test scores and a shrinking achievement gap between white
and minority students during the past five years have drawn
national attention to Texas public schools. But the focus on the
so-called Texas miracle in education has intensified with Gov.
George W. Bush becoming the front-runner for the Republican
presidential nomination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas leads the nation when it comes to improving public
schools,'' Bush said last month in signing a new education bill.
``We are raising standards, strengthening accountability and
funding early intervention so that every child learns to read, and
no child is left behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush doesn't specifically claim credit for the gains, but he
doesn't give credit to others, either. Education experts say Texas'
gains are more the result of reforms initiated 15 years ago _
reduced class sizes and equalized funding for rich and poor school
districts _ than the state's testing and accountability system that
has matured since Bush took office in 1995. What Bush does get
credit for is not retreating from those reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to me that the basic pieces of educational reforms
were put in place by Governor Mark White and others,'' said Gary
Orfield, professor of education at Harvard University, who has
researched student gains in Texas. ``For George Bush to take credit
for academic achievement in Texas is like Bill Clinton taking
credit for bringing down the Berlin Wall. It happened before him.''
</P>
<P>
   Debate over improvement in Texas public schools goes to the
heart of one presidential issue: which candidate is best suited to
lead a nation at a time when education is a top domestic priority?
</P>
<P>
   Although education was a big part of Bush's Texas re-election
campaign _ he touted his plan to end social promotions and enact
reading readiness programs, as well as his support for private
school vouchers _ he has yet to reveal any specifics about how he
would improve the nation's schools. That has caused Democrats to
repeat their charge that Bush is style over substance, but Bush
says he will announce specific policies later. The leading
Democrat, Vice President Al Gore, and several other candidates
already have released specifics about their plans.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Texas public schools have given Bush plenty to
brag about.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has set high standards and focused on reading in early
grades, moved the agenda forward on social promotion and conveyed
he is very conscious of Hispanic, African American as well as
majority children,'' said Lowell J. Bethel, professor of curriculum
and instruction at the University of Texas. ``Texas has given him a
platform on which to run.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokeswoman Linda Edwards says improved student performance
shows the governor's policies are working.
</P>
<P>
   ``In January 1996, he launched the profound goal of every child
reading by the end of third grade,'' she said. ``When you raise the
bar, people rise to the challenge.''
</P>
<P>
   Early reforms
</P>
<P>
   Earlier reformers, including former Democratic Gov. White and
Dallas billionaire Ross Perot, who headed White's special committee
on education in 1984, deserve the bulk of the credit for improved
test scores. They established smaller classes (22 students in
grades kindergarten through four), competency testing for teachers
and no-pass, no-play rules, which sidelined students from athletics
or other extracurricular activities when they failed to score 70
(of a possible 100) on their courses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in 1984, we had a reduction in class sizes, and that has
been one of the greatest reforms that has brought student
achievement up to the level it is,'' said Doug Rogers, executive
director of the Association for Texas Professional Educators, the
state's largest educators' organization.
</P>
<P>
   Al Kauffman, the lead attorney for the Mexican American Legal
Defense and Educational Fund, which successfully sued the state in
1984 to equalize state funding between poor and wealthy districts,
says the financing reforms and smaller class sizes have had the
most impact on raising student performance.
</P>
<P>
   ``When poor districts have closer to the same revenue as other
districts, then they can compete better for teachers, build better
libraries, improve the curriculum and create better learning
environments,'' Kauffman said.
</P>
<P>
   That's how Orfield, the Harvard researcher, sees it, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who knows school reform knows it takes a number of
years to work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Accountability is key
</P>
<P>
   Texas' accountability system is one of the nation's toughest,
according to Education Weekly, a national trade magazine. The
program began under Bush's predecessor, Gov. Ann Richards. Every
year, each of Texas' 7,053 public schools and 1,042 districts are
ranked from ``exemplary'' to ``low-performing,'' based largely on
students' TAAS scores. But the system goes further, holding
individual schools and districts accountable for the performance of
each student subgroup _ black, Hispanic and economically
disadvantaged, as measured by children receiving free and
reduced-price lunches. If any one of those subgroups fails to make
the grade, the entire school or district is ranked low-performing.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has strongly backed the system, and his education
commissioner, Mike Moses, has continued to raise TAAS passing
standards. This year, for the first time, schools also were
accountable for the performance of special education students who
took the TAAS and students with limited English who took a Spanish
version.
</P>
<P>
   Those accomplishments stand out even more, researchers say,
because Texas has turned around its schools in the face of
demographic shifts that have created a public school enrollment
that is mostly Hispanic and African American. A quarter of the 4
million students are poor. Minority and low-income students'
performance, overall, has tended to lag behind whites'.
</P>
<P>
   Several states, including Georgia and California, which also
have a lot of minority and poor students, are looking to replicate
Texas' accountability provisions.
</P>
<P>
   Although most of the reforms predate Bush, he is bound to get
much of the credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could he not glide in on those achievements?'' Rogers
asked.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's initiatives
</P>
<P>
   That aside, Bush has accomplishments _ and failures _ of his
own.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he pushed for legislation in 1995 that overhauled
academic standards for all grade levels, a process begun under
Richards. The new standards require students to take more and
tougher math, English, science, geography and technology courses to
graduate.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Bush used his bully pulpit to emphasize reading and
pass legislation sending an additional $32 million to schools to
improve reading instruction. More third-graders passed the reading
TAAS this year _ 88 percent of students not in special education,
up from 77 percent in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, in three straight legislative sessions, failed to pass
a pilot voucher program that would allow parents to use public tax
dollars to pay tuition at private schools. His home-rule school
district initiative, to free districts from state mandates, fell by
the wayside when no districts adopted it. The data are still out on
the performance of charter schools _ an enterprise pushed by Bush _
and a few of the schools have folded under scandal.
</P>
<P>
   When Bush took office, he proposed increasing the state share of
funding for public education to 60 percent. But the state share has
hovered around 45 percent during his tenure. It is uncertain how
that compares to other states this year. But in 1996, Texas lagged
behind California, which financed 57 percent of public education,
and Florida, with 49 percent. Texas' was ahead of New York, which
funded 37 percent of public education that year, according to
figures provided by the Education Commission of the States.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, high school dropout rates _ particularly among
Hispanics _ still are a problem. The Texas Education Agency says
dropout rates have fallen. About 9 percent of students who started
ninth grade dropped out by 12th grade, according to Texas Education
Agency figures for the period between 1993-94 and 1996-97. That is
lower than the 10 percent reported the previous period that ended
in 1995-96. That was higher than other large states: California and
New York both had drop out rates below 4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But San Antonio-based Intercultural Development Research
Association, which studies education and equity issues affecting
Hispanics, says the dropout rate is four times higher than TEA
reports: 43 percent of students during the four-year period,
1993-94 to 1995-96, did not graduate, according to an IDRA study.
</P>
<P>
   By most accounts, this session was a good one for Bush. He
signed legislation that sent schools their largest state funding
increase ever, giving all teachers, school librarians and
counselors a $3,000 pay raise. More state dollars could help school
districts hold the line on local property tax increases. The bill
expands prekindergarten and kindergarten programs and provides
extra money to help schools offer more advanced placement and
honors courses.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush passed a controversial bill to halt so-called social
promotions _ the practice of passing failing students to keep them
with their age group. Under the law, third-graders starting in the
2002-03 school year will not be promoted if they fail the TAAS
reading test.
</P>
<P>
   Bethel credits Bush for ending automatic promotion and backing
it with $200 million for intervention, tutorial and remedial
programs to diagnose learning deficiencies early and get students
back on track fast. But he, like many other researchers, worries
about using the TAAS to flunk students who otherwise make passing
grades and get high acclaim from teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Testing is a useful device especially as a diagnostic tool,
but it can be misused,'' Bethel said. ``Tests ... can separate
children, being a badge of attainment for some and (a badge of)
failure for others.''
</P>
<P>
   The intensified focus on passing the TAAS and reading on grade
level prompted Austin Independent School District officials to
create the SOAR reading program at several campuses. Schools across
Texas are doing similar things to keep up with tougher standards
and accountability, educators say. The Del Valle district has
extended the school year into the summer to catch up some kids and
advance others. Other districts, including Austin, run TAAS camps
on weekends or during the summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are serious about teaching our kids to read,'' says Linda
D. Clark, principal of SOAR, which meets four hours a day for four
weeks during the summer. ``When the kids come here, we focus on
reading. We don't do recess.''
</P>
<P>
   A. Phillips Brooks writes for the Austin American-Statesman.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
