<HEADER>
A1105 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      07-31 1374
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FREE AGENCY COULD REUNITE HARDAWAY AND O'NEAL 
</HEADLINE>
  (bl) 
 By MIKE WISE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   He could be headed to Toronto for Charles Oakley and Tracy
McGrady. Or to Washington for Mitch Richmond. Jerry West met with
him last week in Los Angeles, and even though the Lakers now appear
to be out of the sweepstakes, who knows how sentimental Shaquille
O'Neal is for his long-lost teammate?
</P>
<P>
   At 12:01 a.m. Sunday, National Basketball Association teams
could officially begin signing free agents to contracts. In
Orlando, that means Anfernee Hardaway's days are numbered. While no
deal appeared imminent, Magic general manager John Gabriel sounded
almost resigned to parting with the All-Star guard, who has caused
the franchise more than its share of headaches over the last two
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``In regards to Penny, we just don't have anything yet,''
Gabriel said Friday. ``And I would be surprised on Sunday if we
did, though things can change awfully quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on which teams have room under the salary cap, Hardaway
would seem to be headed for Chicago, Toronto or the Los Angeles
Clippers _ the three teams with the most money to accommodate a
contract that could approach $70 million. Indiana and Atlanta also
have trade exceptions worth more than $4 million apiece, which they
could use to try to acquire a player of his caliber.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers seemed interested, especially after they picked up
Glen Rice's option year instead of signing him to an exorbitant new
deal _ a move that apparently caused a rift between Rice and the
team's management. O'Neal, who begrudgingly co-existed with
Hardaway in Orlando, said recently that he had a change of heart
about playing with his former teammate.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the Magic, the Hawks are apparently ready to deal
this week. Atlanta is on the cusp of sending Steve Smith to
Portland for Isaiah Rider and either Jim Jackson or Kelvin Cato. In
need of an athletic upgrade with a new arena to fill, the Hawks are
also said to be interested in acquiring the Los Angeles Clippers
free agent Lorenzen Wright.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley, a free agent, wants to make $8 million a season for
three years _ the last three years of his career, most likely. The
Raptors think that's too much, countering with $5.5 million a
season. After Orlando lost Horace Grant, it might take a chance on
Oakley in a sign-and-trade deal with Toronto. And Atlanta is not
out of the picture, either.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a shaky season with the Rockets and interest from other
teams, Scottie Pippen sounded like he was staying put in Houston
after early trade talk. Charles Barkley is making a lot of noise
about other teams contacting his agent, which means he will
probably remain with the Rockets too.
</P>
<P>
   With Sean Elliott most likely out for the season as he awaits a
kidney transplant, the Spurs have turned their attention to George
McCloud and Shandon Anderson to fill the void. But the Utah Jazz
are intent on keeping Anderson, along with all of their old guard.
Karl Malone has already agreed to an extension, while John Stockton
and Jeff Hornacek are just waiting to sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were certainly devastated by our loss in the playoffs
because the expectations were very high,'' said Scott Layden, the
Jazz's vice president of basketball operations. ``But at the same
time, I don't think we can lose sight of what a good regular season
we had. One of the things that has helped us over the last several
years is that we've had a unique blend of veterans and young guys
come in, who have been very good slashers, namely Bryon Russell and
Shandon Anderson.''
</P>
<P>
   The league's lawyers will be in the NBA offices Sunday to help
with and approve transactions. But do not expect them to
rubber-stamp the contract that Corliss Williamson is about to sign
with Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Williamson, who played for $500,000 last season, may sign a deal
for nearly $60 million with the club. The Kings hired William B.
Gould IV, a Stanford law professor and former chairman of the
National Labor Relations Board, to handle the negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise did not want the NBA to get the idea that it
already had a deal in place with Williamson last season when he
agreed to sign for a pittance. But with knowledge of many
under-the-table deals being reached over the last few years, it
would not be shocking to see the league's lawyers investigate
Williamson's new contract. Eventually, they will need to set an
example.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn Near Pact
</P>
<P>
   Keith Van Horn is expected to sign a six-year extension worth
nearly $73 million with the New Jersey Nets as early as Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets apparently took to heart Van Horn's words in July, when
he gave the club one week to work out a new contract after the
signing period began. If the Nets failed to come to terms with him,
Van Horn said, he was prepared to play the last year under his
current deal and become a free agent next summer.
</P>
<P>
   But the extension, all but signed, not only gives Van Horn
long-term security but also insures the franchise's young nucleus
will remain intact for the next few seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Stephon Marbury signed a six-year, $70.9 million deal at the
trading deadline in March, and Kerry Kittles was given a six-year,
$50 million extension. Not coincidentally, all three players are
represented by the agent David Falk. By helping negotiate a deal
with the Timberwolves to move Marbury to the Meadowlands last
season, Falk helped insure that all his clients would be handsomely
compensated. His company's 4 percent take for nearly $195 million
worth of contracts? About $8 million.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn, the Nets' starting power forward, who is currently
doing promotional work in Switzerland for Nike, will probably not
be in the United States for the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets also want to keep the role-playing forward Jamie Feick,
and have offered him $11 million over five years. But Utah is also
in the running. The Jazz has apparently offered Feick its $2
million exception _ and a chance to play in the finals.
</P>
<P>
   Terrell Brandon is expected to sign an extension similar to Van
Horn's with the Timberwolves, a deal that could make Brandon one of
the five highest-paid point guards in the game. At an average of
close to $10 million a season, he would join the exclusive company
of Marbury, Rod Strickland, Allen Iverson and Gary Payton.
</P>
<P>
   Complaints About Rules
</P>
<P>
   From the Rocky Mountain Revue in Denver to the Boston Shootout,
there was one constant at the NBA-sponsored summer leagues the last
week of July: players complaining about the new and allegedly
improved rules.
</P>
<P>
   Since a special committee convened at the finals in June to come
up with a plan to reinvigorate offenses, officials have taken a
by-the-book approach to enforcing the experimental rules.
</P>
<P>
   ``Will it make a difference if they call it like this during the
regular season?'' Antonio Daniels of the San Antonio Spurs asked in
Denver last week. ``Without question. I think you'll see a lot of
guys in foul trouble. A lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of the changes:
</P>
<P>
   A defender who uses a hand or forearm check is immediately
whistled for a foul. An offensive player who moves while setting a
screen is tagged with a foul. Another experimental rule forbids
defenders from impeding offensive players cutting through the lane.
One rule seeks to make illegal defense guidelines more
understandable. Another sets the shot clock at 14 seconds after
fouls or out-of-bounds plays in the frontcourt, rather than the
usual 24 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Rod Thorn, the league's senior vice president of operations,
argued in June that experimenting with the rules was necessary if
for no other reason than the fact that only Sacramento averaged
more than 100 points during the past season. But it appears the
changes make take a while to get used to.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, it appears the league's general managers are already
preparing for a more free-flowing game.
</P>
<P>
   At the NBA draft in June, only two actual half-court power
players were taken in the first round, Elton Brand of Duke and
Kenny Thomas of New Mexico. Some analysts surmised this was a
result of the rules changes. Why bring in a plodding forward when
all he will do is get into foul trouble?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
