<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S OZONE LEVELS ARE WORST IN A DECADE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-HEAT.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ As New Yorkers endure one of the hottest summers
on record, they are also suffering a curse that compounds their
lethargy and sense of ill-being: the worst smog in more than a
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Levels of ozone, a toxic chemical that burns the lungs, stings
the eyes and can dim vistas with a brown haze, are the highest
since the late 1980s, records kept by the state Department of
Environmental Conservation show, and as usual, the worst of it has
blanketed New York City and its suburbs.
</P>
<P>
   The state has already exceeded the federal standard for ozone
pollution more times this year than it did in each of the last
seven years, and there are still two months to go in the
May-to-September smog season. Even upstate areas that are used to
relatively clean air have had a few days this year that were smoggy
enough to violate the federal clean-air standard.
</P>
<P>
   Ozone levels in New York State have generally declined over the
last two decades. The main culprit for this year's upward spike is
the oppressive heat. Ozone is created when other chemicals cook in
sunlight on hot days.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're looking at a combination of things, starting with the
heat, but including power plants working harder to keep up with
record demand, and people doing more driving,'' said Peter M.
Iwanowicz, director of environmental health at the American Lung
Association of New York state.
</P>
<P>
   Put simply, ozone makes it hard to breathe, particularly for the
elderly, small children, people who are exerting themselves and
those with lung diseases. It burns the lungs much like sun burns
the skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Years of exposure can do serious damage,'' Iwanowicz said.
``It impairs the ability to fight off infection, in kids
especially, and it can aggravate the trouble that heart and lung
patients already have breathing, which can be fatal.''
</P>
<P>
   Ozone, commonly known as smog, can trigger asthma attacks, and
experts say it contributes to New York City having the highest
level of asthma in the country. A study released last week showed
that hospitalizations for asthma attacks in the city's low-income
neighborhoods were far more frequent than was previously known.
</P>
<P>
   The New York metropolitan area is one of several around the
country classified by the federal government as being in ``severe
nonattainment'' of ozone standards, the second-worst category. Only
Los Angeles and its near suburbs are in the worst category,
``extreme nonattainment.'' Those grouped with New York include the
Chicago, Houston, Milwaukee, Baltimore and Sacramento metropolitan
areas, and two areas on the outskirts of Los Angeles.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Ozone is not the only form of air pollution _ the Environmental
Protection Agency monitors and sets standards for six lung
irritants _ but in many urban areas it is the most severe.
</P>
<P>
   About one-third of atmospheric nitrogen oxides, the main
chemicals that contribute to ozone, come from electric power
plants. Environmentalists say this summer's ozone problem provides
more evidence that New York state and the federal government should
make old power plants meet the same emissions standards as new
ones. Coal-burning plants built in the 1940s and '50s emit 15 to 20
times as many nitrogen oxides as new gas-burning plants, while
generating the same amount of power.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki administration plans to achieve much of what
environmental groups are asking for on nitrogen oxides, requiring
that power producers reduce emissions of the chemicals by 10
percent this year over last. By 2003, they must have cut the
emissions by 70 percent over 1990 levels.
</P>
<P>
   ``No state is doing more,'' said John Cahill, the state's
Environmental Conservation Commissioner. ``We require more
stringent controls on those facilities than are used in any other
state.''
</P>
<P>
   He also pointed to a law the state enacted last year requiring
heavy trucks to go through the same periodic inspections that cars
are subject to, including meeting the standards for tailpipe
emissions. But as state officials are quick to note, many of New
York's air pollutants, including those that contribute to ozone and
acid rain, blow in from states to the west. No one knows quite how
many arrive that way, but Cahill said, ``New York state could shut
down every facility and still have a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Vehicles, another major source of nitrogen oxides, have also
contributed to rising ozone levels, as people drive more each year
and more of them drive sport utility vehicles and trucks that are
not subject to the same emissions standards as cars.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA plans to close that loophole, which Cahill called ``a
very, very important, a critical component'' of cutting smog.
</P>
<P>
   The state measures ozone levels continuously at 31 sites around
the state. By last Sunday, those sites had recorded 25 violations
of the federal ozone standard, the most in any year since 1991,
when there were 26 for the entire year. Department of Environmental
Conservation officials said there might have been a few more
readings that exceeded the limit in the last week, but the data
were still being collected.
</P>
<P>
   Under a more stringent standard the EPA adopted last year that
is being challenged in court, there were 169 violations by last
Sunday, compared with 162 for all of last year.
</P>
<P>
   Department officials said that if the new standard had been in
place, there would have been 156 violations in 1997, and just 84 in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Ozone molecules are composed of three oxygen atoms, rather than
the two atoms oxygen molecules usually contain. Ozone is created
near ground level when the sun acts on nitrogen oxides emitted by
smokestacks and tailpipes, combined with various hydrocarbons.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, the more severe the heat wave, the worse the ozone. But
it is an unstable chemical that breaks down easily, so it
dissipates quickly when the weather turns cool or when the
chemicals needed to create it are not present.
</P>
<P>
   Ground-level ozone is not to be confused with the ozone layer in
the upper atmosphere, which protects the earth from the sun's
ultraviolet radiation.
</P>
<P>
   Ground-level ozone confers no such benefit, and does not reach
the upper atmosphere before breaking down, while upper-level ozone
is too distant to harm people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
