</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FREEMAN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FASSEL'S PIVOTAL SEASON 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also FBN-GIANTS) 
(mk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ This is how good a teacher New York Giants coach
Jim Fassel is: He has not only worked out the kinks in the throwing
arm of Kerry Collins, but he is also ironing out the creases in the
quarterback's head. When Collins was with the Carolina Panthers he
was known more for his drinking and his sloppy play than anything
else. Today his former teammates might not recognize him; Collins
looks like a completely different person.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel began working with Collins only days after he signed his
four-year, $16.9 million contract with the Giants, and it was not
difficult for a skilled eye like Fassel's to immediately notice
Collins' bad mechanics. During his drop back he raised his left
forearm near his eyes while cocking his throwing hand. Fassel has
erased the move from Collins' memory banks.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel corrected something else. Collins had a hitch in his
throwing motion because he started his passes holding the ball near
his hip. Fassel taught Collins to hold the ball higher, near
shoulder level, before he delivered the pass.
</P>
<P>
   The result of Fassel's work with Collins is impressive. In a
matter of months, Fassel has helped Collins erase years of bad
habits. Collins looks like a professional quarterback now, not a
beaten-down man. Kent Graham is still the better player, but
because of Fassel's work Collins has a fighting chance to succeed
again in the National Football League.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel, 49, is one of the top young coaches in the game right
now. He is creative, he is excellent with quarterbacks, and for the
most part he communicates well with his players.
</P>
<P>
   Yet this season Fassel has to do more than talk about how good
his team can become. He has to win, and not seven games or eight,
but at least nine or 10. Another mediocre season like last year's
8-8, and the organization-wide doubts come creeping in, like a bad
infection. If the Giants win 11, or even 10 games, it would be
proof that Fassel's plan is working. Either way, this is the most
important season of Fassel's career.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Fassel's growing process must include his winning over
two key people within the organization: his general manager, Ernie
Accorsi, and one of the best defensive players in the league,
Michael Strahan.
</P>
<P>
   Accorsi likes Fassel _ the two get along fine. But Accorsi is
not passionate about Fassel, who was hired by George Young, the
former general manager. If the Giants were to win five games this
season, rather than 10 or 11, Accorsi would probably give some
thought to hiring Marty Schottenheimer, the former Kansas City
coach who remains out of football. The two are close friends.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel and the Giants flirted with a contract extension in
January, but the talks never went beyond that. It was a sign that
each side is sizing up the other. Fassel is making sure this is the
place he wants to stay, and the Giants are watching Fassel to make
certain he is right for them.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel and Accorsi will be fine. There is less certainty
concerning the relationship between Fassel and Strahan. If Fassel
is going to capture the minds of all of his players, which he has
not yet done, he must forge a closer relationship with Strahan.
</P>
<P>
   Strahan, a defensive end, has developed one of the best work
ethics in the league. He is respected because of what he does on
the field and how he conducts himself in the locker room. Strahan
is the most popular player on the team now and the important player
the Giants have had since Lawrence Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   But so far Strahan is, at best, lukewarm in his feelings toward
Fassel. Right now the relationship is a precarious one, and
Fassel's mission for the rest of training camp should be to get
inside Strahan's head. Fassel need not worry about a bruised ego.
That is irrelevant. He simply needs to get Strahan completely on
his side.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel's qualities are many. He is loyal to his coaches and
gives them latitude without losing control. He is demanding of his
players. He is smart and has been able to work within the Giants'
rigid system without selling his soul or trying to embarrass the
organization into doing things his way, as Dan Reeves once did.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches hate to hear things like this, but the Giants should win
the National Conference East, which is at its lowest point in
years. Washington is a five-victory team, as is Philadelphia, and
Dallas is an aging, has-been franchise. No other team in the
division possesses the kind of battering defense that New York
does, and the Giants can win the East on the likes of Strahan,
linebacker Jessie Armstead and cornerback Jason Sehorn alone.
</P>
<P>
   Fassel is no longer a rookie head coach, and he is ready to
elevate his game. This is the year to do it and Fassel probably
will. Along the way, if he can make Accorsi and Strahan happy, all
the better.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
