<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1110 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BB0-HITS-MILESTONE-CO     07-31 1319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BB0-HITS-MILESTONE-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Exclusive 3,000 club to get a trio of newcomers in the same
month
 &HT;    (With chart material at end.)
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the rarest convergence of time, place and educated wood,
baseball's most exclusive hitting society is about to be overrun.
</P>
<P>
   As the weekend opened, Tampa Bay's Wade Boggs needed eight hits,
San Diego's Tony Gwynn needed nine and Baltimore's Cal Ripken
needed 34 for all three to reach the 3,000-hit club, a collection
of the game's 20 most accurate and enduring swings. Hitting might
be all about patience, but this triumvirate nevertheless is getting
itchy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, the excitement level is overflowing,'' Boggs said
after going 3-for-4 Wednesday night. ``I'm enjoying the ride. ...
This is what you play your entire career for, to get to a spot
where something you do means something.''
</P>
<P>
   Four times before, two players have reached 3,000 hits in the
same season. Tris Speaker and Eddie Collins did it 21 days apart in
1925. Hank Aaron and Willie Mays got there 4 1/2 weeks apart in
1970. Carl Yastrzemski and Lou Brock arrived in 1979. Fresh Hall of
Fame playmates George Brett and Robin Yount hit No. 3,000 three
weeks apart in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But no season has seen three players reach in the same season.
The game once went 44 seasons, 1926-69, with just two hitters _
Paul Waner and Stan Musial _ getting there. Boggs and Gwynn,
depending on how their plate appearances might be juggled during
early August road trips, should reach within the same week, with
Ripken following by Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   They will bring to eight the number of players to reach 3,000 in
the 1990s. In the '80s, only one, Rod Carew, made it. No one did it
during the '60s. Why three players within one month? Credit
expansion. Credit expansion pitching. Credit the booming offense of
the 1990s. But foremost, credit the players' longevity and three
sweet swings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The secret of hitting,'' Musial once said, ``is physical
relaxation, mental concentration _ and don't hit the fly ball to
center.''
</P>
<P>
   Each man approaches the landmark by separate paths.
</P>
<P>
   Wade Boggs
</P>
<P>
   The question had become, would he ever get there? Mired in a
4-for-30 slump, Boggs asked his 12-year-old son Brett to select a
bat for him and then singled three times against Anaheim at
mid-week in the 220th three-hit game of his career.
</P>
<P>
   At 41, Boggs still knows his way around the strike zone as well
as anyone. Last season was the first in Boggs' 17 years in the
majors that he finished with more strikeouts than walks.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, he found more significance in his first hit, which
came at old Comiskey Park on April 26, 1982, against Pat Dobson.
</P>
<P>
   ``I eventually got the hit and came back to the dugout and was
sitting next to Jerry Remy,'' Boggs said. ``And he said, `Hey, kid.
You only (have) 2,999 more to go.' That sort of stuck in the back
of my mind. Wow. That's coming from a seasoned veteran, to say
something like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it was kind of a humorous remark, but it's sort of come
to fruition.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays just left on six-game road trip, which could
interfere with Boggs hitting No. 3,000 at home. Boggs grew up in
Tampa and went to Plant High School, where he had 26 hits in his
last 32 at-bats as a senior. Reaching the milestone in his hometown
would be significant.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without saying it's going to happen at home, there's a hell of
a good chance it going to happen at home,'' Tampa Bay manager Larry
Rothschild said. ``And the reason I know that is because I fill out
the lineup card.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays next game at Tropicana Field is Friday, against
Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   Tony Gwynn
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn would have reached 3,000 in June, if not for the sore left
calf that twice forced him onto the disabled list and cost him 48
games.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he has been preparing for the moment, retiring his bats
after every hit by sending them to charities, friends, even one
each to his wife Alicia and to Padres owner John Moores. But he
stopped that practice once he reached 2,985.
</P>
<P>
   ``From here to 3,000, I'm keeping everything,'' said Gwynn, not
only holding on to bats but uniforms and other accoutrements.
``I've got a pretty good idea what I want to do with the stuff.
There's a lot of people along the way I want to remember.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of his good work came courtesy of the Braves. He recorded
151 hits at Atlanta-Fulton County Stadium, second among all NL
parks only to Cincinnati's (165).
</P>
<P>
   Of the five pitchers he has pounded most frequently, four are,
or were, Braves: Greg Maddux (35, at the top of the hit list), Rick
Mahler (33, No. 2) and Tom Glavine and John Smoltz (tied for fourth
with 28 each). Gywnn's .452 career average (28 for 62) against
Smoltz is his highest against any pitcher, on a minimum of 50
at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn will become the first National League player in 20 years
to reach 3,000, since Brock. He and Ripken will join a group of six
players to have recorded all 3,000 with one team -- Musial of St.
Louis, Pittsburgh's Roberto Clemente, Detroit's Al Kaline, Boston's
Yastrzemski, Milwaukee's Yount and Kansas City's Brett).
</P>
<P>
   But it is looking as if No. 3,000 will come not in San Diego but
in either St. Louis or Montreal this week: The Padres leave Monday
on a 11-game road trip.
</P>
<P>
   Cal Ripken
</P>
<P>
   Ripken's 3,000 will be footnoted by his longevity, which is
hardly fair. His passle of records already broken, beyond the 2,632
consecutive-game streak, include home runs by a shortstop (345) and
12 fielding marks. But his 3,000th hit should come around his
2,810th game, fewer than either Kaline or Yastrzemski needed.
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, Ripken is not overwhelmed as the date
approaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only time you think about it is when you're asked,'' he
said. ``I can read the big board, and I can read a newspaper on
occasion. But that doesn't help you when you're at the plate. The
best thing you can do is try to have a successful at-bat. You try
to put a good swing on the ball. You can't control what happens
after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Ripken entered the weekend within reach of another milestone:
his 400th homer. Only 28 players have reached 400, and only six of
them also reached 3,000 hits -- Aaron, Mays, Eddie Murray, Musial,
Dave Winfield and Yaz. And while Ripken's average (.277) will be
the lowest among those players to reach 3,000-400, he will be the
only man to do so having spent his primary playing time as a middle
infielder.
</P>
<P>
   More than a third of Ripken's hits (1,009) have gone for extra
bases, far surpassing both Boggs (752) and Gwynn (717).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm someone who doesn't like to sit down and dwell on how well
you're doing and someone who doesn't like to sit down and dwell on
how poor you're doing,'' Ripken said. ``I just want to go work it
out, then ride it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as all three have.
</P>
<P>
   Player/Hits/Date of No. 3000/Age/ of Games Needed
</P>
<P>
   Pete Rose 4,256 May 5, 1978 37 2,370
</P>
<P>
   Ty Cobb 4,189 Aug. 19, 1921 34 2,135
</P>
<P>
   Hank Aaron 3,771 May 17, 1970 36 2,460
</P>
<P>
   Stan Musial 3,630 May 13, 1958 37 2,301
</P>
<P>
   Tris Speaker 3,514 May 17, 1925 37 2,341
</P>
