<SLUG> BC-FBC-SPORTS-AGENTS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coaches taking steps to avoid the agent trap
 &HT;    By Tony Barnhart
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Last August, a somber Al Wilson stood up at a meeting of the
Tennesee football team. As the All-America senior linebacker spoke,
his voice began to quaver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sorry,'' Wilson said, almost in tears. ``I've let you
down. I got caught having contact with an agent. I'm ineligible
this year, and I'm not going to be able to play.''
</P>
<P>
   After the stunned players sat in silence for several moments,
head coach Phillip Fulmer told them that, because of Wilson's
mistake, they would have to return their SEC championship rings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked at (cornerback) Dwayne Goodrich, and I thought he was
getting ready to bawl,'' Fulmer recalled. ``It was incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Wilson started laughing. The scenario had been staged.
</P>
<P>
   ``But the point was made,'' Fulmer said.
</P>
<P>
   The point was to show the team what could happen if any player
violated NCAA rules by accepting money or other benefits from an
agent before his eligibility expired. The exercise is an example of
how coaches are becoming more aggressive in discussing with their
players an issue that has risen to the top of their list of
greatest fears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting a call about agents has become one of our worst
nightmares,'' LSU coach Gerry DiNardo said. ``And the scary thing
is knowing that there is only so much you can do. If a player
really wants to take the money, he's going to do it. You can't stop
it.''
</P>
<P>
   The latest episode to make that point abunduntly clear involves
four players from the University of Florida. The four _ Jevon
Kearse, Johnny Rutledge, Reggie McGrew and Mike Peterson _ are
accused of accepting money from agent Tank Black before their
college eligibility ended. Rutledge has admitted accepting $500
monthly payments from Black, while Kearse and McGrew also have
accepted money, although they did not reveal an amount.
</P>
<P>
   The university is investigating Black under a state law that
prohibits agents from giving cash or other benefits to a college
athlete before his eligibility ends.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known a lot of guys, in my five years, from across the
nation who have gotten away with a lot, and nobody knows about
it,'' Georgia Tech quarterback Joe Hamilton said. ``There are guys
not even in the NFL now, and they're not playing football. But
nobody knows how they got away with $500,000 or a nice car. We try
not to do that at Tech, but it's hard. It's out there for
everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The issue has three components _ the coaches, agents and
players.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches, who fear losing games and championships, preach
that a player should not put his wants above those of the team by
accepting favors from an agent.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very up front with our guys about this,'' Fulmer said.
``After the season, if they want to deal with an agent, fine. But
before that, if you're selfish enough to hurt this whole football
team, I don't want you, and I don't need you. If that's still what
you want, I'll lead the parade out of town so you can go.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of a bottom-line deal with me,'' said Florida coach
Steve Spurrier, who has banned from the school's football complex
his four former players in question. ``We have rules, and if you
break them, there are consequences. If you break the rules, you
can't be a Gator.''
</P>
<P>
   The majority of agents play by the rules, but the competition to
sign the top athletes is cutthroat because the rewards can be
great. To gain an advantage, some agents often use other students
as runners to get money or other benefits to players, to entice the
players to sign with them.
</P>
<P>
   Not every agent can afford to play by the rules, Black's
attorney, Leonard Mungo, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic issue is you have kids who are being exploited by
the schools,'' Mungo told the Associated Press. ``These players
know what they are worth, and they know the school is taking
advantage. Then you have 900 agents out there looking to sign the
240 players who get drafted.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Warrick, a senior wide receiver at Florida State, should
be one of the top players chosen in next year's NFL Draft. Warrick
said he has changed his phone number three times over the past six
months in an effort to get away from agents and their runners.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my last year, and I don't want to do anything to
jeopardize my career or my team,'' Warrick said. ``But it's kind of
hard, if somebody offers you something, not to take it. You've got
to be a real man. I know the athletes bring a lot to the table, and
we don't get anything. But that's why you play in college _ to work
yourself up to the NFL.''
</P>
<P>
   Florida State has plenty of reasons to be concerned about
agents. The school's rules-compliance officials estimate that 20
players on the current team could be drafted. One of them, senior
wide receiver Laveranues Coles, is the subject of a school inquiry
to determine if he attended a party hosted by an agent in Texas.
Several years ago, the school was mired in scandal when an agent's
runner took several players on a shopping spree at a local
sporting-goods store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Agents and gambling are the biggest problems that face college
football right now,'' said Dave Hart, Florida State's athletics
director.
</P>
<P>
   Some players, however, say it is not fair to judge those who
take money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the burden should be on the agent, but I can't blame a
guy who takes the money,'' said Cornelius Griffin, a defensive
tackle from Alabama. ``If you're poor and you've never had
anything, how can you tell a guy not to take it? You don't know his
situation or what kind of shape his mama and daddy are in.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech's Hamilton said he has his roommates screen
telephone calls, but it's not unusual for a runner to show up at
his dormitory with a pizza in hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``They try to find out what you like to do in your free time,
like play video games and stuff,'' Hamilton said. ``That's how they
try to get close to you and act like your friend. But sooner or
later, they are going to want to talk business.''
</P>
<P>
   And when a player starts talking business, that's when an
episode like the one Al Wilson fabricated last summer could become
real.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ultimately, it comes down to the guys and what they think is
important,'' Fulmer said. ``You try to educate them as much as you
can, and I think we've done that. I trust my guys, but I can't
afford to stick my head in the sand. Every damn one of them could
be sitting with an agent right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
