<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Deals slowed by voidable years
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Entering this weekend, only 18 of the 31 first-round picks in
April's NFL draft had signed.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the first 12 choices had not yet reached agreement,
including quarterbacks Akili Smith of Cincinnati and Cade McNown of
Chicago. McNown is expected to start this season; Smith probably
would back up Jeff Blake.
</P>
<P>
   The hangup in negotiations is the teams' reluctance to include
``voidable years'' in the contracts. Voidable years allow a player
to buy back the contract after three or four years. By doing so,
the players would receive a second signing bonus from their current
teams or raise their market price when they become restricted free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   The voidable years concept was introduced by agents Leigh
Steinberg, representing Kerry Collins and Ryan Leaf, and Tom
Condon, for Peyton Manning and Tim Couch.
</P>
<P>
   Couch, the No. 1 pick from Kentucky, signed a seven-year, $48
million contract with Cleveland before this year's draft that
included voidable years.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the other top picks, as well as such lower choices as
defensive back Fernando Bryant of Alabama, taken 26th by
Jacksonville, are demanding similar deals.
</P>
<P>
   McNabb's negotiations with the Eagles got nasty before he agreed
Friday to a seven-year, $50 million deal. His agent, Greg Smith,
told a Philadelphia cable TV station this week that the Eagles were
reluctant to include voidable years because his client is black.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why pull the plug now when, for the past couple of years,
you've been consistently doing it for the white quarterbacks?''
Smith asked.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Smith backtracked and said he does not think race is a
factor, after all.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to drafting Donovan, voidable years was an issue they
did not care to deal with,'' he said. ``I just think that they
truly feel it's not in the best interests of the player.''
</P>
<P>
   Rough start for Ricky
</P>
<P>
   Heisman Trophy winner Ricky Williams got off to a tough start at
New Orleans' training camp. In his first practice in full pads,
Williams fumbled a handoff, bumped into the fullback and dropped
the ball, and dropped a pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not used to going full speed right away,'' he said. ``In
college, you'd have a couple of days in which to gauge the tempo.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams told the media this week he would be available for
interviews only every other day.
</P>
<P>
   Local guys
</P>
<P>
   Danny Kight, 26, of Decatur, is bidding to become the first
African-American kicker in NFL history. Cut by four teams in as
many years, Kight, a former soccer player at Augusta State, is
battling former Texas kicker Phil Dawson in the Cleveland Browns'
camp.
</P>
<P>
   Kight, who came close to making rosters in Dallas and, more
recently, Tampa Bay, spent last year playing for the NFL Europe's
Rhein Fire.
</P>
<P>
   Both players struggled in camp this week, but Kight might have
gotten a break when Dawson, who spent last year on New England's
practice squad, sprained his ankle in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kicking situation is not settled. It's up in the air,''
Browns coach Chris Palmer said.
</P>
<P>
   A breath of fresh air
</P>
<P>
   Jesus Angoy, a Spanish kicker, ended his three-day career with
the Broncos to return to his home in Barcelona for his son's fifth
birthday.
</P>
<P>
   With Jason Elam handling the kicking in Denver, Angoy knew his
chances of making the team were slim. Angoy also said he felt bad
that the Broncos were going to spend money to fly him to Australia
on Sunday to play in the American Bowl next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``He seemed like a nice guy,'' coach Mike Shanahan said. ``I'm
just not sure if he was really into American football.''
</P>
<P>
   Angoy is widely known in Spain as the longtime goalkeeper of
F.C. Barcelona, a first-division soccer team. He retired in 1996
and has been playing football for the NFL Europe's Barcelona
Dragons.
</P>
<P>
   Two-minute drill
</P>
<P>
   Dallas' offensive line already has taken some hits. Reserve
guard Tony Hutson suffered a sprained medial collateral ligament in
his right knee and is expected to miss two to four weeks. Hutson
was supposed to replace right guard Everett McIver, who's
recovering from a torn anterior cruciate ligament that cut short
his 1998 season. McIver is not expected back until late August. ...
Arizona wideout Rob Moore and defensive tackle Mark Smith are
holdouts at the Cardinals' camp in Flagstaff, Ariz. Moore, miffed
at being declared the team's franchise player, wants a long-term
contract. Smith reportedly is demanding $1.2 million to $1.3
million for the coming season; the Cardinals have offered about
one-third that amount. The Cards also are without defensive tackle
Eric Swann, who failed a physical and won't practice for several
weeks because of knee surgery. ... Unless Pro Bowl cornerback Ty
Law agrees to have his contract restructured, wideout Shawn
Jefferson could be cut by the Patriots, who don't have the cap room
to sign first-round choices Damien Woody and Andy Katzenmoyer. ...
San Francisco is taking a closer look at the right leg of
first-round pick Reggie McGrew of Florida, who is coming off knee
surgery. McGrew had an MRI this week after experiencing pain in his
right quadriceps. ... One-sixth of the 49ers' salary cap is devoted
to paying wideouts Terrell Owens, Jerry Rice and J.J. Stokes. ...
Former running back Roger Craig is attending the 49ers' camp two or
three days a week to keep am eye on newly acquired back Lawrence
Phillips, the troubled former star at Nebraska. Craig has no formal
arrangement with the team. ... When Denver and San Diego meet in
next week's preseason opener in Australia, both teams will have
native punters. Jon Ballantyne, an Australian, has agreed to sign
with the Broncos and join the team when it arrives in Sydney on
Tuesday. Darren Bennett, of Sydney, is in his fifth season with the
Chargers. ... Denver tight end Shannon Sharpe missed practice this
week after learning that his 23-year-old nephew, Dedrick Sharpe,
had died in Glennville. Sharpe said his nephew had been born
prematurely and required 24-hour care. ... Shanahan ripped starting
weak-side linebacker John Mobley after he pulled a hamstring in the
first practice. Shanahan wasn't happy with Mobley's offseason
conditioning. ... Jacksonville linebacker Bryce Paup will miss at
least the first two preseason games with a torn right pectoral
muscle. ... The Dolphins are considering signing safety Willie
Clay, the former Georgia Tech star released by New England this
week because of salary-cap problems. ... Rookie free agent Robert
Baker, the former Auburn star who spent time in an Alabama prison
on a cocaine-trafficking conviction, could have a tough time making
the Dolphins as a receiver, but coach Jimmy Johnson might keep him
as a special-teams player. ... Tampa Bay tailback Warrick Dunn has
tendinitis in his right knee and will be slowed in training camp.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
