<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 16:10 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1113 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HEAT-DROUGHT-TREND-2T     07-31 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEAT-DROUGHT-TREND-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ACROSS A PARCHED LAND, SIGNS OF A HOTTER ERA
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Neb., N.C., N.Y., Pa., Va.)   (See also NY-SMOG) 
(rk) 
 By WILLIAM K. STEVENS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In this season of heat and drought, with New York
sweltering through the hottest July on record, the Middle Atlantic
states turning brown and scores of people dying across the country,
the question arises once again:
</P>
<P>
   Is something new and different going on with the weather?
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, experts say, the heat wave and drought of 1999 do not
yet rival some of the great bake-offs of the past, most recently
that of 1988, which seared most of the country for weeks and nearly
dried up the Mississippi River. That one made global warming a
byword, even though it was brought about by a case of natural
atmospheric gridlock that held the heat and dryness in place.
</P>
<P>
   A similarly intractable natural pattern has locked into place
this time, and although it has not yet reproduced the vast scale
and long duration of 1988's heat and drought, it has nonetheless
made a mark on climatic history. In parts of the mid-Atlantic
region, the drought is of a severity occurring only about twice in
a hundred years, on average.
</P>
<P>
   And in July, there have been 11 days when the temperature
reached 95 degrees or more in New York's Central Park. Never has it
been so hot so often in any one month since records were first kept
in 1869, and the city is closing in on the record of 16 95-degree
days for an entire summer, set in 1955.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's incredible,'' said Lee Grenci, a meteorologist at
Pennsylvania State University.
</P>
<P>
   High temperatures like those in New York and elsewhere this
summer appear to extend what federal scientists say is a national
trend toward more extreme summer temperatures since World War II.
That trend, in turn, accompanies a warming of the American climate
that in some places, including the nation's northern tier and parts
of the Middle Atlantic region and the Northeast, has amounted to 2
to 5 degrees over the last century, on an annual average, according
to scientists at the National Climatic Data Center in Asheville,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   Nationally and globally, the warming trend is smaller, as some
areas of both the country and the rest of the world have cooled.
The average annual surface temperature of the earth has risen by
about 1 degree Fahrenheit or a little more in the 20th century, and
that of the contiguous 48 states by a little less, according to the
climatic data center.
</P>
<P>
   The warming is greater at night and in the winter. By
comparison, the earth is 5 to 9 degrees warmer now than in the
depths of the last ice age some 18,000 to 20,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mainstream scientists project that the average surface
temperature of the globe will rise 2 to 6 more degrees in the 21st
century if emissions of heat-trapping waste of industrial gases
like carbon dioxide are not reduced. If that happens, the
scientists say, summer heat waves will probably become more
frequent, with nights becoming especially hot and naturally
occurring droughts becoming worse.
</P>
<P>
   For all that, few if any experts go so far as to attribute any
individual heat waves like the recent one _ or even the observed
trend toward more extreme summer heat _ directly to global warming.
The most they say is that the heat records are in line with what is
to be expected in a warming atmosphere. Much clearer, they say, are
the immediate meteorological causes of the 1999 heat and drought.
</P>
<P>
   Though heat and drought often go together, they are in some
sense separate phenomena. Large-scale patterns of atmospheric
circulation determine where it rains and does not, and these are
what have decreed crop destruction and brown lawns from northern
Virginia through eastern Pennsylvania. The drought began a year ago
and intensified over the winter, thanks to a circulation pattern
associated with La Nina, a natural occurrence of abnormally cool
water in the tropical Pacific that sets off a characteristic
pattern of atmospheric chain reactions.
</P>
<P>
   One consequence of La Nina was that winter storm tracks in North
America shifted westward, making the Middle Atlantic region already
relatively dry before summer arrived. When it did, the jet stream,
the high-altitude, west-to-east river of air that carries storms
and precipitation across the landscape, moved unusually far to the
north, said Mark Svoboda, a research climatologist at the National
Drought Mitigation Center at the University of Nebraska in Lincoln.
Its path missed most of the country, further depriving it of
moisture.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, a semipermanent atmospheric feature over the Atlantic
Ocean, called the Bermuda High, has settled in this summer in such
a position that it has directed unusually hot tropical air into the
Middle Atlantic states and the Northeast, said Fred Gadomski,
another Penn State meteorologist.
</P>
<P>
   The convergence of drought and heat in the region has made both
worse. Heat intensifies drought by increasing evaporation from the
soil. Where there is no water left, the heat that would be spent in
evaporation instead goes into warming the surface. Completing a
destructive feedback loop, the warmer surface heats the air even
more.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Until about mid-July, most of the superheat was confined to the
Northeast and Middle Atlantic states. But then the Bermuda High
expanded greatly, moving well into the country's midsection and
even the north-central United States. Yet another high-pressure
area, in the Pacific, created what Grenci called an immovable
``phalanx'' of linked weather systems. The result was to pump
tropical air into the Northeast, Midwest and upper Plains, sending
temperatures into triple digits in city after city and causing more
than 90 deaths in the last two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1988, a similar continent-sized mass of hot
air, also coupled with a jet stream displaced unusually far to the
north, cast the eastern two-thirds of the nation into drought and
extreme heat. Then, 35 percent of the country was in extreme
drought, said Svoboda, compared with around 15 percent now.
</P>
<P>
   The scope of the present drought ``pales in comparison to the
great droughts'' of the past, said Gadomski. But Svoboda said the
Middle Atlantic drought is now rivaling a major drought experienced
by the region in the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   A notable aspect of the current heat wave, said Gadomski, is
that nights have been especially warm, giving little relief from
the heat for people without air-conditioning. The frequency of
nights in which extreme heat combines with high humidity appears to
have increased substantially since the 1940s, according to a 1998
study by Dian J. Gaffen and Rebecca J. Ross, research
meteorologists for the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration's Air Resources Laboratory in Silver Spring, Md.
</P>
<P>
   This combination of extreme nighttime heat and humidity is a
heat wave's most serious threat to health and life, many experts
say, and the Gaffen-Ross study found that in some places, the
frequency with which this combination exceeded a lethal threshold
had doubled.
</P>
<P>
   What caused the increasing trend toward extreme heat? Some of it
may be accounted for by increasing urbanization, said Gaffen;
concrete absorbs more heat than foliage. But global warming may
also be part of the explanation, she said, adding that while the
trend cannot be attributed directly to that cause, it is consistent
with what scientists expect in a warming atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The National Weather Service has forecast a return to normal
temperatures this week for much of the country, including New York
City and the Northeast, as the gridlock in the skies, at least
temporarily, eases enough to allow the jet stream and a trailing
cold front to dip well down into the country.
</P>
<P>
   One red flag for the future: La Nina is now expected to persist
through next winter, and could throw much of the country into a
moisture deficit once more.
</P>
<P>
   What would kill the present drought is one of two eventualities:
the inevitable readvance southward of the moisture-bearing jet
stream as fall approaches, or tropical storms that drench the East
Coast. The latter could come at a high price: Tropical storms can
become hurricanes, and the 1999 hurricane season, which will enter
its peak period in two weeks or so, is expected to be an active
one.
 &UR;  &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
