<HEADLINE>
MITCHELL WALKS OUT ON JETS
</HEADLINE>
   (Wirh FBN-JETS) 
(rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   HEMPSTEAD, N.Y. _ At 6 a.m. Saturday morning, while his Jets
teammates were trying to wring the last ounce of needed sleep in
their dormitory rooms, Johnny Mitchell packed his gear, toted it to
the locker room and piled it there. Then he walked out of the
team's life for the second time in four years.
</P>
<P>
   This time there will apparently be no return for Mitchell, who
was the Jets' top draft choice in 1992 and had been out of football
for two seasons. One day of training camp may have convinced him
this was no longer what he was meant to do.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell was a multitalented tight end. But his career has taken
a series of bizarre twists and turns since that day in 1995 when,
despondent over a 3-13 club, he opted for free agency. He
eventually quit in 1996 and wound up living in Brazil.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell's unexpected departure Saturday seemed to surprise the
unflappable Bill Parcells, who began his news conference by saying:
``We've got a roster move. Guess?''
</P>
<P>
   When no one guessed, he then asked, ``Who would be
unpredictable?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, there was a second roster move, too. Erik Norgard, a
backup center acquired as a free agent from Tennessee, also quit.
Norgard was considered insurance if Parcells had been unable to
find a starter at guard among the pool of untested prospects now in
camp.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
