<HEADLINE>
SWEATY JULY IN NEW YORK CITY GOES DOWN AS THE HOTTEST EVER 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NY-SMOG, HEAT-DROUGHT-TREND) 
(js) 
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ July was the hottest month ever recorded in New York
City, meteorologists said Saturday. And barring a late-night storm,
it was also the driest.
</P>
<P>
   Never since 1869, when observers began logging the city's daily
temperature and rainfall, have such heat and drought plagued city
residents, said Todd Miner, a meteorologist at Pennsylvania State
University.
</P>
<P>
   Through Friday, July's average daily temperature, including
nights, was 81.4 degrees, half a degree hotter than July 1955 and
almost five degrees above normal, said Fred Gadomski, another Penn
State meteorologist. Saturday's high was expected to be in the
mid-90s, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Through Friday, only 0.44 inches of rain had fallen on New York
City, breaking another record going back to 1869, Miner said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thousand, five hundred and sixty months have transpired
since records have been kept, and this was the warmest of them
all,'' Miner said. ``But it's useful to keep things in perspective.
A single statistic can be misleading.''
</P>
<P>
   Though New York broke many records, maybe even the record for
breaking the most weather records, the heat did not reach historic
levels in other cities nearby, like Newark, N.J., or Bridgeport,
Conn. Newark's average daily temperature through Friday, for
instance, was 81.1 degrees, compared with a record 82.6 degrees in
1983; Bridgeport's July average of 77.5 degrees was also below its
record of 78.4 degrees, set in 1994, Miner said.
</P>
<P>
   But in New York City, July broke the record for the most days of
95-degree heat, with 11 through Saturday. The previous record was
10 in August 1944, Gadomski said.
</P>
<P>
   Five days last month broke or tied single-day heat records: July
5 and 6, which both hit 101 degrees; July 24 and 25, each at 97
degrees, and July 28, which tied the same date in 1949 with a high
of 97, Miner said.
</P>
<P>
   All this has taken a toll on residents, who went to hospital
emergency rooms and beaches in numbers far greater than normal for
July.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Michael Nelson, an attending physician in emergency medicine
at St. Vincent's Hospital in Manhattan, said that in the last week
alone he treated dozens of people struck down by the heat,
including one woman who arrived with a 108-degree temperature and
required emergency treatment to prevent irreversible brain damage.
</P>
<P>
   And about 6.5 million people have visited city beaches so far
this summer, a 25 percent increase over last year, said a City
Parks Department spokesman, Robert Lawson. ``I think you can thank
the weather for that,'' he said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Relief won't arrive until Monday, forecasters said.
</P>
<P>
   The front edge of a cold front, seeded with scattered
thunderstorms, will roll into the region Sunday afternoon, Gadomski
said, but temperatures in the mid-90s were expected to persist.
Sunday night will be a little cooler than other recent nights, he
added. Temperatures should fall to the mid-80s by midday Monday and
reach the low 70s by Sunday night, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By Monday day this heat wave will be over,'' Gadomski said
Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
