<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIANTS' JOHNSON RECOVERS FROM CANCER AND FINDS HIMSELF AT NO.1
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Last year, LeShon Johnson spent the end of July
in a hospital bed awaiting the third of seven chemotherapy
treatments. He had lost 20 pounds in 10 days and all the hair on
his head.
</P>
<P>
   His left arm had swollen to twice its usual size, the result of
an infection that developed where the tube bearing his chemotherapy
had been inserted.
</P>
<P>
   A few days earlier, he had awoken in the middle of the night at
home delirious with a fever. His wife, Nalani, rushed him to the
hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``The infection was right where they would pump that poison in
me,'' said Johnson, a Giants running back who was diagnosed with
non-Hodgkin's lymphoma in May 1998. ``I don't wish that pain on
anyone. I never realized how much pain a man can stand. And that
was just for the infection.''
</P>
<P>
   Nalani Johnson, who married LeShon eight days before a routine
X-ray had discovered the cancerous tumor in her husband's chest,
was shaken by how fast LeShon had deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was lying in that bed almost like a child,'' Nalani said
Friday. ``I couldn't believe how fast things had gone downhill. It
made me really nervous. I remembered what my mom had said to me,
trying to prepare me for the worst: `People die of this disease,
Nalani.'''
</P>
<P>
   A year later, LeShon and Nalani Johnson recount the story of
that heart-wrenching summer with easy smiles, even laughter. They
talk as if describing something that happened years ago, and they
talk of how quickly their story has changed.
</P>
<P>
   This July, LeShon is at the Giants' training camp, running with
an unbridled enthusiasm that is evident to all. Because of an
injury to Giants running back Gary Brown, Johnson is currently the
team's No. 1 running back, the player featured on dozens of plays
as the Giants go through their two-a-day workouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I see him at camp and I feel like bawling,'' Nalani said.
``I'm so proud of him. He never whined or cried or complained. And
look at him now.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Johnson, 28, has never played a down for the Giants _
he signed as a free agent early last year and missed all of the
1998 season because of the cancer _ he has become one of the team's
most popular players.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's just a guy who always has a smile on his face,''
quarterback Kent Graham said. ``We all saw what happened to him.
And we all saw how he reacted. He fought it and then he worked
tremendously hard to get back in shape. That inspires guys. How can
you not root for someone like that?''
</P>
<P>
   Cleared to play in the spring, Johnson said his doctors have
told him he is cancer-free.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day they told me that, now that was a good day,'' said
Johnson, who had surgery to remove the tumor. ``I never doubted I
would get better. I believed that this was something I could
handle, but I know I'm blessed to be here. It's like they say, you
appreciate everything so much more. Having to work out in the hot
sun is nothing compared to what I went through.''
</P>
<P>
   He now weighs 212 pounds, which is a few pounds more than he
weighed in his four previous NFL seasons with Green Bay and
Arizona. Getting his weight up was the final hurdle in his
recovery. A year ago, he was down to 180 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a while, I had the hardest time getting the weight on and
keeping it on,'' Johnson said. ``I was drinking milk shakes and
weight-gaining supplements. But it just didn't stick to my bones. I
think my body was still recovering, and later, as my strength came
back, so did the weight.''
</P>
<P>
   Noted for an explosive, fearless running style, Johnson doesn't
appear to have lost any of his quickness. The Giants signed him
because they believe he can add a dimension they've lacked for
several seasons: breakaway speed in the backfield.
</P>
<P>
   He may not be an every-down back, though Johnson has done that
briefly in his career, but he could rattle defenses, giving them
another threat to worry about, and he will probably return
kickoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``LeShon is a rodeo cowboy and he plays football with the same
all-or-nothing style,'' Giants Coach Jim Fassel said, aware of
Johnson's background as a bull rider in the junior rodeo circuit.
``He hits that hole at 150 miles an hour and that suddenness can
lead to long runs. I remember one game when he had back-to-back,
breakaway touchdowns runs.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when Fassel was the offensive coordinator of the
Arizona Cardinals, Johnson followed a 56-yard touchdown run with a
70-yard touchdown run in a rout of New Orleans. Johnson finished
with 214 rushing yards on 21 carries.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not changing my style, not now,'' Johnson said. ``How many
chances do you get?''
</P>
<P>
   Nalani Johnson enjoys hearing that kind of talk from her
husband.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have been asking me, `Aren't you afraid that he's going
back to football?''' she said. ``I tell them if it wasn't football
he'd just be jumping on some bull. I see it as an accomplishment.
And it's thrilling to see him back out there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
