<SLUG> BC-NY-LOTTERY-RIFT-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FROSTY AIR CREEPS INTO CAMARADERIE IN LOTTERY DISPUTE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The workers at the Pratt Car Service in Brooklyn were
singing a sad ballad about money and obsession on Thursday night.
Accompanying them on guitar was a fellow worker, Emilio Leyva, the
man they blame for a sudden rise _ and a disastrous fall _ in their
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   The workers, many of them immigrants from South and Central
America who came to New York with dreams of streets paved with
gold, say that Leyva is trying to make off with their $25 million
lottery jackpot.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers say they pooled their money for tickets and that
after the May 26 drawing Leyva announced that they had won. They
all celebrated together at the car service, and individually they
made plans: for trips back to their home countries, new houses and
businesses, and college educations for their children.
</P>
<P>
   Then, they say, Leyva vanished. Several days later he returned,
telling them he had only been kidding about the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Leyva vanished once more, this time for several weeks. He came
back with a videotape of his vacation in Florida, but the drivers
say the tape also showed Leyva making a champagne toast about all
the millions he would soon have.
</P>
<P>
   When a lawyer representing someone else, a retired longshoreman
named Eugenio Bertolo, presented the winning ticket for the May 26
drawing to lottery officials, the drivers decided that it was a
fraud: They claim that Bertolo is a fictional character standing in
for Leyva, or is perhaps a friend of his who turned in the ticket
for him.
</P>
<P>
   Six drivers and the owner of the car service have filed a
lawsuit seeking to claim the prize. The state is withholding
payment until the dispute is resolved. A hearing is scheduled for
Sept. 16 in State Supreme Court in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for Bertolo, John Hayes, says the drivers' suit rests
on inadmissible hearsay about events and words that can never be
proved and that his client, who is not Leyva or anyone who knows
Leyva, should get the money.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer for the drivers, Arnold Koenig, says that Leyva
showed off the winning ticket before he vanished, and points out
that the mysterious Bertolo has not been seen.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute has made for odd times at the Pratt Car Service,
where Leyva has returned to work despite the dispute.
</P>
<P>
   While the drivers will sometimes share a beer with Leyva,
shouting often breaks out when he passes his fellow workers, and
sometimes it leads to shoving as he makes his way into the
recreation room behind the dispatcher's office.
</P>
<P>
   Workers at the car service who did not join the lottery pool say
they doubt the dispute will ever be settled. They have grown tired
of listening as their friends rehash what they will do once they
become wealthy.
</P>
<P>
   It has all gone too far, and important friendships have been
broken, said Susonte Aracao, 64.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson is that when money is in the middle, there are no
friends,'' Aracao said. ``That's why I always play the Lotto
alone.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For his part, Leyva refuses to talk about the videotape or the
claim that he also tried to make side deals to split the money with
one or two workers at the car service, though he did offer to sell
the videotape to a reporter for $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   And he said he was not going to spend any money on a lawyer to
fight his co-workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``They need a lawyer, but I don't,'' he said, before leveling
his eyes at an employee with whom he had brawled earlier in the
afternoon. ``God is my lawyer.''
</P>
<P>
   Pulling a pillow from the trunk of his livery car on Thursday
night, Leyva said the dispute had left him poorer than before. With
work slowing at the car service, he cannot afford an apartment and,
suddenly, he has no friends to offer up a bed.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is where I sleep,'' he said in disgust, pointing to the
back of his aging Lincoln Town Car. ``I wish I'd never even played
the Lotto; it was nothing but trouble.''
</P>
</TEXT>
