<SLUG> BC-BBO-UMPIRES-UNION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UMPIRES TOLD NOT TO HARASS COLLEAGUES
</HEADLINE>
  (See also BBO-UMPIRES) 
(nk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As the split between two factions of umpires grows more
heated, the league presidents have warned umpires not to threaten
or harass their colleagues. If they do, the presidents said, they
will face immediate discipline.
</P>
<P>
   The division in the Major League Umpires Association is also
growing uglier and more personal. The wife of John Hirschbeck, an
American League umpire who is one of the leaders of the dissident
faction, received a letter Saturday bearing the signature of the
wife of another umpire, in which her husband was accused of being a
traitor who has undermined ``20 years of work from an association
that reaped him so many benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   In the memo the umpires received Friday, National League
President Leonard Coleman and American League President Gene Budig
said they had received reports suggesting that umpires might have
been involved in ``illegal threats, intimidation or harassment'' of
other umpires who may have different views of the issues raised by
the union's ``illegal mass resignation plan.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We will not tolerate any threats, intimidation or harassment
against any umpire,'' the presidents wrote. ``Anyone who is found
to have engaged in such conduct will be disciplined immediately.
Every umpire is entitled to have his own view on these issues, but
we will not allow any umpire to be threatened, intimidated or
harassed because of his point of view.''
</P>
<P>
   League officials may look into the letter to Denise Hirschbeck
from Marcia Montague, wife of Ed Montague, a National League umpire
for 24 years. The letter, a copy of which was obtained by The New
York Times, indicated that copies went to the wives of umpires in
both leagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say my wife got harassed today,'' Hirschbeck said from
his home in Ohio. ``We'll see what Kevin Hallinan has to say about
it.'' Hallinan is baseball's security chief.
</P>
<P>
   Marcia Montague wrote: ``Where did John go wrong, he shamed us
all.'' Accusing Hirschbeck of having a vendetta against Richie
Phillips, head of the umpires union, Marcia Montague said
Hirschbeck ``didn't have enough nerve'' to attend the umpires' July
14 meeting, where the umpires embarked on their strategy of mass
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead,'' she wrote, ``like a traitor and a coward he kept
quiet 'til the vote was done, then went behind people's backs to
gather support.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a shame,'' the letter went on, ``because it would have
been a good fight against what's wrong in baseball. Maybe we all
could have made a difference in the fight to restore real
leadership to the game. I would have liked to see us take on MLB,
the commissioner and the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Accusing Hirschbeck of being a ``Judas in our midst,'' Marcia
Montague continued, ``we will be looking John in the face, every
time he walks on the field, and you never know, someday we may
knock on your door _ just to ask `why?'''
</P>
<P>
   The two-page letter was accompanied by a cartoon that depicted
an umpire about to be stabbed in the back by two evil-looking
figures depicted as Hirschbeck and Commissioner Bud Selig.
</P>
<P>
   Hirschbeck was one of 14 umpires who voted against Phillips last
February when the lawyer received a five-year contract extension.
He also was one of the umpires who did not resign and urged umpires
who did to rescind their resignations. Some did, and 22 umpires who
did not have lost their jobs, effective Sept. 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still think there's a definite need for new union
leadership,'' Hirschbeck said in a telephone interview. ``The
present leadership has led us down a path that is going nowhere. I
think new leadership is needed to work with baseball. They've given
us every indication that they want to work with us.''
</P>
<P>
   The agreement between the union and leagues expires Dec. 31. The
mass resignation was aimed at inducing Major League Baseball to
begin negotiations for a new agreement. The union plans to file
unfair labor practice charges against baseball with the National
Labor Relations Board next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
