<SLUG> BC-NY-COPS-PLAINCLOTHES-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLICE WELCOME PLAN TO RESTORE PLAIN CLOTHES FOR SOME OFFICERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A tentative plan to put some Street Crime Unit
officers back in plain clothes is being greeted by many New York
City police officers as an important first step in restoring the
unit's effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   But they added that the unit's real problem was sagging morale
and fear of controversy, which has grown worse since the shooting
of Amadou Diallo by four officers in February and the large
demonstrations that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Police Commissioner Howard Safir disclosed the plan on Friday,
saying that statistics had shown that productivity in the unit had
dropped precipitously in the four months since he ordered its
officers to wear uniforms. He said he was asking his staff to
consider a plan under which officers whose tasks require stealth
might dress in street clothes.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Scotto, the president of the Detectives' Endowment
Association, a union that represents many Street Crime Unit
officers, said the uniforms had made the officers more recognizable
while conducting investigations. But he added that the Police
Department still needed to deal with the disapproval the officers
have felt since the fatal shooting of Diallo, an unarmed immigrant,
in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   That shooting led Safir to order in March that all of the unit's
307 officers wear uniforms to minimize confusion in such
potentially lethal confrontations. All four of the officers who
shot Diallo were dressed in street clothes, although their lawyers
have said they identified themselves before the shooting began.
</P>
<P>
   Arrests for illegal gun possession by the unit are down 45
percent this year, according to police statistics. They have
dropped as shootings and homicides are beginning to climb from
30-year-lows in some precincts. Police officials have theorized
that the decline in gun seizures may partly be the reason for the
increase.
</P>
<P>
   Under Safir's plan, two officers in each six-member team would
wear street clothes. After plainclothes officers had finished their
surveillance, the uniformed officers would make arrests.
</P>
<P>
   Undercover officers who deal with narcotics, street crime and
vice said that working in uniform could be a liability. They said
they sometimes follow a suspect for several blocks before he does
anything that might lead to a search. Since the change in policy,
Street Crime Unit officers said they had been forced to do much of
their surveillance from the front seat of their unmarked cars,
unable to blend in on the street because of their uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm out on the street and I see a guy acting suspiciously,
who maybe has a bulge in his waistband that could be a gun or is
looking in car windows, I want to be able to get out of my car and
follow him for a while,'' said one officer. ``But when you're in
uniform you can't jump out, and if you are tailing him in an
unmarked car, they will see you.''
</P>
<P>
   The officers said that the problems within the Street Crime Unit
go far beyond the dispute over uniforms. After the Diallo shooting,
the Police Department transferred many of the unit's veteran
officers into other jobs and filled their vacancies with less
experienced officers in an attempt to broaden the racial makeup of
the force.
</P>
<P>
   The officers also said that since Safir announced that members
of the unit were being promoted to detective-specialists and given
a raise, the unit has gone from one that attracted aggressive
officers to one seen as more of a tenure track, where officers
would get a detective's shield.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   These changes, some officers said, could create a unit that
would not be as aggressive in getting guns off the street, even if
the officers were returned to plain clothes and felt that the
department was behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Street crimes used to attract a certain type of officer,
someone who liked to be on the street and make arrests and didn't
care if he ever got promoted out,'' said another veteran of the
department. ``It was like the Marine Corps attracted Marines. But
the magnet is no longer there, and people are joining just for the
promotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Eric Adams, the co-founder of 100 Blacks in Law Enforcement
Who Care, said that a less aggressive Street Crime Unit was what
New Yorkers wanted. And if the high rate of gun seizures was the
result of illegal searches and the harassment of young minority
youths on the street, he said, the department should accept a
decline in seizures.
</P>
<P>
   He urged Safir not to give in to the unit's demands to be put
back in plain clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone can stop 100 people for no reason and come up with one
or two guns per one hundred,'' he said. ``But they have to play by
the rule book that everyone in law enforcement has to play by and
that is the Constitution. If that means they are no longer the
shining star in the police force, so be it. New Yorkers don't want
them turned loose again.''
</P>
</TEXT>
