u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-OLDEST-CABBIE-ART-     07-31 0759
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-OLDEST-CABBIE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABBIE MAY BE NEW YORK'S OLDEST (80 YEARS) AND BEST (1 TICKET) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Lakeland, Fla.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(bl) 
 By WINNIE HU   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Johnnie Footman turns 80 on Sunday, he won't be
celebrating at home with his friends and family. He'll be right
where he has been most of his life: behind the wheel of a yellow
cab somewhere in New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Footman has swerved in and out of the unruly traffic for 53
years, delivering beleaguered tourists to the airport, rushing
harried commuters to work, honking at careless drivers and all the
while surviving countless near collisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's nothing else for me to do,'' said Footman, who lives
on East 119th Street in Manhattan. ``The driving _ it's like some
people go dancing. It's part of me now.''
</P>
<P>
   Footman may be the city's oldest taxi driver, although that is
difficult to prove because records are not kept by a driver's age,
according to the New York City Taxi and Limousine Commission.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of the drivers are clearly not in their 80s, so God bless
him,'' said Diane McGrath-McKechnie, the commission's chairwoman,
``We've been encouraging long-term drivers, so apparently we really
have one here.''
</P>
<P>
   Footman has a nearly spotless driving record. He got his first
speeding ticket in May for driving 43 miles per hour in a 30 mph
zone on First Avenue. ``I was just following the traffic,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not the streets that worry him these days. In his five
decades behind a taxi wheel, Footman said, the passengers have
become ``bossy'' about telling him how to get someplace, and they
expect a lot more service, all without tipping any more than
before.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a doorman puts two people in this cab, I see them give him
a $5 bill,'' he said. ``But if I've got $3.50 on the meter, they
give me 50 cents or they don't give me anything. You know why?
Because they'll see that doorman again. A cab _ they ain't going to
see me again.''
</P>
<P>
   Footman said his best tip came when a man handed him $20 for a
$9 ride. But he said the average tip is 50 to 80 cents. Sometimes,
when he has helped someone with luggage, he'll ask, ``Is that all
I'm worth?'' That may get him another 75 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Since he started drawing Social Security benefits and a union
pension in 1984, he has cut his taxi shifts to four a week, from
six. He usually makes 25 trips in each 12-hour shift, and if all
the passengers tip, he takes home about $60.
</P>
<P>
   At 7 a.m. Saturday, Footman chatted easily with other drivers in
the parking lot at the 55 STAN taxi company on Vernon Boulevard in
Queens. His regular cab, No. 608, is the oldest in the fleet. He
pays $100 a day to lease it.
</P>
<P>
   Ioan Stoia, a company dispatcher, said he met Footman 11 years
ago when he too was a cab driver just starting out. Footman's
advice, he said, was to ``just keep it rolling'' during the whole
shift and not wait idly for passengers.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy like him, you put him off the job and take his cab away,
I think you kill him,'' Stoia said. ``He's not hungry for the
money. He likes to interact with people, every day is excitement.
He really loves to drive.''
</P>
<P>
   With a cigar in one hand, Footman unpacked his supplies. A water
bottle went underneath his seat, as did a cellular phone. Coffee
cups and well-thumbed maps were stored in the trunk for
emergencies. He snapped plastic shades on top of his thick brown
glasses.
</P>
<P>
   Then he placed a one-inch stack of folded cardboard and foam on
the driver's seat to raise his slight 5-foot-6 frame for a better
view over the dashboard.
</P>
<P>
   Footman, who was born in Lakeland, Fla., moved to New York in
1941. He started out washing cabs for a taxi company before earning
his own license. ``Something told me that's what I wanted to do,''
he said. ``It was the driving that I enjoyed, picking up people and
going different places.''
</P>
<P>
   When he is not driving a taxi, Footman climbs into his black
Chevrolet Blazer and heads for other places. He used to ride a
motorcycle, but he gave that up for his wife _ only to have her
move out several years later, in 1968. He lives alone and has one
son.
</P>
<P>
   Next week, Footman said, he plans to cruise the Interstate down
to Disney World in Florida, and then to his hometown of Lakeland.
But he said he'd always return to New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a New Yorker, when I die, I want to be buried here,'' he
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
