<HEADLINE>
ON NEW YORK STREETS, IT'S NOW A DRUGSTORE WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When a 24-hour CVS store recently opened on Columbus
Avenue directly opposite an even larger 24-hour Duane Reade store,
some neighborhood residents wondered if the escalating drugstore
wars were getting out of hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got nothing against big chains,'' said Thomas Calagna,
the president of the co-op board at Turin House, the building
between 89th and 90th streets where the new Duane Reade is located.
``But the concept of having two giant drugstores across the street
from each other _ I don't know why either one would want to do
that. Who is going to all these places?''
</P>
<P>
   It is a question many people are asking as new chain drugstores
keep multiplying across New York City.
</P>
<P>
   In just three years, Duane Reade, a regional chain that has
become New York's largest drug retailer, has made a big push to
expand beyond downtown and midtown business districts into
residential areas, particularly the Upper West Side. The chain has
grown to 145 stores from 59, 130 of them in the city. The company,
with 84 outlets in Manhattan, has a four-year plan to add at least
20 stores throughout the city each year.
</P>
<P>
   Duane Reade is not alone. The national chains are also zeroing
in on the New York market. CVS, the largest chain in the nation
with 4,122 stores, has 47 stores in New York City, 16 of them in
Manhattan. The company says it will add 200 stores in the city over
the next three years, 75 of them in Manhattan. During the same
period, Rite Aid, CVS's closest competitor, with 3,821 stores,
plans to add 78 stores to its 147 New York stores. The number of
Rite Aid stores in Manhattan is projected to grow to 56 from 32,
company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're drowning in drugstores,'' said Irene Prince, who works
in retail sales and lives on West 96th Street, in a neighborhood
where the blue-and-red Duane Reade sign can be spotted every few
blocks. ``This is insane.''
</P>
<P>
   Not just in New York, but all across the country, drugstore
chains are expanding, often swallowing up independent pharmacies or
tiny chains. The population is aging, new prescription drugs are
being developed at a dizzying rate and drug manufacturers are more
aggressively marketing their products directly to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Chain stores _ which have styled themselves as convenience
stores as well as purveyors of medication _ are considered better
than an independent drugstore in coping with the pressure of
managed care, which has slashed the profits that a pharmacist can
make on a prescription to a razor-thin margin.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the recent influx of chain stores, the industry
views New York as a largely untapped market because half the
drugstores here remain independently operated, compared with only
25 percent nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Many city residents say they are already weary of drugstore
proliferation. But some shoppers said they are happy to have easy
access to a drugstore with lower prices than some of the
independents.
</P>
<P>
   Placing stores close to one another may seem like overkill, but
Duane Reade chairman and chief executive Anthony Cuti calls his
company's strategy ``planned cannibalization.''
</P>
<P>
   In the suburbs, he explained, it is easy for a successful store
to accommodate a growing number of customers by building an
addition. That option usually does not exist in New York, so adding
a store a couple of blocks away is a means of handling the overflow
when the original store becomes too crowded, Cuti said. The new
stores then become the equivalent of annexes.
</P>
<P>
   Time-pressed New Yorkers are seen as ideal customers now that a
drugstore is no longer just a place to stock up on aspirin or
shampoo. These days, they are one-stop convenience stores where
harried apartment dwellers can pick up several small items in one
transaction, including notions they used to buy at variety stores
or defunct chains like Woolworth's.
</P>
<P>
   In residential areas, people are increasingly popping into
drugstores to buy milk, ice cream, cereal, cat food or even a bingo
marker for that impromptu game.
</P>
<P>
   No chain operating in the city has more aggressively sought the
convenience market than Duane Reade. In contrast to most other
drugstore chains, where sales are evenly split between
prescriptions and more profitable nonprescription merchandise, only
about 30 percent of what Duane Reade sells comes from behind the
counter.
</P>
<P>
   Duane Reade officials say that their well-honed knowledge of New
Yorkers' habits _ from how they throw a meal together at the last
minute to which routes they are likely to take on the way home _
gives them a decisive edge.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
