<HEADLINE>
RULING LETS BLACK EMPLOYEES SUE RAIL LINE IN CLASS ACTION
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By THOMAS J. LUECK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A federal appeals court has cleared the way for a
class-action suit by minority employees of the Metro-North Railroad
who accuse the agency of racial discrimination, particularly in
disciplining and promoting employees.
</P>
<P>
   The case involves sweeping charges of discrimination by
Metro-North from 1985 to 1996 in the way it disciplined engineers,
mechanics, conductors and other unionized employees, as well as in
its job promotion policies.
</P>
<P>
   Alan L. Fuchsberg, a Manhattan lawyer serving as lead counsel
for the employees, said Saturday that the case involved charges of
unfair policies in disciplining black workers for infractions
ranging from tardiness to violations of safety rules when operating
Metro-North trains.
</P>
<P>
   Based on a statistical analysis of Metro-North records, which
have been subpoenaed as part of the lawsuit, Fuchsberg said the
railroad's supervisors had disciplined black workers in numbers far
greater proportionally than white workers. He said the records
showed a similar pattern in promotions, in which white workers were
three times more likely to receive promotions than their black
colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   The 1,300 present and former workers named as plaintiffs include
all black employees of Metro-North from 1985 to 1996, including
many who worked for the railroad during only part of that period.
During a typical year, Fuchsberg said, Metro-North employed 1,000
black employees, about one-sixth of its total work force.
</P>
<P>
   A Metro-North spokesman, Dan Brucker, said Saturday that the
railroad's lawyers had not yet reviewed the appeals court decision
and declined to comment further.
</P>
<P>
   The 2-1 ruling late Friday by a three-judge panel of the 2nd
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals reversed a May 1998 ruling by Judge
Jed S. Rakoff of U.S. District Court in Manhattan. That ruling
found that lawyers for the 1,300 workers had failed to establish
common patterns of treatment which would allow them to file suit as
a class, instead of as individuals. The case will now be returned
to Rakoff's court.
</P>
<P>
   Although the appeals court ruling did not reach any conclusion
on the charges of discrimination, Fuchsberg said it was an
important victory for his clients because of the legal leverage
involved in class action lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only is it expensive for people to try to pursue these
things in court as individuals,'' Fuchsberg said, ``it requires
them to stand out by themselves against a company with all the
personal risk that entails.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
