<SLUG> BC-D.C.-INCENTIVES-REAL-730(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN WASHINGTON, A TAX BREAK FOR HOMEBUYERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SHAWN G. KENNEDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When Debbie Chewning started searching for her
first home last year, she often drove from her rental apartment
here to the bucolic streets of Takoma Park in Maryland, just across
the border from northwest Washington, where she hoped to live.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really liked it there,'' said Ms. Chewning, who has lived in
the Washington area since 1981. ``It was one of the first places I
looked when I decided I needed to stop renting.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Ms. Chewning heard that the federal government would
pay her to buy a residence in the nation's capital, she turned her
back on Takoma Park. The incentive: a one-time $5,000 credit
against her federal income tax. ``I started concentrating on the
areas of the district where I could get more space and a yard that
were in my price range,'' said Ms. Chewning, an office manager for
a consulting company that specializes in environmental issues.
</P>
<P>
   In March, she moved into a two-bedroom, Victorian-style home in
the Capitol Hill area of Washington. Her $170,000 home includes a
dining room, full basement and garden.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Chewning's gift from the government is an unusual income-tax
credit, available to income-eligible people who buy a primary
residence in the District of Columbia. It was designed to increase
homeownership in a city that has not only seen a steep decline in
population in the last few years but also holds the dubious record
of having the lowest rate of homeownership in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-'90s, when the district's debt climbed to more than
$700 million, residents could not always count on basic services
like garbage collection and street cleaning. In 1995, Congress put
the district's financial management in the hands of a financial
control board. The city's health has steadily improved since then.
</P>
<P>
   Eligibility for the short-term tax credit, which is available
only in Washington, is limited to single buyers whose income is no
more than $90,000 and married couples who together earn no more
than $130,000. Buyers coming from outside the district may have
owned homes immediately before moving there, but for district
residents to qualify for the tax credit they may not have owned
homes there for one year before they buy. Buyers must close on
principal residences between Aug. 5, 1997, and Dec. 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes this tax-credit program from other
homeownership incentives is that it provides relief on income tax
rather than property tax, which is a common provision of government
programs.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the Internal Revenue Service said the agency had
not tracked the number of taxpayers who received the credit. But a
survey by the not-for-profit Greater Washington Research Center
said its research suggested that up to 3,495 buyers claimed all or
part of the credit.
</P>
<P>
   (For single people with incomes of $70,000 to $90,000, the
credit is reduced by 25 cents for each dollar of income that
exceeds $70,000, and for couples the same phase-out in value
applies for joint incomes over $110,000. For taxpayers who owe less
than $5,000, the remaining credit can be applied in following years
until it is used up.)
</P>
<P>
   The center's figures were based on a sample survey mailed to
about one-third of residential properties that had transferred
ownership in the district last year.
</P>
<P>
   Using the results of the survey, the center concluded that 62
percent of those claiming the credit already lived in the district,
about 18 percent had previous addresses outside the district and
the rest said they previously lived outside the Washington
metropolitan area.
</P>
<P>
   Real estate professionals, housing experts and local officials
say the tax credit has contributed to the best housing market in
the district that they have ever seen. A strong economy, lower
interest rates and an apparent renewed faith in the district as a
place to live have also encouraged people to buy homes.
</P>
<P>
   According to the National Association of Realtors, sales of
existing homes and apartments in the district jumped by 50 percent
last year, the second-biggest increase in the country after
Kentucky.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, 13,000 homes and apartments were sold in Washington,
according to the organization. Sales totaled 8,700 in 1997 and
6,700 in 1996. The NAR figures are rounded off to the nearest 100
and do not include new homes.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   James Assey, a lawyer who returned to Washington after working
in South Carolina for nearly two years, said the tax credit helped
him make his decision to buy a home rather than rent again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came back fully expecting to rent a place,'' said Assey, who
started his rental search in the district as well as in Alexandria
and Arlington in Virginia. ``But I discovered that when I crunched
the numbers and took into consideration the tax credit and the cost
of renting, it made no sense to rent.'' Late last year, Assey paid
$250,000 for a town house on Capitol Hill that includes his
two-bedroom residence and a small rental unit.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Citrin, who bought a $110,000, one-bedroom condominium in a
prewar building in the Adams Morgan neighborhood, said that the tax
credit made it possible for him to buy the apartment he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started looking in 1997 and then stopped to save money and
pay off bills,'' Citrin said. ``When I came back to the market
about Christmas late last year, prices were higher and there were
not as many apartments in my price range. The tax credit definitely
helped.''
</P>
<P>
   Tucker and Susan Greer said the $5,000 tax credit helped them
justify making a commitment to the district.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are both government workers and we love being in
Washington,'' said Greer, who works for the government Printing
Office. ``When it was time for us to buy, I was really open to any
option. When they dangled the $5,000 in front of us, it made the
decision to stay in Washington easier.'' The Greers, who rented an
apartment in Dupont Circle, paid $230,000 for their three-bedroom,
1890 row house in a nearby neighborhood, Logan Circle.
</P>
<P>
   The tax credit was the idea of Eleanor Holmes Norton, who
represents the district in the House of Representatives, as she
searched for ways to use tax policy to revive the city. The program
was part of the Federal Taxpayer Relief Act of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have already lost three times the population in this decade
as we lost in the last,'' said Ms. Norton, who expects the tax
credit to increase the base of taxpayers, stabilize neighborhoods
and stem population loss. ``This tax credit was the fastest way to
stimulate homeownership.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the Census Bureau's estimated population
statistics, the district has had a 13 percent drop in population
since 1990. The census put the estimated population at 606,900 in
1990 and 523,100 as of July 1, 1998. According to the census, in
1998 the rate of homeownership across the country was 66.3 percent,
while in the district about 40 percent of residents owned their
homes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Washington is a city of homes,'' said Ms. Norton, a native
Washingtonian, ``but the majority of residents are tenants. We need
more homeowners. When you own your own home, you are less likely to
flee.''
</P>
<P>
   Eligible buyers claim the credit when they file federal income
tax returns for the year they bought their homes. Fannie Mae, the
nation's largest provider of home mortgage funds, which is based in
Washington, and the district's Housing Finance Agency are working
on a strategy to allow buyers to use the money up front for down
payments or closing costs. The most likely plan will be loans from
employers.
</P>
<P>
   Patrick Lavigne, who with his wife, Lari, bought a three-bedroom
house in the Capitol Hill area, said they were motivated as much by
the city's atmosphere of rejuvenation as by the tax credit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did the $5,000 make us decide to buy in the city; probably
not,'' Lavigne said. ``It certainly didn't hurt.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Given the political situation in the past, living in the
district has been trying,'' Lavigne said. ``This was a community
that for a time was not able to sweep the streets. But recently
some of our concerns have been offset by improvements. We are more
comfortable with our investment now.''(BBOX)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
