u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CT-TOWN-DISPUTE-NYT &LR;      07-31 0726
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-TOWN-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GENERATING IRE IN A PLACE FOND OF PEACE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Mass.)  (mk) 
 By MIKE ALLEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON, Conn. _ Maybe it was because he used his Fifth
Avenue address when he wrote to town hall. Maybe it was because he
sent a lawyer to a crucial town meeting, instead of showing up
himself. Or maybe it was because he tore down a Cape Cod, within
sight of the village green, to make way for a pool and cabana.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the reason, G. Kelly Martin, 39, had no good will to
draw on when he decided to finish off his weekend retreat with a
power generator big enough to light up much of the town. Instead,
Martin, the head of global debt markets for Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.,
quickly accomplished what no one else had been able to: He united
the town's natives with the many newcomers who have begun using
Washington as a hideout from New York City.
</P>
<P>
   Both groups hate his generator.
</P>
<P>
   For now, it sits silently on a concrete pad, ready to protect
Martin, his wife, Elizabeth, and their four young children from
blackouts after they begin spending weekends here in the Litchfield
Hills of northwestern Connecticut. But complaints about the
generator have prompted a review by town authorities of all the
changes Martin has been making, and the improvements have been
found to be more ambitious than the permission he has obtained.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something new every day,'' said Lois Gould, a novelist
who lives next door and who was dismayed last week to find that in
addition to everything else, workers were putting in a new fence.
</P>
<P>
   Nicholas Solley, the chairman of the town's Zoning Board of
Appeals, witnessed a test of the generator and found the noise
level to be ``louder than an idling backhoe,'' but ``consistent
with a commercial lawn mower.'' That was little consolation to Ms.
Gould. ``If there's a power problem and it goes for a day or two or
three, it'll be a real menace,'' she said. ``It'll be like a
continuous car alarm.''
</P>
<P>
   From his vacation home on Nantucket in Massachusetts, Martin
scoffed at speculation here that he was building a shelter against
Year 2000 computer problems. He said he wanted the generator only
because he was concerned that his pipes could freeze during power
failures, which often occur around here because of ice on power
lines. ``We hope the latest misunderstandings can get quickly
behind all of us so we can just enjoy the town,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, R. William Fairbairn, who has lived in town 37
years, said Martin was the victim of out-of-control gossip.
</P>
<P>
   This town of 4,100, named for a famous general who ate breakfast
here in 1781, was once a hub for ironworks but now is known for its
private schools. It has become a retreat for notables from the
worlds of fashion, entertainment and publishing, so tavern fare now
includes ``pan-seared salmon cakes with curried mango chutney.''
Homey touches do remain: The town's annual report lists the year's
births, deaths and marriages (two pages total).
</P>
<P>
   Washington officials have found that Martin has installed
improvements that cover 214 square feet more than had been approved
in 1997. He has offered to tear up one of his sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   But zoning appeals officials will meet Thursday to determine
whether his changes to the original plan are permissible. At a
recent meeting his lawyer, Fairbairn, contended that the total
number of square feet is what counts, not how they are used. That
rankled appeals board members, who told him there was no point in
approving plans a homeowner did not have to follow.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're saying probably we could do these things by mail,''
said Edmund White, a 12-year member of the board.
</P>
<P>
   Joan Kaplan, who works at a bank in New York and has a weekend
place across Kirby Road from the Martins, said they would have
received a warmer welcome if they had shown ``a sense of humility
and a sense of appropriateness.''
</P>
<P>
   So much resentment has been focused on the estate that Martin
has been blamed even for developments that were not his doing. When
a tree was cut down at the front of his property, locals lamented
what they swore was the oldest horse chestnut tree in Connecticut.
It turned out that a utility company had done the deed, but many
here still consider it one more black mark for the neighbor they
have never met.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
