<SLUG> BC-YACHT-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMERICA'S CUP CHALLENGER YACHTS ARRIVING IN NEW ZEALAND 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BARBARA LLOYD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   America's Cup fans eager for a glimpse of new yachts preparing
for challenger races this fall in New Zealand will most likely be
disappointed. The 75-foot sailboats are shrouded in secrecy even as
they are being unloaded in Auckland from ports around the world.
But some trends are becoming apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've seen, the new boats are very, very narrow,''
said Dyer Jones, president of the America's Cup Challenge
Association in Auckland. ``I suspect we're going to see fast boats
out there and slow boats, good boats and snoozers.''
</P>
<P>
   The new sailboats are trickling in for the Oct. 18 start of the
four-month Louis Vuitton Cup challenger trials. Team New Zealand,
the defender of the America's Cup, is scheduled to race against the
winning challenger beginning Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   A preliminary deadline of Sunday requires each challenger to
present its official entry _ a bona fide sail number _ to race
organizers.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen international teams are expected to comply out of the
original 18 that were interested. The lineup includes five
syndicates from the United States, two from France, and one each
from Australia, Italy, Japan, Spain, Switzerland and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The overall challengers' outlook is sketchy. But from what is
known, the following is an early ranking of eight of the top
contenders:
</P>
<P>
   1. Prada Challenge, Italy: Financial wherewithal from the Prada
fashion house has given this team a head start. It has drawn key
players from American teams, as well as luring Doug Petersen, a key
designer on New Zealand's winning 1995 team. The Italians also had
the foresight to buy assets from Bill Koch's unsuccessful America's
Cup defense for the United States in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   2. America One, San Francisco: The tenacity and leadership
potential of this group's skipper, Paul Cayard, cannot be ignored.
Although Cayard has been diverted by fund-raising efforts, his
skill in match racing and last year's toughening in an impressive
Whitbread Round the World Race victory make him a vigorous
opponent.
</P>
<P>
   3. Young America, New York: Seemingly a winner by its
association with the New York Yacht Club, the group has formed a
solid team of cup veterans. Bruce Farr's yacht design expertise has
deprived the Kiwis of a source they might have tapped _ Farr is a
native New Zealander. But the same political strife that ensnared
the New York Yacht Club for the 132 years it held the America's Cup
has entangled it again. A deal that went awry last March over
television sponsorship cost the syndicate more than $2.5 million in
cash and an indeterminate amount of good will.
</P>
<P>
   4. Team Dennis Conner, San Diego: The master of America's Cup
yacht racing has the ability to win again, if only through pluck.
Just when his opponents think he is over the hill at 56, he comes
back and strings them along. Still, a one-boat program and
exhaustive fund raising do not bode well for the veteran. Having
hired Ken Read as helmsman improves Conner's chances.
</P>
<P>
   5. Nippon Challenge, Japan: Failed efforts in 1992 and 1995 have
made this team hungry for victory. In a wise ploy, this time the
Japanese have hired Peter Gilmour of Australia as helmsman. Gilmour
is ranked No. 1 on the world match-racing circuit. The syndicate's
two new boats have already been launched but not yet shipped to New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
   6. Aloha Racing, Honolulu: John Kolius, a seasoned cup sailor
with a top gun attitude, has been more secretive than most. Having
been stomped on in an ill-fated cup attempt in 1986-87 as skipper
for the New York Yacht Club, he has come back with zeal. He is
building two boats, a signal that winning is his only option.
</P>
<P>
   7. America True, San Francisco: As founder of the cup's first
coed team this year, Dawn Riley has revised the all-women approach
to racing that was part of her participation in the 1995 cup
campaign. Determined not to be left behind this time, Riley's group
is the only U.S. team already sailing in Auckland _ albeit with
only one new boat in the works.
</P>
<P>
   8. Spanish Challenge, Spain: Helmsman Pedro Campos came to the
America's Cup races in 1992 and 1995 with more style than
substance. But an effort now that includes rebuilding the old boat
and designing a new one has strengthened his chances for a decent
performance in Auckland.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
