<HEADER>
A1167 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-N.Y.-DECO-REAL-NYT &LR;      07-31 1136
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-N.Y.-DECO-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BANK'S ART DECO SIGNATURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CHRISTOPHER GRAY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A decade ago, the Bank of New York took over Irving
Trust Co., in a move that gave it not just another bank but, last
year, a new headquarters address: Irving Trust's 1931 skyscraper, 1
Wall Street. Now the Bank of New York is spending $1.9 million to
repair the outside of the Art Deco limestone structure, which also
has a striking set of little-known Art Deco interiors.
</P>
<P>
   By the 1920s, Irving Trust, established in 1851, had its
headquarters in the Woolworth Building, but other offices were
spread over the downtown area. In 1928, the bank began assembling a
site for the financial district's most prestigious address, 1 Wall
Street, and construction on its 50-story building began the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The bank hired the architectural firm of Voorhees, Gmelin &AMP;
Walker, which had developed a specialty of industrial and corporate
buildings for electric, telegraph and telephone companies.
</P>
<P>
   Ralph Walker, a designer with the firm, wrote in Architectural
Forum that ``the exterior of a building has to be viewed by
thousands, and we have got to give them mental relief and
pleasure.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker and his partner, Perry Coke Smith, developed a faceted
wall surface of limestone blocks that picked up on the slightly
angled frontage on Wall Street. Walker was not keen on the
aggressive new European modernism that people were talking about.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a little old-fashioned in our belief that one would
rather have some solid spaces in the walls than to have them all
glass'' he wrote in Architectural Forum, obliquely indicating that
an all-glass skyscraper must have at least crossed his mind.
</P>
<P>
   Irving Trust's new headquarters opened in early 1931, after $3
billion in deposits had been shuttled to the new building's
three-story high vault, at all times ``in direct machine-gun
range,'' The New York Times said. The vault was given a protective
chemical coating that would give off paralyzing gas if attacked by
a safecracker's torch.
</P>
<P>
   The magazine Architecture said the goal for Irving Trust had
been different from traditional bank design: Irving Trust's
interior was to be made ``inviting and friendly, rather than
austerely monumental.''
</P>
<P>
   This meant a series of Art Deco interiors that remain among the
most unusual spaces in New York. Facing Wall Street is the bank's
original reception room, with a high, vaulted space in glass mosaic
tile, ranging from dark oxblood, Chinese red and other shades to
near-orange at the top, all interspersed with a spider web of gold
and bronze lines. These were executed by Ravenna Mosaics at a
factory in Berlin.
</P>
<P>
   The entrance to the upper floors is centered on a lobby at a
second entrance on Broadway, with faceted walls of black and white
marble from the Pyrenees, and a split-level entry in back on New
Street _ the architects provided for double-deck elevators that
were never installed. On the ceiling of this space, Hildreth Meiere
executed a mural variously titled ``Power of Wealth to Create
Beauty'' or ``The Only Reason for Wealth Is the Attainment of
Beauty.'' Photographs of the mural show a striking cubist-style
swirl of forms with no obvious narrative or form.
</P>
<P>
   The bank leased out the 11th through 45th floors, but built out
the upper five levels in various striking designs. One was a
``shell room'' dining area on the 46th floor, with faceted walls
and shell-shaped glass forms on the ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Another, at the absolute top, was an observation lounge _
apparently not public _ a gaspingly high space with a vaulted
ceiling faced with luminous Philippine shells and wall coverings
modeled after an American Indian headdress. Period photographs show
this room furnished with Art Deco furniture and light fixtures.
Other rooms were finished in Moderne-style oak, Yuba wood, teak and
pigskin.
</P>
<P>
   Opening in the shadow of a deepening Depression, and the greater
reputation of buildings like 40 Wall Street, the Chrysler Building
and the Empire State Building, the new Irving Trust Building _ with
its comparatively mild exterior _ never acquired architectural
superstar status.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis Mumford, in one of his earliest architecture reviews for
The New Yorker in late 1931, called it ``mere swank, and
unconvincing swank at that,'' much preferring the same architect's
more modest Institute for the Crippled and Disabled at the
northeast corner of 23rd Street and First Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Irving Trust was the standing receiver in bankruptcy for the
Southern District of New York, and by 1933, 150 people were working
in the receivership department at 1 Wall Street, managing failed
businesses from shoe manufacturers to restaurants. In 1933, New
Outlook magazine called it a ``Central Repair Shop for Broken
Business,'' including the Shubert Theater, Radio-Keith-Orpheum and
the Savoy Plaza Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   In 1965, the successor firm to Voorhees, Gmelin &AMP; Walker _ by
then Voorhees, Walker, Smith, Smith &AMP; Haines _ returned to 1 Wall
Street to design an annex directly to the south in a compatible but
simplified modern style. On the interior, it appears the modern
travertine flooring of the main floor of the annex was extended
into the 1931 building at this time, eliminating the deep red
marble of the reception room. Perhaps this was also when the
ceiling in the 1931 lobby was dropped, covering or perhaps even
destroying the Meiere mural.
</P>
<P>
   Upstairs, there is little trace of Irving Trust's original
high-style interiors, except for the angular, shell-faced ceiling
in the observation room.
</P>
<P>
   One change that Bank of New York, which was established in 1784,
has made since making 1 Wall Street its headquarters last year is
installing a museum on the 10th floor with exhibits on the history
of both banks, including Alexander Hamilton's banking records, a
1790s vault key, and a note for what Christine McKay, the Bank of
New York's archivist, says is the first loan ever made to the
United States, in 1789.
</P>
<P>
   There are also photographs of some of the lost Irving Trust Art
Deco furnishings, like a sumptuous ice-water dispenser and Art Deco
ashtrays. To see the exhibit, write to Ms. McKay at the Bank of New
York, 1 Wall Street, New York, N.Y. 10286 for an appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Now the Bank of New York is beginning a complete repointing,
stone repair and cleaning project to address persistent leaks. Left
unexplored will be the area above the dropped ceiling in the lobby
_ the bank is not even sure the Meiere ceiling survives. While the
alterations to the Art Deco interiors are so profound as to seem
irreversible and the observation lounge at the top is for bank use
only, the reception room off Wall Street is open to the public and
still astonishing despite its changes.(BBOX) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
