<SLUG> BC-FBN-GIANTS-TOOMER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOOMER REAPS HIS REWARD
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY _ In his first two seasons with the Giants, wide receiver
Amani Toomer mystified his coaches. Although he missed time because
of injuries, there was talk of missed assignments and improperly
run pass routes. Toomer, a second-round draft pick in 1996, slipped
to fifth on the Giants' five-man depth chart at receiver.
</P>
<P>
   But, last season, in the words of Giants coach Jim Fassel,
``Amani was a totally changed man.''
</P>
<P>
   With 27 catches, including the game-winning touchdown to beat
the previously unbeaten Denver Broncos, Toomer had his best pro
season. And Saturday, that turnaround led to a new four-year
contract. Toomer would have become a free agent after this season;
instead, he agreed to a deal that Toomer said was worth $11.2
million with a $3.2 million signing bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the Giants cut Chris Calloway so they could
elevate Toomer, 24, to a starting role.
</P>
<P>
   General Manager Ernie Accorsi of the Giants said signing Toomer
would have no effect on the team's efforts to sign defensive end
Michael Strahan to a contract extension.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1758EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0186 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1169 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEDFORD-SCHOOL-BATTLE     07-31 1057
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEDFORD-SCHOOL-BATTLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLAN FOR ELITE SCHOOL IN WESTCHESTER DIVIDES HAVES AND HAVE-MORES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By LISA W. FODERARO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEDFORD, N.Y. _ On the surface it seems like the kind of
straightforward development that most towns would welcome. An elite
private day school here, Rippowam Cisqua, wants to build a new high
school on more than 100 acres, with a dozen athletic fields and two
rambling structures designed to fit in with this town's New
Englandy temperament.
</P>
<P>
   But this is Bedford, one of the wealthiest towns in Westchester
County, where Ralph Lauren, Glenn Close and Chevy Chase have homes,
where residents are almost as protective of the town's semirural
character as they are of their own children _ and where nothing is
straightforward.
</P>
<P>
   The plan has turned what would, in most places, be a standard
not-in-my-backyard tiff into a battle royal, with the school's
tremendous financial resources arrayed against the technical
expertise of the opponents, whose resumes include environmental
science, law, public relations and political organizing.
</P>
<P>
   It has also pitted the school's upper-class supporters against
its merely upper-middle-class opponents, who fear increased
traffic, noise and water pollution. And it has divided
conservationists and open-space advocates, many of whom are alumni
of ``Rip,'' a school that for decades has occupied a hallowed spot
in Bedford's so-called Holy Trinity, along with the local Episcopal
church and the golf and tennis club.
</P>
<P>
   If built as proposed, the $25 million high school will resemble
a small college, offering the 400 students two ice rinks and four
basketball courts in a giant field house, 12 athletic fields and
six tennis courts outdoors, and a 500-seat auditorium. The property
itself is a little Eden, with thickly wooded hills and vales, rocky
outcroppings and five clear ponds that shimmer in the sun.
</P>
<P>
   For some 20 years, parents of Rippowam Cisqua students have
dreamed of having an independent high school nearby. That desire
intensified in recent years as more and more parents shied away
from the boarding-school option and found it hard to place their
children in private high schools in nearby Greenwich, Conn., or
elsewhere in Westchester because of the increased competition for
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my kids home with me,'' said Nancy Joyce, a Bedford
resident with two children at Rippowam.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the idea of a Rippowam Cisqua High School suddenly
became feasible. That was when the president of the school's board
of trustees, Dort A. Cameron, who sent four children to Rippowam,
bought the 113-acre property on Route 22 for $6 million. He bought
the site, a former gravel quarry, with the intention of giving it
to the school if the town approved the high school plan.
</P>
<P>
   The school thought its new high school would open this fall, but
it is still in the midst of an approvals process involving the
town's wetlands control commission, planning board and zoning board
of appeals. In May, the town signed off on the draft environmental
impact statement, a compendium of maps, traffic studies, hydrology
reports and appendices weighing 39 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Now the school, which needs a special permit to build in a
residential zone, is answering questions raised by town officials
and residents. A verdict is not expected until early 2000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's just say we were naive about the time it would take to
move through the permitting process,'' said David D. Blanchard, who
was brought in 2 1/2 years ago to be headmaster and to oversee the
high school project. He gave up his duties as headmaster in July to
devote all his time to the high school.
</P>
<P>
   Bedford officials are always meticulous about analyzing and
approving projects. But in this case, the school has had the added
burden of a vociferous and savvy opposition.
</P>
<P>
   One of the foes is Donna De Bernardo Marino, a lawyer and former
ombudsman for Gov. Mario Cuomo. (Her husband is John A. Marino, the
former chairman of the New York state Democratic Party and now the
managing partner of Dan Klores Associates, a powerful public
relations firm in Manhattan.) Another opponent is Lee Wordsman, a
scientist who writes environmental impact statements for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the opponents, who call themselves Concerned Citizens of
Bedford, live in a section of town near the proposed school called
the Farms. By Bedford standards, it is a modest neighborhood, where
houses sell for $350,000 to $450,000 and Toyotas and Hondas fill
the driveways. Children typically attend the well-regarded public
schools.
</P>
<P>
   But many families whose children attend Rippowam live in the
``estate area,'' where mansions sell in the millions, Jaguars and
Range Rovers punctuate long driveways, and properties (not yards)
are measured in multiple acres. The school's current student body
includes the children of Chevy Chase, author Michael Crichton and
financier George Soros.
</P>
<P>
   A byproduct of the fight is class friction. ``The opposition
lives on one acre in the Farms, whereas the students attending the
school live on four acres-plus,'' said one alumnus of the school.
``So clearly there is an `us-them,' `town-gown,'
`hilltopper-flatlander' issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Wordsman put it more simply: ``The doctors and lawyers are
feeling threatened by the brokers and bankers.''
</P>
<P>
   Both sides have embarked on slick publicity campaigns to win
over residents and town officials.
</P>
<P>
   This spring, opponents commissioned a random survey of 200 of
the town's 18,000 residents by a Washington-based polling firm, and
Dan Klores Associates, working pro bono, pitched the results to
reporters. ``Bedford Residents Overwhelmingly Oppose Rippowam
Cisqua's Proposed Development (60 percent vs. 31 percent),''
shouted the headline on the press release. (The school decried the
poll as a marketing device, calling the 32 questions slanted.)
</P>
<P>
   ``Who can argue with another school?'' Mrs. Marino said in an
interview. ``It's very hard to oppose something that on paper is a
good thing for the town. But it's too big a project in a location
where it doesn't belong.''
</P>
<P>
   The poll revealed that traffic is the top concern of residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Traffic is already awful,'' Mrs. Marino said. ``The additional
cars will all let out at once. It's just going to be a nightmare.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
