<HEADER>
A1170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      07-31 0898
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-CHASS-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON BASEBALL: AN ENEMY OF THE PEOPLE RETURNS TO FENWAY PARK
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mike Stanley recalled that when Wade Boggs returned to
Fenway Park for the first time in a New York Yankees uniform, the
Fenway Park faithful first saluted their former hero with an
ovation, then booed him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's that adoration and appreciation for what he did,''
said Stanley, now a member of the Red Sox, ``but then it gets back
to you're the enemy, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger Clemens had appeared at Fenway as the enemy before
Saturday. He pitched here for the first time and the second time in
1997 as a member of the Toronto Blue Jays. But compared with the
Yankees, the Blue Jays are allies in Red Sox land.
</P>
<P>
   Wearing the road gray uniform of the Yankees _ never mind that
it has no pinstripes _ he was the enemy Saturday. He was actually
standing on the Fenway Park mound and pitching for the Yankees
against the Red Sox. Some things are just never meant to happen.
</P>
<P>
   For 13 seasons, Clemens stood on that same mound and pitched for
the Red Sox, sometimes against the Yankees. The thought of
reversing that scenario was unthinkable. But baseball, especially
as it is practiced by the Red Sox, is a different business. Some
teams try to keep their star players; the Red Sox seem to encourage
them to leave.
</P>
<P>
   In the case of Mo Vaughn last winter, it was a case of not
wanting to pay him the going market price, or anywhere near it, for
that matter. After the 1996 season, the Red Sox decided that
Clemens had a foot in baseball's graveyard of used-up players.
</P>
<P>
   Except they watched him work for the Blue Jays the next two
seasons and win 41 games and two Cy Young awards.
</P>
<P>
   Clemens could have defected to the enemy when he was a free
agent. He even said he wanted to go to a team that had a chance to
play in the World Series. Perhaps it was his brain that had a
problem that winter, not his arm, because he shunned the Yankees,
who would play in the World Series in 1998, and the Cleveland
Indians, who would play in the World Series in 1997, and signed on
with the Blue Jays, who last played in the World Series in 1993. He
finally asked out of Toronto last winter, again saying he wanted to
play for a contender, but his move was a thinly veiled play for
money.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Brown and Randy Johnson were signing free-agent contracts
far more lucrative than he had received, and he wanted his. So he
was on the mound at Fenway Saturday pitching for the team that will
very likely take him to his World Series, and the Fenway fans were
waiting for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the All-Star Game, they gave him a nice round of boos,''
Willie Randolph, a Yankees coach, said before the game, ``so I'm
sure they'll be out in force today.''
</P>
<P>
   Clemens was introduced at Fenway 2 1/2 weeks ago as one of the
100 players whom baseball has designated as the best players of the
century. He was not a member of the American League All-Star team,
so he didn't pitch in the game, and he did not pitch when the
Yankees played here in May. In 1997, in his first post-Red Sox
appearance here, the dominating right-hander struck out 16 in eight
innings and allowed one hit and four walks in eight innings of a
3-1 Toronto victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we played him with Toronto, it was a pretty exciting
game,'' John Valentin, the Red Sox third baseman, said Saturday.
``He was really juiced and he pitched well.'' Stanley said that
game with the Blue Jays was ``the one that was most hyped, that was
most anticipated.'' But, Stanley added: ``He's in pinstripes now.
He's the enemy. That whole aura. It's still special for him to come
back and pitch here.''
</P>
<P>
   David Cone, who has traveled and changed teams even more
extensively than his teammate, was looking forward to seeing how
the fans would treat Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of those unique days at Fenway,'' Cone said. ``It's
going to be tough for a lot of Red Sox fans to see this day, more
so than when he came back with Toronto, I'm sure.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the fans felt, Valentin looked forward to facing
Clemens again. Valentin drove in the lone run in Boston's 4-1 loss
to Clemens at Yankee Stadium in May.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was pretty much the same,'' Valentin said of the pitcher
who has not dominated teams this season. ``I really haven't seen
any decline.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a theory that Clemens becomes too intense, especially
early in games, and tries to do too much, succeeding only in
getting himself in trouble. Valentin didn't buy that theory
generally but said: ``There are times when the adrenaline does flow
and it may affect him. Just like a hitter who goes up and tries to
do too much.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Valentin set about preparing to go against Clemens. ``You
hope now that we're facing him he's not the Roger that Roger is,''
he said. Then he added, ``It was a pleasure playing with him. Now
it's a pleasure playing against him.''
</P>
<P>
   A pleasure? A challenge maybe, but a pleasure? ``Yeah, you're
right,'' Valentin said. ``It's a difficult challenge. If you're an
athlete, a competitor, you enjoy the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   And if you're a Red Sox fan sitting in Fenway Park, you boo,
which is what the fans did when Clemens' name came across the
public-address system. Oh sure, they booed all of the Yankees when
the lineup was read, but they saved their boisterous best for
Clemens.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
