<HEADER>
A1173 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-LITTLETON-COX     07-31 0662
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-LITTLETON-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Littleton community's advice for Atlanta
 &HT;    By Patricia Guthrie
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Forgiveness is not a word in Brian Rohrbough's
vocabulary.
</P>
<P>
   At least not when it comes to the killers of his son, Daniel,
the boy in the green shirt shown crumpled outside Columbine High
School on live television April 20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Fifteen-year-old Daniel, Rohrbough's only child, died with 11
other classmates and a teacher during the shooting rampage of two
students who then killed themselves. Parents of those killed in
Littleton, Colo., and those left with severely wounded children say
they were horrified to hear that yet another mass shooting/suicide
had occurred in Atlanta on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Although the ages of the victims varied and the site of Mark
Barton's murderous spree was offices and a home, not a school,
Littleton families say Atlanta's families are bound tohave emotions
and reactions similar to those they experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to tell the families in Atlanta to keep their eyes open
for people who want you to forgive and forget the murderer,''
Rohrbough, 40, said Saturday in a telephone interview. ``There are
people who will want to make excuses for the murderer. ... But he
is a vicious killer and nothing else. No one should make up any
excuse for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Rohrbough said many well-meaning people have advised him in
letters and to his face to forgive the Columbine killers, teenagers
Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris. Quoting the Bible's Book of Luke,
Chapter 17, Verse 3, Rohrbough says he cannot forgive because the
murderers were too cowardly to face their sins and repent.
</P>
<P>
   Barton's rampage, which included beating his wife and two
children to death before aiming his fury at two Buckhead stock
firms, ended when he turned the gun on himself in his van as police
caught up with him.
</P>
<P>
   Linda Mauser, whose son Daniel also died at Columbine High, had
this advice for the Atlanta families now attending or planning
funerals for their child, parent or spouse. ``Be gentle on
yourselves. Allow time for grieving, and try and support each
other.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's easy to feel isolated because so very few of your peers
will know what you are going through,'' she said. The Littleton
families get together informally about once a month in one
anothers' homes.
</P>
<P>
   Mauser and her husband, Tom, are planning to buy a cedar chest
to store many mementoes of their son. They also erected a park
bench in Daniel's name. He would have turned 16 on June 25.
</P>
<P>
   The Mausers, who have taken up the cause of stricter gun-control
laws, say they've received tremendous help from mental-health
therapists and by reading books on the stages of grief.
</P>
<P>
   What isn't helpful, they say, is complete strangers' coming
around to express their condolences.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've had people call us from around the country who were
coming through Denver and wanted to stop and visit us because they
know us from the media,'' Linda Mauser said. ``That's intrusive.
... Don't be afraid to say, `No.' And don't think you have to
return every phone call.''
</P>
<P>
   Some Littleton families said Barton's crime seemed a copy-cat of
Columbine that perhaps could have been avoided with stricter
gun-control laws. Others said taking away all of the firearms in
the world won't prevent madmen from carrying out their fury.
</P>
<P>
   Police say the the two firearms used by Barton were legally
purchased and that his lack of a criminal record meant he could
possess them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at Oklahoma City. That wasn't guns. That was diesel fuel
and fertilizer,'' said Rick Castaldo, whose son, Richard, was left
with eight bullet holes and paralyzed from the chest down in the
Columbine tragedy. He is in a wheelchair and still hospitalized at
a Denver rehabilitation center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's individual behavior,'' Castaldo said, ``and how are we
going to change that?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
