<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1176 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-LAW-COX     07-31 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-LAW-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Praise for Atlanta police
 &HT;    By Lyda Longa
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It was the kind of crime scene where if anything could
have gone wrong, it would have.
</P>
<P>
   Police in riot gear fanned out in search of a killer. People
bolted from their workplaces wondering if a sniper was perched on
an office building roof waiting to take out his next victim. Nine
people were shot dead; at least 13 were injured. Emotions ran high.
</P>
<P>
   But office workers who were evacuated from 13 buildings in the
heart of the Buckhead business district Thursday when a man opened
fire on 22 people, killing nine, said the sudden retreat from their
desks ran smoothly because Atlanta police officers kept their cool.
</P>
<P>
   Several people who fled their offices at 3500 and 3525 Piedmont
Road _ the buildings where Mark O. Barton shot and killed his
victims _ in the middle of the workday under a harsh sun and
oppressive temperatures said officers were composed, kind and
sensitive even under the tough circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   ``They calmed us down,'' said Martha Pendergrast, who had gone
to visit a friend in one of the offices at Two Securities Centre,
the building at 3500 Piedmont where the killings started just after
2:30 p.m. ``I was in there dropping my friend off and all of a
sudden the police come running in and told us to get out because of
a shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   At least three APD officers escorted Pendergrast and a queue of
15 to 20 people from the office building where Barton unleashed his
frustration Thursday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The officers talked to their charges as they walked them through
the throng of reporters and onlookers who had gathered along the
intersection of Piedmont Road and the Buckhead Loop to gawk at the
chaos.
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 Atlanta police officers, as well as members of the
GBI and FBI SWAT units, agents from the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco
and Firearms and Fulton County sheriff's deputies flooded the area
within minutes of the first frantic telephone call to a 911
dispatcher at 2:56 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The call was from a woman at Momentum Securities at 3500
Piedmont who said a man had shot and killed several people in her
office.
</P>
<P>
   About 20 minutes after police assessed the situation at both
buildings, a call went out over the police radio asking all
available Atlanta cops to report to the scene so they could assist
in the search for Barton, as well as help route office workers and
direct traffic, said Police Chief Beverly Harvard.
</P>
<P>
   ``The coordination between our own officers, as well as APD with
the other agencies that helped out, was excellent,'' Harvard said
Saturday. ``We also asked the other agencies to help us with
specific duties, and the turnaround was fantastic. Everything
worked extremely well, given the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the challenges facing investigators was conflicting
information from witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officers were told Barton was on the roof,'' said Atlanta
Deputy Chief Carter Jackson. ``We were also told he was holding
hostages. The main concern was finding Barton and keeping people
safe.
</P>
<P>
   ``The officers are to be commended. They took great care with
people who were terrified. They acted with sensitivity and
caution,'' Jackson added.
</P>
<P>
   Displaced office workers also heaped praise on Fulton sheriff's
deputies who directed traffic along the Buckhead Loop: ``Those guys
were great,'' said Josie Parrish, who works at 3500 Piedmont.
``Directing traffic under these conditions and in this weather
would make anyone nasty. These guys were nice. They answered all
our annoying questions.''
</P>
<P>
   After police had evacuated both buildings, Scott Belazi, a sales
manager at Allegiance Telecom, a local telephone service at 3500
Piedmont, was trying to cool off and regain his composure as he
sipped a beer at a nearby Mexican restaurant just outside the
police perimeter. Belazi, surrounded by dozens of sweaty people
calling their loved ones on cell phones, was still thinking about
the trail of blood left behind by one of Barton's victims in the
hallway of the building where he works.
</P>
<P>
   He also remembered the police officer who noticed his angst and
gently told him to leave the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``This whole thing was surreal,'' Belazi said. ``I'll tell you,
the Atlanta police really kept us all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
