<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1180 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-DECLINE-ART-3RD     07-31 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-DECLINE-ART-3RDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TOKYO: from abroad. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Why does Japan so obstinately subsidize its past at the expense
of its future?
</P>
<P>
   One reason is a political system in which small towns and rural
areas wield disproportionate influence, such that an upper house
member of Parliament from rural Tottori prefecture has only
one-fifth as many constituents as a member from Tokyo. The late
economist Mancur Olson, in examining why great economies lose their
dynamism, emphasized the rise of special interests that win
protections and clog up the gears of a market economy; although
Olson was writing primarily about the experience of the West, the
same analysis applies to Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Yet what is just as important as special-interest politics is a
profound Japanese commitment to equality across the country, and a
revulsion for ``jaku niku, kyo shoku'' society _ one where the
strong eat the weak. Most Japanese accept that businesses may be
predatory abroad, but there is some yearning for them to be
vegetarians at home. There is a genuine and broad-ranging sympathy
for the weakest elements of the economy, and there are virtually no
calls for cutting off the spigots of cash for rural areas or
declining industries.
</P>
<P>
   In effect, Japan has fostered a gentle, merciful brand of
capitalism, one that keeps dying businesses on artificial life
support. The effort to run a country as if it were a Disney movie
strikes Americans as deeply admirable and hopelessly naive, and
Japan has indeed found it increasingly difficult to nurture an
economy drawn entirely in cheerful pastels.
</P>
<P>
   In a system too squeamish to let industries or islands die,
taxes increasingly go to rescue the feeblest competitors, those
that in a more ruthless system would have gone the way of
blacksmiths and buggy-whip factories. Take Japan's ubiquitous
sento, or public baths, for although they are a tiny industry they
are symptomatic of Japan's difficulties letting go of its past.
</P>
<P>
   These sento are glorious nooks of steam and history, privately
owned, where people can go and scrub and then relax together in an
oversize, overheated tub. After adjusting to the sensation of being
boiled alive, it is difficult to think of anything more pleasant
than a Japanese bath, or anything less essential.
</P>
<P>
   In the old days, of course, the sento were necessary
institutions, because many families had no bath or shower at home.
Now nearly all homes have baths, and young people almost never use
the sento, but Japan cannot muster the courage to let them go
bankrupt. So, even though their time is past and they have no hope
of competing in the market place, many sento are kept alive with
government loans and subsidies that each year total almost $100
million.
</P>
<P>
   The result is not only higher taxes but capital and labor that,
in the public bath industry, are at Indonesian levels of
productivity and dropping. Everybody knows one way to raise
productivity here _ let the sento go bankrupt _but Japan is not
prepared to pay that price.
</P>
<P>
   The same kinds of sentimental subsidies keep islands like
Akashima alive. There has not even been any discussion of cutting
back the ferry service to once daily, and islanders seem stunned
when they are asked whether the government should continue to
provide expensive services to a tiny, aging population.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've never talked about cutting off services,'' said
Mankichi Kokou, 73, an Akashima resident. ``Even if this becomes a
ghost town, the services will continue. They have to.''
</P>
<P>
   There is a good deal of talk about how Japan may be beginning a
``third revolution'' of social and economic transformation as great
as the Meiji period beginning in 1868 and the post-World War II
era. Increasing mergers and the breakdown of the lifetime
employment system give some evidence of this, and officials are
talking a good game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is essential that we radically transform this nation's
system and character in order to promote further prosperity,''
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, as Obuchi suggested, the key changes are yet to
come. Japan's steps have been tentative, and South Korea has more
obviously embraced markets in just the last 18 months than Japan
has in the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Another way that Japan could stave off the demographic
projections is by encouraging large-scale immigration.
</P>
<P>
   The United States, in particular, has shown that a country need
not worry too much about low birth rates so long as immigrants fill
the ranks of workers. And America has brought in not only low-wage
laborers, working as nannies or farm workers, but also computer
technicians and software engineers who have contributed enormously
to the dynamism of Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``The great strength of America is that it draws in continually
the best of everywhere,'' said Jagdish Bhagwati, a Columbia
University professor of international economics who is from India.
``Japan cannot really match that openness.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Japan has the bottleneck,'' he said, ``of not being really
open to foreign cultures.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0194 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1181 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JAPAN-DECLINE-ART-4TH     07-31 0892
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JAPAN-DECLINE-ART-4THTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TOKYO: foreign cultures.'' 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It has been 145 years since Japan abandoned its ``sakoku''
policy, which meant barring almost all foreigners. Yet even now
Japan is more hostile to immigration than any other industrialized
country: It is, for example, exceptionally difficult for foreigners
to acquire Japanese nationality without marrying a Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   Tens of thousands of Chinese are sneaking into Japan to take
dirty or dangerous jobs, and they are beginning to leave an imprint
on the country. But because some of the Chinese immigrants are
gangsters who are handy with cleavers, many Japanese are more
frightened than ever of large-scale immigration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the government would try to find any other means of
solving the labor shortage rather than mass immigration,'' said
Charles Horioka, an American economist at Osaka University. ``Japan
is so concerned about maintaining cultural and racial
homogeneity.''
</P>
<P>
   If Tokyo made an all-out effort, it could recruit many of the
best young scholars and engineers from India, Taiwan, Vietnam and
China to study and work in Japan. That could revitalize the economy
and create a boom of entrepreneurship, but few in Japan seem
enthusiastic about that idea, and many seem fatalistic about the
waves of Asian migration that bypass Japan and continue on to the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``English has become a common language, so it's natural for the
best and brightest to go to America to study,'' said Yosano, the
international trade minister. ``If they come to Japan, then they
face the language barrier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I envy America for attracting them, but that's just the way it
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative is for Japan to try to boost its own
fertility rates, by persuading women like Miki Fujii to have
babies. Mrs. Fujii, 32, has a good office job in Tokyo and the last
thing she wants is a child.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's really a matter of whether having a child is worth all
the stress and pressure,'' Mrs. Fujii said. ``Besides, I'd get no
help from my husband. He has this traditional idea that women
should raise children and that they enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've heard men say they're staying at work late because going
home early means having to take care of children, and they'd rather
work than do that,'' Mrs. Fujii continued. ``I totally understand
that. I think it's quite natural to feel that way. I know I would
feel that way.''
</P>
<P>
   Japan is a difficult place for a woman to raise a child, partly
because in practice this is a nation of single mothers. Husbands
stagger home late from the office or a bar, and a government poll
found that fathers spend an average of just six minutes a day
looking after their children.
</P>
<P>
   Profound social changes _ such as the emergence of husbands who
changed diapers _ might help fertility rates. But the Japanese
government's bleak population projections already assume some
recovery in fertility. If the total fertility rate stays where it
is, then the population will plummet even faster: to 92 million in
2050 and 50 million in 2100.
</P>
<P>
   Some Scandinavian countries have raised fertility a bit by
offering improved child care and various other incentives, and some
Japanese localities are even offering cash rewards for extra
children. Still, in countries like Sweden that have tried this
approach, the cost has been considerable and the long-term increase
in fertility very slight.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, an increase in birth rates would take a long time to
work through the system, for nearly all of Japan's labor force in
the year 2025 has already been born.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot evade the phenomenal change in population structure
and phenomenal change in population size,'' said Makoto Atoh, one
of Japan's leading demographers. ``It's an inevitability derived
from the current level of fertility and longevity.''
</P>
<P>
   Atoh said that Japan could partly compensate for the decline in
the labor force by having the elderly hold their jobs longer and by
encouraging more women to work. Fewer Japanese women hold jobs than
in most Western countries, so there may be room to expand the rate,
he noted, but he said that Japan's population will shrink so
quickly that adjusting to it will be very difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem of the aging of Japan's population will be how
to pay for it. The social security system is underfinanced by a
huge sum about equivalent to Japan's entire annual gross domestic
product, and corporate pension funds are underfinanced by hundreds
of billions of dollars, leaving them with a burden equivalent in
scale to the banking crisis that has dogged Japan's economy for the
last half-dozen years.
</P>
<P>
   As for Akashima, the island remains a gorgeous but depressing
reminder of what can happen to a place when its population ages.
Most of the remaining people on Akashima say they believe that
there will still be at least one person living on the island for
the next decade, but there is the sobering example of another
nearby island, Himejima, which has been entirely abandoned.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I think of my young days, I remember how my friend lived
over there, and another friend's house was over there,'' said
Yoshie Kokou, the fisherman, pointing sadly at clumps of bushes.
``And I long for the past.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear young people aren't having kids now,'' he said. ``I
guess it's just the changing times.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 1849EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
