<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1184 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOT-KIDS-COX     07-31 1627
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOT-KIDS-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    `Open season on kids'
 &HT;    By Diane Lore
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The 11-year-old sat on a couch in his grandmother's
living room Thursday night, staring blankly at the television that
was firing out news of the carnage in Buckhead.
</P>
<P>
   He could not turn away, even though maybe he should have.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to watch it,'' Santonio Lucas said.
</P>
<P>
   At 11, he already knows first-hand about unthinkable violence.
Just last month, he was dragged by the neck around his Atlanta
apartment and forced to watch as his mother's boyfriend shot six
members of Santonio's family to death _ and then shot Santonio. The
sixth-grader feigned death and was the sole survivor.
</P>
<P>
   And now, three weeks later, Santonio could not pull himself away
from news reports of Atlanta's latest spasm of deadly violence,
courtesy of Mark O. Barton, whose two children were among the 13
people he killed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to watch it even though it made me sad,'' said
Santonio, who still is undergoing physical therapy.
</P>
<P>
   Both nationally and in metro Atlanta, the past four months have
been marked by violence _ especially violence toward children. And
make no mistake, the experts say: The kids are reeling from it,
even if they appear to be detached as they watch it and read about
it in the media.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're being bombarded with violence,'' said Dr. Nadine Kaslow,
chief psychologist at Grady Health System and an Emory University
professor. ``Kids are less protected _ and they feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been open season on kids,'' said Cassandra Collins, 43, a
Smyrna mother of three, as she watched her children play outside
last week. ``And I think everyone, especially children, are having
a hard time comprehending it.''
</P>
<P>
   Since April, children have been hurt or killed with frightening
callousness and frequency:
</P>
<P>
   _ In Littleton, Colo., a dozen students were killed at Columbine
High School. The shooters, teenagers Dylan Klebold and Eric Harris,
killed themselves after firing on the students in the library and
cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Franklin, Ind., Ronald Lee Shanabarger killed his
7-month-son by suffocating him with plastic wrap. Shanabarger told
authorities he planned the murder even before his son was
conceived, saying he wanted his wife to pay for not coming home
from a vacation when his father died.
</P>
<P>
   _ In Conyers, six students were shot at Heritage High School by
a fellow student who was disgruntled over a breakup with his
girlfriend.
</P>
<P>
   _ In southwest Atlanta, Santonio's mother, Deleane Briskey, her
sister Essie Jo Huguley, and four of Briskey's six children: David
Antonio Lucas, 13, Craig DeCarlo Briskey, 15, Antione DeAndre
Lucas, 9, and Torsha Briskey, 16, were killed by Briskey's
boyfriend, Cyrano Marks. Santonio was forced to watch each killing
before Marks put a pillow over Santonio and tried to shoot him in
the head. The gun jammed on the first try; Marks fired again,
wounding Santonio in the elbow.
</P>
<P>
   And now this.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Before killing nine strangers and injuring a dozen more in two
office buildings, Barton, 44, killed his wife, Leigh Ann, on
Tuesday, and his son, Matthew, 11, and daughter, Mychelle, 8, on
Wednesday, in their Stockbridge apartment. He later took his own
life. He left notes on his children's bodies after striking them
with a hammer and drowning them in a tub.
</P>
<P>
   For Matthew, he wrote: ``My son, my buddy.''
</P>
<P>
   For Mychelle: ``My daughter, my sweetheart.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a violent end for two kids who had gone to summer camp,
learned to swim and played soccer.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the month, Matthew, a Tenderfoot Scout in Troop 297,
was proud to have received his swimming merit badge while at a
weeklong Boy Scout camp, said Jerry Martin, director of the Boy
Scouts at The Rock Baptist Church in Rex, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   The day before Mychelle was murdered, she was at a Girl Scout
day camp called Starlight Adventure working on costumes for a play,
said Barbie Grammel, a Girl Scout leader who was good friends with
Leigh Ann, also a troop leader.
</P>
<P>
   Matthew was mature for his age, according to family and friends,
and he was protective of his younger sister, especially after their
mother and grandmother were found hacked to death at an Alabama
campground in 1993. Their father was a suspect in those slayings,
but was never indicted.
</P>
<P>
   Mychelle became the family jokester, a happy child who loved to
swim in a neighbor's pool.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't comprehend it,'' said Grammel, whose 7-year-old
daughter, Natasha, played with Mychelle. ``Tuesday night was the
last night we saw them alive. The girls were chasing fireflies in
the parking lot. Just being little girls on a summer night.''
</P>
<P>
   Grammel told her daughter that Mychelle was dead when she picked
Natasha up from the Starlight Adventure, which ended a day early
because of the shootings. ``She cried, she was very upset,''
Grammel said. ``She needed to be held.''
</P>
<P>
   The hardest part for Grammel is when her daughter started asking
why. Why did Barton do this? Why did they have to die?
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her sometimes we don't know,'' Grammel said.
``Sometimes there are reasons we don't understand.''
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to help Matthew's friends, Martin's troop plans to
meet Tuesday to talk to counselors and with each other. ``We're
going to be like a family and cry on each other's shoulders,''
Martin said. ``When we hurt, we all hurt together.''
</P>
<P>
   The main message, Martin said, will be that the world is not a
bad place, even if there are bad people.
</P>
<P>
   But the reality is that homicide is the No. 4 reason for death
among children ages 1 to 4; No. 3 for kids 5 and 14; and No. 2 for
teens and young adults, ages 15 to 24, according to national vital
statistics.
</P>
<P>
   Deaths among children, which includes homicides, are declining
nationwide, dropping to 26 per 100,000 in 1996 from 34 per 100,000
in 1985, according to Kids Count, an annual survey conducted by the
Annie E. Casey Foundation. The rate in Georgia continues to be
higher than the national average, with 31 per 100,000 in 1996,
although that is down from 37 per 100,000 in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia also lags badly when it comes to teen deaths due to
accidents, homicide and suicide. The U.S. rate was 62 per 100,000
in 1996; Georgia's rate was 83 per 100,000.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   About 1,500 children die each year in this country at the hands
of their parents, according to a U.S. Justice Department study.
</P>
<P>
   When children are killed by their parents, the most common
reason is a combination of frustration and anger..
</P>
<P>
   But in some cases, the parents _ usually deeply depressed _
don't want to leave their children behind with uncertain futures.
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, South Carolinian Susan Smith let her car roll into a
lake with her two sons strapped in their car seats. She said she
did it because she had planned to commit suicide and simply could
not face letting her sons, ages 3 and 14 months, be raised by
someone else.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as in Barton's case, some parents do not want their children
to suffer the throes of life that they themselves have suffered. In
a suicide note, Barton wrote: ``I killed the children to exchange
them for five minutes of pain for a lifetime of pain. I forced
myself to do it to keep them from suffering so much later. No
mother, no father, no relatives. The fears of the father are
transferred to the son. It was from my father to me and from me to
my son. He already had it and now to be left alone. I had to take
him with me.''
</P>
<P>
   But the loved ones and a shaken community must deal with the
aftermath _ and kids are the most vulnerable, especially those
whose parents or grandparents were killed or wounded.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Dean Delawalla, 52, leaves behind his 15-year-old
son, Faisal, and his daughter, Shayla, who turned 4 on Wednesday.
He loved to watch his son play sports, from soccer to hockey.
</P>
<P>
   And Allen Charles Tenenbaum, buried Friday, leaves behind three
children, 3-year-old Scott, 11-year-old Megan and 13-year-old
Brittany.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the closer violence gets to the home, the more
frightening it is,'' said Emory's Kaslow. ``You want to tell your
children the world is a safe place with unsafe people, but with
what they're seeing, it's getting harder to make a convincing
case.''
</P>
<P>
   And the violence doesn't have to be agonizingly personal to have
that impact, experts say.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the saddest thing I'm witnessing is children do not
seem surprised by all these murders,'' said Martha Christison, a
social worker for almost three decades at the Grady Health System
Outpatient Child Psychiatry Clinic. ``It's like they've been
exposed to it, they can't control it and they don't really
understand it. There's a solemn resignation about it.''
</P>
<P>
   But an innocence is forever lost.
</P>
<P>
   Travis Holmes, a 14-year-old Boy Scout who lived near the
Bartons in Stockbridge, said he had struck up a conversation in
their apartment's parking lot with Matthew and his father after
noticing they were wearing Scout uniforms. It was the night Barton
apparently killed his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's freaking me out,'' Holmes said. ``I'm not going to talk
to any more strangers, even if they're Scouts.''
</P>
<P>
   And Collins, the parent in Smyrna who was merely an observer
like most area residents, said she sees the shock slowly fading
from her children's reactions _ especially with her 10-year-old,
Nikolaus. ``I think he's seen so much, and yet he still doesn't
really understand what's happening,'' she said. ``He doesn't really
understand the permanence of death. ... That all these poor little
kids are gone forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta Journal-Constitution staff writer Duane Stanford
contributed to this article.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
