<DOCNO> NYT19990731.0197 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1187 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-R-NYC-SUMMER-2TAKES-N     07-31 1007
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-NYC-SUMMER-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS TEMPERATURES CLIMB, A NEIGHBORHOOD GETAWAY IN BROOKLYN BECKONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to DELETE photo note)  (mk) 
 By JOE SEXTON    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ It was 11:13 in the morning on Wednesday, and the
temperature was 88 degrees and climbing. Samuel Marrow, 74, had
risen with the sun, but now he wanted out of it. And so, as he had
over the course of the last 51 summers, he walked down Quincy
Street in the Bedford-Stuyvesant section of Brooklyn and over to
the former Tompkins Park, now known as Herbert Von King Park.
</P>
<P>
   A seat in the shade, a moment of mercy after a month of historic
heat, was all Marrow was looking for, and he found it where he
always had _ on the bench six strides inside the Greene Avenue
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   There, in the simple cool, he could see everything, looking back
in time as well as straight in front of him. On his right was the
tree from which several young boys were hanged in the gang wars of
the 1950s. To his left was a line of young children, the children
of the neighborhood's poor and working class, running sprints in
the sun, the temperature draining from them everything but their
smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came to Brooklyn from North Carolina after the war,'' said
Marrow, who back then worked in a shipyard in Kearny, N.J. ``I'd
get home hot and dirty, but gather my kids and come here. Back
then, you could spend the night out in this park. It's always been
the coolest park in Brooklyn. There's a lot of history here.''
</P>
<P>
   It is the history, in many ways, of a certain kind of summer in
New York City, the summers lived out by children for whom a fancy
day camp is a pipe dream, summers lived out by fathers and
grandmothers for whom vacation is an absolutely local experience.
Across the city, there are parks and playgrounds, schoolyards and
street corners that have always served as improvised summer
retreats, unglamorous, but rich and fully used.
</P>
<P>
   They are found at the backs of falling-apart schools and
squeezed between housing projects, or, like Von King Park, standing
squarely at the center of a storied neighborhood of culture and
strife. And at midsummer, people are driven to them before
daybreak, and many don't leave until well past midnight, early
bedtimes seeming a needless cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   In those parks and schoolyards, people taste the modest, sweet
freedoms and comforts of shade and laughter, invented games, the
little dramas of romance and athletics. Of course, they are not
places of complete summer sanctity: There is commerce in drugs,
sometimes in revenge; people bring their dinner to the park, and
others roll dice; anger can rise like the heat, quickly and with
menace.
</P>
<P>
   On this day, when the temperature rose to 97 degrees, teen-agers
flirted openly, the strength of their hormones undefeated by the
heat. And on a center bench, the resident storytellers and wise
guys were in full voice, their tales driven by pride and nostalgia,
boredom, hope and the brown bags between their feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``When it is smoldering everywhere else, there are places in
this park that can feel refrigerated,'' said Lemuel Mial, a Parks
Department official who has worked at the park since 1967. ``Of
course, it's not totally innocent, either. But this, I think, is
the bright green spot of the neighborhood. And summer here is going
day and night.''
</P>
<P>
   To spend 24 hot and unpredictable hours in Von King Park, then,
is to appreciate what that kind of summer of constraint and
creativity can feel like.
</P>
<P>
   6:17 a.m., 78 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Bill Crowder, 54, sat in a quadrangle of the day's first
sunlight and opened his flute case. It would be the sixth straight
day of temperatures over 90, the 28th day of a month that would
become the hottest ever recorded in the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm kind of like the gypsy of Bed-Stuy,'' he said. ``Actually,
I can play this flute in the house now. My new roommate doesn't
mind. But I have to come back to my roots to play. This park is my
roots.''
</P>
<P>
   Just after daybreak, Von King Park _ its name was changed in
1985 to honor the neighborhood advocate who had earned the
unofficial title of ``mayor of Bed-Stuy'' _ is populated by the
elderly, the unemployed and the ambitious, Tracy Moore's ambition
amounting to doing pull-ups on the playground bars before it got
too hot and before he had to go to work.
</P>
<P>
   At 6:49 a.m., John Stevens, 73, a former porter, began the
park's first game of checkers. ``It's too hot and too early to
think clearly,'' he said, laughing, ``but it ain't too hot or too
early to cheat.''
</P>
<P>
   The working people from the streets around the park _ it is
bordered by Greene, Lafayette, Marcy and Tompkins Avenues _ also
walk through, wearing the uniforms of hospital orderlies and
Sanitation Department workers. And they each steal a second or two
of breezy relief.
</P>
<P>
   Hard luck can bring people to the park, too. Ruben Gonzalez, 47,
played in the park as a child, and he remembered how he used to
come dressed in a suit and shoes with his father. Gonzalez had been
away for years, but returned to Von King Park when he was sent
there to work for his welfare check.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have improved the park a lot, created more things for
kids,'' he said. ``I brought my daughter here the other day. I told
her it wasn't like this when I was here. But I told her to sit
where I had sat. It felt good for me to see that.''
</P>
<P>
   By 9 a.m., the sun had climbed up off Tompkins Avenue, a hot
coin rising in the sky.
</P>
<P>
   Laurine Harrison, a grandmother and former bookkeeper, sat in a
swing, her pleasure nothing more lavish than to stretch her arms
and legs. And Eddie Vick, 66, a former boxer, walked with his
grandson, his shirt soaked across his broad shoulders, his
grandson's hand lost in his aging boxer's fist.
</P>
<P>
   Marcus Bryant, 11, had waited in his Greene Avenue apartment for
hours before getting the final OK to go to the park with his
brother, Kaheem, to play their invented game of Black Mat Tag.
``This park is enough for us,'' Marcus said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   12:49 p.m., 92 degrees
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Jolly, 15, walked onto the basketball court at the
southeast corner of Von King Park. There, with five others, the
day's first game started. It was a game of dubious shot selections
and endless talk, with the chief conversational constant being the
total failure to mention the word ``job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Work? I'm working on my jump shot,'' said Aaron, his laugh as
soft as his shot floating through the netless hoop. Aaron is one of
eight siblings, and he said he had worked earlier in the summer at
a nursing home. He was waiting to be called back.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, he listened only for the call of ``next.''
</P>
<P>
   A generational shift had taken place at the park as the
afternoon arrived. It is largely the young who are out in the
midday heat, and even they treated the sunlight as a flame to
dodge.
</P>
<P>
   The youngsters come from the row houses along the park's
borders, and from the Louis Armstrong projects on Quincy Street, a
set of buildings that function as squat, remorseless ovens. The
children turn the park's asphalt paths into racing strips, and the
two sprinklers empty a reservoir's worth of water into the air.
</P>
<P>
   It is not Cape Cod, but it is more than all right, something
deeper than simply a last resort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have two options,'' said Stacey Tyler, the mother of six
children, four of whom were with her in the sprinkler. ``I can stay
at home and run the hose on them, or I can use the city's water. I
just got my water bill, and so that settled that.''
</P>
<P>
   The park has a rich history. In 1857, it became the first park
formally established by the city of Brooklyn, and it was originally
named for Daniel Tompkins, the abolitionist and four-term governor
of New York. Its final design was by Calvert Vaux and Frederick Law
Olmstead, the designers of Central Park. A library once stood at
its center, and it was often used for military reviews. It is full
of oak and maple trees.
</P>
<P>
   The multiple uses of the park are organized, accidental, and
occasionally urgent. There are nighttime concerts, and a handful of
dance and arts programs are run out of the park building. A local
church that had been damaged by fire now conducts its Sunday
services in the park's outdoor auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   And it gets used, too, as a place for people to come and hold
hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came because of the heat,'' Luisa Matos said.
</P>
<P>
   Next to her, Shawn Blake smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came for love,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The two, both 19, had just discovered Von King Park, and shortly
after 2 p.m., with the temperature at 95 degrees, they sat side by
side and talked of their future. They had dated for two and a half
years, and had moved to Brooklyn only months before from St. Thomas
in the Virgin Islands. They had taken an apartment together and
were looking for work. Von King Park offered a place for their
hearts to calm down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how it will work out,'' Ms. Matos said. ``I want
to go to school as well as work. But it's going to be hard, I
think.'' She put her head on her boyfriend's shoulder and closed
her eyes.
</P>
<P>
   6:10 p.m., 96 degrees
</P>
<P>
   The sun's slow, almost exhausted decline over Marcy Avenue at
the west end of Von King Park had done nothing to thwart the
temperature's ascent. Through that heat and the first hints of
twilight, Homer Stewart walked with his 6-year-old son, Kwame.
Stewart, who works for a bank in Flatbush, had changed his suit for
shorts and was about to have his first game of catch with his son,
an exercise in sweat and tenderness.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the baseball lover,'' Stewart said of his son. ``And we
are here to register for the park's baseball program.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, the two moved to the ballfield at the northwest corner of
the park, where the baseball games begin after dusk.
</P>
<P>
   The park in the early evening is more full than ever, its
characters including the near-permanent residents who have, during
the day, moved from one bench to another, their courses charted by
their own private maps of quiet desires and distractions.
</P>
<P>
   One of them is Queen Curry, 69. She was born in Camden, S.C.,
but moved to Bedford-Stuyvesant 30 years ago and raised four
children. The park was always there, full of pleasures and perils.
She said one of her children had been ensnared by the drug scene
that prevailed at the park years ago. ``I've made a whole circle
around this park,'' she said, listing the houses she had lived in
on the four surrounding streets. ``But I always walked through
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Some choose to march through it, and shortly after 8 p.m., the
sounds of a drum and bugle corps rise. There, gathering for
practice, are the Toppers, who say they make up the oldest active
African-American drum corps in the country.
</P>
<P>
   In sunglasses and baseball caps, Victor English and Daniel
Wright, bugles in their white-gloved hands, work their way through
a medley as night falls. ``We're doing this as a hook for kids in
the park,'' said English. ``I started in 1961, and the drum corps
taught me discipline, self-respect. And it gave me the chance to
get out of this city.''
</P>
<P>
   9:11 p.m., 89 degrees
</P>
<P>
   With the darkness, the degrees of separation in the park had
grown more stark. Certain corners of the park had grown slightly
sinister, taken over by teen-agers and other young men and women,
the language often loud and hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say this park is nice, that it has grass and whatnot,''
said a 16-year-old who identified himself as Little G. ``But young
people get hurt in this place, too. And the police precinct is
right on the corner. But they don't care.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, almost everyone, including police officers at the 79th
Precinct at the southeast corner of the park, agrees that Von King
Park has come a long way during the last decade on the question of
safety. There were years, Officer Jeannette Morales said, when
almost all the pursuits of criminal suspects either started, ran
through or wound up in the park.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we even track the number of incidents in the
park these days, the number is so low,'' said Morales, who has been
the precinct's community affairs officer for six years. ``Cops even
play handball in there.''
</P>
<P>
   That sense of security is hardly universal, though. A girl was
raped in the park on July 22.
</P>
<P>
   But, as late night approached, there still were mothers in the
park with their children, gamely hanging on and hanging out by the
sprinklers, the spray of water looking in the dark air like a kind
of fine smoke.
</P>
<P>
   Maria Figueroa was there with her daughter Angelica, 3. The
night hours in the park are what Ms. Figueroa can manage, for she
does not get off work until 6. They would stay until Angelica fell
asleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a place where you feel like you can break away,'' Ms.
Figueroa said. ``Break away from the heat. And, you know, break
away from the ordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   With midnight coming, and the forecast calling for four more
days of 90-degree heat, a breeze still ran through Von King Park, a
breeze that felt freighted with something _ rain, mischief, peace,
the scent of summer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
