<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    AL notebook
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AL EAST
</P>
<P>
   Toronto is hailing the trade for David Segui as one of the most
consequential the franchise has made in the '90s. Manager Jim
Fregosi will play him at first base, in left field and as a DH. The
switch-hitter bringing a veteran's edge to a young team just
beginning to taste success.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a front office point of view, this sends the message down
to the
</P>
<P>
   clubhouse that they are committed to winning and that's great,''
first baseman Carlos Delgado said. The Jays opened the weekend atop
the wild card race.
</P>
<P>
   Fregosi has some experience with working a veteran into a lineup
in three positions. He did it with Don Baylor in California in 1979
and Baylor, the Braves' hitting coach, responded by winning the
league MVP award. . . .
</P>
<P>
   It took Baltimore second baseman Delino DeShields five weeks to
come back from a hamstring injury and the interim might have cost
him his future as an Oriole. Jerry Hairston Jr. hit .277 with two
homers, seven RBIs and six steals in 25 games as DeShields'
replacement. The O's sent him back to Class AAA, but next year is a
different story.
</P>
<P>
   AL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   Now that the Tigers are poised to move into a new park, it is
only fitting one final adjustment be made as Detroit enters the new
millennium: the owner is getting more involved. Mike Ilitch, the
Little Ceasar pizza baron, has put all his business enterprises
into a holding company so that he can personally oversee his club's
transfer into Comerica Park.
</P>
<P>
   GM Randy Smith denies Ilitch barred the trade of any front-line
player leading up to the trading deadline but the owner has begun
issuing more control. Whereas former manager Buddy Bell picked his
staff, Ilitch has since subtly affected staff changes. Ilitch put
up $150 million of his money to build Comerica. . . .
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox not only don't regard the Indians as a dynasty
they expect to contend for the division next season. Said GM Ron
Scheuler, ``That All-Star lineup they have, they found out with an
injury here or there and that pitching that they're still looking
for, that a lot of things can happen.''
</P>
<P>
   AL WEST
</P>
<P>
   If Juan Gonzalez's image took a knock for his refusal to take
part in the All-Star Game, his act at the Cooperstown Hall of Fame
game should knock him off the chart. The Texas right fielder
declined to play because his uniform pants _ 1993 replicas from
inductee Nolan Ryan's last season _ were too baggy.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, he begged out of the lineup, claiming a wrist hurt.
Then he neglected to inform manager Johnny Oates, who didn't learn
of the injury until 15 minutes before first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Juan can make it difficult at times,'' Mark McLemore said.
``At times, it becomes harder for some of us to keep focused on
what we're out there to do every day. Every day. Not five out of
every seven or six out of every seven but every day.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's dealing away of Segui and Butch Huskey had both Ken
Griffey Jr. and Jay Buhner holding closed-door meetings with
manager Lou Piniella over the Mariners' intentions. ``These deals
give you the sense we are looking for next year,'' Edgar Martinez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
