<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NLNOTES01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NL East notes
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NL EAST
</P>
<P>
   With Livan Hernandez's departure, the next Florida object of
trading desire becomes right-hander Alex Fernandez, who is still
working with a 100-pitch limit but has shown he has overcome
rotator cuff surgery. Do not expect him to leave Florida anytime
soon.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez is halfway through his four-year $35 million contract
that was specifically negotiated with trade stipulations. The
Marlins can only deal him to Cleveland, Texas, St. Louis, Atlanta,
Baltimore, Tampa Bay or the Chicago Cubs _ note the paucity of New
York clubs _ and bear in mind Fernandez accepted an offer worth $7
million less to go back to Miami, his hometown.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not much consideration (of leaving),'' said Scott
Boras, his agent. ``This is Alex's home.'' . . .
</P>
<P>
   Rick Reed, at 9-3 the New York Mets' most solid starter,
petitioned again for admittance to the Players Association. Reed,
like Atlanta's Kerry Ligtenberg, was a replacement player during
the 1994-95 strike and has been excluded from the union and all
licensing income.
</P>
<P>
   NL CENTRAL
</P>
<P>
   The Astros look back this weekend at the Randy Johnson deal,
consummated at the trading deadline a year ago, and see it netted
them nothing. Johnson is in first place in Arizona. Freddy Garcia
and John Halama, who the Astros sent to Seattle, have won a
combined 17 games.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, general manager Gerry Hunsicker, saying, ``I would
do it again 100 times out of 100,'' will not second guess the
decision. Then he gave a telling sermonette on the nature of the
trading deadline: ``This is a great example of why you have to be
careful when making trades in the middle of the season, because in
reality, there's only one team in the National League that gets to
the World Series, and the odds aren't great regardless of what
moves you make.'' . . . St. Louis third base coach Rene Lachemann
did his best to keep Mark McGwire away from umpire Sam Holbrook
Wednesday when McGwire disputed a strike call.
</P>
<P>
   ``(He) threw me around like a helicopter,'' said Lachemann. ``He
said, ``Don't come close to me. I want to go ahead and say what I
want to go ahead and say, so leave me alone.'.''
</P>
<P>
   NL WEST
</P>
<P>
   The flop to last place has done nothing to clarify the bad
situation of the Los Angeles Dodgers. Quite the opposite. Second
baseman Eric Young, finally on the DL with an ankle that has
bothered him all year, feels manager Davey Johnson has made him a
scapegoat for the club's bad mix. ``I've gone out there and played
hurt all year,'' said Young, whom the club had tried unsuccessfully
to deal, ``but I guess that doesn't matter.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Eric Karros has also had it with being included in
every trade rumor to emanate from the organization. Then there is
Raul Mondesi, who declined to return to the dugout during the fifth
inning changeover in Arizona last Friday night, sitting in the
Dodgers bullpen while the team batted. When confronted, Mondesi
said he did it in San Diego earlier in the year and no one cared,
adding, ``I got better things to worry about.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
