<SLUG> BC-BBO-FEATURE01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Last-place Cubs feeling unloved
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Incredibly, the fun already has expired in Chicago. Not even a
full season removed from one of their most enjoyable summers, the
Cubs are the Cubs once again: in last place and disbelieving.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play with more passion and pride, come ready to
beat the other club,'' manager Jim Riggleman said. ``You can't just
go out there. There are no games on the schedule that say you are
going to win. Theoretically, you can go 0-162.''
</P>
<P>
   Theoretically, you should also be able to cough up a
championship once every 90 years. But these remain the Cubs. After
running in second place of the NL Central much of the first two
months, the Cubs entered the week with a 20-33 record since June 1,
delivering them to last place and 13 1/2 games back as the weekend
opened.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Sammy Sosa was king of the north side, the NL MVP
who elevated his team to its first postseason appearance in eight
years. This summer, the pitching evaporated the moment the scalpel
touched Kerry Wood's elbow. With 16 players 30 or older, the Cubs
look old and play older. And for the third time in three years, the
populace is calling for Riggleman's head.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're stuck in the middle of trying to save some respect for
ourselves,'' reliever Rod Beck said, ``but we now live in the land
of misfit toys.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the weekend series with the New York Mets, the Cubs just
returned from a 1-5 trip through Montreal and New York that saw
them score only 13 runs. They opened their current 13-game
homestand by blowing a 7-2 lead in Friday's loss to the Mets and
things are only going to get tougher. Houston and Arizona close out
the homestand.
</P>
<P>
   Pitchers Kevin Tapani and Steve Trachsel, a combined 34-18 last
season, are 9-22. Imported closer Rick Aguilera has been a disaster
with a 6.08 ERA and four blown saves since arriving in May.
</P>
<P>
   The offense has consisted of Sosa, Henry Rodriguez and Glenallen
Hill, who entered the weekend with 72 home runs combined. When one
of them leaves the park, Chicago is 34-18. When none of them homer,
the Cubs are 13-35.
</P>
<P>
   The lightning rod is the low-key Riggleman, who finished third
to San Diego's Bruce Bochy and Houston's Larry Dierker in manager
of the year voting last season. His contract runs through 2000 and
he has received blessings from general manager Ed Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   But with a 6-9 start in the second half and losing series to
Montreal and Kansas City, the crowds are turning against Riggleman
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell plumbers how to fix a sink or electricians how to
get power going in their homes,'' Riggleman said. But (fans and
media) can criticize me because we are in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what we are as a ballclub and where I stand as a
manager. To ever have the security that Tony La Russa, Jim Leyland
and Bobby Cox have, you have to have a track record of winning. I
don't have it, so I completely understand my vulnerability.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
