<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-FALCONS01-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Injured Falcons adjusting
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, S.C. _ Every pro football player fears it. Many have
endured some form of it. A few never make it back once it happens.
</P>
<P>
   Falcons running back Gary Downs was relatively upbeat Saturday,
however, a day after injuring his right knee and likely scuttling
his season.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie reserve center Todd McClure, who almost certainly will
miss the season after tearing his right anterior cruciate knee
ligament in the same practice, seemed to still be in shock.
</P>
<P>
   As Downs carried the ball through the line Friday morning in the
second practice of training camp, a falling defensive lineman
leg-whipped the sixth-year pro.
</P>
<P>
   Downs planted his right leg, and then screamed while his knee
hyperextended the wrong way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could kind of see it coming, but I couldn't do anything,''
he said Saturday. ``My leg was going to plant. I knew it was bad,
but I was hoping it wasn't too bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Downs will have surgery Monday or Tuesday to repair a torn
lateral collateral ligament. It's a rare injury that team
orthopedist Andrew Bishop said normally requires a four-month
rehabilitation.
</P>
<P>
   If surgery reveals less of a tear than Bishop anticipates, Downs
could come back sooner.
</P>
<P>
   He has just one carry for two yards in two seasons for the
Falcons, but has been an immensely valuable special teams player.
</P>
<P>
   A Columbus native, he also figured that while Jamal Anderson
continued to hold out, he could could show his stuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a chance to showcase my ability,'' he said.
``I've been a special teams leader, but I... just kind of thought,
`I'm going to go for it.' That's just the breaks. It was my turn to
go in.''
</P>
<P>
   Moments after the injury, defensive end Lester Archambeau
screamed across the field, ``Hang in there, Downsy.''
</P>
<P>
   Running back Byron Hanspard, who is trying to return from a
serious knee injury that caused him to miss all of last season,
hovered briefly nearby.
</P>
<P>
   As he got in a cart, fullback Bob Christian, who injured a knee
last Dec. 13 that kept him out of the final two games and the
postseason, offered Downs consolation.
</P>
<P>
   Not much later, practice resumed, and Downs was in the locker
room, sobbing.
</P>
<P>
   McClure was injured in almost exactly the same spot on the field
when a defensive linemen crashed into the side of his leg. He
returned briefly, but later hobbled off for good.
</P>
<P>
   ``I strained the medial collateral at LSU, and (Dr. Bishop)
thinks maybe I damaged the ACL at that time,'' McClure said. ``It's
not etched in stone yet. They'll do surgery in a couple weeks, and
see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Dan Reeves is ready to count McClure out for the season,
and the eam probably won't sign another offensive lineman.
</P>
<P>
   Deep snapper Adam Schreiber, starting left guard Calvin Collins,
who started 13 games at center in '97, and perhaps reserve right
guard Bob Hallen will share backup center duties.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the team signed former Falcons running back Harold
Green. He was waived after last season, when the nine-year
veteran's role dwindled almost to nothing as Anderson took over
most of what had been Green's third-down duties in '97.
</P>
<P>
   The move saved $825,000 against the Falcons' salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Green's one-year deal with signing bonus and incentives might be
worth more than $500,000. The Falcons are about $250,000 under the
salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   The team won't put Downs on injured reserve until knowing how
long he'll be out.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
