<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 07/31/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT19) NEW YORK -- July 31, 1999 -- CYC-ARMSTRONG, 7-31 --
Lance Armstrong, 27, and his wife, Kristin, at a press conference
at Niketown, along with his Tour de France bike and the yellow
jersey he wore as the winner. There's not much to imagine about
Armstrong. At 27, Winning the Tour de France three years after a
diagnosis of testicular cancer that had spread to his lungs and
brain, Armstrong became only the second American to win one of the
most physically demanding athletic events. (Andrea Mohin/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) CHANDLER, Ariz. -- July 31, 1999 -- BBO-UMPIRES, 7-31 --
Mike Everitt at his home in Chandler, with a print of Norman
Rockwell's ``Umpires.'' Everitt has been offered a full-time job at
$95,000 a year by the American League. Everitt had worked in the
major leagues as a fill-in umpire, and had been waiting a dozen
years to hear he had made it on a permanent basis. ``Major league
umps get paid year round,'' says Everitt. ``That is something I
can't really fathom until the day I go to the mailbox and get the
check.'' (Tom Story/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) AMUR, Russia -- July 31, 1999 -- RUSSIA-PRIVATE-FARMS-2,
7-31 --In Russia's Far East in the Amur region, Sergei Kitayev has
only his garden plot since he gave up his dream of farming to drive
a taxi. Defeated by an economy that has given little support to
enterprising farmers, Kitayev stuck it out for two seasons. Would
he ever go back to commercial farming? Not now, says Kitayev. ``The
disappointments were too great, too bitter. Ten years ago, there
was an incentive to try,'' he says. (James Hill/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) BIROBIDZHAN, Russia -- July 31, 1999 --
RUSSIA-PRIVATE-FARMS-1, 7-31 -- In Birobidzhan, Zhuang Yimin of
Harbin, China, checks a piglet for a Russian farmer. To survive in
Russia's Far East, some farmers rely on the skills of Chinese
seasonal workers. Today, there are some 600 Chinese farm workers in
Birobidzhan. Zhuang and his wife, Lizhe, 35, make about $120 a
month -- or twice their regular wage in Harbin. They work long
hours, but as Zhuang says ``I didn't come here to travel, but to
work.'' (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) BOSTON -- July 31, 1999 -- GUN-ID-SYSTEM, 7-31 -- Sgt.
Detective Mark Vickers of the Boston Police Department firing a
.357 Magnum as part of a ballistics test. As cities and states
challenge the gun industry to change its marketing practices, one
proposal that keeps coming up is the creation of a nationwide
database of bullets and ammunition shell casings. Using such a
system, police could connect evidence at the scenes of murders and
shootings to the guns used in such crimes. (Evan Richman/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) MIAMI -- July 31, 1999 -- MIAMI-TRAFFIC, 7-31 -- Morning
commuters in Miami heading slowly into downtown. Voters have
rejected a new mass transit tax intended to replace highway tolls
and reduce traffic. (Cindy Karp/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) JERSEY CITY, N.J. -- July 31, 1999 -- GA-SHOOT-TRADERS,
7-31 -- Daytraders at work in Jersey City. Many day traders,
conceding that their job is stressful, blame the mechanics of the
system for their anxiety. Many in the field say that the stresses,
like coping with wild gains and losses from day to day, are
unfamiliar to most Americans, who have begun to indulge in day
trading by the thousands only in recent years. (G. Paul Burnett/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) AKASHIMA, Japan -- July 31, 1999 -- JAPAN-DECLINE-2,
7-31 -- Yoshie Kokou, a 70-year-old fisherman, visits the graves of
his parents in the Akashima cemetery. Akashima's hospital, school,
stores and most of its homes are abandoned, and aside from Kokou
only four people still live on the 128-acre island. The little
island of Akashima, in the Goto chain in southern Japan, remains a
gorgeous but depressing reminder of what can happen to a place when
its population ages. (Nicholas D. Kristof/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) AKASHIMA, Japan -- July 31, 1999 -- JAPAN-DECLINE-1,
7-31 -- Mankichi Kokou, 73, one of five people still living on the
the little island of Akashima, in the Goto chain in southern Japan.
The Japanese government predicts that the working-age population of
Japan will drop by about 650,000 a year over the next 50 years.
Moreover, each Japanese worker will have to support more
non-workers, as the aged rise from one-sixth of the population now
to one-third by the middle of the next century. (Nicholas D.
Kristof/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) GORNJE OBRINJE, Yugoslavia -- July 31, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REBUILD-3, 7-31 -- Shaban Delijaj drinking tea in a room
that sheltered 17 ethnic Albanians during the war. Ten months ago,
21 members of the extended Delijaj family were killed in a gully
here. After a summer of guerrilla warfare against the Serbian
police, it was a dramatic display of Serbian violence, the mass
killing, that propelled NATO into threatening to bomb Yugoslavia.
(Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) GORNJE OBRINJE, Yugoslavia -- July 31, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REBUILD-2, 7-31 -- Imer Delijaj, 39, who used to be a rebel
fighter, is proud that he and other survivors of a Serbian attack
made a new start in their village. Ten months ago, 21 members of
the extended Delijaj family were killed in a gully here. ``Ilost a
lot, and have a lot of pain that can't be recovered,'' he says.
``This is like a game of waiting and it's not clear from the
agreements that Kosovo will be free in 10 years. There's not a
single clear definition for the future of Kosovo.'' (Tyler
Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) GORNJE OBRINJE, Yugoslavia -- July 31, 1999 --
KOSOVO-REBUILD-1, 7-31 -- Imer Delijaj, 39, sifting through fallen
markers left by a forensic team at the site where 21 members of the
extended Delijaj family were killed in a gully here. After a summer
of guerrilla warfare against the Serbian police, it was a dramatic
display of Serbian violence, the mass killing, that propelled NATO
into threatening to bomb Yugoslavia. (Tyler Hicks/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- July 31, 1999 -- NY-OLDEST-CABBY-2, 7-31 --
Johnnie Footman, 80, may be New York City's oldest taxi driver,
although that is difficult to prove because records are not kept by
a driver's age, according to the New York City Taxi and Limousine
Commission. Footman, who was born in Lakeland, Fla., moved to New
York in 1941. He started out washing cabs for a taxi company before
earning his own license. ``Something told me that's what I wanted
to do,'' he says. ``It was the driving that I enjoyed, picking up
people and going different places.'' (Frances Roberts/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- July 31, 1999 -- NY-OLDEST-CABBY-2, 7-31 --
No one knows if Johnnie Footman, 80, is the oldest cab driver in
New York City, since records are not kept by age, but he must have
one of the best driving records:, one ticket, for speeding, in his
long career. Footman, who was born in Lakeland, Fla., moved to New
York in 1941. He started out washing cabs for a taxi company before
earning his own license. ``Something told me that's what I wanted
to do,'' he says. ``It was the driving that I enjoyed, picking up
people and going different places.'' (Frances Roberts/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- July 31, 1999 -- NY-OLDEST-CABBY-1, 7-31 --
No one knows if Johnnie Footman, 80, is the oldest cab driver in
New York City, since records are not kept by age, but he must have
one of the best driving records:, one ticket, for speeding, in his
long career. Footman, who was born in Lakeland, Fla., moved to New
York in 1941. He started out washing cabs for a taxi company before
earning his own license. ``Something told me that's what I wanted
to do,'' he says. ``It was the driving that I enjoyed, picking up
people and going different places.'' (Frances Roberts/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) WASHINGTON -- July 31, 1999 -- VA-HOSPITALS-2, 7-31 --
Joe Uhring, who lost his leg in Italy in World War II, waits for a
doctor at a Veterans Affairs hospital in Washington. Uhring is
among a declining number being treated in the federal health care
system for veterans. The Department of Veterans Affairs receives
more than $17 billion a year to provide health care to veterans,
but spends one-fourth of the money caring for the 4,700 buildings
at its medical centers around the country. Forty percent of the
buildings are at least 50 years old. (Shana Raab/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) LOS ANGELES -- July 31, 1999 -- VA-HOSPITALS-1, 7-31 --
The health care of veterans in the United States is shifting
primarily from hospitals to outpatient clinics like this one in the
San Fernando Valley in Los Angeles. Still, even after eliminating
half of its hospital beds in the last five years, the federal
health care system for military veterans still spends more than $1
million a day to operate unneeded hospital buildings, where a
dwindling number of veterans receive care in underpopulated wards,
federal investigators say. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) NANTUCKET, Mass. -- July 31, 1999 -- NANTUCKET-DEVELOP-3,
07-31 -- Cyclists and sport utility vehicles compete for space on
the cobblestone Main Street of Nantucket, where wealthy visitors
who crave a piece of the island's charm are buying up houses and
ripping them apart. Once treasured by a relative few for its
cobblestone streets, its picket fences bathed in icy-pink roses and
its isolation, Nantucket is awakening to the din and clash of
construction, threatening both its look and its historic integrity.
(Rob Benchley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NANTUCKET, Mass. -- July 31, 1999 -- NANTUCKET-DEVELOP-2,
07-31 -- Lee Bryant, a mason, working on a chimney for a new house
in the 200-lot Naushop subdivision in Nantucket. The houses sell
for $500,000. Nantucket, an idyllic, mist-covered island 30 miles
out at sea, is under siege. Once treasured by a relative few for
its cobblestone streets, its picket fences bathed in icy-pink roses
and its isolation, Nantucket is awakening to the din and clash of
construction, threatening both its look and its historic integrity.
(Rob Benchley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NANTUCKET, Mass. -- July 31, 1999 -- NANTUCKET-DEVELOP,
07-31 -- A house under construction on Mill Street maximizes use of
a small lot. Nantucket, an idyllic, mist-covered island 30 miles
out at sea, is under siege. Once treasured by a relative few for
its cobblestone streets, its picket fences bathed in icy-pink roses
and its isolation, Nantucket is awakening to the din and clash of
construction, threatening both its look and its historic integrity.
(Rob Benchley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
