</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT CUBS, 10-9  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Even though the Mets found themselves alone in first
place Saturday morning for the first time this late in a season in
nearly nine years, some of the players had other thoughts on their
minds.
</P>
<P>
   Like Saturday night's midnight trading deadline, for instance.
</P>
<P>
   Others, like Mike Piazza, tried not to think about the slumping
Atlanta Braves at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's still a lot of time left,'' Piazza said, hours after
he had hit his 21st home run to help the Mets come back from a
five-run deficit for a 10-9 victory over the Cubs on the hottest
day (103 degrees) of the year here.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was Masato Yoshii, whose spot in the starting
rotation has become increasingly tenuous.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one's asked me about anything,'' Yoshii said Friday,
sounding genuinely surprised when asked if he was worried that he
was headed for the bullpen. ``What's that all about?''
</P>
<P>
   He expressed no concern about the possibility of losing his job
as a starter. ``Even if I was told to go to the bullpen, why should
I be worried about it?'' Yoshii said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, after allowing seven runs in one and a third innings, the
shortest outing by a Mets starter in nearly two years, Yoshii
seemed likely to lose his spot in the rotation, unless Kenny
Rogers' tight right hamstring prevents him from making his start
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny's leg has a lot of bearing on my decision right now,''
Mets Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``That's my first priority.
Yoshii might come back on the fifth day.''
</P>
<P>
   That would happen only if Rogers needs Yoshii to substitute for
him, Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii, who was nearly demoted to the minor leagues after the
first month of the season only to pitch like the Mets' ace in May,
is on the downswing again.
</P>
<P>
   From June 11 to June 27, he allowed only 7 earned runs in 271/3
innings, a stingy 2.30 earned run average. Since then, he has had a
July to forget: 25 earned runs in 22 innings covering five starts.
That is a 10.23 e.r.a., lifting his season e.r.a. to 5.67, the
highest of anyone on the staff other than Bobby Jones, who has been
on the disabled list with shoulder soreness since May 23.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii's problem on Friday was with his control.
</P>
<P>
   ``He left too many balls up,'' Piazza said. ``He didn't have
much movement. They were hitting a lot of his off-speed stuff. He
had no snap on his cut fastball. And his split-finger was
hanging.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than that, Yoshii was fine.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike last season, however, Yoshii has benefited from some run
support. The Mets have actually won three of his five July starts.
And they won at Wrigley Field, on the hottest day most of them
could remember, by coming back after being down by 7-2.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the Braves lost to the Phillies in Atlanta and the
Mets were alone in first for the first time since September 1990.
Not only that, the Mets were also in first place at the same time
as the Yankees for the first time since July 27, 1988.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine has never finished a season in first place as a player
or a coach. With two months left in the season, he is tantalizingly
close.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
