A1221 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-McHALE-COLUMN-LAD     07-31 0716
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-McHALE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INCOMPLETE SEASON LEAVES BROWN DOWN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ ``Just get me to Pedro Borbon'' was not the legacy
the Dodgers envisioned for Kevin Brown when they signed him last
winter.
</P>
<P>
   Brown came here to give the bullpen the night off, to give the
fans a lift and to give the Dodgers a reason to strut. Instead, he
has given them something very incomplete, and it just isn't the
game.
</P>
<P>
   Forget the money. If his contract upsets you, blame the team,
not him. It's not what he takes to the bank, it's what he takes to
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   That's why fans were booing Friday night when Davey Johnson came
to get him with two outs and one on in the eighth inning. They came
to see Brown give them a reason to care about the final two months
of this season.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they got to watch Borbon and especially Jeff Shaw lead
an eighth-inning meltdown that turned the crowd of 45,839 into an
angry mob.
</P>
<P>
   All they ask is that Brown be Brown, as dominant a right-hander
as the there has been in baseball the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   When he pitches the way he did last Sunday in beating Randy
Johnson 2-1 in Arizona, the reasons for giving him the moon seem
reasonable.
</P>
<P>
   When he left the June 4 game against the Angels with Mo Vaughn
walking to the plate with the game on the line, there weren't as
many boos as Friday, but there should have been. It might have been
the only Kodak moment the Dodgers had this year.
</P>
<P>
   When the Dodgers needed to open the second half with conviction,
Brown lasted just 51/3 innings against the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, whose 2.33 ERA the past three seasons is the best in
baseball, has not pitched into the ninth inning this season. He has
61 complete games in his career, but the only one this year was an
eight-inning 3-2 loss in Cincinnati.
</P>
<P>
   No one is asking him to go the distance every fifth day. That
isn't realistic. He has pitched superbly much of the time but has
never made the statement that you can't mess with his team.
</P>
<P>
   If this was a health issue, that would be one thing. Injuries
seem to have gotten Eric Young off the hook for an unproductive
season.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said earlier this season that Brown was feeling the
weight of expectations after signing the seven-year, $105 million
contract. All year, Johnson has said he gets a little concerned
when Brown gets to 105 pitches. Friday, he also said there have
been a few games where he left Brown in too long.
</P>
<P>
   Brown clearly is disappointed with the dysfunctional family he
joined. He couldn't be blamed for thinking he made a mistake
joining a team that needs yet another overhaul. But he doesn't let
out those kinds of thoughts.
</P>
<P>
   That's his right, but he has remained aloof from teammates. With
this bunch, that is not OK.
</P>
<P>
   He has never connected with his teammates, who were desperate
for guidance. He has never made the Dodgers his team the way Pedro
Martinez has done in Boston and Curt Schilling has done in
Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   When Johnson elected to skip Friday's start to give his arm an
extra day's rest, some thought he was ducking Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The truth was Johnson had thrown 138 and 143 pitches in his last
two starts. Earlier this season, he was the victim of four
consecutive shutouts. If anybody had a right to be upset with
teammates, it was Johnson, who just shrugged and helped put the
Diamondbacks back in first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he pitches, it gives us a lift physically and emotionally
for days,'' said Luis Gonzalez, who helped Johnson on Saturday with
a two-run homer. ``When he is out there, there is an electricity.
We haven't always been there for him this season, but he is there
for us.''
</P>
<P>
   It would have been nice to hear the Dodgers say something like
that about Brown. Gary Sheffield, who played with him in Florida
when the Marlins won the World Series in 1997, sounded more like an
accountant than a teammate when talking about Brown's game on
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has made the tremendous investment with him,''
Sheffield said, ``and you don't want to jeopardize that.''
</P>
<P>
   Don't worry. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Sports Editor Matt McHale covers baseball for the Daily
News. He can be reached at (800) 777-4953 or mch013aol.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
