<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
METS GAMBLE WITH ROGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Kenny Rogers began his second tour in New York on
Tuesday with a 9-2 victory over the Pittsburgh Pirates, but the New
York Mets also know he brought some baggage.
</P>
<P>
   Although Oakland is very much in the AL wild-card hunt, Rogers
told GM Billy Beane it was time to go. Rogers reportedly cleaned
out his locker before the A's recent road trip and returned to
Tampa, not Oakland, after the trade to get his family. Veteran
players told Beane they wanted Rogers out.
</P>
<P>
   Mets GM Steve Phillips said he was aware of Rogers' differences
with players in Oakland. Rogers punched one teammate with his
pitching hand in a card-game dispute and destroyed a bank of phones
in 3Com Park over poor defense that cost him a four-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have fights all time,'' said Phillips, who has seen manager
Bobby Valentine and Bobby Bonilla exchange words and nearly punches
this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets' playoff chances are far better than the A's. But when
Rogers played for the Yankees, he was overwhelmed by the big city.
He also has never pitched in the NL.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kenny never really wanted to be here,'' Beane said. ``At
times, this became a distraction. I had hoped the continued
improvement of the team would help rope him into the momentum, but
that didn't happen.'' &QL; 
On the mark
</P>
<P>
   Cubs first baseman Mark Grace knew long before Saturday's trade
deadline that he wasn't going anywhere. He is a free agent at the
end of the year and any new team would have wanted to negotiate a
new deal rather than risk losing him after the season. That never
happened. But even if Grace remains in a Cubs uniform to collect
his 2,000th hit early next month, there is no guarantee he will be
back next season. His agent, Barry Axelrod, is aware that the
Giants' J.T. Snow signed a four-year, $24 million contract Friday.
The Cubs haven't talked contract since Grace rejected an offer
three months ago. ``Hopefully something will get done,'' said
Grace, who is earning $4.1 million this year. ``If you know
anything about the Cubs' history, it's usually down to the last
minute. It's been that way with me. It was that way with Greg
Maddux, Rick Sutcliffe, Ryne Sandberg, Andre Dawson. The only guy
they've gotten taken care of early was Sammy (Sosa).'' &QL; 
Something in return
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Diamondbacks are ecstatic with new closer Matt
Mantei, who had seven saves in his first three weeks with the club.
But Florida, which received top pitching prospect Brad Penny for
Mantei, also is pleased with the other pitcher it got in the deal,
Vladimir Nunez. A reliever with the Diamondbacks, Nunez was
impressive Monday against Philadelphia and pitched Saturday vs.
Pittsburgh. Nunez is on a strict pitch count to strengthen his arm
for starting. He was limited to 65 pitches Monday and 80 on
Saturday. He has taken the place of Livan Hernandez, a good friend
since the two pitched together on the Cuban junior national team.
He now has a locker next to the two lockers Hernandez had before he
was traded to San Francisco. ``They have to close off those lockers
now,'' Nunez said. ``Those are history.'' &QL; 
Getting a chance
</P>
<P>
   Steve Schrenk, a 30-year-old rookie and father of five, made his
first major-league start Wednesday for Philadelphia in place of
Curt Schilling (strained right bicep) and pitched six scoreless
innings in a 9-4 victory over Florida. Schrenk was a 24-year-old
right-hander on the fast track to the Chicago White Sox starting
rotation when Phillies manager Terry Francona last managed him.
Schrenk had gone 5-1 with a 1.17 ERA in eight starts for Francona's
Double-A Birmingham club. But after undergoing two shoulder
operations, he quickly went from big-league prospect to
minor-league journeyman, passing through four organizations in
three seasons before signing as a minor-league free agent with the
Phillies last October. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 2012EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
