u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT &LR;      07-31 0920
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-REDSOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX BEAT YANKEES, 6-5  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Most of the Yankees did not see what happened in left
field on the last play of Saturday's 6-5 loss to the Red Sox. Under
the low ceiling of the Yankees' dugout, they could see Shane
Spencer chasing a lazy fly ball toward the left-field corner, until
both were hidden from view by the stands.
</P>
<P>
   And then they heard Fenway Park explode in joy, saw Jose
Offerman sprinting home with the winning run, and the Yankees in
the dugout were turning and asking each other: what happened?
</P>
<P>
   The whole tedious game, played under the last July sun of the
hottest summer in memory, seemed like this to the Yankees: they
battered the Red Sox in the early innings _ pounding them with
hits. Roger Clemens, pitching in a Yankees cap in Fenway for the
first time, had appeared to overcome his usual big-game adrenaline
rush. And then the Yankees blew a couple of leads and just lost
sight of victory. The Yankees (62-40), who beat Boston on Friday,
will play the third and final game of the series Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen Roger with 2-0 leads, and then 5-2 leads,'' said
George Steinbrenner, the Yankees' principal owner, who watched and
grinned and grimaced from the seats next to his team's dugout. ``I
was ready to say the ball game is over. But it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   No, it didn't, and the Yankees blamed themselves as Derek Jeter
and Tino Martinez and others sat around a table afterward,
recalling some of the afternoon's low points _ and for the Yankees,
most of them occurred when big innings fell apart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't put the game away,'' said Scott Brosius, the
Yankees' third baseman. ``They kind of bent all day but didn't
break, and it was just enough for them to creep back in.''
</P>
<P>
   Chuck Knoblauch, who led off Friday's victory with a home run,
started Saturday's game the same way; two batters later, Paul
O'Neill homered as well. Thereafter, their rallies were stunted:
Brosius singled opening the second and was thrown out stealing.
Knoblauch slammed a ball off the left-field wall to lead off the
third and was thrown out trying to stretch his hit into a double.
Two runners reached base subsequently, before Martinez took a
called third strike to end the inning.
</P>
<P>
   The crossroads in this game came in the fourth. The Yankees had
four straight hits to start the inning _ they would collect 13 hits
in the first six innings. The Yankees led by 4-2, there were two
runs in, two on base, nobody out and Boston's Brian Rose was
getting shelled, every hit a missile.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch turned and tried bunting toward third, a surprise and
a nice idea; either he would get an infield hit or advance the
runners into scoring position for Jeter. Knoblauch popped up his
bunt, however, for the first out, and on the very next pitch, Jeter
grounded into a double play. The Red Sox had bent, and had not
broken.
</P>
<P>
   But Clemens, the former Boston pitcher, was bending in the heat.
Sweat poured off his face, down his arms, onto his wrists and
hands, and he could not grip his split-fingered fastball, a pitch
he usually uses to finish off opposing hitters with two strikes.
``It just took the splitter away from me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His pitch count mounted quickly, he was having trouble throwing
strikes, and the Fenway crowd booed him at every opportunity. (Joe
Torre, the Yankees' manager, noted before the game that Clemens'
portrait on the facing of the second deck here, added because he
was named one of baseball's 100 greatest players, pictures Clemens
in a Yankees cap.) They derisively chanted his name when he fell
into trouble in the fifth inning, the cry of ``Roger'' mournfully
sarcastic. ``We had a lot of Yankees' fans here,'' Clemens said
with a straight face, when asked about the fans.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra singled to lead off the sixth, and Clemens was
relieved by Jason Grimsley; Boston scored a run in that inning,
then tied the score at 5-5 in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Offerman was first to hit for the Red Sox in the ninth, against
Ramiro Mendoza. He slammed a line drive to center, the ball
bounding into wide open space in center field, for a triple. The
Yankees' infield moved in, with John Valentin at the plate, trying
to cut off the winning run.
</P>
<P>
   Valentin pulled a high fly down the third-base line. Brosius was
playing close to the line and when it passed him, he would say
later, it was headed far into foul territory. Valentin thought so,
too. ``As soon as I hit it,'' Valentin said later, ``I thought it
was foul. When it didn't hook, I knew it was going to come back.''
</P>
<P>
   The fans in the stands along the left-field line stood and
watched Spencer charge toward the line. All along the way, he was
assessing the situation. The runner at third base, Offerman, is
fast, and if Spencer caught the ball in the left-field corner, then
Offerman would tag up and score easily.
</P>
<P>
   So Spencer went to the spot where he thought the ball might come
down, and hoped. He hoped the ball would go foul. He hoped an
anxious fan would reach out and touch the ball.
</P>
<P>
   The left-field corner cannot be seen from the Yankees' dugout,
because of the way the stands jut out, nearly meeting the
left-field foul line. David Cone watched Valentin, who stood at the
plate, waited, then began to move toward first and then run hard,
and then the Yankees knew. Spencer had let the ball drop in fair
territory _ the right play, the Yankees all agreed. The wrong
result. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
