<SLUG> BC-RAC-POWELL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SANTA ANITA CEO WAS RAISED ON HORSES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK C. GIRARDOT  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARCADIA, Calif. _ The Sylmar earthquake of 1971 forever changed
the course of Lonny Powell's life.
</P>
<P>
   The son of a jockey who rode the Southern California circuit,
Powell, 39, recently took over as Santa Anita Park's president and
chief executive officer. He was born in Newhall and raised in San
Fernando, but Powell is a relative newcomer to the local racing
scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``We moved after the 1971 earthquake.... It had everything to do
with the move,'' Powell said. ``My parents had become so gun shy
and the earthquake did damage our home in San Fernando really bad.
So we ended up in Idaho.''
</P>
<P>
   Leaving the area didn't mean the Powell family lost touch with
local developments, and Lonny has spent the better part of his
adult life on a path back home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The majority of my dad's work was here in California. He was
at that time the manager of the Jockey's Guild,'' Powell said.
``The only reason we ended up in Idaho was that he liked to hunt
and he had the type of job that as long as he could get to an
airport he could live basically wherever he wanted....
</P>
<P>
   ``We still kept the strong ties with the racing industry. It
kept me well-wired.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this month, Powell was president and CEO at Turf Paradise
in Phoenix. His Santa Anita hiring came on the heels of the
resignations of Santa Anita president William C. Baker and
executive vice president and general manager Cliff Goodrich.
</P>
<P>
   Powell's duties at Santa Anita will encompass the
responsibilities of both Goodrich and Baker. Powell also will be
vice president of Ventures, a corporation formed by Santa Anita
owner Frank Stronach that will be involved in real estate
development and gambling activities in Europe and North America.
</P>
<P>
   Stronach said he hired Powell because of his youth and
experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt maybe I need somebody young with a new, innovative
approach,'' Stronach said. ``I'm very optimistic that Lonny will do
a great job.''
</P>
<P>
   Stronach said Powell impressed him with his open mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's open to new ideas,'' Stronach said. ``So I want
to have somebody (who) is open _ no preconceived ideas to say what
can we do to make this place exciting and get people here.''
</P>
<P>
   Glad to be home, Powell just might have the formula for success.
His credentials certainly are unusual.
</P>
<P>
   ``My father was a jockey, my uncle was a trainer,'' Powell said.
``My father-in-law was a trainer, my wife galloped and was a
trainer. Every job I've had since high school has been at the
racetrack _ going from cleaning the jocks' room to mowing the
paddock lawns to working as an assistant starter in the starting
gate.''
</P>
<P>
   Powell also has the educational background. He attended the
University of Arizona and studied in its prestigious racetrack
program.
</P>
<P>
   Before his five-year stint at Turf Paradise, Powell served as
president of Multnomah Greyhound Park, executive vice president and
chief operating officer of Longacres, general manager of the
Woodlands and director of the University of Arizona's racetrack
industry program.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been very fortunate and blessed that every job I've had
in the business I've exceeded my expectations and my employers'
(expectations),'' Powell said.
</P>
<P>
   Santa Anita might pose some special problems for Powell. There
is grumbling among old-timers in the racing community about
Powell's perceived lack of experience. Stronach has encountered
some resistance over his sweeping plans for change at the facility.
</P>
<P>
   Powell isn't worried. He's optimistic about his future and the
future of horse racing at Santa Anita Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's an old saying that the pioneers take all the arrows,''
Powell said. ``I'm definitely up to the task. I use the word
`jacked' a lot.... I truly am. I mean, I'm jacked about the whole
thing _ geared up, fired up, however you want to put it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be here at the pinnacle of racing. I'm excited
about the future that lies ahead for this facility.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
