<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1248 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GLF-DUMAURIER-NYT &LR;      07-31 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-DUMAURIER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INKSTER FALLS BEHIND DAVIES IN BID FOR YEAR'S THIRD MAJOR  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIDDIS, Alberta _ If Juli Inkster is to win her third major of
the year, she will have to catch Laura Davies.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster fell four strokes back Saturday as Davies shot a
three-under-par 69. Davies used her length to overpower most of the
par 5's and held a two-stroke lead over Dawn Coe-Jones of Canada
after the third round of the du Maurier Classic Saturday. Davies is
nine under par for the tournament (207), two strokes ahead of
Coe-Jones, who shot a 72 Saturday, and three strokes ahead of
Catriona Matthew of Scotland, who also shot a 72.
</P>
<P>
   Inkster struggled to a 74 Saturday, leaving her at five under
par for the tournament, tied with Karrie Webb, who shot a 66 to
roar into contention.
</P>
<P>
   The final round at Priddis Greens Golf and Country Club will be
pressure-packed for Inkster, who would clinch a spot in the LPGA
Hall of Fame with a victory. And Inkster is also trying to become
only the second player to win three of the four LPGA modern majors
in the same year, joining Pat Bradley, who won three majors in
1986.
</P>
<P>
   While Inkster was not thrilled with her performance Saturday,
she hardly saw her four-shot deficit as insurmountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to have to shoot a real good score tomorrow, because
I don't see Laura backing up,'' said Inkster, who suffered her
first over-par round since April, ending a streak of 27 rounds. ``I
know I'm capable of shooting some good scores and getting that
putter going.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a strange round for Inkster, who struggled
uncharacteristically with her putter, even missing a two-footer on
No.12 for a costly bogey. Meanwhile, Davies was solid during a
round that included five birdies and just two bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   Davies has won four career majors, including the 1996 du
Maurier, and she is usually a strong front-runner. Asked about her
strategy for Sunday, Davies planned to remain aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I shoot the best round tomorrow, then obviously I win,''
said Davies, who is from England. ``That is my plan tomorrow, get
out, make some birdies and not too many mistakes. Any of the names
on that leader board can go out and shoot the 66, 65. You can't sit
back, because the minute you sit back, somebody is going to go
straight past you.''
</P>
<P>
   Davies started the day at six under par, one stroke behind
Inkster and Coe-Jones, but she took the lead on the back nine with
a birdie on the par 5, 517-yard 12th hole. Capable of driving the
ball almost 300 yards in the 4,000-foot altitude, Davies can reach
all of the par 5 greens in two shots, while many of her competitors
need three shots. Davies birdied three of the five par 5 holes
Saturday, and she is eight under par on the par 5's for the
tournament. Meanwhile, Davies has played her short game smartly as
well, using irons off the tee for accuracy and avoiding the deep
rough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The others stand up there with drivers, and they still have a
narrow target,'' Davies said. ``They can afford to miss the
fairways even less than I can.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Davies falters, a handful of players are waiting to take
advantage, including Webb, the tour's leading money-winner, who has
won five times this year but has yet to win a major. Webb played
aggressively off the tee, then made putts once she reached the
green.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my position, I had to do what I did or I didn't have a
chance of winning,'' said Webb, who started the day at one over
par, eight strokes off the lead. ``Today, I rolled the first putt
in, then took it from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Coe-Jones will have the gallery's support Sunday as a
Canadian, and she hoped to use that as inspiration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope there are a lot of people out there,'' said Coe-Jones.
``Hopefully I will make lots of putts and make them scream really
loud.''
</P>
<P>
   But Inkster will remain the focal point of the tournament, still
hoping to add another victory to an already remarkable year.
Saturday, Inkster was not at her best. But she hoped that he was
saving her best for last.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been the leader, I've been in the hunt, and now I'm
coming from behind,'' Inkster said. ``If you can win three, you
might as well do it a little different each time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
