<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SRF-SURFING-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SLATER CHASES RECORD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE STEVENS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HUNTINGTON BEACH, Calif. _ Kelly Slater's surfing scene wasn't
unique to him. The six-time world champion repeatedly slashed
across waves, rode them to shore and relished the raucous support
from the Huntington Beach crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Slater scored 24.10, the highest of any surfer in Saturday's
Gotcha Pro, to beat Australian Todd Prestage and advance to today's
quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   But while the scene wasn't unique to Slater, the scenario is.
Slater, who's endured a high-profile lifestyle that included dating
Baywatch's Pamela Anderson and starting a rock band, is off
surfing's World Championship Tour. The Floridian has planned to
compete in just two WCT events this year the Gotcha Pro and Pipe
Masters Championship in Banzai Pipeline, Hawaii. Slater is
considered ``semi-retired,'' but he may have shown he still could
be the world's top ranked surfer if he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a goal,'' Slater said. ``I've won at least one event on
the tour for the past seven years, and I'd like to keep that going.
But now, I only have two chances to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Slater is chasing Tom Curren's record of winning a WCT event for
10 consecutive years. Winning off the tour could be more impressive
than on tour because it shows the surfer can periodically bring out
his surfing skills when needed. Slater has done that at Huntington,
while implementing old strategies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found being on tour, that it is best to build momentum
throughout the contest,'' Slater said. ``Sometimes you can psyche
out your opponent if you keep getting better scores.''
</P>
<P>
   Prestage wasn't necessarily psyched out, but the Australian had
an uncharacteristic two wipe outs in the heat.
</P>
<P>
   Slater competes against Brazilian Fabio Gouveia today in the
quarterfinals, which start at 9 a.m. The semifinals and finals
follow today.
</P>
<P>
   Gouveia is one of three Brazilians in the quarterfinals. So is
Neco Padaratz, who has become the talk of the competition after
knocking out Mark Occhilupo, Mick Campbell and Renan Rocha.
</P>
<P>
   Padaratz, 22, has not granted interviews throughout the
tournament. He is a wild-card entry who was ranked as high as 10th
last year on the WCT. This year, he is trying to rejoin the tour
after leaving it last season to spent time with his wife and
newborn. With dyed blond hair and a piercing of a blue spike under
his lip, Padaratz rode the best wave for the second successive day
and scored a 9.0.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a quickie, but he's still pretty young,'' Slater said of
Padaratz. ``The main thing he has to focus on is smoothing out his
surfing.''
</P>
<P>
   Victor Ribas is another Brazilian who is surfing strongly. He
knocked out Curren Saturday. Ribas, a small-wave specialist, said
he is accustomed to Huntington's conditions, sans the cold water.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned a lot from Tom Curren,'' Ribas said. ``He's one
of my favorite surfers. I still have all of his videos at home.''
</P>
<P>
   Curren, who was admitted to the Gotcha Pro as a legend, said he
was disappointed with being knocked out, but didn't feel he had a
bad performance. If he made mistake, it was taking a wave early
that wasn't big enough, which gave Ribas the upper hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not really a difference,'' the 35-year-old Curren said
about his surfing now compared with 10 years ago. ``The boards are
different. That's about it.''
</P>
<P>
   How Padaratz fares against Australian Michael Lowe and how Ribas
does against Aussie Nathan Webster are of interest. Another curious
heat could be Hawaiian Sunny Garcia against San Clemente's Shea
Lopez, who won last week's U.S. Open of Surfing.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Andy Irons won both competitions, so Lopez could
replicate that. ``It's still there in the memory,'' Lopez said
about last week. ``Trying to win each heat, I'm hoping to have the
necessary patience and calm to win.''
</P>
<P>
   But Garcia, who says that luck and catching the best wave are
the keys to victory, stands in Lopez's way. ``I'm not the fastest
paddler, but I 'm the most aggressive on the tour,'' Garcia said.
``If there is a wave and a battle between me and you, I'm going to
get it.''
</P>
<P>
   (Women's final set subhed)
</P>
<P>
   As opposed to past years, the women's final, which normally
would have been Saturday, is scheduled today at 12:10 p.m., right
before the 12:40 men's final. Australian Trudy Todd will face
Hawaiian Rochelle Ballard. Todd knocked out fellow countrywoman
Pauline Menczer, and Ballard beat Brazilian Tita Tavares.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
