A1455 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-HERSHISER-LADN     07-31 0914
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-HERSHISER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BULLDOG STILL HAS BITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE DILBECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Some guys just won't take the hint. They won't go
away, won't fade into that good night.
</P>
<P>
   Orel Hershiser has been given up on more than fad diets. He's a
40-year-old right-hander with a rebuilt shoulder. People see him
hanging on, seemingly a shadow of his Cy Young past, and suspect
each season will be his last.
</P>
<P>
   And then he goes out and surprises again. Hooks up with another
pitching-desperate club, and wins. Wins like he is this year with
the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser is 10-8 for the surprising Mets, and even if he does
seem somewhat embarrassed by that 4.92 ERA, he could win 15 games
this season. Fifteen-game winners are difficult to find these days,
even if they come with a young arm and 95-mph fastball.
</P>
<P>
   Yet here is Hershiser, now actually having won more games since
Dr. Frank Jobe's historic 1990 surgery than he did before, when he
came equipped with some of the nastiest stuff in baseball. He's not
planning on exiting anytime soon, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most advice I'm getting from the people I respect is,
`Make them tear the uniform off you, because you're not going to
find anything like it,''' Hershiser said. ``That you're always
going to be hungry for something like that. You're going to be
comparing everything else to this.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser won 99 games before undergoing Jobe's scalpel and has
won an amazing 101 since. None have approached the magic of his '88
season, when he helped lead the Dodgers to the World Series title
and captured his only Cy Young Award, but Hershiser keeps finding
new teams, new ways to win, new reasons to appreciate it all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love pitching, I love being in the locker room, I love
teaching baseball,'' he said. ``I love the smell of the game. I
just love what it's all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Wallace, the former Dodgers pitching coach who was the
Mets' senior executive adviser of player personnel before being
asked to take over as the team's pitching coach during the season,
recommended the Mets take a chance on Hershiser.
</P>
<P>
   And Wallace knew this was another year when most were ready to
write Hershiser off.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had a chance to get him, I was all for it,'' Wallace
said. ``He's got so much pride and so much competitiveness. So I
have to take a chance on a guy like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, not even Wallace could have predicted Hershiser would
already have 10 victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who'd of thunk it?,'' he said. ``But he comes prepared,
physically and mentally. He knows his limits. He knows himself.
Everybody knows his work ethic. He knows the game so well.
</P>
<P>
   ``Naturally he doesn't have the sinker and curveball he had in
his prime years, but at times his sinker is still really good. He
really knows how to pitch; throws a little slider. He's savvy.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser still looks the same. Still has the long, lanky frame,
the gee-whiz boyish look, the wire-rimmed glasses, a head of full
brown hair.
</P>
<P>
   But if ``Bulldog'' outwardly has fought the reach of time, he
said there has been concessions to his advancing years.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's different about being older and playing this game is,
when you get your aches and pains you're not sure if it's going to
grow into a major injury or if it's just going to go away,''
Hershiser said. ``That can weigh on you. I've learned about a lot
about my body since that time in '95.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had to start learning about rest. Because as an athlete, to
me, the harder you worked, the better you got. Well, you get to an
age where that equation doesn't work anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser said he nearly retired after '95 in Cleveland, his
first with the Indians after not being re-signed by the Dodgers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a crisis in our lives,'' Hershiser said.
</P>
<P>
   His wife and two boys remained in Pasadena. Spring training
didn't mean six weeks in Vero Beach, where his parents lived.
Suddenly he was three time zones away, and then when summer
arrived, his family had to move. All things he and his family had
never experienced.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had won the World Series, I don't know... I probably
would have still come back, but we had to make some adjustments,''
he said. `The first adjustment I thought of was, `I'm just done.'
Because that's the easiest. You're causing so much pain and turmoil
to everyone else's life, you start to say the easiest thing is for
me to change my lifestyle. Then slowly as we thought about baseball
not being part of our lives, everyone started to tell me that it
wasn't as bad as they thought. They were saying it is tough, but we
can still do it. Now that we've been doing that kind of lifestyle
for so long, every year has gotten easier.''
</P>
<P>
   That offseason he moved to Orlando. He signed a two-year
extension with the Indians.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought that would be it for sure,'' Hershiser said. ``I
thought maybe even '95 might end up being it.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he kept rolling, kept defying the odds and the years.
This year he became the 95th pitcher in baseball to win 200 games.
He may no longer be the game's most consistent pitcher, but he has
more career victories than any active pitcher except Roger Clemens
and Greg Maddux.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm having fun, on a great team, in a fun city, my family is
healthy, and my boys are growing quickly and enjoying my career
more and more because they're old enough to remember it and
enjoy,'' he said. ``I'm doing great.'' &UR; !dlim! &LR; !end! &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
