<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRETT-PARADE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARADE PAYS ADDITIONAL TRIBUTE TO GEORGE BRETT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EDWARD M. EVELD and STEVE EVERLY  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Royals fan Ed Follis has a George Brett
story. Doesn't everyone?
</P>
<P>
   Follis' tale takes place in the bleachers at Yankee Stadium in
1990. The Yankee fans are booing every Royals player who comes to
the plate.
</P>
<P>
   But when Brett steps up, a self-appointed leader of the bleacher
fans raises his arms for silence. ``This man is George Brett,'' he
shouts to the Yankee faithful. ``He's earned our respect.''
</P>
<P>
   All jeering stopped.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the last place I expected to see that,'' said Follis of
Overland Park.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, in a light rain that didn't last, Follis
and hundreds of other Brett believers made their way to the Brett
parade in Kansas City and congregated for a celebration in Mill
Creek Park near the Country Club Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   They wanted to glimpse their baseball hero and to show their
gratitude for his extraordinary efforts on the field, which landed
him in Baseball's Hall of Fame at Cooperstown, N.Y., last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   On the main stage at the park, Buck O'Neil, Negro Leagues
baseball great and Saturday's parade grand marshal, put it this
way: ``I'd rather be right here right now honoring this man than
anyplace I've ever been.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Brett wanted to turn the thanks around. He
recalled his earliest days with the Royals, which go back to 1973.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a no-brainer,'' Brett said. ``I fell in love with the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   Several former Royals players -- including Mark Gubicza, Willie
Wilson and Jim Eisenreich -- rode in the parade and came on stage
to show their support for Brett. Kansas City Mayor Kay Barnes and
several radio personalities shared their thanks.
</P>
<P>
   And the crowd joined in a musical chorus about Brett: ``No. 5 is
No. 1, the best you'll ever see. Hurray for our great No. 5, a hero
in ol' KC.''
</P>
<P>
   After Brett urged the fans to support the current version of the
Royals -- ``We've got a lot of youngsters out there busting their
rear ends'' -- he expressed his gratitude to the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't thank you people enough for what you've done over the
past 25 years,'' he said. ``I am so proud to call Kansas City my
home -- thanks for coming out.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier along the parade route, Sue and Brian Nelson and their
10-year-old son, Matt, himself a third baseman, waited in
anticipation as the Ararat Shriners' minicars motored by and the
Kansas City Monarchs float slowed in front of them.
</P>
<P>
   The float sported a giant No. 5 and a big cube with Brett
photos, including the June 21, 1976, cover of Sports Illustrated
calling Brett the ``Hot bat at the hot corner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Nelsons moved to Shawnee from Des Moines, Iowa, about a year
ago, but Brian Nelson lived here until the sixth grade.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always my hero,'' said Nelson about Brett. ``So we just
had to come. And you don't get this in Des Moines, a Hall-of-Famer
parading by.''
</P>
<P>
   The crowd yelled ``Whitey'' as former Royals manager Whitey
Herzog rode by in a baby-blue 1952 Chevy. They waved at Wilson,
sitting tall and lanky in a tiny convertible. Former Royals player
Greg Pryor swung his head backward and joked, ``Has anybody seen
George yet? I think he's back there.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Brett arrived in a Hummer stretch limousine, first
resting his chin on his hand but soon enough responding to the
crowd. A little girl of about 3 waved at Brett and he blew her a
kiss. Brett spotted a person who attended the Hall of Fame
induction and called out, ``Have a good time up there?''
</P>
<P>
   Fans waved and displayed homemade signs. One read:
``Congratulations, George Brett, KC's MVP forever.''
</P>
<P>
   The parade began at 10 a.m. at Volker Boulevard and Rockhill
Road and ended at the park almost an hour later. The early
sprinkles and the 80-degree weather were the area's first respite
from a prolonged heat wave, which had pushed temperatures to 100
and above.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody asked me, `What if it rains?' '' said Bubbles the
Clown, a parade participant also known as Louise Ohap of
Independence. ``At this point I'd say, `Thank you, God.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At the park, families waited in lines for a ride on a Kansas
City Power &AMP; Light Co. bucket truck, for a face-painting session,
for a turn in a plastic-ball pit or for a ride down a giant,
blow-up slide. A petting zoo featured goats, pigs, sheep and
llamas.
</P>
<P>
   Fans could learn about Lou Gehrig's disease and donate to the
ALS Association, an important cause for Brett. They could buy
commemorative envelopes from the U.S. Postal Service for $10. The
envelopes recounted Brett's career and featured a Cooperstown
postmark.
</P>
<P>
   All of it was wonderful to John Luciani, who arrived in town
from Denver just weeks ago to start a job with HOK Sports, a firm
that designs stadiums. Luciani arrived at 8:30 a.m. -- ``I think I
was the first one here'' -- to watch the setup. He was gleeful
about the autographs he got from O'Neil and Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   A self-professed baseball nut, Luciani was honored to pay
tribute to Brett. Not long ago, he and a buddy, another hard-core
fan, were making separate lists of baseball greats. The question
came up: Who was the greatest player of the 1980s?
</P>
<P>
   ``We both wrote down `George Brett.' ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 2246EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
