<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 22:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1464 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DROUGHT-DEVASTATION-K     07-31 1212
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DROUGHT-DEVASTATION-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DROUGHT, BUILDING FOR MORE THAN A YEAR, IS DEVASTATING PARTS OF
U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREEN RIDGE STATE FOREST, Md. -- Even as a belated summer rain
pelted the canopy of oak and hickory trees that cloaks the
Allegheny Mountains last week, ranger Francis Zumbrun scratched his
toe into a parched forest floor.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dry as paper. It could burn in a second,'' he said. ``The
rain is nice, but they say we need the equivalent of a couple of
tropical hurricanes to make things right.''
</P>
<P>
   Zumbrun has never seen this forest so dry or anticipated such a
frightful fall fire season. To the north in Pennsylvania, the
ground hasn't been so dry since the mid-1960s. Stretches of the
Potomac River are running lower than they have since the early
1930s, while the Susquehanna River has fallen to a 100-year low.
</P>
<P>
   The water shortage in northern Virginia has made a sin of car
washing, while threatening fruit orchards and forcing ranchers to
unload cattle at a loss.
</P>
<P>
   With Maryland's key reservoirs more than half empty, the
governor last week declared the state's first-ever drought
emergency and said he might impose mandatory conservation measures.
Pennsylvania, Delaware and New York have already issued similar
alarms.
</P>
<P>
   Overlooked in the death and misery of July's stifling heat wave,
drought has struck some regions of the country. It's been building
for more than a year, and its damage may more profoundly devastate
sections of the country in the months and years to come.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a severe problem and a very real drought in those
mid-Atlantic states,'' said Douglas LeComte, a senior meteorologist
for the federal Climate Prediction Center. ``It doesn't look like
there will be any significant relief any time soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, if hot and dry weather continues to bake parts of Oklahoma
and northern Texas, that region will endure its second consecutive
year of drought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our farmers who planted corn and the like are just hoping to
cash in the insurance on a lost crop,'' said JoAnn Rollins, the
manager of Farmers Co-op Gin in Grandfield, Okla. ``There's been no
rain, so there's no crop to speak of.''
</P>
<P>
   The drought prompts people to use more water for their crops,
yards and flower beds. That, in turn, has water treatment systems
running full tilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our fire department can't flush its hydrants as often and
we're not flushing our sewer lines as much because you've got to
start saving water somewhere,'' said Dave Lehfeldt, the utility
operations manager in Wichita Falls, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   In the Northwest, forest and brush fires rage across parts of
eastern Washington and Oregon and northern Idaho. Ironically, a wet
spring is partly responsible. Brush that grew thick during the thaw
has dried into tinder for wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   The soggy-spring/dry-summer phenomenon also has made a
pronounced difference between those farmers who irrigate and those
who don't. Dry-land farmers see their crops wither in the field,
while the irrigators can draw from the waterways.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it comes down the river, we've got it and we're doing
great,'' said Dale Lovejoy, who grows strawberries, flowers and
herbs near Eltopia, Wash. ``But our neighbors who don't irrigate
are in big trouble. It just isn't raining this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather experts attribute the Northwest drought to La Nina, the
weather system that usually follows the bigger El Nino with drier
times. The lack of rain in the East generally stems from a
high-pressure system loitering over the north Atlantic and blocking
a jet stream of moisture from reaching the Eastern seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   In Stephens City, Va., Dudley Rinker can't explain precipitation
rates or pressure systems. He just knows his apples and his plums
are too small this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'll be sweeter and tastier,'' Rinker said, ``but I get
paid for size.''
</P>
<P>
   Trees that usually produce apples upward of 3 inches in diameter
that would bring him about 10 cents a pound this year will produce
fruit smaller than 2.5 inches across that often bring in less than
4 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
   ``It costs me just as much to grow and pick it,'' he said, ``but
I get less money.''
</P>
<P>
   Cattle ranchers in the region see their pastures grow more
barren with each rainless day. Without grass for their cattle to
graze on, many have been forced to buy feed, cutting sharply into
any hopes for profits. Others have sold off their cattle early --
at a loss -- rather than take on more expenses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running out of pasture,'' said Philip Shenk of
Berryville, Va. ``We don't have much choice but to unload the
cattle.''
</P>
<P>
   A half-hour drive away, the effect can be felt in towns as well.
Frank Sanders, director of public utilities in Winchester, Va.,
keeps a careful eye on the Shenandoah River.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not its lowest ever yet,'' Sanders said. ``But our driest
time is in the fall, and we're headed for dangerous territory.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside Delta, Pa., Elwood Krick tends to a herd of newly skinny
cows. The hot weather that has come with the drought meant his 100
dairy cows lost an average of 15 pounds. The trimmer Holsteins, in
turn, produce only two-thirds their normal output of milk.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been at this here for 25 years and I've never seen it
even close to this dry before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His well, competing for water with development that has crept
into the countryside in recent years, has run dangerously low this
summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've got to make sure I'm not trying to use water at two
places -- say to clean out the milking equipment and run something
in the home -- or we'll run out,'' he said. ``It seems like we're
on the verge of disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   At Cramer's Posie Patch near Elizabethtown, Pa., most of the
flowers are shorter and stumpier than usual -- often half their
normal size, and an unusually large number of plants never poke
through the parched ground. Farm manager Keith Cramer said it was
as if almost a month of the six-month season had been entirely lost
to drought. And the water shortage has made production for the rest
of the season far below normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were positioned to have a really big year,'' he said,
walking among ankle-high flowers that should stand higher than his
waist. ``Instead, it's been real disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Amid the tinderbox that is the Green Ridge State Forest, Zumbrun
can walk across a dry stream that would be teeming with stocked
trout in most years. Rainfall here for 1999 is 10 inches below, or
less than half of, normal.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't see a lot of the effect until next spring,'' Zumbrun
said. ``Then the trees won't have the starches and carbohydrates
stored up in the roots to put out leaves.'' He expect 10 to 20
percent of the trees in the western Maryland forest to die.
</P>
<P>
   The toasting of the drought has set the forest ablaze. In a
typical year, there are no significant forest fires here in the
summer. They come far more often in the fall, after the leaves have
fallen and the sun has dried the forest floor.
</P>
<P>
   But this year there have already been at least 10 fires,
including one 10-acre blaze that smoldered for almost two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not been good,'' Zumbrun said. ``I don't even want to
think about the fall.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
