forest,'' &UR; the tall, distinctively white-barked trees with round
leaves like little sails that tremble in the slightest breeze.
Groves of quaking aspens attract thousands of tourists to northern
Arizona in the late summer and early fall as their leaves turn from
green to iridescent gold. It's a beautiful sight that is
disappearing at at an alarming rate from the forests of Arizona and
New Mexico. By MARK SHAFFER. Story will move in the ``A''
category. &QL; 
