<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MONDESI WEARING DODGER BLUES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Raul Mondesi wasn't going to be traded Saturday
even though his bags have been packed for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Emotionally, the Dodgers right fielder has been so angered and
drained by speculation that he was leaving the organization that
signed him at age 17 that he asked to sit out the Dodgers' 4-2 loss
to the Arizona Diamondbacks at Dodger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   It might have looked like Mondesi was ducking left-hander Randy
Johnson, who struck out 12 and pitched a complete game. But that
would have been easy.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing is easy with Mondesi these days.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, he was deeply hurt when his name surfaced in trade
talks with the Cincinnati Reds. After a hot start this season, he
went 112 at-bats without a homer. His .245 batting average was
raised only after an eighth-inning pinch single.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't mind if they trade me. What am I going to do, cry?''
he said, hours before the 9 p.m. trading deadline. ``It may have a
different name on the front of the shirt, but it is the same bats
and balls.''
</P>
<P>
   There was little reason for Mondesi's foul mood. The Dodgers,
certain to gut their disappointing team during the winter, had few
takers for a slumping slugger who still has three years and $29
million left on his contract. He also has two years for $11 million
each at the club's option.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers (45-59), who fell 13{ games behind Arizona in
the National League West, elected to pass on several deals that
would have altered their starting rotation, including at least one
for Saturday's starter, Ismael Valdes.
</P>
<P>
   Although they now have dropped back into last place by losing 10
of 12, the Dodgers claim they will use the final two months to
answer questions about the team's character.
</P>
<P>
   They know the team does not work in its present form and could
try to move five of the eight regulars, including Eric Karros, Eric
Young, Devon White and Gary Sheffield, this winter if they can get
someone to take the players' multiyear contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of discussions, we've been open-minded to what
other clubs say,'' Dodgers general manager Kevin Malone said. ``But
there were some situations that were presented to us that were not
in our best interest in the long term.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday, Malone got to watch Johnson, whom he tried to sign
last winter as a free agent. The Dodgers offered Johnson a
three-year contract worth $39 million, but he signed with the
Diamondbacks for four years and $52 million.
</P>
<P>
   As he has all season, Johnson looked like a bargain, limiting
the Dodgers to six hits, including a two-run homer by Karros that
cut Arizona's lead to 3-2 in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   From there, Johnson (11-8) limited the Dodgers to four hits and
a walk to record his major-league leading ninth complete game and
raise his record to 11-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is the best pitcher I've ever faced,'' said Trenidad
Hubbard, who started in place of Mondesi in right. ``This was the
first time for me today. I think I'm a pretty good fastball hitter.
But that thing was unbelievable.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi entered the game as a pinch hitter for Valdes (8-9), who
allowed seven hits and three runs in eight innings and tied a
season high with 10 strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi singled to left, putting the tying run at first with one
out. But Johnson struck out Mark Grudzielanek and got Hubbard on a
fly ball to left.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson walked Gary Sheffield to open the ninth but struck out
Karros, White and Adrian Beltre to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Mondesi tried to be playful about the trade deadline
but turned serious when talking about how much he would miss the
fans and his teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, his name hasn't been mentioned since last month when a
whopper hit the Internet that had Mondesi heading to Detroit as
part of deal involving the Tigers' Tony Clark and Bobby Higginson.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the Cincinnati rumor last winter, Mondesi was upset
with the public's perception about his drunk driving arrest last
season. Charges were later dropped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hearing your name mentioned all the time can be really hard on
your concentration,'' said Grudzielanek, who came over from
Montreal last year at the July 31 deadline. ``I think it would be
particularly tough for Mondy since he grew up in the organization
and has been such a big part of this team.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's career includes a National League Rookie of the Year
award in 1994 and back-to-back 30 home run seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``None of that matters now,'' Mondesi said. ``They traded (Mike)
Piazza. They traded (Hideo) Nomo. They were rookies of the year.
Maybe I'm next.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
