<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-MERCEDES-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGASSI ATTACKS USTA AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ If the ATP tour is in Los Angeles, it must be time
for Andre Agassi to launch a verbal assault on the U.S. Tennis
Association and explain why he won't play Davis Cup matches in the
foreseeable future.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, an ATP official recalled, Agassi criticized the USTA
for choosing Milwaukee as a Davis Cup site.
</P>
<P>
   He revisited those themes Friday night after his quarterfinal
victory over Lleyton Hewitt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an example of how players don't have a say-so in the most
important issues,'' Agassi said.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi, who played in the Davis Cup last year, also knocked the
USTA over its dismissal of George Fareed as Davis Cup team doctor.
Agassi believes Fareed would be able to keep players better
hydrated than other doctors on the professional tennis circuit.
</P>
<P>
   So while Pete Sampras has expressed a desire to play more Davis
Cup matches in the future, Agassi reiterated his refusal to
participate.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Not) till they reconsider George,'' Agassi said. ``George
will never let that (dehydration) happen to us. Once you're
dehydrated, it's too late. George would've had the fluids and the
minerals all week.''
</P>
<P>
   Day vs. night: Agassi has yet to play a day match. Sampras has
yet to play at night, although he participated in a celebrity
fund-raiser Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Today's final is at 2 p.m. Perhaps Sampras has an advantage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've enjoyed playing at night,'' Agassi said. ``The sun plays
an element. The heat plays an element. The ball plays quicker. The
court plays quicker. Your toss changes on serve. I would've loved
to play during the day.''
</P>
<P>
   All is forgiven: Earlier this week, Patrick Rafter ascended to
the world's No.1 ranking and blasted Sampras for what he perceives
as a lack of respect for other players. Rafter beat Sampras in
their last three meetings, including the U.S. Open semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   The rift began after a match last year in Cincinnati. Sampras,
beaten by Rafter, was upset at the chair umpire's reversing a call
that gave Rafter the match. Sampras refused to shake the umpire's
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras has said he has no problem with Rafter. The two spoke
this week by telephone, and Sampras is convinced there is no rift.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spoke to Pat, and we smoothed it over,'' he said. ``I was
surprised to hear the things he said. He's not that kind of guy. I
respect Pat. There's not a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Doubles faulted: While Nos.1 and 2 play in today's singles
final, there is no such situation in the doubles final, which
follows Agassi-Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   No seeds reached the final. Only one seeded team reached
Saturday's semifinals: No. 2 Wayne Black of Zimbabwe and Sandon
Stolle of Australia, and they lost in straight sets to Byron
Black/Wayne Ferreira.
</P>
<P>
   Black and Ferreira have been the seed killers, having also
knocked off third-seeded John-Laffnie de Jager/Jim Grabb in
straight sets on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Also on Friday, top-seeded Leander Paes of India/Jonas Bjorkman
of Sweden lost to Martin Damm/Adam Peterson. Unseeded Goran
Ivanisevic/Brian MacPhie beat No. 4 Justin Gimelstob/Scott
Humphries. Those two matches went three sets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
