<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PLAZA-MAINSTREAM-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHANGES AT PLAZA REFLECT MOVEMENT TOWARD MAINSTREAM ENTERTAINMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK P. COUCH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. -- Call it the Plaza reformation.
</P>
<P>
   The managers of the Country Club Plaza didn't tack a list of
grievances on tenants' doors to announce a break with tradition.
</P>
<P>
   But recent changes in the venerable district are tilting the
tony shops of the Plaza more heavily toward the hottest trend in
retailing: entertainment for the masses.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of the year, the Plaza has made several
changes that push the shopping center closer to the mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   Among the changes:
</P>
<P>
   - The 14 movie screens in Cinemark's Palace on the Plaza embrace
the new era of the multiplex.
</P>
<P>
   - A host of national merchants are moving into stores once
reserved for local boutiques.
</P>
<P>
   - Chain restaurants, from Chicago-style deep-dish pizza to a
Chinese bistro, are adding flavors to the Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   - And, perhaps the ultimate sign that a mainstream trend has
trickled to the Plaza: Starbucks will open a cafe on the Plaza in
September.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, as the Plaza adapts to contemporary tastes and adds
tenants with deeper pockets and broader appeal, the Plaza's public
face is adopting some features that resemble the long-planned Power
&AMP; Light District.
</P>
<P>
   That $454 million project still sits on the drawing board, but
its key features include a complex of at least 20 movie screens,
trendy retailers and some chain restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   No one would confuse the stately Plaza with the neon dreams for
downtown of the late movie-theater magnate Stan Durwood. After all,
the 14-screen Plaza on the Palace has a marble lobby rather than
the splashes of neon Cinemark has at other venues.
</P>
<P>
   But neither district is a pure play. The Power &AMP; Light District
would be an entertainment district featuring shopping. The Plaza
has become a shopping district featuring more entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   David Fenley, lawyer for J.C. Nichols, said the Plaza's managers
didn't set out to conquer the same territory scouted by the
voter-approved Power &AMP; Light District.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Plaza folks put the pedal to the metal and said,
`Let's get this place moving forward,' they said, `What do people
want to do in 1996?' '' Fenley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They did not say, `What did people want to do in 1928?' They
did not say, `What did people want to do in 1962?' They did not
say, `What did people want to do in 1975?' They were saying, `In
the context of the world we're living in right now, what do people
want to do?' ''
</P>
<P>
   The answers are fairly simple: They go to movies. They eat at
nice restaurants. They shop for convenience and style.
</P>
<P>
   The Plaza and the proposed Power &AMP; Light District might overlap
in some respects, but that's only because the retail elite across
the country are asking the same question and coming to similar
conclusions.
</P>
<P>
   From San Francisco, where Sony Corp. recently opened an $85
million retail and entertainment complex called Metreon, to the
Mall of America in Bloomington, Minn., to Times Square in New York,
developers are chasing the Holy Grail mix of shopping, food and
fun.
</P>
<P>
   In Kansas City, backers of the Power &AMP; Light District and
managers of the Plaza pooh-pooh comparisons of their projects.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Bashkiroff, managing director of Power &AMP; Light District
LLC, said he didn't think the projects were similar.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are suburban,'' Bashkiroff said of the Plaza. ``It's a
suburban shopping center. Ours is the Midwest's version of Times
Square.''
</P>
<P>
   The Power &AMP; Light District would offer a 12-block mix of stores,
movie theaters, offices, apartments, hotels, live-performance
stages and parking garages north of Truman Road between Wyandotte
and McGee streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have an entertainment orientation that will be
regionally exclusive,'' Bashkiroff said. ``The Plaza is much more
retail-oriented.''
</P>
<P>
   Barrett Brady, vice president of Highwoods Properties Inc.,
owner of J.C. Nichols, said the Plaza wouldn't become as glitzy as
the Power &AMP; Light District or other urban entertainment districts
around the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``That name doesn't fit for what we're doing,'' Brady said.
``We're not neon-oriented. We're more conservative entertainment,
and maybe they're more than that.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Brady contends the ever-evolving Plaza and the emerging
Power &AMP; Light District are compatible.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think people will still visit the Plaza, and I think they
will tack on a trip to the Power &AMP; Light District because that will
be a unique experience,'' Brady said. ``They are not mutually
exclusive. It's not a market where if they succeed, then we will
fail. We can all succeed.'' -- MORE --
</P>
<P>
   But before the projects can succeed in tandem, Brady's primary
job is to guarantee that the Plaza succeeds on its own.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, J.C. Nichols unveiled its $240 million plan for
building improvements and additional parking structures. The
company received $50 million in tax breaks to implement its plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Plaza area is facing pressure that downtowns have been
facing for the last 35 or 40 years,'' Brady said in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time, the Plaza could be called suburban because it
was on the edge of town. By 1997, the Plaza's problems had become
much more urban than suburban as the edge of new development swept
toward the far horizon.
</P>
<P>
   The Plaza needed to update aging buildings, squeeze more parking
into an increasingly crowded area and create a setting that would
draw people from the fringes of town.
</P>
<P>
   The redevelopment plan also emphasized pedestrian living with
more housing and offices, confirming the Plaza's status as one of
the few areas of the city where people can live without a car.
</P>
<P>
   While the company addressed its building needs, J.C. Nichols was
also shaking up the tenants in the Plaza.
</P>
<P>
   Glenn Stephenson, J.C. Nichols' director of asset management and
leasing, said the company needed a mix of mainstay shops like the
Gap and one-of-a-kind stores like Pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   Although the company has accelerated tenant changes in the past
three years, J.C. Nichols is constantly reviewing its tenant base.
More than 100 tenants have left the Plaza since 1991, Stephenson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Some tenants were ready to go, but sometimes those tenants left
with a Plaza manager's hand on their back.
</P>
<P>
   Some tenants complained that J.C. Nichols raised their rent by
changing the formula to calculate charges for operating costs.
Kelly Taylor, spokeswoman for Nichols, said the changes were fair.
</P>
<P>
   Several tenants, including Overland Sheep Skin Co. and Russell
Stover Candies, said J.C. Nichols wouldn't renew their leases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nichols didn't want us to stay,'' said Tom Ward, president of
Russell Stover Candies, which closed its Plaza store a few years
ago. ``We had been on the Plaza since 1947. They told us, `We don't
want national chains,' and then they turn around and bring in the
Gap and they bring in Banana Republic. What's that all about?''
</P>
<P>
   It's about money.
</P>
<P>
   Some national stores haul in cash faster than other stores, and
Plaza officials concluded they wanted to attract more of those
stores.
</P>
<P>
   Not that the Plaza, which gets more than 40 percent of sales
from out-of-town visitors, is hurting for revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Stephenson said the Plaza merchants, including restaurants, had
annual average sales of $375 per square foot. The 1998 national
average was $301, according to the International Council of
Shopping Centers, a trade group.
</P>
<P>
   J.C. Nichols is constantly evaluating the Plaza's tenants. That
means the Plaza must retire bowling alleys, faded retailers and
chili kitchens when they lose their appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Plaza certainly has changed from the days when it had gas
stations and a bowling alley,'' said Kansas City architect E.
Crichton Singleton.
</P>
<P>
   It also means the Plaza will pass on some prospects if they
don't fit management's goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked long and hard at Hard Rock Cafe, and we thought we
wanted them and they thought they wanted us,'' Brady said.
</P>
<P>
   That deal didn't happen, but the Plaza has nabbed tenants such
as Pizzeria Uno, a chain that makes Chicago-style deep-dish pizza.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will continue as long as the Plaza endures, said
Jonathan Barnett, a University of Pennsylvania professor of city
and regional planning who has worked as a consultant for the city.
</P>
<P>
   The latest changes might appear as if the Plaza is bowing to
current fads in the retail industry, but the area won't become a
fashion victim as long as it retains its original character,
Barnett said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the Plaza has attributes of an urban entertainment
district, but I consider it much more of a `real' place,'' Barnett
said. ``An urban entertainment district is almost like a casino
without the casino.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6 million visitors who trek to the Plaza every year should
find that the Plaza's incremental changes are in step with their
tastes, said Glen LeRoy, principal with Gould Evans Goodman
Associates in Kansas City. In some ways, the Plaza was an
entertainment district before the term became trendy.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Plaza has always been an entertainment district,'' LeRoy
said. ``But it has been entertainment in a mixed-use development.
It's just that the nature of the entertainment has changed.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
