<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-31 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1480 &Cx1f; tic-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      07-31 0659
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FRIENDLY BARRIER TO SAFER ROADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The claims she was going to fix the deadly problem anyway _ soon
_ but the fact is, Gov. Jane Hull didn't finally decide to install
cable barriers on local freeway medians until the day after a
friend nearly got killed in an accident.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, former legislator Polly Getzwiller and her husband
were critically injured on the Squaw Peak Freeway when their car
was crushed by &UR; a BMW that had crossed the unfenced median.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Hull committed the state to building 138 miles of
barriers.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't a new idea. People have been dying on barrier-free
highways around here for years.
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona Department of Transportation has been looking into
the idea of stringing cable barriers for quite some time, but
hasn't released a report yet.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, speaking in fluent politician, said, ``Although
the report is not yet complete, we now have enough information to
see what ADOT's recommendation will be.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly translated, this means, ``I'm not waiting around for
another buddy of mine to get wasted.''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody has a problem with the result. Whatever it takes to get
crews out there installing barriers is fine by us.
</P>
<P>
   Not only that, but Getzwiller is a wonderful woman.
</P>
<P>
   She was loved at the state Capitol, where she put in more time
than just about any politician this century, conducting herself
with such grace that, attached to her name, the term ``public
servant'' doesn't seem like a joke.
</P>
<P>
   I can understand why the friend of such a fine woman would want
to take action immediately. &QL; 
ANOTHER GOOD PERSON
</P>
<P>
   Then again, by all the accounts I've read, Tim Landers was a
pretty good person, too.
</P>
<P>
   He was a former football star at Arizona State University who
went on to become a Phoenix police officer. After working the late
shift one day in April, 1997, a driver crossed an open median on
the Squaw Peak and plowed head-on into Landers' vehicle, killing
him.
</P>
<P>
   The barriers could have _ and should have _ been put up right
then.
</P>
<P>
   But they weren't.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a little over a year later, Landers' wife and two young
children won a $4.5 million settlement from Phoenix and the state
of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Landers' lawyers collected reports on 27 accidents
resulting in five deaths that occurred within a half-mile of where
Landers was killed.
</P>
<P>
   All were the result of vehicles crossing the median.
</P>
<P>
   Any one of the people hurt or killed in those accidents was
reason enough to put up barriers.
</P>
<P>
   People like George Riley.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1992, the husband and father was fatally injured after a
guy trying to elude police drove his pickup truck across the median
and struck Riley's truck.
</P>
<P>
   It goes on. &QL; 
TAKE YOUR PICK
</P>
<P>
   Pick any year and any road like the Squaw Peak, the Loops 101
and 202, U.S. 60 or I-10 and you'll find the names of men, women
and children who weren't close to any politician but died in
crashes, and whose passing should have stirred some action.
</P>
<P>
   But didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Cable barriers are said to cost $155,000 a mile to construct.
</P>
<P>
   In the government decisionmaking process, money always comes
before lives.
</P>
<P>
   Except, maybe, with old chums.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about the proximity of Getzwiller's accident to her
decision to build barriers, Hull answered, ``It's no one thing.
It's rather the fact that in June, we requested that ADOT present
us with facts, figures and a plan of action.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a fluke, in other words, an unpredictable confluence of
events.
</P>
<P>
   I don't know. Perhaps the mysteries of coincidence, fate and the
inner workings of state government can't be understood or explained
by a newspaper writer, but require one of those self-help books so
popular these days.
</P>
<P>
   The one I imagine would be called, ``When Bad Things Happen to
Good. . .Friends of the Governor''. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-31-99 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
