<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUMMERPRO-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONE MAN'S SPL ALL-STARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONG BEACH, Calif. _ Show us a league that exists to promote the
basketball welfare of sleepers, and we'll give you a Dream Team.
</P>
<P>
   Consider it our little wakeup call.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, after a lengthy discussion (two minutes, tops), we decided
to provide one (1) glory day for a few Summer Pro League irregulars
before NBA general managers slap the snooze button on their
careers.
</P>
<P>
   Our list will deliver a few shocks and surprises among
subjective-thinking agents and wannabe coaches. But we believe you
can't have a Dream Team without producing a collateral cause for
alarm.
</P>
<P>
   We also appreciate any bitterness stirred in those players who
didn't qualify for our Dream Team. But know this: Our squad was
chosen through the scientific method of noticing who was playing
well while we just happened to be inside the Pyramid at Cal State
Long Beach. And we probably witnessed a lot more of the SPL's 30th
edition than you did.
</P>
<P>
   We were there when some irony manipulator pushed a button that
caused the PA system to spit out the Village People anthem ``YMCA''
during a break in the action involving a team fronted by abstract
rap artist Percy ``Master P'' Miller.
</P>
<P>
   What a lovely dichotomy that was.
</P>
<P>
   We also were there long enough to notice the SPL's mightiest
slam dunk. The nasty jam was a right-handed fastball delivered with
bad intent by 6-foot-5 lefty Warren Rosegreen, who performed this
feat for the Korean All-Stars. The victim was Khari Stanley of the
NBA Pros. To humans other than Rosegreen, Stanley _ who goes about
6-10 and 270 _ seems imposing enough to make a grizzly bear call
for backup.
</P>
<P>
   And we were there long enough to keep score on lottery picks.
</P>
<P>
   Four of the first 13 players selected in June's NBA draft
competed in SPL '99. The roll call: Andre Miller and Trajan Langdon
(Cavaliers), Shawn Marion (Suns) and Baron Davis (Hornets). Of
course, the Suns and Hornets didn't sponsor SPL teams, so Marion
and Davis performed in the division largely populated by players
who make their living overseas.
</P>
<P>
   We were there long enough to accuse Clippers candidate Kebu
Stewart of qualifying as the Outstanding Player in the NBA
division. The 6-8, 245-pound Stewart had the league's highest
per-game scoring average (24.1), while ranking second in rebounding
(9.1).
</P>
<P>
   Three years after the Lakers shook the Pyramid by turning loose
a kid named Kobe, the Clippers weighed in with the delightfully
finesse-free and similar-sounding Kebu. In a loss to Boston,
Stewart made 15 of 16 field-goal attempts and all 10 of his free
throws. When the math was accounted for, he had 40 points and 15
rebounds.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, Stewart was given the OP nod over Boston's Paul
Pierce, whose SPL participation created the same caliber of
mismatch that would occur if Jeffrey Osborne sang on ``Star
Search.'' Pierce, a 6-7 small forward with NBA All-Star potential,
spent a great deal of SPL time refining his anticipated conversion
to the shooting-guard position.
</P>
<P>
   We believe this could move could backfire, but since the Boston
coaching staff behaves as if it invented basketball, it must be a
sage decision.
</P>
<P>
   One of Pierce's SPL teammates on the well-stocked and unbeaten
Boston squad was Vitaly Potapenko, the Celtics' starting center. In
lyrical tribute to his geographical history and surplus bulk,
Potapenko is referred to as the ``Ukraine Train.'' But this
provincial fame soon may be challenged by Stanislav Medvedenko, the
``Ukraine Trainee.''
</P>
<P>
   Medvedenko is a 6-10, 20-year-old forward and our choice as the
Outstanding Player from the SPL's free-agent division. ``Slav''
averaged 26.7 points and 10.5 rebounds at the Pyramid, but his
average of 6.5 turnovers suggests he can be as careless as
Gilligan.
</P>
<P>
   We admit to seeing quite enough SPL action to be impressed by
many free-agent division point guards. Our list includes ex-UC
Santa Barbara sniper Ray Kelly, Tes Whitlock, the former Orange
County prep star, Donte Mathis, a rookie from Southwest Texas
State, and busy Sean Cornell.
</P>
<P>
   Cornell, who only seems to show up with more teams than Anthony
Robbins, played at Southern Arkansas State, finishing his
collegiate run in 1996. A special education teacher at Texas High
in Texarkana, Texas, he made his first SPL appearance in 1998 but
was injured in the opening week.
</P>
<P>
   He has averaged 21 points and 3.5 steals in SPL '99, splitting
time between Toyota of Orange and Fila Select.
</P>
<P>
   The 30th Summer Pro League roars to its conclusion tonight.
</P>
<P>
   As far as our Dream Team is concerned, the well-earned rest will
be history.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
