r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SWANSON-DINNER-AZR &LR;      07-31 0906
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SWANSON-DINNER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHIZ TURNED FROZEN DINNER INTO TRULY HOT COMMODITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER CORBETT  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It may be as painful as freezer burn to accept, but the man who
invented the TV dinner _ 8.4 billion meals sold _ does not eat from
aluminum.
</P>
<P>
   Gerry Thomas, a 77-year-old former marketing whiz who emerged
this year from the deep freeze of Americana to celebrate the 45th
anniversary of his culinary breakthrough, favors gourmet meals on
china.
</P>
<P>
   He and his wife, Susan, enjoy cooking in their well-appointed
Paradise Valley kitchen. And there's no TV-watching over dinner.
</P>
<P>
   In the freezer, where the Swanson chicken or Salisbury steak
dinners might be, is martini mix.
</P>
<P>
   ``A day without a martini is . . .'' he says dryly, letting the
thought drift off.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas is enjoying the warmth of the limelight after all these
years of relative obscurity.
</P>
<P>
   ``My kids (he has seven) say, `Hey, Dad, you're really cool.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In March, the frozen-food luminary's hand prints and his
four-compartment aluminum tray were immortalized on the Hollywood
Walk of Fame, right there with other recent inductees Sean Connery
and Ron Howard.
</P>
<P>
   Edgy men's magazine ``Maxim'' named Thomas one of the ``50
Greatest Guys of the Century'' in its July/August issue. He's No.
28 along with with TV inventor Philo Farnsworth and Edwin
Shoemaker, who dreamed up the La-Z-Boy recliner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You owe them big,'' is the magazine's maxim on these guy-hero
inventors.
</P>
<P>
   They rank ahead of Chef Boyardee and James Bond, among others.
</P>
<P>
   So, how did he do it? How did a fresh-out-of-college guy making
$300 a month stamp out his place in history?
</P>
<P>
   His brilliant marketing marriage of television and turkey, sweet
potatoes and peas, was an instant hit with a nation hungry for
black and white images of Milton Berle in drag flickering across
tiny Philco TV screens. The cardboard food, as critics called it,
was secondary.
</P>
<P>
   It all started with turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   C.A. Swanson &AMP; Sons of Omaha, Neb., found itself with 520,000
pounds of frozen fowl after Thanksgiving that it couldn't unload.
Ten rail cars full of turkeys crisscrossed the country to keep the
train's refrigeration systems operating.
</P>
<P>
   At a frozen-food warehouse in Pittsburgh, Thomas stumbled across
a metal tray that a supplier for Pan American Airlines was
experimenting with so the carrier could offer hot meals on overseas
flights.
</P>
<P>
   He put the tray into his overcoat pocket and did some
``noodling'' on the flight back to Omaha to design the
three-compartment tray.
</P>
<P>
   His experience in the Army mess hall told him that Americans
wouldn't go for a frozen meal if the food mixed together like it
did in a soldier's mess kit. Hence, the original tray's three
compartments.
</P>
<P>
   A fourth compartment was added in 1960, not to add desert, but
so Swanson could get a design patent, Thomas said.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, the desperate Swanson brothers, Gilbert and Clark,
gobbled up Thomas' idea and borrowed several hundred thousand
dollars to start production of the Swanson TV dinners.
</P>
<P>
   The TV dinner name Thomas coined was a natural for the era when
few Americans had televisions and everyone wanted one. He recalls
lunchtime window shoppers staring in store windows at test patterns
on TV screens about the size of today's microwave dinner plates.
Broadcasts were limited to about four hours of prime-time
programming.
</P>
<P>
   The other ingredient of the TV dinner's success was the
increasing number of working mothers in Eisenhower-era America who
liked the fast-food convenience and throwaway dishes.
</P>
<P>
   The original TV dinners, which sold for 98 cents, cooked at 425
degrees for 25 minutes. By today's standards of five-minute
microwave meals, that's glacial speed; but in 1954, that was
avalanche fast.
</P>
<P>
   Swanson had a hit. In the first year of national distribution,
the company sold 10 million TV dinners.
</P>
<P>
   For a generation of baby boomers, TV dinner night, eaten off TV
trays, was akin to home-delivery pizza night for their kids.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas shakes his head at how his invention took off.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason in the world we should have been
successful,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Most grocery stores had only small coffin cabinet freezers to
sell frozen foods, and most home refrigerators at the time had ice
boxes with scarcely enough room for two trays of ice. But it
worked.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, who left Swanson in 1970 after a heart attack and bought
a home in Arizona, said he never really thought about his
contribution to American popular culture. Not until last year, when
Swanson wanted to rebuild its slumping sales by celebrating the
anniversary of the TV dinner.
</P>
<P>
   He's had a lot of fun with the media attention, spots on CNN,
``Good Morning America'' and the ``Roseanne'' show. But there is an
important business lesson from the TV dinner, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's never been a great idea that has come out of a large
company,'' said Thomas, who went on to consulting after leaving
Swanson.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas jokes that he wishes he would have gotten a penny per
dinner, but his idea only earned him a $1,000 bonus.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and all these years later a spot in the Frozen Food Hall of
Fame, his name immortalized in the concrete outside Mann's Chinese
Theater and his aluminum TV dinner tray in the Smithsonian. &QL; 
Peter Corbett can be reached at (602) 444-4815 or at
peter.corbett &LR; pni.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
