<SLUG> BC-RAC-HAMBLETONIAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HAMBLETONIAN FIELD HAS BEEN DETERMINED  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERRY BREWER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Angus Hall and Self Possessed won their
Hambletonian heats Saturday, making them the favorites for next
Saturday's $1 million race here at the Meadowlands Racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   Angus Hall won the first elimination heat Saturday in 1 minute
54.3 seconds, leading for most of the way and holding off the pack.
The second- through-fifth-place trotters _ Cherry Hills, Raffaello
Ambrosio, Pearsall Hanover and CR Commando _ also advanced to the
final.
</P>
<P>
   ``He raced very well today,'' said John Campbell, Angus Hall's
driver. ``The horse is in good shape, and if he stays healthy until
next Saturday he'll have a very good shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said that Angus Hall's trainer, Bob Stewart, had
brought the horse a long way.
</P>
<P>
   Starchip Enterprise, who entered the day a 2-1 favorite in the
first heat, went off stride to begin the race and finished last.
</P>
<P>
   In the second heat, Self Possessed (1:53) came from behind in
the final three-eighths of a mile to win by three lengths over CR
Renegade, who had led for most of the race. Enjoy Lavec, Comets
Tail and Davanti finished third, fourth and fifth, earning spots in
the 10-horse final.
</P>
<P>
   The Hambletonian, for 3-year-old trotters, is harness racing's
premier event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm cautiously confident for the final,'' said Ron Gurfein,
Self Possessed's trainer. ``I had Self Possessed real light. I
added weight to his shoes to temper his speed. I had him as light
as possible, and he was almost pacing. I've had to sacrifice speed
for safety, however, and it's paid off.''
</P>
<P>
   The driver Mike Lachance said Self Possessed will be ready next
week. ``He's so versatile,'' he said. ``He was very relaxed today.
And it doesn't matter to him whether he's out front or not.''
</P>
<P>
   In the Breeders Crown race for mares, Shore by Five, the second
longest shot on the board at 15-1 odds, won in a photo finish over
Extreme Velocity. Robert McIntosh, trainer of Shore by Five, had
hoped Saturday that his mare would place high enough in the
$282,500 race to earn back the $7,500 entry fee posted by the
owner, Roger Saint-Germain, and his family. The victory in 1:50.4
earned Saint-Germain $141,250.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a big shocker,'' McIntosh said. ``Going into the race,
I thought she had a chance for fourth or fifth. But she's a
grinder. She showed a lot of quality in the stretch.''
</P>
<P>
   In the two other Breeders Crown races, the 2-1 favorite Red Bow
Tie won the $380,000 pace for horses and geldings by a neck over
Color Me Best with a time of 1:50. And in the $580,000 open trot,
Super Grit come on at the end and upset the 6-5 favorite Fern in
1:53.1, a career-best time for the 6-year-old.
</P>
<P>
   But Shore by Five's surprising victory highlighted the day. She
didn't make her push until about an eighth of a mile was left in
the race.
</P>
<P>
   Sanabelle Island, the 5-2 favorite, led for much of the race,
but faded. Without the favorite in the mix down the stretch, Shore
by Five capitalized, finishing just ahead of Extreme Velocity.
Galleria was third.
</P>
<P>
   ``This horse is a home bred,'' said Saint-Germain, who lives in
Quebec. ``It's a surprise for us, but we thought she could be in
the first five. Five is our lucky number. Her name is Shore By
Five, she had Post 5. I went to renew my license at the racing
commission today, and the guy who fingerprinted me was named Albert
Five and we have five boys.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, Saint-German decided to switch drivers. Daniel
Dube replaced William O'Donnell because, Saint-Germain said, he
wanted a familiar driver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made the decision myself,'' Saint-Germain said. ``Daniel
drove her last year in Quebec and won with her. She did not have a
consistent driver. I thought it was better she had someone who
knows her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
