<SLUG> BC-RAC-SARATOGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARLEY VALE PUTS THE PIECES TOGETHER IN TEST AT SARATOGA  
 (HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARATOGA SPRINGS, N.Y. _ Marley Vale, a 3-year-old daughter of
Forty Niner, put all the ingredients together Saturday _ time,
distance and pace _ and outran 11 other star fillies to win the
Test, the first Grade I stakes of the season at Saratoga.
</P>
<P>
   It was a victory of patience and planning for Todd Pletcher, who
trains the filly for Eugene Melnyk. He found the right combination
Saturday when Marley Vale gunned her way from sixth place to
fourth, then into the lead in the homestretch and defeated Awful
Smart by 2{ lengths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything worked out beautifully,'' said Pletcher, who won
the training title at Saratoga last year at 31 and has already won
two major stakes in the first four days this year. ``The fractions
were hot, and we were close enough to be in position to take
advantage.''
</P>
<P>
   In her three previous starts, Pletcher had tried his filly at
distances greater than one mile instead of in the sprints that she
had successfully handled in the past.
</P>
<P>
   Two races ago, Marley Vale ran in the Kentucky Oaks but was
overmatched by Silverbulletday, the superstar of fillies, when she
tried to go a mile and one-sixteenth at Churchill Downs. She
finished fifth. Then Pletcher brought her back to the sprints,
hoped for a fast pace and got it. In the Prioress at Belmont Park
four weeks ago, she ran second by a neck to Sapphire n' Silk.
</P>
<P>
   This time, back at seven furlongs with a streaking pace that
took them half a mile in 44 seconds and three-quarters in 1:09 1/5,
Marley Vale was in good position.
</P>
<P>
   John Velazquez, her jockey, moved her smartly to the outside,
got four-wide clearance as they headed home and drove past Bag Lady
Jane and Sapphire n' Silk. She crossed with daylight to spare,
while Awful Smart won second place by a head over Emanating. The
favorite, Olympic Charmer, who shipped here from California with
her rider, Chris McCarron, grew weary of it early and finished
10th.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were on the Breeders' Cup pace last year,'' Pletcher said,
``but she had a little problem with her shins and we had to back
off her. We tried to stretch her out in Florida; it was simply too
far. We were planning on going to the Acorn last month, but she was
a really tired horse.''
</P>
<P>
   Marley Vale ran the seven furlongs in 1:22 3/5, paid $9.40 for a
$2 bet to win and earned $150,000.
</P>
<P>
   McCarron, who flew 2,700 miles to ride Olympic Charmer for Ron
McAnally, said: ``She didn't show her usual speed. This is the
first time I had to chirp to her and really get into her at the
start. I believe this is also the first time she has had dirt
kicked in her face.''
</P>
<P>
   FINISH LINES
</P>
<P>
   The Whitney, the main event of the season for handicap horses,
still looks like a match race between the two leading seniors:
Behrens, the winner of four straight stakes, and Victory Gallop,
who won the Belmont last year and has raced with distinction since.
But they will have six rivals, including Sir Bear, winner of the
Metropolitan Mile, and Connecting Terms, the rabbit entered by
Elliott Walden to protect the finishing kick expected from Victory
Gallop. ``In my mind,'' Walden said, ``the most important races are
the Kentucky Derby, the Triple Crown and the Breeders' Cup. But the
Whitney is the race of the year so far.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
