<HEADER>
A1500 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     07-31 0881
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV08-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, August 8)  
(js) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; The Murder of Helen Jewett: The Life and Death of a Prostitute
in Nineteenth-Century New York &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Patricia Cline Cohen. Vintage, $14.
</P>
<P>
   In 1836 it was possible to kill and get away with it, at least
if the victim was less than respectable. That is one of the lessons
of this history, which centers on the notorious bludgeoning of a
young prostitute by her lover, a small-time embezzler. ``Cohen does
a masterly job of identifying the mysteries at the heart of the
case,'' Janet H. Murray said last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Natural History &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Maureen Howard. Carroll &AMP; Graf, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   Bridgeport, Conn., the author's hometown, is a prominent player
in her sixth novel, first published in 1992. It deals with the
Brays, Irish Catholics whose patriarch, Billy, was the police
detective investigating the local murder of a soldier by a
socialite during World War II. The book details how the episode has
molded the lives of his grown children. John Casey wrote that the
novel is ``a synergy of Maureen Howard's meditative social vision
and storytelling immediacy, of her highly developed technical skill
and of her alert heart.'' Howard's autobiography,  &UR; Facts of Life &LR; 
(Penguin, $12.95), has also been restored to print. Reissued with a
new afterword, it chronicles her working-class girlhood with
parents who were ambitious for Howard and her brother but deeply
ambivalent about their children's successes. The book is
``interesting and enjoyable,'' Diane Johnson said in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Salt Water &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Charles Simmons.
</P>
<P>
   Washington Square/Pocket Books, $12.
</P>
<P>
   A reimagining of Turgenev's novella ``First Love,'' this story
unfolds in the summer of 1963. The narrator, then 15, falls for an
older girl, who, he later discovers, is in love with his father.
The novel ``is a small masterpiece,'' Katharine Weber wrote last
year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Black Notebooks: An Interior Journey &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Toi Derricotte. Norton, $13.
</P>
<P>
   The author, a poet and teacher, is a light-skinned black woman.
In this memoir she examines the consequences, to herself and
others, of the various times in her life that she has chosen to
pass for white. The book is distinguished by ``poignantly realized
details of feeling,'' Benjamin DeMott said in 1997. Questions of
racial identity are also explored in  &UR; The Accidental Asian: Notes
of a Native Speaker &LR; , by Eric Liu (Vintage, $12). The successful
son of immigrants from Taiwan, the author defends his own feelings
that he is ultimately more American than Chinese. Last year Gary
Krist, called the book ``remarkable for its ... refusal to buy into
the party line of identity politics.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The World I Made For Her &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Thomas Moran. Riverhead, $12.
</P>
<P>
   The narrator is speechless but not deaf, silenced by the
respirator tube that is keeping him alive in a hospital where he is
being treated for severe complications of chickenpox. Based on the
author's own experiences, the novel describes the rich inner life
the patient still manages and the imaginary universe in which he
places his nurses. Moran is ``an admirably resourceful writer,''
Michael Upchurch said in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Opium: A History &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Martin Booth. St. Martin's Griffin, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   The author traces the science and culture surrounding a
substance that is older than mankind and that has proved to be both
a medical solace and a sociological scourge. ``It is a crowded, sad
and dramatic story,'' Jonathan Spence wrote last year. In  &UR; The
American Disease: Origins of Narcotic Control &LR;  (Oxford University,
$17.95), David F. Musto looks at the legislative response to
addiction in the United States. Now in a third edition that
continues the chronicle to the present, the book argues that strict
narcotics laws have often been inspired more by racial prejudice
and xenophobia than by sincere attempts to cure a problem. The book
``will probably become mandatory reading for anyone who wants to
understand how we got into our present mess,'' James M. Markham
said in 1973.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Rich Man's Table &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Scott Spencer. Berkley, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   This novel chronicles the narrator's obsession with the man he
believes to be his father, a famous folk-rock singer and 1960s icon
who bears an uncanny resemblance to Bob Dylan. Last year Gary Krist
described the book as ``another charismatic and heartfelt
performance'' by its author.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In the Night Season &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Bausch. Harper Perennial, $13.
</P>
<P>
   Nora Michaelson, alone with a young son, finds herself suddenly
haunted by more than the accident that made her a widow. Two men
descend on her family, determined to recover the remnants of a
high-tech smuggling operation that, unbeknown to Nora, involved her
husband. This is ``a brutal and relentless thriller,'' A.O. Scott
wrote in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Black Glass: Short Fictions &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Karen Joy Fowler. Ballantine, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   These stories, which take place in locations ranging from
17th-century Japan to modern America, are peopled with characters
who are not necessarily human. The author ``manages to re-create
both life's extraordinary and its ordinary magic,'' Jenny McPhee
said last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
